B019C069V005	19	69	5	O God, you know my folly,my guilt is not hidden from you.
B019C069V006	19	69	6	Through me let not any be shamed,who wait for you, 
B019C069V007	19	69	7	It’s in your cause that I have borne taunts,and my face has been covered with shame;
B019C069V008	19	69	8	I became to my kindred a foreigner,to my mother's sons a stranger. 
B019C069V009	19	69	9	It was zeal for your house that consumed me,and the insults they hurled at you fell upon me.
B019C069V010	19	69	10	When I chastened myself with fasting,they took occasion to taunt me.
B019C069V011	19	69	11	When I put on a garment of sackcloth,they made me the theme of a taunt-song.
B019C069V012	19	69	12	Those who sit in the gate make sport of mein the music of drunken songs. 
B019C069V013	19	69	13	But I pray to you, 
B019C069V014	19	69	14	from sinking down in the mire.Lift me out of the deep deep waters,
B019C069V015	19	69	15	that the rushing flood may not drown me,that the deep may not swallow me up,nor the pit close her mouth upon me.
B019C069V016	19	69	16	Answer me, 
B019C069V017	19	69	17	Hide not your face from your servant,for I am in trouble; O answer me speedily.
B019C069V018	19	69	18	Draw near to me, redeem me;because of my enemies, ransom me. 
B019C069V019	19	69	19	You know how I am insulted;in your sight are all my foes.
B019C069V020	19	69	20	Insult has broken my heart,past cure are my shame and confusion.For pity I looked --- there was none!And for comforters, but I found none.
B019C069V021	19	69	21	Poison they gave me for food,and to slake my thirst they gave vinegar. 
B019C069V022	19	69	22	May their table, outspread, be a trap to them,and their peace-offerings be a snare.
B019C069V023	19	69	23	May their eyes be darkened and blind,make their loins to shake without ceasing.
B019C069V024	19	69	24	Pour your indignation upon them,let your burning wrath overtake them.
B019C069V025	19	69	25	May their camp be a desolation,in their tents be there none to live.
B019C069V026	19	69	26	For those whom you struck, they persecute,and those whom you wounded, they pain yet more.
B019C069V027	19	69	27	Charge them with sin upon sin,may they not be acquitted by you.
B019C069V028	19	69	28	From the book of life be they blotted,may their names not be written with the righteous. 
B019C069V029	19	69	29	Lift me, O God, by your helpabove my pain and misery.
B019C069V030	19	69	30	Then will I praise God in songand magnify him with thanksgiving,
B019C069V031	19	69	31	which shall please the 
B019C069V032	19	69	32	The oppressed shall rejoice at the sight.You who seek after God, let your heart revive.
B019C069V033	19	69	33	For the 
B019C069V034	19	69	34	Let the heavens and the earth sing his praises,the seas, and all creatures that move in them.
B019C069V035	19	69	35	For God will bring help to Zion,and build up the cities of Judah,his people shall live there in possession.
B019C069V036	19	69	36	His servants’ children shall have it for heritage,and those who love him shall live therein.
B019C070V001	19	70	1	Quickly, God, deliver me,hasten to help me, 
B019C070V002	19	70	2	May those who are seeking my life,be ashamed and confounded.
B019C070V003	19	70	3	May those who delight in my hurtbe defeated and brought to dishonour.
B019C070V004	19	70	4	But may all who seek after yourejoice and be glad in you.May all who love your salvationsay, “Glory to God,” evermore.
B019C070V005	19	70	5	I am weak and needy:make haste, God, to me.You are my help and deliverer;
B019C071V001	19	71	1	In you, O 
B019C071V002	19	71	2	In your faithfulness save me and rescue me,bend your ear to me and save me.
B019C071V003	19	71	3	Be to me a rock of defence,a fortified house, to save me;for my rock and my fortress are you. 
B019C071V004	19	71	4	Save me, my God, from the hand of the wicked,from the grasp of the unjust and cruel.
B019C071V005	19	71	5	For you, 
B019C071V006	19	71	6	On you have I leaned from my birth;from my mother’s womb it was you who did draw me.In you is my hope evermore. 
B019C071V007	19	71	7	I have been as a wonder to many,for you are my refuge and strength.
B019C071V008	19	71	8	All the day long my mouthis filled with your praise and your glory.
B019C071V009	19	71	9	Cast me not off in the time of old age;when my strength is spent, forsake me not.
B019C071V010	19	71	10	For my foes whisper against me,they who watch me take counsel together;
B019C071V011	19	71	11	“God has left him,” they say: “pursueand seize him, for he is helpless.” 
B019C071V012	19	71	12	O God, be not far from me,haste, O my God, to my help.
B019C071V013	19	71	13	Put my foes to shame and dishonour,with insult and shame be they covered.
B019C071V014	19	71	14	But I will never stop hoping,and more and yet more will I praise you.
B019C071V015	19	71	15	All the day long shall my mouthtell your faithfulness and your salvation,though I know not how they may be counted. 
B019C071V016	19	71	16	I will tell of the might of the 
B019C071V017	19	71	17	You have taught me, O God, from my youth,and till now have I told of your wonders.
B019C071V018	19	71	18	Even in old age and grey hair,O God, do not forsake me.Still would I tell of your mightunto all generations to come. 
B019C071V019	19	71	19	Your power and your justice, O God,extend as far as the heavens:for great are the things you have done.Who is like you, O God?
B019C071V020	19	71	20	You have caused us to see troubles many,but you will revive us again.From the depths of the earthyou will bring me up again.
B019C071V021	19	71	21	You will multiply my greatness,and comfort me again. 
B019C071V022	19	71	22	So with harp I will praise you,and your faithfulness, O my God;and make music to you on the lyre,O you Holy One of Israel.
B019C071V023	19	71	23	My lips shall ring out their joy,my mouth shall sing praises to you;all of me, which you have redeemed.
B019C071V024	19	71	24	Yes, all the day long shall my tongueutter your righteousness;for ashamed and confounded are theywho were seeking my hurt.
B019C072V001	19	72	1	Give the king, O God, your own spirit of justiceyour spirit of right to the son of the king,
B019C072V002	19	72	2	that with right he may judge your people,and your downtrodden ones with justice. 
B019C072V003	19	72	3	May the mountains bear weal for the people,and the hills yield fruits of justice.
B019C072V004	19	72	4	The weak may he help to their rights,may he save the sons of the needyand crush the oppressor in pieces. 
B019C072V005	19	72	5	May he live as long as the sun,while the moon shines — for ages and ages.
B019C072V006	19	72	6	May he be like the rain on the meadow,like showers that water the earth. 
B019C072V007	19	72	7	In his days may justice flourish,and welfare abound, till the moon be no more.
B019C072V008	19	72	8	May he reign from ocean to ocean,from the river to the ends of the earth. 
B019C072V009	19	72	9	May his foes bow down before him,his enemies lick the dust.
B019C072V010	19	72	10	May tribute be rendered by kingsof the isles and of Tarshish;may gifts be brought by the kingsof Sheba and Seba. 
B019C072V011	19	72	11	May all kings fall prostrate before him,and all nations yield him their service.
B019C072V012	19	72	12	For he saves the poor when he cries,the helpless and the downtrodden. 
B019C072V013	19	72	13	He pities the weak and the poor,he saves the lives of the poor.
B019C072V014	19	72	14	He redeems them from wrong and from violence,for dear is their blood in his sight. 
B019C072V015	19	72	15	Long may he live;and may gold of Sheba be given him;prayer, too, be made for him ceaselessly,all the day long may men bless him. 
B019C072V016	19	72	16	May the land have abundance of corn,to the tops of the hills may it wave.May the fruit thereof flourish like Lebanon,may men spring from the city like grass of the earth. 
B019C072V017	19	72	17	May his name be blessed forever,may his fame endure as the sun.May all nations envy his blessedness,all tribes of the earth call him happy. 
B019C072V018	19	72	18	Blest be the 
B019C072V019	19	72	19	And blest be forever his glorious name.  Let all the earth be filled with his glory.  Amen and Amen.  
B019C072V020	19	72	20	Here end the prayers of David, son of Jesse.
B019C073V001	19	73	1	Yes, God is good to the upright,the 
B019C073V002	19	73	2	But my feet were almost gone,my steps had nearly slipped,
B019C073V003	19	73	3	through envy of godless braggarts,when I saw how well they fared. 
B019C073V004	19	73	4	For never a pang have they,their body is sound and sleek.
B019C073V005	19	73	5	They have no trouble like mortals,no share in human pain.
B019C073V006	19	73	6	So they wear their pride like a necklace,they put on the garment of wrong,
B019C073V007	19	73	7	their eyes stand out with fatness,their heart swells with riotous fancies.
B019C073V008	19	73	8	Their speech is mocking and evil,condescending and crooked their speech.
B019C073V009	19	73	9	They have set their mouth in the heavens,while their tongue struts about on the earth.
B019C073V010	19	73	10	Small wonder that people resort to them,and drink deep draughts of their lore.
B019C073V011	19	73	11	“How does God know?” they say,“And has the Most High any knowledge?”
B019C073V012	19	73	12	See! These are the godless,with wealth and ease ever increasing. 
B019C073V013	19	73	13	Yes, in vain have I kept my heart pure,and washed my hands in innocence;
B019C073V014	19	73	14	for all the day long was I plaguednot a morning but I was chastised.
B019C073V015	19	73	15	But to resolve to speak like they dowould be treachery to your children. 
B019C073V016	19	73	16	So I sought to understand it,but a wearisome task it seemed:
B019C073V017	19	73	17	till I entered the holy world of Godand saw clearly their destiny. 
B019C073V018	19	73	18	Yes, you set them on slippery places;down to destruction you hurl them.
B019C073V019	19	73	19	One moment and then what a horror of ruin!They are finished and ended in terrors.
B019C073V020	19	73	20	Like a dream, when one wakes, shall they be,whose phantoms the waker despises. 
B019C073V021	19	73	21	So my bitterness of mindand the pain that stabbed my heart
B019C073V022	19	73	22	show how dull I was and stupidjust like a beast before you. 
B019C073V023	19	73	23	But I am always with you,you have hold of my right hand.
B019C073V024	19	73	24	By a plan of yours you guide meand will afterward take me to glory. 
B019C073V025	19	73	25	Whom have I in the heavens but you?And on earth there is none I desire beside you.
B019C073V026	19	73	26	Though flesh and heart waste away,yet God is the rock of my heart,yet God is my portion forever. 
B019C073V027	19	73	27	For see! Those who are far from you must perish,you destroy all who are false to you.
B019C073V028	19	73	28	But I am happy when close to God;the 
B019C074V001	19	74	1	Why, O God, have you spurned us forever?Why smokes your wrath against the sheep of your pasture?
B019C074V002	19	74	2	Remember the community you purchased of oldto become by redemption the tribe of your heritage,Zion, the mountain you made your home.
B019C074V003	19	74	3	Rouse yourself, visit its ruins complete.In the temple the foe has made havoc of all things. 
B019C074V004	19	74	4	Like lions your enemies roared through your house,replacing our symbols by signs of their own,
B019C074V005	19	74	5	hacking, like woodsmen who liftaxes on thickets of trees,
B019C074V006	19	74	6	smashing with hatchets and hammersall of its carved work together.
B019C074V007	19	74	7	They have set your temple on fire,to the very ground they have outragedthe place where lives your name.
B019C074V008	19	74	8	They have said in their heart, “Let us utterly crush them.”They have burned all the houses of God in the land. 
B019C074V009	19	74	9	No symbol of ours do we see any more:no prophet is there any more,none is with us who knows how long.
B019C074V010	19	74	10	How long, O God, is the foe to insult?Shall the enemy spurn your name forever?
B019C074V011	19	74	11	Why, O 
B019C074V012	19	74	12	Yet God is our king from the ancient days,in the midst of the earth working deeds of salvation.
B019C074V013	19	74	13	It was you who did cleave the sea by your might,and shatter the heads of the ocean monsters.
B019C074V014	19	74	14	It was you who did crush many-headed Leviathan,and give him as food to the beasts of the wilderness.
B019C074V015	19	74	15	It was you who did cleave the fountains and torrents;it was you who did dry the perennial streams.
B019C074V016	19	74	16	Yours is the day; yours, too, is the night,it was you who did establish the sun and the star.
B019C074V017	19	74	17	It was you who did fix all the borders of earth:summer and winter it’s you who have made them. 
B019C074V018	19	74	18	Yet, for all this, the foe has insulted you, 
B019C074V019	19	74	19	Do not give your dove to the beasts,do not forget your afflicted forever.
B019C074V020	19	74	20	Look to the sleek ones - how full they are:the dark places of earth are the dwellings of violence.
B019C074V021	19	74	21	O let not the downtrodden turn back ashamed:let the poor and the needy sing praise to your name. 
B019C074V022	19	74	22	Arise, God, and defend your cause:remember how fools all the day insult you.
B019C074V023	19	74	23	Do not forget the uproar of your enemies,the din of your foes that ascends evermore.
