B044C001V003	44	1	3	With abundant proofs, he showed himself to them, still living, after his death; appearing to them from time to time during forty days, and speaking of all that related to the kingdom of God.
B044C001V004	44	1	4	And once, when he had gathered them together, he charged them not to leave Jerusalem, but to wait there for the fulfilment of the Father’s promise — he said,
B044C001V006	44	1	6	So, when the apostles had met together, they asked Jesus this question — “Master, is this the time when you intend to re-establish the kingdom for Israel?”
B044C001V007	44	1	7	His answer was:
B044C001V008	44	1	8	
B044C001V009	44	1	9	No sooner had Jesus said this than he was caught up before their eyes, and a cloud received him from their sight.
B044C001V010	44	1	10	While they were still gazing up into the heavens, as he went, suddenly two men, clothed in white, stood beside them,
B044C001V011	44	1	11	and said: “People of Galilee, why are you standing here looking up into the heavens? This same Jesus, who has been taken from you into the heavens, will come in the same way in which you have seen him go into the heavens.”  
B044C001V012	44	1	12	Then the apostles returned to Jerusalem from the hill called Olivet, which is about three quarters of a mile from the city.
B044C001V013	44	1	13	When they reached Jerusalem, they went to the upstairs room, where they were staying. There were there Peter, John, James, and Andrew, Philip and Thomas, Bartholomew and Matthew, James the son of Alphaeus, Simon the Zealot, and Judas the son of James.
B044C001V014	44	1	14	They all united in devoting themselves to prayer, and so did some women, and Mary, the mother of Jesus, and his brothers.  
B044C001V015	44	1	15	About this time, at a meeting of the Lord's followers, when there were about a hundred and twenty present, Peter rose to speak.
B044C001V016	44	1	16	“Friends,” he said, “it was necessary who the prediction of scripture should be fulfilled, which the Holy Spirit made by the lips of David about Judas, who acted as guide to the men that arrested Jesus,
B044C001V017	44	1	17	for he was one of our number and had his part allotted him in this work of ours.”
B044C001V018	44	1	18	(This man had bought a piece of land with the price of his treachery; and, falling heavily, his body had burst open, and all his bowels protruded.
B044C001V019	44	1	19	This became known to everyone living in Jerusalem, so that the field came to be called, in their language, ‘Akeldama,’ which means the ‘Field of Blood.’)
B044C001V020	44	1	20	“For in the book of Psalms,” Peter continued, “it is said —  ‘Let his home,And let no one live in it’;  and also —  ‘His office let another take.’
B044C001V021	44	1	21	Therefore, from among the men who have been with us all the time that Jesus, our Master, went in and out among us —
B044C001V022	44	1	22	From his baptism by John down to that day on which he was taken from us — some one must be found to join us as a witness of his resurrection.”
B044C001V023	44	1	23	So they put forward two men, Joseph called Barsabas, whose other name was Justus, and Matthias;
B044C001V024	44	1	24	and they offered this prayer —  “Lord, who reads all hearts, show which of these two men you have chosen
B044C001V025	44	1	25	To take the place in this apostolic work, which Judas has abandoned, to go to his proper place.”
B044C001V026	44	1	26	Then they drew lots between them; and, the lot having fallen on Matthias, he was added to the number of the eleven apostles.  
B044C002V001	44	2	1	In the course of the Festival at the close of the Harvest the disciples had all met together,
B044C002V002	44	2	2	when suddenly there came from the heavens a noise like a strong wind rushing by; it filled the whole house in which they were sitting.
B044C002V003	44	2	3	Then there appeared tongues of what seemed to be flame, separating, so that one settled on each of them;
B044C002V004	44	2	4	and they were all filled with the Holy Spirit, and began to speak with strange ‘tongues’ as the Spirit prompted their utterances.
B044C002V005	44	2	5	Now there were then staying in Jerusalem religious Jews from every country in the world;
B044C002V006	44	2	6	and, when this sound was heard, numbers of people collected, in the greatest excitement, because each of them heard the disciples speaking in his own language.
B044C002V007	44	2	7	They were utterly amazed, and kept asking in astonishment:  “What! Are not all these people who are speaking Galileans?
B044C002V008	44	2	8	Then how is it that we each of us hear them in our own language?
B044C002V009	44	2	9	Some of us are Parthians, some Medes, some Elamites; and some of us live in Mesopotamia, in Judea and Cappadocia, in Pontus and Roman Asia,
B044C002V010	44	2	10	in Phrygia and Pamphylia, in Egypt and the districts of Libya adjoining Cyrene; some of us are visitors from Rome,
B044C002V011	44	2	11	either Jews by birth or converts, and some are Cretans and Arabians — yet we all alike hear them speaking in our own tongues of the great things that God has done.”
B044C002V012	44	2	12	They were all utterly amazed and bewildered.  “What does it mean?” they asked one another.
B044C002V013	44	2	13	But there were some who said with a sneer: “They have had too much new wine.”  
B044C002V014	44	2	14	Then Peter, surrounded by the eleven other apostles, stood up, and, raising his voice, addressed the crowd. “People of Judea,” he began, “and all you who are staying in Jerusalem, let me tell you what this means. Mark well my words.
B044C002V015	44	2	15	These people are not drunk, as you suppose; for it is only now nine in the morning! No!
B044C002V016	44	2	16	This is what is spoken of in the prophet Joel —
B044C002V017	44	2	17	‘It will come about in the last days,’ God says,‘That I will pour out my Spirit on all humanity;Your sons and your daughters will become prophets,Your young men will see visions,And your old men dream dreams;
B044C002V018	44	2	18	Yes, even on the slaves — for they are mine — both men and women,I will in those days pour out my Spirit,And they will become prophets;
B044C002V019	44	2	19	And I will show wonders in the heavens above,And signs on the earth below —Blood and fire and mist of smoke;
B044C002V020	44	2	20	The sun will become darkness,And the moon blood-red,Before the day of the Lord comes — that great and awful day.
B044C002V021	44	2	21	Then will everyone who invokes the name of the Lord be saved.’
B044C002V022	44	2	22	People of Israel, listen to what I am saying. Jesus of Nazareth, a man whose mission from God to you was proved by miracles, wonders, and signs, which God showed among you through him, as you know full well —
B044C002V023	44	2	23	He, I say, in accordance with God’s definite plan and with his previous knowledge, was betrayed, and you, by the hands of lawless men, nailed him to a cross and put him to death.
B044C002V024	44	2	24	But God released him from the pangs of death and raised him to life, it being impossible for death to retain its hold on him.
B044C002V025	44	2	25	Indeed he was the one David was referring to when he said —  ‘I have had the Lord ever before my eyes,For he stands at my right hand, so that I should not be disquieted.
B044C002V026	44	2	26	Therefore my heart was cheered, and my tongue told its delight;Yes, even my body, too, will rest in hope;
B044C002V027	44	2	27	For you will not abandon my soul to the place of death,Nor surrender me, your holy one, to undergo corruption.
B044C002V028	44	2	28	You have shown me the path to life,You will fill me with gladness in your presence.’
B044C002V029	44	2	29	Friends, I can speak to you the more confidently about the patriarch David, because he is dead and buried, and his tomb is here among us to this very day.
B044C002V030	44	2	30	David, then, prophet as he was, knowing that God ‘had solemnly sworn to him to set one of his descendants on his throne,’ looked into the future,
B044C002V031	44	2	31	and referred to the resurrection of the Christ when he said that ‘he had not been abandoned to the place of death, nor had his body undergone corruption.’
B044C002V032	44	2	32	It was this Jesus, whom God raised to life; and of that we are ourselves all witnesses.
B044C002V033	44	2	33	And now that he has been exalted to the right hand of God, and has received from the Father the promised gift of the Holy Spirit, he has begun to pour out that gift, as you yourselves now see and hear.
B044C002V034	44	2	34	It was not David who went up into heaven; for he himself says —  ‘The Lord said to my master: “Sit on my right hand,
B044C002V035	44	2	35	Until I put your enemies as a footstool under your feet.”’
B044C002V036	44	2	36	So let the whole nation of Israel know beyond all doubt, that God has made him both Lord and Christ — this Jesus whom you crucified.”  
B044C002V037	44	2	37	When the people heard this, they were conscience-smitten, and said to Peter and the rest of the apostles: “Friends, what can we do?”  
B044C002V038	44	2	38	“Repent,” answered Peter, “and be baptized every one of you in the faith of Jesus Christ for the forgiveness of your sins; and then you will receive the gift of the Holy Spirit.
B044C002V039	44	2	39	For the promise is for you and for your children, and also for all those now far away, who may be called by the Lord our God.”  
B044C002V040	44	2	40	Peter spoke to them for a long time using many other arguments and pleaded with them — “Save yourselves from the perverse spirit of this age.”
B044C002V041	44	2	41	So those who accepted his teaching were baptized, and about three thousand people joined the disciples on that day alone.
B044C002V042	44	2	42	They devoted themselves to the teaching of the apostles and to the Common life of the church, to the breaking of the bread and to the Prayers.  
B044C002V043	44	2	43	A deep impression was made on everyone, and many wonders and signs were done at the hands of the apostles.
B044C002V044	44	2	44	All who became believers in Christ held everything for the common use;
B044C002V045	44	2	45	they sold their property and their goods, and shared the proceeds among them all, according to their individual needs.
B044C002V046	44	2	46	Every day they devoted themselves to meeting together in the Temple Courts, and to the breaking of bread at their homes, while they partook of their food in simple-hearted gladness, praising God, and winning the goodwill of all the people.
B044C002V047	44	2	47	And the Lord daily added to their company those who were in the path of salvation.  
B044C003V001	44	3	1	One day, as Peter and John were going up into the Temple Courts for the three o’clock Prayers, a man, who had been lame from his birth, was being carried by.
B044C003V002	44	3	2	This man used to be set down every day at the gate of the Temple called ‘the Beautiful Gate,’ to beg of those who went in.
B044C003V003	44	3	3	Seeing Peter and John on the point of entering, he asked them to give him something.
B044C003V004	44	3	4	Peter fixed his eyes on him, and so did John, and then Peter said: “Look at us.”
B044C003V005	44	3	5	The man was all attention, expecting to get something from them;
B044C003V006	44	3	6	but Peter added: “I have no gold or silver, but I give you what I have. In the name of Jesus Christ of Nazareth, get up and walk.”
B044C003V007	44	3	7	Grasping the lame man by the right hand, Peter lifted him up. Instantly the man’s feet and ankles became strong,
B044C003V008	44	3	8	and, leaping up, he stood and began to walk about, and then went with them into the Temple Courts, walking, and leaping, and praising God.
B044C003V009	44	3	9	All the people saw him walking about and praising God;
B044C003V010	44	3	10	and, when they recognised him as the man who used to sit begging at the Beautiful Gate of the Temple, they were utterly astonished and amazed at what had happened to him.
B044C003V011	44	3	11	While the man still clung to Peter and John, the people all quickly gathered round them in the Colonnade named after Solomon, in the greatest astonishment.  
B044C003V012	44	3	12	On seeing this, Peter said to the people: “People of Israel, why are you surprised at this? And why do you stare at us, as though we, by any power or piety of our own, had enabled this man to walk?
B044C003V013	44	3	13	The God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, the God of our ancestors, has done honour to his servant Jesus — him whom you gave up and disowned before Pilate, when he had decided to set him free.
B044C003V014	44	3	14	You, I say, disowned the holy and righteous one, and asked for the release of a murderer!
B044C003V015	44	3	15	The guide to life you put to death! But God raised him from the dead — and of that we are ourselves witnesses.
B044C003V016	44	3	16	And it is by faith in the name of Jesus, that this man, whom you all see and know, has — by his name — been made strong. Yes, it is the faith inspired by Jesus that has made this complete cure of the man, before the eyes of you all.
B044C003V017	44	3	17	And yet, my friends, I know that you acted as you did from ignorance, and your rulers also.
B044C003V018	44	3	18	But it was in this way that God fulfilled all that he had long ago foretold, as to the sufferings of his Christ, by the lips of all the prophets.
B044C003V019	44	3	19	Therefore, repent and turn so that your sins may be wiped away; so that happier times may come from the Lord himself,
B044C003V020	44	3	20	and so that he may send you, in Jesus, your long-appointed Christ.
B044C003V021	44	3	21	But heaven must be his home, until the days of the Universal Restoration, of which God has spoken by the lips of his holy prophets from the very first.
B044C003V022	44	3	22	Moses himself said —  ‘The Lord your God will raise up from among yourselves a prophet, as he raised me. To him you will listen whenever he speaks to you.
B044C003V023	44	3	23	And it will be that should anyone among the people not listen to that prophet, he will be utterly destroyed.’
B044C003V024	44	3	24	Yes, and all the prophets from Samuel onwards, and all their successors who had a message to deliver, told of these days.
B044C003V025	44	3	25	You yourselves are the heirs of the prophets, and heirs, too, of the covenant which God made with your ancestors, when he said to Abraham —  ‘In your descendants will all the nations of the earth be blessed.’
B044C003V026	44	3	26	For you, first, God raised up his servant, and sent him to bless you, by turning each one of you from his wicked ways.”  
B044C004V001	44	4	1	While Peter and John were still speaking to the people, the chief priest, with the officer in charge at the Temple and the Sadducees, came up to them,
B044C004V002	44	4	2	much annoyed because they were teaching the people, and because, through Jesus, they were preaching the resurrection from the dead.
B044C004V003	44	4	3	They arrested the apostles and, as it was already evening, had them placed in custody until the next day.
B044C004V004	44	4	4	Many, however, of those who had heard the apostles’ message became believers in Christ, the number of the men alone amounting to about five thousand.
B044C004V005	44	4	5	The next day, a meeting of the leaders of the people, the councillors, and the teachers of the law was held in Jerusalem.
B044C004V006	44	4	6	There were present Annas the high priest, Caiaphas, John, Alexander, and all who were of High-Priestly rank.
B044C004V007	44	4	7	They had Peter and John brought before them, and questioned them. 
B044C004V008	44	4	8	Then, Peter, filled with the Holy Spirit, said: “Leaders of the people and councillors,
B044C004V009	44	4	9	since we are on our trial today for a kind act done to a helpless man, and are asked in what way the man here before you has been cured,
B044C004V010	44	4	10	let me tell you all and all the people of Israel, that it is by the name of Jesus Christ of Nazareth, whom you crucified and whom God raised from the dead — it is, I say, by his name that this man stands here before you lame no longer.
B044C004V011	44	4	11	Jesus is ‘the stone which, scorned by you the builders, has yet become the corner stone.’
B044C004V012	44	4	12	And salvation is in him alone; for there is no other name in the whole world, given to people, to which we must look for our salvation.”  
B044C004V013	44	4	13	When the Council saw how boldly Peter and John spoke, and found that they were uneducated men of humble station, they were surprised, and realised that they had been companions of Jesus.
B044C004V014	44	4	14	But, when they looked at the man who had been healed, standing there with them, they had nothing to say.
B044C004V015	44	4	15	So they ordered them out of court, and then began consulting together.  
B044C004V016	44	4	16	“What are we to do to these men?” they asked one another. “That a remarkable sign has been given through them is obvious to everyone living in Jerusalem, and we cannot deny it.
B044C004V017	44	4	17	But, to prevent this thing from spreading further among the people, let us warn them not to speak in this name any more to anyone whatever.”  
B044C004V018	44	4	18	So they called the apostles in, and ordered them not to speak or teach in the name of Jesus.  
B044C004V019	44	4	19	But Peter and John replied: “Whether it is right, in the sight of God, to listen to you rather than to him —
B044C004V020	44	4	20	judge for yourselves, for we cannot help speaking of what we have seen and heard.”
B044C004V021	44	4	21	However, after further warnings, the Council set them at liberty, not seeing any safe way of punishing them, because of the people, for they were all praising God for what had occurred;
B044C004V022	44	4	22	for the man who was the subject of this miraculous cure was more than forty years old.  
B044C004V023	44	4	23	After they had been set at liberty, the apostles went to their friends and told them what the chief priests and the councillors had said to them.
B044C004V024	44	4	24	All who heard their story, moved by a common impulse, raised their voices to God in prayer:  “Sovereign Lord, it is you who has ‘made the heavens, the earth, the sea, and everything that is in them,’
B044C004V025	44	4	25	And who, by the lips of our ancestor, your servant David, who spoke under the influence of the Holy Spirit, have said —  ‘Why did the nations rage,And the peoples form vain designs?
B044C004V026	44	4	26	The kings of the earth set their array,And its rulers gathered together,Against the Lord and against his Christ.’
B044C004V027	44	4	27	There have indeed gathered together in this city against your holy servant Jesus, whom you has consecrated the Christ, not Herod and Pontius Pilate only, but the nations and the people of Israel besides —
B044C004V028	44	4	28	Yet only to do what you, by your power and of your own will, did long ago destine to be done.
B044C004V029	44	4	29	Now, therefore, Lord, mark their threats, and enable your servants, with all fearlessness, to tell your message,
B044C004V030	44	4	30	while you stretch out your hand to heal, and cause signs and wonders to take place through the name of your holy servant Jesus.”
B044C004V031	44	4	31	When their prayer was ended, the place in which they were assembled was shaken; and they were all filled with the Holy Spirit, and began to tell God’s message fearlessly.
B044C004V032	44	4	32	The whole body of those who had become believers in Christ were of one heart and mind. Not one of them claimed any of his goods as his own, but everything was held for the common use.
B044C004V033	44	4	33	The apostles continued with great power to bear their testimony to the resurrection of the Lord Jesus, and God’s blessing rested on them all abundantly.
B044C004V034	44	4	34	Nor was there anyone in need among them, for all who were owners of land or houses sold them, and brought the proceeds of the sales
B044C004V035	44	4	35	And laid them at the apostles’ feet; and then everyone received a share in proportion to his wants.
B044C004V036	44	4	36	A Levite of Cyprian birth, named Joseph, (who had received from the apostles the additional name of ‘Barnabas’ — which means ‘The Consoler,’)
B044C004V037	44	4	37	Sold a farm that belonged to him, and brought the money and laid it at the apostles’ feet.
B044C005V001	44	5	1	There was, however, a man named Ananias, who, with his wife Sapphira, sold some property,
B044C005V002	44	5	2	and, with her connivance, kept back some of the proceeds. He brought only a part and laid it at the apostles’ feet.
B044C005V003	44	5	3	“Ananias,” Peter exclaimed, “how is it that Satan has so taken possession of your heart that you have lied to the Holy Spirit, and kept back a part of the money paid for the land?
B044C005V004	44	5	4	While it was unsold, was not it your own? And after it was sold, was not the money at your own disposal? How did you come to think of such a thing? You have lied, not to people, but to God!”  
B044C005V005	44	5	5	As Ananias heard these words, he fell down and expired; and everyone who heard of it was appalled.
B044C005V006	44	5	6	The young men got up, and, winding the body in a sheet, carried it out and buried it.  
B044C005V007	44	5	7	After an interval of about three hours his wife came in, not knowing what had happened.
B044C005V008	44	5	8	“Is it true,” Peter asked, addressing her, “that you sold your land for such a sum?”  “Yes,” she answered, “we did.”
B044C005V009	44	5	9	Then Peter said: “How did you come to agree to provoke the Spirit of the Lord? Listen! The footsteps of those who have buried your husband are at the door; and they will carry you out too.”  
B044C005V010	44	5	10	Instantly Sapphira fell down at Peter’s feet and expired. On coming in, the young men found her dead; so they carried her out and buried her by her husband’s side.
B044C005V011	44	5	11	The whole church and all who heard of these events were appalled.  
B044C005V012	44	5	12	Many signs and wonders continued to occur among the people, through the instrumentality of the apostles, whose custom it was to meet all together in the Colonnade of Solomon;
B044C005V013	44	5	13	but of the rest no one ventured to join them. On the other hand, the people were full of their praise,
B044C005V014	44	5	14	and still larger numbers, both of men and women, as they became believers in the Lord, were added to their number.
B044C005V015	44	5	15	The consequence was that people would bring out their sick even into the streets, and lay them on mattresses and mats, in the hope that, as Peter came by, at least his shadow might fall on some one of them.
B044C005V016	44	5	16	Besides this, the inhabitants of the towns round Jerusalem flocked into the city, bringing with them their sick and those who were troubled by foul spirits; and they were cured everyone.
B044C005V017	44	5	17	At this the high priest was roused to action, and he and all his supporters (who formed the party of the Sadducees), moved by jealousy,
B044C005V018	44	5	18	arrested the apostles, and had them placed in custody.
B044C005V019	44	5	19	An angel of the Lord, however, opened the prison doors at night and led them out.
B044C005V020	44	5	20	“Go,” he said, “and stand in the Temple Courts, and tell the people the whole message of this new life.”
B044C005V021	44	5	21	When they heard this, they went at daybreak into the Temple Courts, and began to teach. The high priest and his party, on their arrival, summoned the High Council, including all the leaders of the people among the Israelites, and sent to the jail to fetch the apostles.
B044C005V022	44	5	22	But, when the officers got there, they did not find them in the prison; so they returned and reported that,
B044C005V023	44	5	23	while they had found the goal barred securely and the guards posted at the doors, yet, on opening them, they had not found anyone inside.
B044C005V024	44	5	24	When the officer in charge at the Temple and the chief priests heard their story, they were perplexed about the apostles and as to what all this would lead to.
B044C005V025	44	5	25	Presently, however, some one came and told them, that the men whom they had put in prison were actually standing in the Temple Courts, teaching the people.
B044C005V026	44	5	26	Then, the officer went with his men and fetched the apostles — without using violence, for they were afraid of being stoned by the people —
B044C005V027	44	5	27	And then brought them before the Council. The high priest demanded an explanation from them.
B044C005V028	44	5	28	“We gave you strict orders,” he said, “not to teach in this name. Yet you have actually flooded Jerusalem with your teaching, and you want to make us responsible for the death of this man.”  
B044C005V029	44	5	29	To this Peter and the apostles replied: “We must obey God rather than people.
B044C005V030	44	5	30	The God of our ancestors raised Jesus, whom you put to death by hanging him on a cross.
B044C005V031	44	5	31	It is this Jesus whom God has exalted to his right hand, to be a guide and a Saviour, to give Israel repentance and forgiveness of sins.
B044C005V032	44	5	32	And we are witness to the truth of this, and so is the Holy Spirit — the gift of God to those who obey him.”  
B044C005V033	44	5	33	The members of the Council became frantic with rage on hearing this, and were for putting the apostles to death.
B044C005V034	44	5	34	But Gamaliel, a Pharisee, who was a Doctor of the law and who was held in universal respect, rose in the Council, and directed that the men should be taken out of court for a little while.  
B044C005V035	44	5	35	He then said: “People of Israel, take care as to what you intend to do with these men.
B044C005V036	44	5	36	For not long ago Theudas appeared, professing to be somebody, and was joined by a body of some four hundred men. But he was killed; and all his followers scattered and dwindled away.
B044C005V037	44	5	37	After him, Judas the Galilean appeared at the time of the census, and induced people to follow him; Yet he, too, perished and all his followers were dispersed.
B044C005V038	44	5	38	And, in this present case, my advice to you is not to interfere with these men, but to let them alone, for, if their designs and their work are merely of human origin, they will come to an end;
B044C005V039	44	5	39	but, if they are of divine origin, you will be powerless to put an end to them — or else you may find yourselves fighting against God!”  
B044C005V040	44	5	40	The Council followed his advice, and, calling the apostles in, had them flogged, and then, after cautioning them not to speak in the name of Jesus, set them free.
B044C005V041	44	5	41	But the apostles left the Council, rejoicing that they had been thought worthy to suffer disgrace for that name;
B044C005V042	44	5	42	and never for a single day, either in the Temple Courts or in private houses, did they cease to teach, or to tell the good news of Jesus, the Christ.  
B044C006V001	44	6	1	About this time, when the number of the disciples was constantly increasing, complaints were made by the Greek speaking Jews against the Aramaic speaking Jews, that their widows were being overlooked in the daily distribution.
B044C006V002	44	6	2	The Twelve, therefore, called together the general body of the disciples and said to them: “It is not well for us to see to the distribution at the tables and neglect God’s message.
B044C006V003	44	6	3	Therefore, friends, look for seven men of reputation among yourselves, wise and spiritually-minded men, and we will appoint them to attend to this matter;
B044C006V004	44	6	4	while we, for our part, will devote ourselves to prayer, and to the delivery of the message.”
B044C006V005	44	6	5	This proposal was unanimously agreed to; and the disciples chose Stephen — a man full of faith and of the Holy Spirit — and Philip, Prochorus, Nicanor, Timon, Parmenas, and Nicholas of Antioch, a former convert to Judaism;
B044C006V006	44	6	6	and they brought these men to the apostles, who, after praying, placed their hands on them.  
B044C006V007	44	6	7	So God’s message spread, and the number of the disciples continued to increase rapidly in Jerusalem, and a large body of the priests accepted the faith.
B044C006V008	44	6	8	Meanwhile Stephen, divinely helped and strengthened, was showing great wonders and signs among the people.
B044C006V009	44	6	9	But some members of the Synagogue of the Freed Slaves (as it was called), Cyrenians, Alexandrians, and Visitors from Cilicia and Roman Asia, were roused to action and began disputing with Stephen;
B044C006V010	44	6	10	yet they were quite unable to withstand the wisdom and the inspiration with which he spoke.
B044C006V011	44	6	11	Then they induced some men to assert that they had heard Stephen saying blasphemous things against Moses, and against God;
B044C006V012	44	6	12	and they stirred up the people, as well as the councillors and the teachers of the law, and set on Stephen, and arrested him, and brought him before the High Council.
B044C006V013	44	6	13	There they produced witnesses who gave false evidence.  “This man,” they said, “is incessantly saying things against this Holy place and the law;
B044C006V014	44	6	14	indeed, we have heard him declare that this Jesus of Nazareth will destroy this place, and change the customs handed down to us by Moses.”
B044C006V015	44	6	15	The eyes of all the members of the Council were riveted on Stephen, and they saw his face looking like the face of an angel.  
B044C007V001	44	7	1	Then the high priest asked: “Is this true?”
B044C007V002	44	7	2	Stephen replied: “Brothers and fathers, hear what I have to say. God, who manifests himself in the glory, appeared to our ancestor Abraham when he was in Mesopotamia, and before he settled in Haran, and said to him —
B044C007V003	44	7	3	‘Leave your country and your kindred, and come into the country that I will show you.’
B044C007V004	44	7	4	And so Abraham left the country of the Chaldaeans and settled in Haran; and from there, after his father’s death, God caused him to migrate into this country, in which you are now living.
B044C007V005	44	7	5	God did not at that time give him any part of it, not even a foot of ground. But he promised to ‘give him possession of it and his descendants after him, though at that time he had no child.
B044C007V006	44	7	6	God’s words were these — ‘Abraham’s descendants will live in a foreign country, where they will be enslaved and ill-treated for four hundred years.
B044C007V007	44	7	7	But I myself will judge the nation, to which they will be enslaved,’ God said, ‘and after that they will leave the country and worship me in this place.’
B044C007V008	44	7	8	Then God made with Abraham the covenant of circumcision; and under it Abraham became the father of Isaac, and circumcised him when he was eight days old; and Isaac became the father of Jacob; and Jacob of the Twelve Patriarchs.
B044C007V009	44	7	9	The Patriarchs, out of jealousy, sold Joseph into slavery in Egypt; but God was with him,
B044C007V010	44	7	10	and delivered him out of all his troubles, and enabled him to win favour and show wisdom before Pharaoh, king of Egypt, who appointed him Governor of Egypt and of his whole household.
B044C007V011	44	7	11	Then a famine spread over the whole of Egypt and Canaan, causing great distress, and our ancestors could find no food.
B044C007V012	44	7	12	Hearing, however, that there was corn in Egypt, Jacob sent our ancestors there on their first visit.
B044C007V013	44	7	13	In the course of their second visit, Joseph revealed himself to his brothers, and his family became known to Pharaoh.
B044C007V014	44	7	14	Then Joseph sent an urgent invitation to his father Jacob and to his relations, seventy-five persons in all;
B044C007V015	44	7	15	and so Jacob went down into Egypt. There he died, and our ancestors also,
B044C007V016	44	7	16	and their bodies were removed to Shechem, and laid in the tomb which Abraham had bought for a sum of money from the sons of Hamor in Shechem.
B044C007V017	44	7	17	As the time drew near for the fulfilment of the promise which God had made to Abraham, the people increased largely in numbers in Egypt,
B044C007V018	44	7	18	until a new king, who knew nothing of Joseph, came to the throne.
B044C007V019	44	7	19	This king acted deceitfully towards our race and ill-treated our ancestors, making them abandon their own infants, so that they should not be reared.
B044C007V020	44	7	20	It was just at this time that Moses was born. He was an exceedingly beautiful child, and for three months was brought up in his own father’s house;
B044C007V021	44	7	21	and, when he was abandoned, the daughter of Pharaoh found him and brought him up as her own son.
B044C007V022	44	7	22	So Moses was educated in all the learning of the Egyptians, and proved his ability both by his words and actions.
B044C007V023	44	7	23	When he was in his fortieth year, he resolved to visit his fellow Israelites;
B044C007V024	44	7	24	and, seeing an Israelite ill-treated, he defended him, and avenged the man, who was being wronged, by striking down the Egyptian.
B044C007V025	44	7	25	He thought his own people would understand that God was using him to save them; but they failed to do so.
B044C007V026	44	7	26	The next day he again appeared on the scene, when some of them were fighting, and tried to make peace between them. ‘Men,’ he said, ‘you are brothers; how is it that you are ill-treating one another?’
B044C007V027	44	7	27	But the man who was ill-treating his fellow workman pushed Moses aside saying — ‘Who made you a ruler and judge over us?
B044C007V028	44	7	28	Do you mean to make away with me as you did yesterday with that Egyptian?’
B044C007V029	44	7	29	At these words Moses took to flight, and became an exile in Midian; and there he had two sons born to him.
B044C007V030	44	7	30	Forty years had passed when there appeared to him, in the desert of Mount Sinai, an angel in a flame of fire in a bush.
B044C007V031	44	7	31	When Moses saw it, he was astonished at the vision; but on his going nearer to look at it more closely, the voice of the Lord was heard to say —
B044C007V032	44	7	32	‘I am the God of your ancestors, the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob.’ Moses trembled, and did not dare to look.
B044C007V033	44	7	33	Then the Lord said to him — ‘Take your sandals off your feet, for the spot where you are standing is holy ground.
B044C007V034	44	7	34	I have seen the oppression of my people who are in Egypt, and heard their groans, and I have come down to deliver them. Come now and I will send you into Egypt.’
B044C007V035	44	7	35	This same Moses, whom they had disowned with the words — ‘Who made you a ruler and a judge?’ was the man whom God sent to be both a ruler and a deliverer, under the guidance of the angel that had appeared to him in the bush.
B044C007V036	44	7	36	He it was who led them out, after he had shown wonders and signs in Egypt, in the Red Sea, and in the desert during forty years.
B044C007V037	44	7	37	This was the Moses who said to the people of Israel — ‘God will raise up for you, from among yourselves, a prophet, as he raised up me.’
B044C007V038	44	7	38	He, too, it was who was present at the assembly in the desert, with the angel who talked to him on Mount Sinai, and with our ancestors, and who received living truths to impart to you.
B044C007V039	44	7	39	Yet our ancestors refused him obedience; more than that, they rejected him, and in their hearts turned back to Egypt,
B044C007V040	44	7	40	while they said to Aaron — ‘Make us Gods who will lead the way for us, since, as for this Moses who has brought us out of Egypt, we do not know what has become of him.’
B044C007V041	44	7	41	That was the time when they made the calf and offered sacrifice to their idol, and held festivities in honour of their own handiwork!
B044C007V042	44	7	42	So God turned from them and left them to the worship of the Starry Host, as is written in the book of the prophets —  ‘Did you offer victims and sacrifices to me, house of Israel,All those forty years in the desert?
B044C007V043	44	7	43	You took with you the tent where Moloch is worshippedAnd the star of the god Rephan —The images which you had made to worship.Therefore I will exile you beyond Babylon.’
B044C007V044	44	7	44	Our ancestors had the tent where they worshipped God in the desert, constructed, just as he who spoke to Moses had directed him to make it, after the model which he had seen.
B044C007V045	44	7	45	This tent, which was handed down to them, was brought into this country by our ancestors who accompanied Joshua (at the conquest of the nations that God drove out before their advance), and remained here until the time of David.
B044C007V046	44	7	46	David found favour with God, and prayed that he might provide the God of Jacob with a place to reside.
B044C007V047	44	7	47	But it was Solomon who built a house for God.
B044C007V048	44	7	48	Yet it is not in buildings made by hands that the Most High dwells. As the prophet says —
B044C007V049	44	7	49	‘The heavens are a throne for me,And the earth a stool for my feet.What manner of house will you build me, saith the Lord,Or what place is there where I may rest?
B044C007V050	44	7	50	Was it not my hand that made all these things?’
B044C007V051	44	7	51	Stubborn race, heathen in heart and ears, you are for ever resisting the Holy Spirit; your ancestors did it, and you are doing it still.
B044C007V052	44	7	52	Which of the prophets escaped persecution at their hands? They killed those who foretold the coming of the righteous one; of whom you, in your turn, have now become the betrayers and murderers —
B044C007V053	44	7	53	You who received the law as transmitted by angels and yet failed to keep it.”
B044C007V054	44	7	54	As they listened to this, the Council grew frantic with rage, and gnashed their teeth at Stephen.
B044C007V055	44	7	55	He, filled as he was with the Holy Spirit, fixed his eyes intently on the heavens, and saw the glory of God and Jesus standing at God’s right hand.  
B044C007V056	44	7	56	“Look,” he exclaimed, “I see heaven open and the Son of Man standing at God’s right hand!”
B044C007V057	44	7	57	At this, with a loud shout, they stopped their ears and all rushed on him, forced him outside the city,
B044C007V058	44	7	58	and began to stone him, the witnesses laying their clothes at the feet of a young man named Saul.
B044C007V059	44	7	59	And they stoned Stephen, while he cried to the Lord: “Lord Jesus! Receive my spirit!”
B044C007V060	44	7	60	Falling on his knees, he called out loudly: “Lord! Do not charge them with this sin;” and with these words he fell asleep.  
B044C008V001	44	8	1	Saul approved of his being put to death. 
B044C008V002	44	8	2	Some religious men buried Stephen, with loud lamentations for him.
B044C008V003	44	8	3	But Saul began to devastate the church; he entered house after house, dragged out men and women alike, and threw them into prison. 
B044C008V004	44	8	4	Now those who were scattered in different directions went from place to place proclaiming the good news.
B044C008V005	44	8	5	Philip went down to the city of Samaria, and there began to preach the Christ.
B044C008V006	44	8	6	The people, one and all, listened attentively to what Philip told them, when they heard of, and saw, the miracles which he was working.
B044C008V007	44	8	7	For there were many instances of people with foul spirits, where the spirits, with loud screams, came out of them;
B044C008V008	44	8	8	and many who were paralysed or lame were cured, so that there was great rejoicing throughout that city.
B044C008V009	44	8	9	There was staying in the city a man named Simon, who had been practicing magic there and mystifying the Samaritan people, giving himself out to be some great being.
B044C008V010	44	8	10	Everyone, high and low, paid attention to him. ‘This man,’ they used to say, ‘must be that power of God which people call “The Great Power.”’
B044C008V011	44	8	11	And they paid attention to him because they had for a long time been mystified by his magic arts.
B044C008V012	44	8	12	However, when they came to believe Philip, as he told them the good news about the kingdom of God and the name of Jesus Christ, they were baptized, both men and women.
B044C008V013	44	8	13	Even Simon believed, and after his baptism attached himself to Philip, and was in his turn mystified at seeing signs and great miracles constantly occurring.
B044C008V014	44	8	14	When the apostles at Jerusalem heard that the Samaritans had welcomed God’s message, they sent Peter and John to them;
B044C008V015	44	8	15	and they, on their arrival, prayed that the Samaritans might receive the Holy Spirit.
B044C008V016	44	8	16	(As yet the Spirit had not descended on any of them; they had only been baptized into the faith of the Lord Jesus).
B044C008V017	44	8	17	Then Peter and John placed their hands on them, and they received the Holy Spirit.  
B044C008V018	44	8	18	When Simon saw that it was through the placing of the apostles’ hands on them that the Spirit was given, he brought them a sum of money and said:
B044C008V019	44	8	19	“Give me also this power of yours, so that, if I place my hands on anyone, he may receive the Holy Spirit.”  
B044C008V020	44	8	20	“A curse on you and on your money,” Peter exclaimed, “for thinking that God’s free gift can be bought with gold!
B044C008V021	44	8	21	You have no share or part in our message, for your ‘heart is not right with God.’
B044C008V022	44	8	22	Therefore repent of this wickedness of yours, and pray to the Lord, that, if possible, you may be forgiven for such a thought;
B044C008V023	44	8	23	for I see that you have fallen into the ‘bitterness of envy’ and the ‘fetters of sin.’”  
B044C008V024	44	8	24	“Pray to the Lord for me, all of you,” Simon answered, “so that none of the things you have spoken of may happen to me.”  
B044C008V025	44	8	25	Peter and John, having borne their testimony and delivered the Lord’s message, returned to Jerusalem, telling the good news, as they went, in many Samaritan villages.  
B044C008V026	44	8	26	Meanwhile an angel of the Lord had said to Philip: “Set out on a journey southwards, along the road that runs down from Jerusalem to Gaza.” (It is now deserted).
B044C008V027	44	8	27	So Philip set out on a journey; and on his way he came on an official of high rank, in the service of Candace, Queen of the Abyssinians. He was her treasurer, and had been to Jerusalem to worship,
B044C008V028	44	8	28	and was now on his way home, sitting in his carriage and reading the prophet Isaiah.  
B044C008V029	44	8	29	The Spirit said to Philip: “Go up to the carriage over there and keep close to it.”
B044C008V030	44	8	30	So Philip ran up, and he heard the Abyssinian reading the prophet Isaiah.  “Do you understand what you are reading?” he asked.
B044C008V031	44	8	31	“How can I,” the other answered, “unless some one will explain it to me?” and he invited Philip to get up and sit by his side.
B044C008V032	44	8	32	The passage of scripture which he was reading was this —  ‘Like a sheep, he was led away to slaughter,And as a lamb is dumb in the hands of its shearer,So he refrains from opening his lips.
B044C008V033	44	8	33	He was humiliated and justice was denied him.Who will tell the story of his generation?For his life is cut off from earth.’
B044C008V034	44	8	34	“Now,” said the Treasurer, addressing Philip, “tell me, of whom is the prophet speaking? Of himself, or of some one else?”
B044C008V035	44	8	35	Then Philip began, and, taking this passage as his text, told him the good news about Jesus.  
B044C008V036	44	8	36	Presently, as they were going along the road, they came to some water, and the Treasurer exclaimed: “Look! Here is water; what is to prevent my being baptized?”
B044C008V038	44	8	38	So he ordered the carriage to stop, and they went down into the water — both Philip and the Treasurer — and Philip baptized him.
B044C008V039	44	8	39	But, when they came up out of the water, the Spirit of the Lord caught Philip away, and the Treasurer saw no more of him; for he continued his journey with a joyful heart.
B044C008V040	44	8	40	But Philip was found at Ashdod, and, as he went on his way, he told the good news in all the towns through which he passed, until he came to Caesarea.  
B044C009V001	44	9	1	Meanwhile Saul, still breathing murderous threats against the disciples of the Lord, went to the high priest,
B044C009V002	44	9	2	and asked him to give him letters to the Jewish congregations at Damascus, authorising him, if he found there any supporters of the cause, whether men or women, to have them put in chains and brought to Jerusalem.
B044C009V003	44	9	3	While on his journey, as he was nearing Damascus, suddenly a light from the heavens flashed around him.
B044C009V004	44	9	4	He fell to the ground and heard a voice saying to him — 
B044C009V005	44	9	5	“Who are you, Lord?” he asked. the voice answered;
B044C009V006	44	9	6	
B044C009V007	44	9	7	The men traveling with Saul were meanwhile standing speechless; they heard the sound of the voice, but saw no one.
B044C009V008	44	9	8	When Saul got up from the ground, though his eyes were open, he could see nothing. So his men led him by the hand, and brought him into Damascus;
B044C009V009	44	9	9	and for three days he was unable to see, and took nothing either to eat or to drink.  
B044C009V010	44	9	10	Now there was at Damascus a disciple named Ananias, to whom, in a vision, the Lord said:  “Yes, Lord,” he answered.
B044C009V011	44	9	11	said the Lord,
B044C009V012	44	9	12	
B044C009V013	44	9	13	“Lord,” exclaimed Ananias, “I have heard from many people about this man — how much harm he has done at Jerusalem to your people there.
B044C009V014	44	9	14	And, here, too, he holds authority from the chief priests to put in chains all those who invoke your name.”
B044C009V015	44	9	15	But the Lord said to him:
B044C009V016	44	9	16	
B044C009V017	44	9	17	So Ananias went, entered the house, and, placing his hands on Saul, said: “Saul, my brother, I have been sent by the Lord — by Jesus, who appeared to you on your way here — so that you may recover your sight and be filled with the Holy Spirit.”
B044C009V018	44	9	18	Instantly it seemed as if a film fell from Saul’s eyes, and his sight was restored. Then he got up and was baptized,
B044C009V019	44	9	19	and, after he had taken food, he felt his strength return.  Saul stayed for some days with the disciples who were at Damascus,
B044C009V020	44	9	20	and at once began in the Synagogues to proclaim Jesus as the Son of God.
B044C009V021	44	9	21	All who heard him were amazed.  “Is not this,” they asked, “the man who worked havoc in Jerusalem among those that invoke this name, and who had also come here for the express purpose of having such persons put in chains and taken before the chief priests?”
B044C009V022	44	9	22	Saul’s influence, however, kept steadily increasing, and he confounded the Jewish people who lived in Damascus by the proofs that he gave that Jesus was the Christ.  
B044C009V023	44	9	23	After some time some of them laid a plot to kill Saul,
B044C009V024	44	9	24	but it became known to him. They even watched the gates day and night, to kill him;
B044C009V025	44	9	25	but his disciples let him down by night through an opening in the wall, lowering him in a basket.  
B044C009V026	44	9	26	On his arrival in Jerusalem, Saul attempted to join the disciples, but they were all afraid of him, as they did not believe that he was really a disciple.
B044C009V027	44	9	27	Barnabas, however, taking him by the hand, brought him to the apostles, and told them the whole story of how Saul on his journey had seen the Lord, and how the Lord had talked to him, and how in Damascus he had spoken out fearlessly in the name of Jesus.
B044C009V028	44	9	28	After that, Saul remained in Jerusalem, in close intercourse with the apostles; and he spoke fearlessly in the name of the Lord,
B044C009V029	44	9	29	talking and arguing with the Jews of foreign birth, who, however, made attempts to kill him.
B044C009V030	44	9	30	But, when the followers found this out, they took him down to Caesarea, and sent him on his way to Tarsus.  
B044C009V031	44	9	31	And so it came about that the church, throughout Judea, Galilee, and Samaria, enjoyed peace and became firmly established; and, ordering its life by respect for the Lord and the help of the Holy Spirit, it increased in numbers.
B044C009V032	44	9	32	Peter, while traveling from place to place throughout the country, went down to visit the people of Christ living at Lydda.
B044C009V033	44	9	33	There he found a man named Aeneas, who had been bedridden for eight years with paralysis.
B044C009V034	44	9	34	“Aeneas,” Peter said to him, “Jesus Christ cures you. Get up, and make your bed.” Aeneas got up at once;
B044C009V035	44	9	35	and all the inhabitants of Lydda and of the Plain of Sharon saw him, and came over to the Lord’s side.
B044C009V036	44	9	36	At Jaffa there lived a disciple whose name was Tabitha, which is in Greek ‘Dorcas’ — a Gazelle. Her life was spent in doing kind and charitable actions.
B044C009V037	44	9	37	Just at that time she was taken ill, and died; and they had washed her body and laid it out in an upstairs room.
B044C009V038	44	9	38	Jaffa was near Lydda, and the disciples, having heard that Peter was at Lydda, sent two men with the request that he come to them without delay.
B044C009V039	44	9	39	Peter returned with them at once. On his arrival, he was taken upstairs, and all the widows came round him in tears, showing the coats and other clothing which Dorcas had made while she was among them.
B044C009V040	44	9	40	But Peter sent everybody out of the room, and knelt down and prayed. Then, turning to the body, he said: “Tabitha! Stand up.”  She opened her eyes, and, seeing Peter, sat up.
B044C009V041	44	9	41	Giving her his hand, Peter raised her up, and, calling in the widows and others of Christ’s people, presented her to them alive.
B044C009V042	44	9	42	This became known all through Jaffa, and numbers of people came to believe in the Lord.
B044C009V043	44	9	43	And Peter stayed some days at Jaffa with a tanner named Simon.  
B044C010V001	44	10	1	At Caesarea there was a man named Cornelius, a captain in the regiment known as the ‘Italian Regiment,’
B044C010V002	44	10	2	A religious man and one who reverenced God, with all his household. He was liberal in his charities to the people, and prayed to God constantly.
B044C010V003	44	10	3	One afternoon, about three o’clock, he distinctly saw in a vision an angel from God come to him, and call him by name.
B044C010V004	44	10	4	Cornelius fixed his eyes on him and, in great alarm, said: “What is it, Lord?”  “Your prayers and your charities,” the angel answered, “have been an acceptable offering to God.
B044C010V005	44	10	5	And now, send messengers to Jaffa and fetch a man called Simon, who is also known as Peter.
B044C010V006	44	10	6	He is lodging with a tanner named Simon, who has a house near the sea.”  
B044C010V007	44	10	7	When the angel, who had spoken to him, had gone, Cornelius called two servants and a religious soldier, who was one of his constant attendants,
B044C010V008	44	10	8	and, after telling them the whole story, sent them to Jaffa.  
B044C010V009	44	10	9	On the next day, while these men were on their way, just as they were nearing the town, Peter went up on the housetop about midday to pray.
B044C010V010	44	10	10	He became hungry and wanted something to eat; but while it was being prepared, he fell into a trance,
B044C010V011	44	10	11	and saw that the heavens were open, and that something like a great sail was descending, let down by its four corners towards the earth.
B044C010V012	44	10	12	In it were all kinds of quadrupeds, reptiles, and birds.
B044C010V013	44	10	13	Then he was aware of a voice which said — 
B044C010V014	44	10	14	“No, Lord, I cannot,” answered Peter, “for I have never eaten anything ‘defiled’ and ‘unclean’.”
B044C010V015	44	10	15	Again he was aware of a voice which said —
B044C010V016	44	10	16	This happened three times, and then suddenly it was all taken up into the heavens.  
B044C010V017	44	10	17	While Peter was still perplexed as to the meaning of the vision that he had seen, the men sent by Cornelius, having enquired the way to Simon’s house, came up to the gate,
B044C010V018	44	10	18	and called out and asked if the Simon, who was also known as Peter, was lodging there.
B044C010V019	44	10	19	Peter was still pondering over the vision, when the Spirit said to him: “There are two men looking for you at this moment.
B044C010V020	44	10	20	Go down at once and do not hesitate to go with them, for I have sent them.”  
B044C010V021	44	10	21	Peter went down to the men and said: “I am the person you are looking for. What is your reason for coming?”  
B044C010V022	44	10	22	The men replied: “Our captain, Cornelius, a pious man who reverences God and is well spoken of by the whole Jewish nation, has been instructed by a holy angel to send for you to his house, and to listen to what you have to say.”
B044C010V023	44	10	23	So Peter invited them in and entertained them.  The next day he lost no time in setting out with them, accompanied by some of the Lord's followers from Jaffa;
B044C010V024	44	10	24	and the day following he entered Caesarea. Cornelius was expecting them, and had invited his relations and intimate friends to meet them.
B044C010V025	44	10	25	So, when Peter entered the city, Cornelius met him, and, throwing himself at Peter’s feet, bowed to the ground.
B044C010V026	44	10	26	Peter, however, lifted him up, saying as he did so: “Stand up, I am only human like yourself.”  
B044C010V027	44	10	27	Talking with him as he went, Peter entered the house, where he found a large gathering of people, to whom he said:
B044C010V028	44	10	28	“You are doubtless aware that it is forbidden for a Jew to be intimate with a foreigner, or even to enter his house; and yet God has shown me that I ought not to call anyone ‘defiled’ or ‘unclean.’
B044C010V029	44	10	29	That was why I came, when I was sent for, without raising any objection. And now I ask your reason for sending for me.”  
B044C010V030	44	10	30	“Just three days ago this very hour,” Cornelius said, “I was in my house, saying the Afternoon Prayers, when a man in dazzling clothing suddenly stood before me.
B044C010V031	44	10	31	‘Cornelius,’ he said, ‘your prayer has been heard, and your charities have been accepted, by God.
B044C010V032	44	10	32	Therefore send to Jaffa, and invite the Simon, who is also known as Peter, to come here. He is lodging in the house of Simon the tanner, near the sea.’
B044C010V033	44	10	33	Accordingly I sent to you at once, and you have been so good as to come. And now we are all here in the presence of God, to listen to all that you have been instructed by the Lord to say.”
B044C010V034	44	10	34	Then Peter began.  “I see, beyond all doubt,” he said, “that ‘God does not show partiality,’
B044C010V035	44	10	35	But that in every nation he who reverences him and does what is right is acceptable to him.
B044C010V036	44	10	36	God has sent his message to the Israelites and told them, through Jesus Christ, the good news of peace — and Jesus is Lord of all!
B044C010V037	44	10	37	You yourselves know the story which spread through all Judea, how, beginning form Galilee, after the baptism which John proclaimed —
B044C010V038	44	10	38	The story, I mean, of Jesus of Nazareth, and how God consecrated him his Christ by enduing him with the Holy Spirit and with power; and how he went about doing good and curing all who were under the power of the devil, because God was with him.
B044C010V039	44	10	39	We are ourselves, too, witnesses to all that he did in Judea and in Jerusalem; yet they put him to death by hanging him on a cross!
B044C010V040	44	10	40	This Jesus God raised on the third day, and enabled him to appear,
B044C010V041	44	10	41	not indeed to everyone, but to witnesses chosen beforehand by God — to us, who ate and drank with him after his resurrection from the dead.
B044C010V042	44	10	42	Further, God charged us to proclaim to the people, and solemnly affirm, that it is Jesus who has been appointed by God judge of the living and the dead.
B044C010V043	44	10	43	To him it is that all the prophets bear witness, when they say that everyone who believes in him receives through his name forgiveness of sins.”  
B044C010V044	44	10	44	Before Peter had finished saying these words, the Holy Spirit fell on all who were listening to the message.
B044C010V045	44	10	45	Those converts from Judaism, who had come with Peter, were amazed that the gift of the Holy Spirit had been bestowed even on the Gentiles;
B044C010V046	44	10	46	for they heard them speaking with ‘tongues’ and extolling God. At this Peter asked:
B044C010V047	44	10	47	“Can anyone refuse the water for the baptism of these people, now that they have received the Holy Spirit as we did ourselves?”
B044C010V048	44	10	48	And he directed that they should be baptized in the faith of Jesus Christ; after which they asked him to stay there a few days longer.  
B044C011V001	44	11	1	The apostles and the followers throughout Judea heard that even the Gentiles had welcomed God’s message.
B044C011V002	44	11	2	But, when Peter went up to Jerusalem, those who were converts from Judaism began to attack him,
B044C011V003	44	11	3	on the ground that he had visited people who were not circumcised, and had taken meals with them.
B044C011V004	44	11	4	So Peter began to relate the facts to them as they had occurred.
B044C011V005	44	11	5	“I was in the town of Jaffa,” he said, “and was praying; and, while in a trance, I saw a vision. There was something like a great sail descending, let down by its four corners out of the heavens; and it came right down to me.
B044C011V006	44	11	6	Looking intently at it, I began to distinguish quadrupeds, wild beasts, reptiles, and birds;
B044C011V007	44	11	7	and I also heard a voice saying to me —
B044C011V008	44	11	8	‘No, Lord, I cannot,’ I answered, ‘for nothing ‘defiled’ or ‘unclean’ has ever passed my lips.’
B044C011V009	44	11	9	Then a second time there came a voice from the heavens. it said,
B044C011V010	44	11	10	This happened three times, and then all was drawn up again into the heavens.
B044C011V011	44	11	11	At that moment three men, who had been sent from Caesarea to see me, came up to the house in which we were.
B044C011V012	44	11	12	The Spirit told me to go with them without hesitation. These six companions also went with me. And, when we came into the man’s house,
B044C011V013	44	11	13	he told us how he had seen the angel standing in his house, and how the angel had said to him — ‘Send to Jaffa and fetch the Simon, who is also known as Peter;
B044C011V014	44	11	14	for he will tell you truths, which will prove the means of salvation to you and all your household.’
B044C011V015	44	11	15	I had but just begun to speak,” continued Peter, “when the Holy Spirit fell on them, exactly as on us at the first;
B044C011V016	44	11	16	and I recalled the saying of the Master —
B044C011V017	44	11	17	Since then, God had given them the very same gift as he gave us when we became believers in Jesus Christ the Master — who was I that I could thwart God?”
B044C011V018	44	11	18	On hearing this statement, they said no more, but broke out into praise of God. “So even to the Gentiles,” they exclaimed, “God has granted the repentance which leads to life!”  
B044C011V019	44	11	19	Now those who had been scattered in different directions, in consequence of the persecution that followed the death of Stephen, went as far as Phoenicia, Cyprus, and Antioch, telling the message — but only to Jews.
B044C011V020	44	11	20	Some of them, however, who were men of Cyprus and Cyrene, on coming to Antioch, addressed themselves also to the Jews of foreign birth, telling them the good news about that Lord Jesus.
B044C011V021	44	11	21	The power of the Lord was with them, so that a great number who had learned to believe came over to the Lord’s side.
B044C011V022	44	11	22	The news about them reached the ears of the church at Jerusalem, and they sent Barnabas to Antioch.
B044C011V023	44	11	23	On coming there he saw to his great joy these tokens of the loving kindness of God, and encouraged them all to make up their minds to be faithful to the Lord —
B044C011V024	44	11	24	For Barnabas was a good man and full of the Holy Spirit and of faith — and a large number of people took their stand on the Lord’s side.
B044C011V025	44	11	25	Afterwards Barnabas left for Tarsus to look for Saul;
B044C011V026	44	11	26	and, when he had found him, he brought him to Antioch. And so it came about that, for a whole year, they attended the meetings of the church there, and taught a large number of people; and it was in Antioch that the disciples were first called ‘Christians.’
B044C011V027	44	11	27	During this time, some prophets came to Antioch from Jerusalem.
B044C011V028	44	11	28	One of them, named Agabus, came forward and, under the influence of the Spirit, foretold a great famine that was to spread over all the world — a famine which occurred in the reign of Claudius.
B044C011V029	44	11	29	So the disciples, without exception, determined, in proportion to their means, to send something to help the followers living in Judea.
B044C011V030	44	11	30	And this they did, sending it to the officers of the church by the hands of Barnabas and Saul.
B044C012V001	44	12	1	It was at that time that King Herod began to ill-treat some of the members of the church.
B044C012V002	44	12	2	He had James, the brother of John, beheaded;
B044C012V003	44	12	3	and, when he saw that the Jews were pleased with this, he proceeded to arrest Peter also. (This was during the Festival of the unleavened bread.)
B044C012V004	44	12	4	After seizing Peter, Herod put him in prison, and entrusted him to the keeping of four Guards of four soldiers each, intending, after the Passover, to bring him up before the people.
B044C012V005	44	12	5	So Peter was kept in prison, but meanwhile the prayers of the church were being earnestly offered to God on his behalf.
B044C012V006	44	12	6	Just when Herod was intending to bring him before the people, on that very night Peter was asleep between two soldiers, chained to them both, while there were sentries in front of the door, guarding the prison.
B044C012V007	44	12	7	Suddenly an angel of the Lord stood by him, and a light shone in the cell. The angel struck Peter on the side, and roused him with the words: “Get up quickly.”
B044C012V008	44	12	8	The chains dropped from his wrists, and then the angel said: “Put on your girdle and sandals.” When Peter had done so, the angel added: “Throw your cloak round you and follow me.”
B044C012V009	44	12	9	Peter followed him out, not knowing that what was happening under the angel’s guidance was real, but thinking that he was seeing a vision.
B044C012V010	44	12	10	Passing the first Guard, and then the second, they came to the iron gate leading into the city, which opened to them of itself; and, when they had passed through that, and had walked along one street, all at once the angel left him.  
B044C012V011	44	12	11	Then Peter came to himself and said: “Now I know beyond all doubt that the Lord has sent his angel, and has rescued me from Herod’s hands and from all that the Jewish people have been expecting.”
B044C012V012	44	12	12	As soon as he realized what had happened, he went to the house of Mary, the mother of John who was also known as Mark, where a number of people were gathered together, praying.
B044C012V013	44	12	13	On his knocking at the door in the gate, a maidservant, named Rhoda, came to answer it.
B044C012V014	44	12	14	She recognized Peter’s voice, but in her joy left the gate unopened, and ran in, and told them that Peter was standing outside.  
B044C012V015	44	12	15	“You are mad!” they exclaimed. But, when she persisted that it was so, they said: “It must be his spirit!”  
B044C012V016	44	12	16	Meanwhile Peter went on knocking, and, when they opened the gate and saw him, they were amazed.
B044C012V017	44	12	17	Peter signed to them with his hand to be silent, and then told them how the Lord had brought him out of the prison, adding: “Tell James and the others all this.” Then he left the house, and went away to another place.  
B044C012V018	44	12	18	In the morning there was a great stir among the soldiers — what could have become of Peter!
B044C012V019	44	12	19	And, when Herod had made further search for him and failed to find him, he closely questioned the Guard, and ordered them away to execution. Then he went down from Judea to stay at Caesarea.  
B044C012V020	44	12	20	It happened that Herod was deeply offended with the people of Tyre and Sidon, but they went in a body to him, and, having succeeded in winning over Blastus, the Chamberlain, they begged Herod for a reconciliation, because their country was dependent on the king’s for its food supply.
B044C012V021	44	12	21	On an appointed day Herod, wearing his state robes, seated himself on his throne, and delivered an oration.
B044C012V022	44	12	22	The people kept shouting: “It is the voice of God, and not of a person!”  
B044C012V023	44	12	23	Instantly an angel of the Lord struck him, because he did not give God the glory; and he was attacked with worms, and died.
B044C012V024	44	12	24	Meanwhile the Lord’s message kept extending, and spreading far and wide.  
B044C012V025	44	12	25	When Barnabas and Saul had carried out their mission, they returned to Jerusalem, and took with them John, who was also known as Mark.
B044C013V001	44	13	1	Among the members of the church at Antioch there were several prophets and teachers — Barnabas, Simeon who was known by the name of ‘Black’, Lucius of Cyrene, Manaen, foster-brother of Prince Herod, and Saul.
B044C013V002	44	13	2	While they were engaged in the worship of the Lord and were fasting, the Holy Spirit said: “Set apart for me Barnabas and Saul, for the work to which I have called them.”
B044C013V003	44	13	3	Accordingly, after fasting and prayer, they placed their hands on them and dismissed them.
B044C013V004	44	13	4	Barnabas and Saul, sent on this mission, as they were, by the Holy Spirit, went down to Seleucia, and from there sailed to Cyprus.
B044C013V005	44	13	5	On reaching Salamis, they began to tell the message of God in the Jewish Synagogues; and they had John with them as an assistant.
B044C013V006	44	13	6	After passing through the whole island, they reached Paphos, where they found an astrologer who pretended to be a prophet — a Jew by birth, whose name was Barjoshua.
B044C013V007	44	13	7	He was at the court of the Governor, Sergius Paulus, a man of intelligence, who sent for Barnabas and Saul and asked to be told God’s message.
B044C013V008	44	13	8	But Elymas, the astrologer (for that is the meaning of the word), opposed them, eager to divert the Governor’s attention from the faith.
B044C013V009	44	13	9	However, Saul (who is the same as Paul), full of the Holy Spirit, fixed his eyes on him and said:
B044C013V010	44	13	10	“You incarnation of deceit and all fraud! You son of the devil! You opponent of all that is good! Will you never cease to divert ‘the straight paths of the Lord’? Listen!
B044C013V011	44	13	11	The hand of the Lord is on you even now, and you will be blind for a time and unable to see the sun.” Immediately a mist and darkness fell on him, and he went feeling about for some one to guide him.
B044C013V012	44	13	12	When the Governor saw what had happened, he became a believer in Christ, being greatly impressed by the teaching about the Lord.
B044C013V013	44	13	13	After this, Paul and his companions set sail from Paphos and went to Perga in Pamphylia, where John left them and returned to Jerusalem.
B044C013V014	44	13	14	The others went on from Perga and arrived at Antioch in Pisidia. There they went into the synagogue on the Sabbath and took their seats.
B044C013V015	44	13	15	After the reading of the law and the prophets, the synagogue leader sent them this message — “Friends, if you have any helpful words to address to the people, now is the time to speak.”
B044C013V016	44	13	16	So Paul rose and, motioning with his hand, said:  “People of Israel and all here who worship God, hear what I have to say.
B044C013V017	44	13	17	The God of this people Israel chose our ancestors, and during their stay in Egypt increased the prosperity of the people, and then ‘with uplifted arm brought them out from that land.’
B044C013V018	44	13	18	For about forty years ‘he bore with them in the desert’;
B044C013V019	44	13	19	then, after destroying seven heathen nations in Canaan, he allotted their land to this people —
B044C013V020	44	13	20	For about four hundred and fifty years. In later times he gave them Judges, of whom the prophet Samuel was the last.
B044C013V021	44	13	21	And, when they demanded a king, God gave them Saul the son of Kish, a man of the tribe of Benjamin, who reigned for forty years.
B044C013V022	44	13	22	After removing him, he raised David to the throne, and bore this testimony to him — ‘In David, the son of Jesse, I have found a man after my own heart, who will carry out all my purposes.’
B044C013V023	44	13	23	It was from this man’s descendants that God, in accordance with his promise, gave Israel a Saviour — Jesus;
B044C013V024	44	13	24	John having first proclaimed, before the appearance of Jesus, a baptism on repentance for all the people of Israel.
B044C013V025	44	13	25	As John was drawing towards the end of his career, he said what do you suppose that I am? I am not the Christ. But there is “one coming” after me, whose sandal I am not worthy to untie.’
B044C013V026	44	13	26	Brothers and sisters, descendants of Abraham, and all those among you who worship God, it was to us that the message of this salvation was sent.
B044C013V027	44	13	27	The people of Jerusalem and their leaders, failing to recognise Jesus, and not understanding the utterances of the prophets that are read every Sabbath, fulfilled them by condemning him.
B044C013V028	44	13	28	They found no ground at all for putting him to death, and yet demanded his execution from Pilate;
B044C013V029	44	13	29	and, after carrying out everything written about him, they took Jesus down from the cross, and laid him in a tomb.
B044C013V030	44	13	30	But God raised him from the dead;
B044C013V031	44	13	31	and he appeared for many days to those who had gone up with him from Galilee to Jerusalem, and who are now witnesses for him to the people.
B044C013V032	44	13	32	We also have good news to tell you, about the promise made to our ancestors —
B044C013V033	44	13	33	That our children have had this promise completely fulfilled to them by God, by his raising Jesus. That is just what is said in the second Psalm —  ‘You are my Son; this day I have become your Father.’
B044C013V034	44	13	34	As to his raising Jesus from the dead, never again to return to corruption, this is what is said —  ‘I will give to you the sacred promises made to David;’
B044C013V035	44	13	35	And, therefore, in another Psalm it is said —  ‘You will not give up the Holy One to undergo corruption.’
B044C013V036	44	13	36	David, after obediently doing God’s will in his own time, ‘fell asleep and was laid by the side of his ancestors, and did undergo corruption;
B044C013V037	44	13	37	but Jesus, whom God raised from the dead, did not undergo corruption.
B044C013V038	44	13	38	I would, therefore, like you to know, friends, that through Jesus forgiveness of sins is being proclaimed to you,
B044C013V039	44	13	39	and that, in union with him, everyone who believes in him is absolved from every sin from which under the law of Moses you could not be absolved.
B044C013V040	44	13	40	Beware, therefore, that what is said in the prophets does not come true of you —
B044C013V041	44	13	41	‘Look, you despisers, and wonder, and perish;For I am doing a deed in your days —A deed which, though told you in full, you will never believe’.”
B044C013V042	44	13	42	As Paul and Barnabas were leaving the synagogue, the people begged for a repetition of this teaching on the next Sabbath.
B044C013V043	44	13	43	After the congregation had dispersed, many of the Jews, and of the converts who joined in their worship, followed Paul and Barnabas, who talked with them and urged them to continue to rely on the loving kindness of God.  
B044C013V044	44	13	44	On the following Sabbath, almost all the city gathered to hear God’s message.
B044C013V045	44	13	45	But the sight of the crowds of people filled the minds of the Jews with jealousy, and they kept contradicting Paul’s statements in violent language.
B044C013V046	44	13	46	Then Paul and Barnabas spoke out fearlessly, and said:  “It was necessary that the message of God should be told to you first; but, since you reject it and reckon yourselves not worthy of the eternal life — we turn to the Gentiles!
B044C013V047	44	13	47	For this is the Lord’s command to us —  ‘I have destined you for a light to the Gentiles,A means of salvation to the ends of the earth’.”
B044C013V048	44	13	48	On hearing this, the Gentiles were glad and extolled God’s message; and all those who had been enrolled for eternal life became believers in Christ;
B044C013V049	44	13	49	and the Lord’s message was carried throughout that district.
B044C013V050	44	13	50	But the Jews incited the women of high social standing who worshiped with them, and the leading men of the town, and started a persecution against Paul and Barnabas, and drove them out of their neighbourhood.
B044C013V051	44	13	51	They, however, shook the dust off their feet in protest,
B044C013V052	44	13	52	and went to Iconium, leaving the disciples full of joy and of the Holy Spirit.  
B044C014V001	44	14	1	The same thing occurred in Iconium, where Paul and Barnabas went into the Jewish synagogue, and spoke in such a way that a great number of both Jews and Greeks believed in Christ.
B044C014V002	44	14	2	But the Jews who refused to believe stirred up the Gentiles, and poisoned their minds against the Lord's followers.
B044C014V003	44	14	3	Therefore Paul and Barnabas spent a long time there, and spoke out fearlessly, relying on the Lord, who confirmed the message of his love by permitting signs and wonders to take place at their hands.
B044C014V004	44	14	4	But the townspeople were divided, some siding with the Jews, some with the apostles;
B044C014V005	44	14	5	and, when there was an attempt on the part of both Gentiles and Jews, with their leaders, to resort to violence and to stone them,
B044C014V006	44	14	6	the apostles heard of it, and took refuge in Lystra and Derbe, towns in Lycaonia, and in the district round,
B044C014V007	44	14	7	and there they continued to tell the good news.
B044C014V008	44	14	8	In the streets of Lystra there used to sit a man who had no power in his feet; he had been lame from his birth, and had never walked.
B044C014V009	44	14	9	This man was listening to Paul speaking, when Paul, looking intently at him, and seeing that he had the faith to be healed,
B044C014V010	44	14	10	said loudly: “Stand upright on your feet.”  The man leaped up, and began walking about,
B044C014V011	44	14	11	and the crowd, seeing what Paul had done, called out in the Lycaonian language: “The Gods have come down to us in human form.”
B044C014V012	44	14	12	So they called Barnabas ‘Zeus,’ and Paul ‘Hermes,’ because he took the lead in speaking;
B044C014V013	44	14	13	and the priest of Zeus-beyond-the-Walls, accompanied by the crowd, brought bullocks and garlands to the gates, with the intention of offering sacrifices.
B044C014V014	44	14	14	But, when the apostles Barnabas and Paul heard of it, they tore their clothes and rushed out into the crowd.  “Friends, why are you doing this?” they shouted.
B044C014V015	44	14	15	“We are only people like yourselves, and we have come with the good news that you should turn away from these follies to a living God, ‘who made the heavens, the earth, the sea, and everything that is in them.’
B044C014V016	44	14	16	In bygone times he permitted all the nations to go their own ways.
B044C014V017	44	14	17	Yet he has not failed to give you, in the good he does, some revelation of himself — sending you from heaven rain and fruitful seasons, and gladdening your hearts with plenty and good cheer.”
B044C014V018	44	14	18	Even with this appeal they could hardly restrain the people from offering sacrifice to them.  
B044C014V019	44	14	19	Presently, however, there came some Jews from Antioch, and Iconium who, after they had won over the people, stoned Paul, and dragged him out of the town, thinking him to be dead.
B044C014V020	44	14	20	But, when the disciples had gathered round him, he got up and went back into the town; the next day he went with Barnabas to Derbe.
B044C014V021	44	14	21	After telling the good news throughout that town, and making a number of converts, they returned to Lystra, Iconium, and Antioch,
B044C014V022	44	14	22	reassuring the minds of the disciples, urging them to remain true to the faith, and showing that it is only through many troubles that we can enter the kingdom of God.
B044C014V023	44	14	23	They also appointed officers for them in every church, and, after prayer and fasting, commended them to the Lord in whom they had learned to believe.
B044C014V024	44	14	24	Paul and Barnabas then went through Pisidia, and came into Pamphylia,
B044C014V025	44	14	25	and, after telling the message at Perga, went down to Attaleia.
B044C014V026	44	14	26	From there they sailed to Antioch — the place where they had been committed to the gracious care of God for the work which they had now finished.
B044C014V027	44	14	27	After their arrival, they gathered the church together, and gave an account of all that God had helped them to do, and especially how he had opened to the Gentiles the door of faith;
B044C014V028	44	14	28	and at Antioch they stayed with the disciples for a considerable time.  
B044C015V001	44	15	1	But certain persons came down from Judea, and began to teach the Lord's followers that, unless they were circumcised, in accordance with the custom required by Moses, they could not be saved.
B044C015V002	44	15	2	This gave rise to a serious dispute, and much discussion, between Paul and Barnabas and these people, and it was therefore settled that Paul and Barnabas and others of their number should go up to Jerusalem, to consult the apostles and officers of the church about the matter under discussion.
B044C015V003	44	15	3	The church, therefore, sent them on their journey, and they made their way through Phoenicia and Samaria, telling the story of the conversion of the Gentiles, to the great joy of all the followers.
B044C015V004	44	15	4	On their arrival at Jerusalem, they were welcomed by the church, as well as by the apostles and the officers, and gave an account of all that God had helped them to do.
B044C015V005	44	15	5	Some of the Pharisees’ party, however, who had become believers in Christ, came forward and declared that they were bound to circumcise converts and to direct them to observe the law of Moses.
B044C015V006	44	15	6	The apostles and the officers of the church held a meeting to consider this question.
B044C015V007	44	15	7	After much discussion, Peter rose and said:  “You, my friends, know well that long ago God singled me out — that through my lips the Gentiles should hear the message of the good news, and become believers in Christ.
B044C015V008	44	15	8	Now God, who reads all hearts, declared his acceptance of the Gentiles, by giving them the Holy Spirit, just as he did to us.
B044C015V009	44	15	9	He made no distinction between them and us, when he purified their hearts by their faith.
B044C015V010	44	15	10	Why, then, do you now provoke God, by putting on the necks of these disciples a yoke which neither our ancestors nor we were able to bear?
B044C015V011	44	15	11	No, it is through the loving kindness of the Lord Jesus that we, just as they do, believe that we have been saved.”  
B044C015V012	44	15	12	Every voice in the assembly was hushed, as they listened to Barnabas and Paul, while they gave an account of all the signs and wonders which God had shown among the Gentiles through them.
B044C015V013	44	15	13	After they had finished speaking, James addressed the Council.  “Friends,” he began, “hear what I have to say.
B044C015V014	44	15	14	Simon has described the manner in which God first visited the Gentiles, in order to take from among them a people to bear his name.
B044C015V015	44	15	15	And that is in harmony with the words of the prophets, where they say —
B044C015V016	44	15	16	‘“After this I will return;And I will rebuild the house of David which has fallen —Its ruins I will rebuild,And will set it up once more;
B044C015V017	44	15	17	That so the rest of mankind may earnestly seek the Lord —Even all the Gentiles on whom my name has been bestowed.”
B044C015V018	44	15	18	Says the Lord, as he does these things, foreknown from of old.’
B044C015V019	44	15	19	In my judgment, therefore, we should not add to the difficulties of those Gentiles who are turning to God,
B044C015V020	44	15	20	but we should write to them to abstain from food that has been polluted by being sacrificed to idols, from impurity, from eating the flesh of strangled animals, and from blood.
B044C015V021	44	15	21	For in every town, for generations past, there have been those who preach Moses, read as he is in the Synagogues every Sabbath.”  
B044C015V022	44	15	22	It was then decided by the apostles and the officers, with the assent of the whole church, to choose some of their number, and send them to Antioch with Paul and Barnabas. Those chosen were Judas (called Barsabas) and Silas, who were leaders among the community.
B044C015V023	44	15	23	They were bearers of the following letter —  ‘The apostles, and the followers who are the officers of the church, send their greetings to the followers of the Lord of Gentile birth in Antioch, Syria, and Cilicia.
B044C015V024	44	15	24	As we had heard that some of our number had upset you by their assertions, and unsettled your minds — without instructions from us —
B044C015V025	44	15	25	We met and decided to choose certain men and send them to you with our dear friends Barnabas and Paul,
B044C015V026	44	15	26	who have risked their lives for the name of our Lord, Jesus Christ.
B044C015V027	44	15	27	We are accordingly sending Judas and Silas, and they will tell you by word of mouth what we are now writing.
B044C015V028	44	15	28	We have, therefore, decided, under the guidance of the Holy Spirit, to lay no further burden on you beyond these necessary conditions —
B044C015V029	44	15	29	That you abstain from food offered to idols, from blood, from eating the flesh of strangled animals, and from impurity. If you guard yourselves against such things, it will be well with you. Farewell.’
B044C015V030	44	15	30	So the bearers of this letter were sent on their way, and went down to Antioch. There they called a meeting of all the followers,
B044C015V031	44	15	31	and delivered the letter, the reading of which caused great rejoicing by its encouraging contents.
B044C015V032	44	15	32	Judas and Silas, who were themselves prophets, further encouraged the them by many an address, and strengthened their faith.
B044C015V033	44	15	33	After some stay, they were dismissed with kind farewells from the followers, and returned to those who had sent them.  
B044C015V035	44	15	35	Paul and Barnabas, however, remained in Antioch, where they taught and, with the help of many others, told the good news of the Lord’s message.
B044C015V036	44	15	36	Some time after this, Paul said to Barnabas: “Let us go back and visit the Lord's followers in every town in which we have told the Lord’s message, and see how they are prospering.”
B044C015V037	44	15	37	Barnabas wished to take with them John, whose other name was Mark;
B044C015V038	44	15	38	but Paul felt that they ought not to take with them the man who had deserted them in Pamphylia, and had not gone on with them to their work.
B044C015V039	44	15	39	This caused such unpleasant feeling between them that they parted ways, Barnabas taking Mark and sailing for Cyprus,
B044C015V040	44	15	40	while Paul chose Silas for his companion and, after he had been committed by the followers to the gracious care of the Lord,
B044C015V041	44	15	41	started on his journey and went through Syria and Cilicia, strengthening the churches in the faith.  
B044C016V001	44	16	1	Among other places Paul went to Derbe and Lystra. At the latter place they found a disciple, named Timothy, whose mother was a Jewess who had become a believer in Christ, while his father was a Greek,
B044C016V002	44	16	2	and who was well spoken of by the followers of the Lord in Lystra and Iconium.
B044C016V003	44	16	3	Wishing to take this man with him on his journey, Paul caused him to be circumcised out of consideration for the Jews in that neighbourhood, for they all knew that his father had been a Greek.
B044C016V004	44	16	4	As they traveled from town to town, they gave the followers the decisions which had been reached by the apostles and officers of the church at Jerusalem, for them to observe.
B044C016V005	44	16	5	So the churches grew stronger in the faith, and increased in numbers from day to day.  
B044C016V006	44	16	6	They next went through the Phrygian district of Galatia, but were restrained by the Holy Spirit from delivering the message in Roman Asia.
B044C016V007	44	16	7	When they reached the borders of Mysia, they attempted to go into Bithynia, but the Spirit of Jesus did not permit them.
B044C016V008	44	16	8	Passing through Mysia, they went down to Troas;
B044C016V009	44	16	9	and there one night Paul saw a vision. A Macedonian was standing and appealing to him — ‘Come over to Macedonia and help us.’
B044C016V010	44	16	10	So, immediately after Paul had seen the vision, we looked for an opportunity to cross over to Macedonia, concluding that God had summoned us to tell the good news to the people there.  
B044C016V011	44	16	11	Accordingly we set sail from Troas, and ran before the wind to Samothrace, reaching Neapolis the next day.
B044C016V012	44	16	12	From there we made our way to Philippi, which is the principal city of that part of Macedonia, and also a Roman Settlement.  In that city we spent several days.
B044C016V013	44	16	13	On the Sabbath we went outside the gate to the riverside, where we supposed there would be a place of prayer; and we sat down and talked to the women who were gathered there.
B044C016V014	44	16	14	Among them was a woman, named Lydia, belonging to Thyatira, a dealer in purple cloth, who was accustomed to join in the worship of God. The Lord touched this woman’s heart, so that she gave attention to the message delivered by Paul,
B044C016V015	44	16	15	and, when she and her household had been baptized, she urged us to become her guests. 
B044C016V016	44	16	16	One day, as we were on our way to the place of prayer, we were met by a girl possessed by a divining spirit, who made large profits for her masters by fortune-telling.
B044C016V017	44	16	17	This girl followed Paul and the rest of us, calling: “These men are servants of the most high God, and they are bringing you news of a way to salvation.”
B044C016V018	44	16	18	She had been doing this for several days, when Paul, much vexed, turned and said to the spirit within her: “In the name of Jesus Christ I command you to leave her.” That very moment the spirit left her.  
B044C016V019	44	16	19	When her masters saw that there was no hope of further profit from her, they seized Paul and Silas, dragged them into the public square to the authorities,
B044C016V020	44	16	20	and took them before the Magistrates.  “These men are causing a great disturbance in our town,” they complained;
B044C016V021	44	16	21	“They are Jews, and they are teaching customs which it is not right for us, as Romans, to sanction or adopt.”  
B044C016V022	44	16	22	The mob rose as one person against them, and the Magistrates stripped them of their clothing and ordered them to be beaten with rods.
B044C016V023	44	16	23	After beating them severely, the Magistrates put them in prison, with orders to the jailer to keep them in safe custody.
B044C016V024	44	16	24	On receiving so strict an order, the Governor put them into the inner cell, and secured their feet in the stocks.
B044C016V025	44	16	25	About midnight, while Paul and Silas were praying and singing hymns to God, and while the prisoners were listening to them,
B044C016V026	44	16	26	suddenly there was an earthquake of such violence that the jail was shaken to its foundations; all the doors flew open, and all the prisoners’ chains were loosened.
B044C016V027	44	16	27	Roused from his sleep, and seeing the prison doors open, the Governor drew his sword intending to kill himself, in the belief that the prisoners had escaped.
B044C016V028	44	16	28	But Paul called our loudly: “Do not harm yourself; we are all here.”  
B044C016V029	44	16	29	Calling for a light, the Governor rushed in, and flung himself trembling at the feet of Paul and Silas.
B044C016V030	44	16	30	Then he led them out, and said: “What must I do to be saved?”  
B044C016V031	44	16	31	“Believe in Jesus, our Lord,” they replied, “and you will be saved, you and your household too.”
B044C016V032	44	16	32	Then they spoke to him of God’s message, and to all his household as well.
B044C016V033	44	16	33	And that very hour of the night he took them and washed their wounds, and he himself and everyone belonging to him were baptized without delay.
B044C016V034	44	16	34	Afterwards he took them up to his house and set before them something to eat, rejoicing that he, with all his household, had come to believe in God.  
B044C016V035	44	16	35	In the morning the Magistrates sent the police with an order for the men to be discharged.
B044C016V036	44	16	36	The jailer told Paul of his instructions. “The Magistrates have sent an order for your discharge,” he said, “so you had better leave the place at once and go quietly away.”  
B044C016V037	44	16	37	But Paul’s answer to them was: “They have flogged us in public without trial, though we are Roman citizens, and they have put us in prison, and now they are for sending us out secretly! No, indeed! Let them come and take us out themselves.”
B044C016V038	44	16	38	The police reported his words to the Magistrates, who, on hearing that Paul and Silas were Roman citizens, were alarmed,
B044C016V039	44	16	39	and went to the prison, and did their best to conciliate them. Then they took them out, and begged them to leave the city.
B044C016V040	44	16	40	When Paul and Silas left the prison, they went to Lydia’s house, and, after they had seen the Lord's followers, and encouraged them, they left the place.  
B044C017V001	44	17	1	After passing through Amphipolis and Apollonia, Paul and Silas came to Thessalonica. Here the Jews had a synagogue;
B044C017V002	44	17	2	and, following his usual custom, Paul joined them, and for three Sabbaths addressed them, drawing his arguments from the scriptures.
B044C017V003	44	17	3	He laid before them and explained that the Christ must undergo suffering and rise from the dead; and “It is this man,” he declared, “who is the Christ — this Jesus about whom I am telling you.”
B044C017V004	44	17	4	Some of the people were convinced, and threw in their lot with Paul and Silas, as did also a large body of Greeks who were accustomed to join in the Jewish services, and a great number of leading women.
B044C017V005	44	17	5	But the Jewish leaders, becoming jealous, engaged some worthless fellows from the streets, and, getting a mob together, kept the city in an uproar. They attacked Jason’s house, with the intention of bringing Paul and Silas before the Popular Assembly;
B044C017V006	44	17	6	and, not finding them there, they proceeded to drag Jason and some of the Lord's followers before the city magistrates, shouting out:  “These men, who have turned the world upside down, have now come here,
B044C017V007	44	17	7	and have been harboured by Jason! They say that some one else is king — a man called Jesus!”  
B044C017V008	44	17	8	On hearing this, the people and the city magistrates were much concerned;
B044C017V009	44	17	9	and, before letting them go, they took bail from Jason and the others.
B044C017V010	44	17	10	That very night the followers sent Paul and Silas off to Beroea; and on reaching that place, they went to the Jewish synagogue.
B044C017V011	44	17	11	These Jews of Beroea were better disposed than those in Thessalonica, for they welcomed the message with great readiness, and daily examined the scriptures to see if what was said was true.
B044C017V012	44	17	12	As a consequence, many of them became believers in Christ, besides a considerable number of Greek women of position, and of men also.
B044C017V013	44	17	13	But, when the Jewish leaders in Thessalonica found out that God’s message had been delivered by Paul at Beroea, they came there too, exciting and disturbing the minds of the people.
B044C017V014	44	17	14	The followers immediately arranged for Paul to go away to the coast, but both Silas and Timothy stayed behind in Beroea.
B044C017V015	44	17	15	The friends who escorted Paul took him as far as Athens, and, after receiving a message for Silas and Timothy to join him as quickly as possible, they started on their return.  
B044C017V016	44	17	16	While Paul was waiting for them at Athens, his heart was stirred at seeing the whole city full of idols.
B044C017V017	44	17	17	So he argued in the synagogue with the Jews and with those who joined in their worship, as well as daily in the public Square with those who happened to be there.
B044C017V018	44	17	18	Among others, some Epicurean and Stoic Philosophers joined issue with him. Some asked “What is this prater wanting to make out?”, while others said “He seems to be a preacher of foreign Deities.” (This was because he was telling the good news about Jesus and the resurrection).
B044C017V019	44	17	19	So they laid hold of him and took him to the Court of Areopagus.  “May we hear,” they asked, “what new teaching this is which you are giving?
B044C017V020	44	17	20	For you are bringing some strange things to our notice, and we should like to know what they mean.”
B044C017V021	44	17	21	(All Athenians and the foreigners staying in the city found no time for anything else but telling, or listening to, the last new thing.)  
B044C017V022	44	17	22	So Paul took his stand in the middle of the Court, and said — “People of Athens, on every hand I see signs of your being very devout.
B044C017V023	44	17	23	For as I was going about, looking at your sacred shrines, I came upon an altar with this inscription — ‘To an Unknown God.’ What, therefore, you worship in ignorance, that I am now proclaiming to you.
B044C017V024	44	17	24	The God who made the world and all things that are in it — he, Lord as he is of heaven and Earth, does not live in temples made by hands,
B044C017V025	44	17	25	neither do human hands minister to his wants, as though he needed anything, since he himself gives, to all, life, and breath, and all things.
B044C017V026	44	17	26	He made all races of the earth’s surface — fixing a time for their rise and fall, and the limits of their settlements —
B044C017V027	44	17	27	That they might search for God, if by any means they might feel their way to him and find him. And yet he is not really far from any one of us;
B044C017V028	44	17	28	for in him we live and move and are. To use the words of some of your own poets —  ‘His offspring, too, are we.’
B044C017V029	44	17	29	Therefore, as the offspring of God, we must not think that the Deity has any resemblance to anything made of gold, or silver, or stone — a work of human art and imagination.
B044C017V030	44	17	30	True, God looked with indulgence on the days of people’s ignorance, but now he is announcing to everyone everywhere the need for repentance,
B044C017V031	44	17	31	because he has fixed a day on which he intends to ‘judge the world with justice,’ by a man whom he has appointed — and of this he has given all people a pledge by raising this man from the dead.”  
B044C017V032	44	17	32	On hearing of a resurrection of the dead, some began jeering, but others said that they wanted to hear what he had to say about that another time.
B044C017V033	44	17	33	And so Paul left the Court.
B044C017V034	44	17	34	There were, however, some people who joined him, and became believers in Christ. Among them were Dionysius, a member of the Court of Areopagus, a woman named Damaris, and several others.  
B044C018V001	44	18	1	On leaving Athens, Paul next went to Corinth.
B044C018V002	44	18	2	There he met a Jew of the name of Aquila, from Pontus, who, with his wife Priscilla, had lately come from Italy, in consequence of the order which had been issued by the Emperor Claudius for all Jews to leave Rome. Paul paid them a visit,
B044C018V003	44	18	3	and, since their trade was the same as his, he stayed and worked with them — their trade was tent-making.
B044C018V004	44	18	4	Every Sabbath Paul gave addresses in the synagogue, trying to convince both Jews and Greeks.
B044C018V005	44	18	5	But, when Silas and Timothy had come down from Macedonia, Paul devoted himself entirely to delivering the message, earnestly maintaining before the Jews that Jesus was the Christ.
B044C018V006	44	18	6	However, as they set themselves against him and became abusive, Paul shook his clothes in protest and said to them: “Your blood be on your own heads. My conscience is clear. From this time forward I will go to the Gentiles.”  
B044C018V007	44	18	7	So he left, and went to the house of a certain Titius Justus, who had been accustomed to join in the worship of God, and whose house was next door to the synagogue.
B044C018V008	44	18	8	Crispus, the synagogue leader, came to believe in the Lord, and so did all his household; and many of the Corinthians, as they listened to Paul, became believers in Christ and were baptized.
B044C018V009	44	18	9	One night the Lord said to Paul, in a vision:
B044C018V011	44	18	11	So he settled there for a year and a half, and taught God’s message among the people.  
B044C018V012	44	18	12	While Gallio was governor of Greece, some of the Jewish leaders made a combined attack on Paul, and brought him before the Governor’s Bench,
B044C018V013	44	18	13	charging him with persuading people to worship God in a way forbidden by the law.
B044C018V014	44	18	14	Just as Paul was on the point of speaking, Gallio said to them:  “If this were a case of misdemeanour or some serious crime, there would be some reason for my listening patiently to you;
B044C018V015	44	18	15	but, since it is a dispute about words, and names, and your own law, you must see to it yourselves. I do not choose to be a judge in such matters.”  
B044C018V016	44	18	16	Saying this, he drove them back from the Bench.
B044C018V017	44	18	17	Then they all set on Sosthenes, the synagogue leader, and beat him in front of the Bench, but Gallio did not trouble himself about any of these things.  
B044C018V018	44	18	18	Paul remained there some time after this, and then took leave of the followers, and sailed to Syria with Priscilla and Aquila, but not before his head had been shaved at Cenchreae, because he was under a vow.
B044C018V019	44	18	19	They put into Ephesus, and there Paul, leaving his companions, went into the synagogue and addressed the Jews.
B044C018V020	44	18	20	When they asked him to prolong his stay, he declined, saying however,
B044C018V021	44	18	21	as he took his leave, “I will come back again to you, please God,” and then set sail from Ephesus.
B044C018V022	44	18	22	On reaching Caesarea, he went up to Jerusalem and exchanged greetings with the church, and then went down to Antioch.
B044C018V023	44	18	23	After making some stay in Antioch, he set out on a tour through the Phrygian district of Galatia, strengthening the faith of all the disciples as he went.  
B044C018V024	44	18	24	Meanwhile there had come to Ephesus an Alexandrian Jew, named Apollos, an eloquent man, who was well-versed in the scriptures.
B044C018V025	44	18	25	He had been well-instructed in the cause of the Lord, and with burning zeal he spoke of, and taught carefully, the facts about Jesus, though he knew of no baptism but John’s.
B044C018V026	44	18	26	This man began to speak out fearlessly in the synagogue; and when Priscilla and Aquila heard him, they took him home and explained the cause of God to him more carefully still.
B044C018V027	44	18	27	When he wanted to cross to Greece, the followers furthered his plans, and wrote to the disciples there to welcome him. On his arrival he proved of great assistance to those who had, through the loving kindness of God, become believers in Christ,
B044C018V028	44	18	28	for he vigorously confuted the Jews, publicly proving by the scriptures that Jesus was the Christ.
B044C019V001	44	19	1	While Apollos was at Corinth, Paul passed through the inland districts of Roman Asia, and went to Ephesus. There he found some disciples, of whom he asked:
B044C019V002	44	19	2	“Did you, when you became believers in Christ, receive the Holy Spirit?” 
B044C019V003	44	19	3	“What then was your baptism?” Paul asked.
B044C019V004	44	19	4	“John’s baptism was a baptism on repentance,” rejoined Paul, “and John told the people (speaking of the ‘one coming; after him) that they should believe in him — that is in Jesus.”  
B044C019V005	44	19	5	On hearing this, they were baptized into the faith of the Lord Jesus,
B044C019V006	44	19	6	and, after Paul had placed his hands on them, the Holy Spirit descended on them, and they began to speak with ‘tongues’ and to preach.
B044C019V007	44	19	7	There were about twelve of them in all.  
B044C019V008	44	19	8	Paul went to the synagogue there, and for three months spoke out fearlessly, giving addresses and trying to convince his hearers, about the kingdom of God.
B044C019V009	44	19	9	Some of them, however, hardened their hears and refused to believe, denouncing the cause before the people. So Paul left them and withdrew his disciples, and gave daily addresses in the lecture-hall of Tyrannus.
B044C019V010	44	19	10	This went on for two years, so that all who lived in Roman Asia, Jews and Greeks alike, heard the Lord’s message.  
B044C019V011	44	19	11	God did miracles of no ordinary kind by Paul’s hands;
B044C019V012	44	19	12	so that people would carry home to the sick handkerchiefs or aprons that had touched his body, and their diseases would leave them and the wicked spirits go out of them.
B044C019V013	44	19	13	An attempt was made by some itinerant Jews, who were exorcists, to use the name of the Lord Jesus over those who had wicked spirits in them.  “I order you,” they would say, “by the Jesus, whom Paul preaches.”
B044C019V014	44	19	14	The seven sons of Sceva, a Jewish chief priest, were doing this;
B044C019V015	44	19	15	but the wicked spirit answered them: “Jesus I acknowledge, and Paul I know, but you — who are you?”  
B044C019V016	44	19	16	Then the man, in whom this wicked spirit was, sprang on them, mastered both of them, and so completely overpowered them, that they fled out of the house, stripped of their clothes, and wounded.
B044C019V017	44	19	17	This incident came to the knowledge of all the Jews and Greeks living at Ephesus; they were all awe-struck, and the name of the Lord Jesus was held in the highest honour.
B044C019V018	44	19	18	Many, too, of those who had become believers in Christ came with a full confession of their practices;
B044C019V019	44	19	19	while a number of people, who had practiced magic, collected their books and burnt them publicly; and on reckoning up the price of these, they found it amounted to fifty thousand silver coins.
B044C019V020	44	19	20	So irresistibly did the Lord’s message spread and prevail.  
B044C019V021	44	19	21	Sometime after these events Paul resolved to go through Macedonia and Greece, and then make his way to Jerusalem. “And after I have been there,” he said, “I must visit Rome also.”
B044C019V022	44	19	22	So he sent to Macedonia two of his helpers, Timothy and Erastus, while he himself stayed for some time longer in Roman Asia.
B044C019V023	44	19	23	Just about that time a great disturbance arose about the cause.
B044C019V024	44	19	24	A silversmith named Demetrius, who made silver models of the shrine of Artemis, and so gave a great deal of work to the artisans,
B044C019V025	44	19	25	got these men together, as well as the workmen engaged in similar occupations, and said:  “Men, you know that our prosperity depends on this work,
B044C019V026	44	19	26	and you see and hear that not only at Ephesus, but in almost the whole of Roman Asia, this Paul has convinced and won over great numbers of people, by his assertion that those Gods which are made by hands are not Gods at all.
B044C019V027	44	19	27	So that not only is this business of ours likely to fall into discredit, but there is the further danger that the Temple of the great Goddess Artemis will be thought nothing of, and that she herself will be deprived of her splendour — though all Roman Asia and the whole world worship her.”  
B044C019V028	44	19	28	When they heard this, the men were greatly enraged, and began shouting — “Great is Artemis of the Ephesians!”
B044C019V029	44	19	29	The commotion spread through the whole city, and the people rushed together into the amphitheater, dragging with them Gaius and Aristarchus, two Macedonians who were Paul’s traveling companions.
B044C019V030	44	19	30	Paul wished to go into the amphitheater and face the people, but the disciples would not let him,
B044C019V031	44	19	31	while some of the chief religious officials of the province, who were friendly to him, sent repeated entreaties to him not to trust himself inside.
B044C019V032	44	19	32	Meanwhile some were shouting one thing and some another, for the Assembly was all in confusion, most of those present not even knowing why they had met.
B044C019V033	44	19	33	But some of the crowd prompted Alexander, whom several of the Jewish leaders had pushed to the front, and he waved his hand to show that he wanted to speak in their defence to the people.
B044C019V034	44	19	34	However, when they recognised him as a Jew, one cry broke from them all, and they continued shouting for two hours — “Great is Artemis of the Ephesians!”  
B044C019V035	44	19	35	When the Recorder had succeeded in quieting the crowd, he said: “People of Ephesus, who is there, I ask you, who needs to be told that this city of Ephesus is the Warden of the Temple of the great Artemis, and of the statue which fell down from Zeus?
B044C019V036	44	19	36	As these are undeniable facts, you ought to keep calm and do nothing rash;
B044C019V037	44	19	37	for you have brought these men here, though they are neither robbers of Temples nor blasphemers of our Goddess.
B044C019V038	44	19	38	If, however, Demetrius and the artisans who are acting with him have a charge to make against anyone, there are court days and there are Magistrates; let both parties take legal proceedings.
B044C019V039	44	19	39	But if you want anything more, it will have to be settled in the regular Assembly.
B044C019V040	44	19	40	For I tell you that we are in danger of being proceeded against for today’s riot, there being nothing to account for it; and in that case we will be at a loss to give any reason for this disorderly gathering.”  
B044C019V041	44	19	41	With these words he dismissed the Assembly.  
B044C020V001	44	20	1	When the uproar had ceased, Paul sent for the disciples, and, with encouraging words, bade them goodbye, and started on his journey to Macedonia.
B044C020V002	44	20	2	After going through those districts and speaking many encouraging words to the disciples, he went into Greece, where he stayed three months.
B044C020V003	44	20	3	He was about to sail to Syria, when he learned that a plot had been laid against him by several of the Jewish leaders; so he decided to return by way of Macedonia.
B044C020V004	44	20	4	He was accompanied by Sopater the son of Pyrrhus, of Beroea, Aristarchus and Secundus from Thessalonica, Gaius of Derbe, and Timothy, as well as by Tychicus and Trophimus of Roman Asia.
B044C020V005	44	20	5	These people went to Troas and waited for us there;
B044C020V006	44	20	6	while we ourselves sailed from Philippi after the Passover, and joined them five days later at Troas, where we stayed for a week.
B044C020V007	44	20	7	On the first day of the week, when we had met for the breaking of bread, Paul, who was intending to leave the next day, began to address those who were present, and prolonged his address until midnight.
B044C020V008	44	20	8	There were a good many lamps in the upstairs room, where we had met;
B044C020V009	44	20	9	and a young man named Eutychus, sitting at the window, was gradually overcome with great drowsiness, as Paul continued his address. At last, quite overpowered by his drowsiness, he fell from the third story to the ground, and was picked up for dead.
B044C020V010	44	20	10	But Paul went down, threw himself on him, and put his arms round him.  “Do not be alarmed,” he said, “he is still alive.”
B044C020V011	44	20	11	Then he went upstairs; and, after breaking and partaking of the bread, he talked with them at great length until daybreak, and then left.
B044C020V012	44	20	12	Meanwhile they had taken the lad away alive, and were greatly comforted.  
B044C020V013	44	20	13	We started first, went on board ship, and sailed for Assos, intending to take Paul on board there. This was by his own arrangement, as he intended to go by land himself.
B044C020V014	44	20	14	So, when he met us at Assos, we took him on board and went on to Mitylene.
B044C020V015	44	20	15	The day after we had sailed from there, we arrived off Chios, touched at Samos the following day, and the next day reached Miletus;
B044C020V016	44	20	16	for Paul had decided to sail past Ephesus, so as to avoid spending much time in Roman Asia. He was making haste to reach Jerusalem, if possible, by the Festival at the close of the Harvest.  
B044C020V017	44	20	17	From Miletus, however, he sent to Ephesus and invited the officers of the church to meet him;
B044C020V018	44	20	18	and, when they came, he said to them: “You know well the life that I always led among you from the very first day that I set foot in Roman Asia,
B044C020V019	44	20	19	serving the Lord, as I did, in all humility, amid the tears and trials which fell to my lot through the plots of some of the Jewish leaders.
B044C020V020	44	20	20	I never shrank from telling you anything that could be helpful to you, or from teaching you both in public and in private.
B044C020V021	44	20	21	I earnestly pointed both Jews and Greeks to the repentance that leads to God, and to faith in Jesus, our Lord.
B044C020V022	44	20	22	And now, under spiritual constraint, I am here on my way to Jerusalem, not knowing what will happen to me there,
B044C020V023	44	20	23	except that in town after town the Holy Spirit plainly declares to me that imprisonment and troubles await me.
B044C020V024	44	20	24	But I count my life of no value to myself, if only I may complete the course marked out for me, and the task that was allotted me by the Lord Jesus — which was to declare the good news of the love of God.
B044C020V025	44	20	25	And now, I tell you, I know that none of you will ever see my face again — you among whom I have gone about proclaiming the kingdom.
B044C020V026	44	20	26	Therefore I declare to you this day, that my conscience is clear in regard to the fate of any of you,
B044C020V027	44	20	27	for I have not shrunk from announcing the whole purpose of God regarding you.
B044C020V028	44	20	28	Be watchful over yourselves, and over the whole flock, of which the Holy Spirit has placed you in charge, to shepherd the church of God, which he won for himself at the cost of his life.
B044C020V029	44	20	29	I know that, after my departure, merciless wolves will get in among you, who will not spare the flock;
B044C020V030	44	20	30	and from among yourselves, too, people will arise, who will teach perversions of truth, so as to draw away the disciples after them.
B044C020V031	44	20	31	Therefore, be on your guard, remembering how for three years, night and day, I never ceased, even with tears, to warn each one of you.
B044C020V032	44	20	32	And now I commend you to the Lord and to the message of his love — a message which has the power to build up your characters, and to give you your place among all those who have become Christ’s people.
B044C020V033	44	20	33	I have never coveted anyone’s gold or silver or clothing.
B044C020V034	44	20	34	You, yourselves, know that these hands of mine provided not only for my own wants, but for my companions also.
B044C020V035	44	20	35	I left nothing undone to show you that, labouring as I laboured, you ought to help the weak, and to remember the words of the Lord Jesus, how he said himself —
B044C020V036	44	20	36	When Paul had finished speaking, he knelt down and prayed with them all.
B044C020V037	44	20	37	All were in tears; and throwing their arms round Paul’s neck, they kissed him again and again,
B044C020V038	44	20	38	grieving most of all over what he had said — that they would never see his face again. Then they escorted him to the ship.
B044C021V001	44	21	1	When we had torn ourselves away and had set sail, we ran before the wind to Cos; the next day we came to Rhodes, and from there to Patara,
B044C021V002	44	21	2	where we found a ship crossing to Phoenicia, and went on board and set sail.
B044C021V003	44	21	3	After sighting Cyprus and leaving it on the left, we sailed to Syria, and put into Tyre, where the ship was to discharge her cargo.
B044C021V004	44	21	4	There we found the disciples and stayed a week with them. Speaking under the influence of the Spirit, they warned Paul not to set foot in Jerusalem.
B044C021V005	44	21	5	However, when we had come to the end of our visit, we went on our way, all the disciples with their wives and children escorting us out of the city. We knelt down on the beach, and prayed,
B044C021V006	44	21	6	and then said goodbye to one another; after which we went on board, and they returned home.
B044C021V007	44	21	7	After we had made the run from Tyre, we landed at Ptolemais, and exchanged greetings with the followers there, and spent a day with them.
B044C021V008	44	21	8	The next day we left, and reached Caesarea, where we went to the house of Philip, the missionary, who was one of ‘the Seven,’ and stayed with him.
B044C021V009	44	21	9	He had four unmarried daughters, who had the gift of prophecy.
B044C021V010	44	21	10	During our visit, which lasted several days, a prophet, named Agabus, came down from Judea.
B044C021V011	44	21	11	He came to see us, and, taking Paul’s girdle, and binding his own feet and hands with it, said: “This is what the Holy Spirit says — ‘The man to whom this girdle belongs will be bound like this by the religious authorities in Jerusalem, and they will give him up to the Gentiles’.”
B044C021V012	44	21	12	When we heard that, we and the people of the place began to entreat Paul not to go up to Jerusalem.  
B044C021V013	44	21	13	It was then that Paul made the reply: “Why are you weeping and breaking my heart like this? For my part, I am ready not only to be bound, but even to suffer death at Jerusalem for the name of the Lord Jesus.”
B044C021V014	44	21	14	So, as he would not be persuaded, we said no more to him, only adding — “The Lord’s will be done.”  
B044C021V015	44	21	15	At the end of our visit, we made our preparations, and started on our way up to Jerusalem.
B044C021V016	44	21	16	Some of the disciples from Caesarea went with us, and brought Mnason with them, a Cypriot disciple of long standing, with whom we were to stay.
B044C021V017	44	21	17	On our arrival at Jerusalem, the followers of the Lord there gave us a hearty welcome;
B044C021V018	44	21	18	and the next day Paul went with us to see James, and all the officers of the church were present.
B044C021V019	44	21	19	After greeting them, Paul related in detail all that God had done among the Gentiles through his efforts;
B044C021V020	44	21	20	and, when they had heard it, they began praising God, and said to Paul:  “You see, brother, that those of our people who have become believers in Christ may be numbered by tens of thousands, and they are all naturally earnest in upholding the Jewish law.
B044C021V021	44	21	21	Now they have heard it said about you, that you teach all of our people in foreign countries to forsake Moses, for you tell them not to circumcise their children or even to observe Jewish customs.
B044C021V022	44	21	22	Well now, as they are certain to hear of your arrival, do what we are going to suggest.
B044C021V023	44	21	23	We have four men here, who have of their own accord put themselves under a vow.
B044C021V024	44	21	24	Join these men, share their purification, and bear their expenses, so that they may shave their heads; and then all will see that there is no truth in what they have been told about you, but that, on the contrary, you yourself rule your life in obedience to the Jewish law.
B044C021V025	44	21	25	As to the Gentiles who have become believers in Christ, we have sent our decision that they should avoid food offered to idols, and blood, and the flesh of strangled animals, and impurity.”  
B044C021V026	44	21	26	Paul joined the men, and the next day shared their purification, and went into the Temple, and gave notice of the expiration of the period of purification when the usual offering should have been made on behalf of each of them.  
B044C021V027	44	21	27	But, just as the seven days were drawing to a close, some of the Jewish people from Roman Asia caught sight of Paul in the Temple, and caused great excitement among all the people present, by seizing Paul and shouting:
B044C021V028	44	21	28	“People of Israel! Help! This is the man who teaches everyone everywhere against our people, our law, and this place; and, what is more, he has actually brought Greeks into the Temple and defiled this sacred place.”
B044C021V029	44	21	29	(For they had previously seen Trophimus the Ephesian in Paul’s company in the city, and were under the belief that Paul had taken him into the Temple.)
B044C021V030	44	21	30	The whole city was stirred, and the people quickly collected, seized Paul, and dragged him out of the Temple, when the doors were immediately shut.
B044C021V031	44	21	31	They were bent on killing him, when it was reported to the officer commanding the garrison, that all Jerusalem was in commotion.
B044C021V032	44	21	32	He instantly got together some officers and soldiers, and charged down on the crowd, who, when they saw the commanding officer and his soldiers, stopped beating Paul.
B044C021V033	44	21	33	Then he went up to Paul, arrested him, ordered him to be doubly chained, and proceeded to inquire who he was, and what he had been doing.
B044C021V034	44	21	34	Some of the crowd said one thing, and some another; and, as he could get no definite reply because of the uproar, he ordered Paul to be taken into the barracks.
B044C021V035	44	21	35	When Paul reached the steps, he was actually being carried by the soldiers, owing to the violence of the mob;
B044C021V036	44	21	36	for the people were following in a mass, shouting out: “Kill him!”  
B044C021V037	44	21	37	Just as he was about to be taken into the Fort, Paul said to the commanding officer: “May I speak to you?”  “Do you know Greek?” asked the commanding officer.
B044C021V038	44	21	38	“Are not you, then, the Egyptian who some time ago raised an insurrection and led the four thousand Bandits out into the wilderness?”  
B044C021V039	44	21	39	“No,” said Paul, “I am a Jew of Tarsus in Cilicia, a citizen of a city of some note; and I beg you to give me permission to speak to the people.”  
B044C021V040	44	21	40	The commanding officer gave his permission, and Paul, standing on the steps, made signs with his hand to the people, and, when comparative silence had been obtained, he said to them in Hebrew:  
B044C022V001	44	22	1	“Brothers and fathers, listen to the defence which I am about to make.”
B044C022V002	44	22	2	When they heard that he was speaking to them in Hebrew, they were still more quiet; and Paul went on:
B044C022V003	44	22	3	“I am a Jew, from Tarsus in Cilicia, but I was brought up in this city under the teaching of Gamaliel, and educated in accordance with the strict system of our ancestral law. I was as zealous in God’s service as any of you who are here today.
B044C022V004	44	22	4	In my persecution of this cause I did not stop even at the taking of life. I put in chains, and imprisoned, men and women alike —
B044C022V005	44	22	5	And to that the high priest himself and all the Council can testify. For I had letters of introduction from them to our fellow Jews at Damascus, and I was on my way to that place, to bring those whom I might find there prisoners to Jerusalem for punishment.
B044C022V006	44	22	6	While I was still on my way, just as I was getting close to Damascus, about midday, suddenly there flashed from the heavens a great light all round me.
B044C022V007	44	22	7	I fell to the ground, and heard a voice saying to me
B044C022V008	44	22	8	‘Who are you, Lord?’ I replied. Then the voice said
B044C022V009	44	22	9	The men with me saw the light, but did not hear the speaker’s voice.
B044C022V010	44	22	10	Then I said ‘What am I to do, Lord?’ The Lord said to me,
B044C022V011	44	22	11	In consequence of that dazzling light I could not see, but my companions held me by the hand, until I reached Damascus.
B044C022V012	44	22	12	There a man named Ananias, a strict observer of our law, well spoken of by all the Jewish inhabitants, came to see me.
B044C022V013	44	22	13	Standing close to me, he said ‘Saul, my brother, recover your sight.’ And then and there I recovered my sight and looked up at him.
B044C022V014	44	22	14	Then he said ‘The God of our ancestors has appointed you to learn his will, and to see the righteous one, and to hear words from his lips;
B044C022V015	44	22	15	for you will be a witness for him to all the world of what you have just seen and heard.
B044C022V016	44	22	16	And now why wait any longer: Be baptized at once, wash away your sins, and invoke his name.
B044C022V017	44	22	17	After my return to Jerusalem, while I was praying one day in the Temple, I fell into a trance,
B044C022V018	44	22	18	and saw Jesus saying to me
B044C022V019	44	22	19	‘Lord,’ I answered, ‘these people know that I used to imprison and scourge, in synagogue after synagogue, those who believed in you;
B044C022V020	44	22	20	and, when the blood of your martyr, Stephen, was being shed, I was myself standing by, approving of his death, and took charge of the clothes of those who were murdering him.
B044C022V021	44	22	21	But Jesus said to me 
B044C022V022	44	22	22	Up to this point the people had been listening to Paul, but at these words they called out: “Kill him! A fellow like this ought not to have been allowed to live!”
B044C022V023	44	22	23	As they were shouting, tearing off their clothes, and throwing dust in the air,
B044C022V024	44	22	24	the commanding officer ordered Paul to be taken into the Fort, and directed that he should be examined under the lash so that he might find out the reason for their outcry against him.  
B044C022V025	44	22	25	But just as they had tied him up to be scourged, Paul said to the captain standing near: “Is it legal for you to scourge a Roman citizen, unconvicted?”
B044C022V026	44	22	26	On hearing this, the captain went and reported it to the commanding officer. “Do you know what you are doing?” he said. “This man is a Roman citizen.”
B044C022V027	44	22	27	So the commanding officer went up to Paul and said: “Tell me, are you a Roman citizen?”  “Yes,” replied Paul.
B044C022V028	44	22	28	“I had to pay a heavy price for my position as citizen,” said the officer. “I am one by birth,” rejoined Paul.  
B044C022V029	44	22	29	The men who were to have examined Paul immediately drew back, and the officer, finding that Paul was a Roman citizen, was alarmed at having put him in chains.  
B044C022V030	44	22	30	On the next day the commanding officer, wishing to find out the real reason why Paul was denounced by the Jewish leaders, had his chains taken off, and directed the chief priests and the whole of the High Council to assemble, and then took Paul down and brought him before them.
B044C023V001	44	23	1	Paul fixed his eyes on the Council, and began:  “Brothers, for my part, I have always ordered my life before God, with a clear conscience, up to this very day.”
B044C023V002	44	23	2	At this, the high priest Ananias ordered the men standing near to strike him on the mouth;
B044C023V003	44	23	3	Paul turned to him and said:  “God will strike you, you whitewashed wall! Are you sitting there to try me in accordance with law, and yet, in defiance of law, order me to be struck?”
B044C023V004	44	23	4	The people standing near said to Paul: “Do you know that you are insulting God’s high priest?”  
B044C023V005	44	23	5	“I did not know, brothers, that it was the high priest,” said Paul, “for scripture says —  ‘Of the Ruler of your people you should speak no ill’.”
B044C023V006	44	23	6	Noticing that some of those present were Sadducees and others Pharisees, Paul called out in the Council: “Brothers, I am a Pharisee and a son of Pharisees. It is on the question of hope for the dead and of their resurrection that I am on my trial.”  
B044C023V007	44	23	7	As soon as he said this, a dispute arose between the Pharisees and the Sadducees; and there was a sharp division of opinion among those present.
B044C023V008	44	23	8	(For Sadducees say there is no such thing as a resurrection, and that there is neither angel nor spirit, while Pharisees believe in both.)
B044C023V009	44	23	9	So a great uproar ensued, and some of the Teaches of the law belonging to the Pharisees’ party stood up and hotly protested: “We find nothing whatever wrong in this man. Suppose a spirit did speak to him, or an angel...”
B044C023V010	44	23	10	The dispute was becoming so violent, that the commanding officer, fearing that Paul would be torn in pieces between them, ordered the Guard to go down and rescue him from them, and take him into the Fort.  
B044C023V011	44	23	11	That night the Lord came and stood by Paul, and said:
B044C023V012	44	23	12	In the morning some Jewish men combined together, and took an oath that they would not eat or drink until they had killed Paul.
B044C023V013	44	23	13	There were more than forty in the plot;
B044C023V014	44	23	14	and they went to the chief priests and the councillors, and said: “We have taken a solemn oath not to touch food until we have killed Paul.
B044C023V015	44	23	15	So we want you now, with the consent of the Council, to suggest to the commanding officer that he should bring Paul down before you, as though you intended to go more fully into his case; but, before he comes here, we will be ready to make away with him.”  
B044C023V016	44	23	16	However, the son of Paul’s sister, hearing of the plot, went to the Fort, and on being admitted, told Paul about it.
B044C023V017	44	23	17	Paul called one of the Captains of the garrison and asked him to take the lad to the commanding officer, as he had something to tell him.
B044C023V018	44	23	18	The captain went with the lad to the commanding officer, and said: “The prisoner Paul called me and asked me to bring this lad to you, as he has something to tell you.”  
B044C023V019	44	23	19	The commanding officer took the lad by the hand, and, stepping aside, asked what it was he had to tell him.
B044C023V020	44	23	20	“Some men have agreed,” answered the lad, “to ask you to bring Paul down before the Council tomorrow, on the plea of your making further inquiry into his case.
B044C023V021	44	23	21	But do not let them persuade you, for more than forty of them are lying in wait for him, who have taken an oath that they will not eat or drink, until they have made away with him; and they are at this very moment in readiness, counting on your promise.”
B044C023V022	44	23	22	The commanding officer then dismissed the lad, cautioning him not to mention to anybody that he had given him that information.
B044C023V023	44	23	23	Then he called two Captains, and ordered them to have two hundred soldiers ready to go to Caesarea, as well as seventy troopers and two hundred lancers, by nine o’clock that night,
B044C023V024	44	23	24	and to have horses ready for Paul to ride, so that they might take him safely to Felix, the Governor.
B044C023V025	44	23	25	He also wrote a letter along these lines:
B044C023V026	44	23	26	‘Claudius Lysias sends his compliments to His Excellency Felix the Governor.
B044C023V027	44	23	27	The man whom I send with this had been seized by some Jews, and was on the point of being killed by them, when I came upon them with the force under my command, and rescued him, as I learned that he was a Roman citizen.
B044C023V028	44	23	28	Wanting to know exactly the ground of the charges they made against him, I brought him before their Council,
B044C023V029	44	23	29	when I found that their charges were connected with questions of their own law, and that there was nothing alleged involving either death or imprisonment.
B044C023V030	44	23	30	Having, however, information of a plot against the man, which was about to be put into execution, I am sending him to you at once, and I have also directed his accusers to prosecute him before you.’
B044C023V031	44	23	31	The soldiers, in accordance with their orders, took charge of Paul and conducted him by night to Antipatris;
B044C023V032	44	23	32	and on the next day, leaving the troopers to go on with him, they returned to the Fort.
B044C023V033	44	23	33	On arriving at Caesarea, the troopers delivered the letter to the Governor, and brought Paul before him.
B044C023V034	44	23	34	As soon as Felix had read the letter, he enquired to what province Paul belonged, and, learning that he came from Cilicia, he said:
B044C023V035	44	23	35	“I will hear all you have to say as soon as your accusers have arrived.” And he ordered Paul to be kept under guard in Herod’s Government house.  
B044C024V001	44	24	1	Five days afterwards the high priest Ananias came down with some of the councillors and a barrister named Tertullus. They laid an information with the Governor against Paul;
B044C024V002	44	24	2	and, when the hearing came on, Tertullus began his speech for the prosecution.
B044C024V003	44	24	3	“We owe it to your Excellency,” he said, “that we are enjoying profound peace, and we owe it to your foresight that this nation is constantly securing reforms — advantages which we very gratefully accept at all times and places.
B044C024V004	44	24	4	But — not to be tedious — I beg you, with your accustomed fairness, to listen to a brief statement of our case.
B044C024V005	44	24	5	We have found this man a public pest; he is one who stirs up disputes among our people all the world over, and is a ringleader of the Nazarene heretics.
B044C024V006	44	24	6	He even attempted to desecrate the Temple itself, but we caught him;
B044C024V008	44	24	8	and you will be able, by examining him on all these points, to satisfy yourself as to the charges which we are bringing against him.”
B044C024V009	44	24	9	The Jewish crowd also joined in the attack and bore out his statements.
B044C024V010	44	24	10	On a sign from the Governor, Paul made this reply:  “Knowing, as I do, for how many years you have acted as judge to this nation, it is with confidence that I undertake my own defence.
B044C024V011	44	24	11	For you can easily verify that it is not more than twelve days ago that I went up to worship at Jerusalem,
B044C024V012	44	24	12	where my prosecutors never found me holding discussions with anyone, or causing a crowd to collect — either in the Temple, or in the Synagogues, or about the city;
B044C024V013	44	24	13	and they cannot establish the charges which they are now making against me.
B044C024V014	44	24	14	This, however, I do acknowledge to you, that it is as a believer in the cause which they call heretical, that I worship the God of my ancestors. At the same time, I believe everything that is in accordance with the law and that is written in the prophets;
B044C024V015	44	24	15	and I have a hope that rests in God — a hope which they also cherish — that there will one day be a resurrection of good and bad alike.
B044C024V016	44	24	16	This being so, I strive at all times to keep my conscience clear before both God and people.
B044C024V017	44	24	17	After some years’ absence I had come to bring charitable gifts to my nation, and to make offerings;
B044C024V018	44	24	18	and it was while engaged in this that they found me in the Temple, after completing a period of purification, but not with any crowd or disorder.
B044C024V019	44	24	19	There were, however, some Jews from Roman Asia who ought to have been here before you, and to have made any charge that they may have against me —
B044C024V020	44	24	20	Or else let my opponents here say what they found wrong in me when I was before the Council,
B044C024V021	44	24	21	except as to the one sentence that I shouted out as I stood among them — ‘It is about the resurrection of the dead that I am on my trial before you today’.”  
B044C024V022	44	24	22	Felix, however, adjourned the case — though he had a fairly accurate knowledge of all that concerned the cause — with the promise: “When Lysias, the commanding officer, comes down, I will give my decision in your case.”
B044C024V023	44	24	23	So he gave orders to the captain in charge of Paul to keep him in custody, but to relax the regulations, and not to prevent any of his personal friends from attending to his wants.  
B044C024V024	44	24	24	Some days later Felix came with his wife Drusilla, who was herself a Jewess, and, sending for Paul, listened to what he had to say about faith in Christ Jesus.
B044C024V025	44	24	25	But, while Paul was speaking at length about righteousness, self-control, and the coming judgment, Felix became terrified, and interrupted him — “Go for the present, but, when I find an opportunity, I will send for you again.”
B044C024V026	44	24	26	He was hoping, too, for a bribe from Paul, and so he used to send for him frequently and talk with him.
B044C024V027	44	24	27	But, after the lapse of two years, Felix was succeeded by Porcius Festus; and, wishing to gain popularity with the Jewish leaders, he left Paul a prisoner.  
B044C025V001	44	25	1	Three days after Festus had arrived in his province, he left Caesarea and went up to Jerusalem.
B044C025V002	44	25	2	There the chief priests and the leading men among the Jews laid an information before him against Paul,
B044C025V003	44	25	3	and asked a favour of him, to Paul’s injury — to have Paul brought to Jerusalem. All the while they were plotting to make away with him on the road.
B044C025V004	44	25	4	But Festus answered that Paul was in prison at Caesarea, and that he himself would be leaving for that place shortly.
B044C025V005	44	25	5	“So let the influential men among you,” he said, “go down with me, and if there is anything amiss in the man, charge him formally with it.”
B044C025V006	44	25	6	After staying among them some eight or ten days, Festus went down to Caesarea. The next day he took his seat on the Bench, and ordered Paul to be brought before him.
B044C025V007	44	25	7	On Paul’s appearance, the Jewish leaders who had come down from Jerusalem surrounded him, and made many serious charges, which they failed to establish.
B044C025V008	44	25	8	Paul’s answer to the charge was — ‘I have not committed any offence against the Jewish law, or the Temple, or the Emperor.’
B044C025V009	44	25	9	But, as Festus wished to gain popularity with the Jews, he interrupted Paul with the question: 
B044C025V010	44	25	10	“No,” replied Paul, “I am standing at the Emperor’s court, where I ought to be tried. I have not wronged the Jews, as you yourself are well aware.
B044C025V011	44	25	11	If, however, I am breaking the law and have committed any offence deserving death, I do not ask to escape the penalty; but, if there is nothing in the accusations of these people, no one has the power to give me up to them. I appeal to the Emperor.”  
B044C025V012	44	25	12	Festus, after conferring with his Council, answered: “You have appealed to the Emperor; to the Emperor you will go.”  
B044C025V013	44	25	13	Some days later King Agrippa and Bernice came down to Caesarea, and paid a visit of congratulation to Festus;
B044C025V014	44	25	14	and, as they were staying there for several days, Festus laid Paul’s case before the king. “There is a man here,” he said, “left a prisoner by Felix,
B044C025V015	44	25	15	about whom, when I came to Jerusalem, the Jewish chief priest and the councillors laid an information, demanding judgment against him.
B044C025V016	44	25	16	My answer to them was, that it was not the practice of Romans to give up anyone to their accusers until the accused had met them face to face, and had also had an opportunity of answering the charges brought against them.
B044C025V017	44	25	17	So they met here, and without loss of time I took my seat on the Bench the very next day, and ordered the man to be brought before me.
B044C025V018	44	25	18	But, when his accusers came forward, they brought no charge of wrong-doing such as I had expected;
B044C025V019	44	25	19	but I found that there were certain questions in dispute between them about their own religion, and about some dead man called Jesus, whom Paul declared to be alive.
B044C025V020	44	25	20	And, as I was at a loss how to enquire into questions of this kind, I asked Paul if he were willing to go up to Jerusalem, and be put on trial there.
B044C025V021	44	25	21	Paul, however, appealed to have his case reserved for the consideration of his August Majesty, so I ordered him to be detained in custody, until I could send him to the Emperor.”  
B044C025V022	44	25	22	“I should like to hear this man myself,” Agrippa said to Festus. 
B044C025V023	44	25	23	So the next day, when Agrippa and Bernice had come in full state and had entered the Audience Chamber, with the superior officers and the principal people of the city, by the order of Festus Paul was brought before them.
B044C025V024	44	25	24	Then Festus said: “King Agrippa, and all here present, you see before you the man about whom the whole Jewish people have applied to me, both at Jerusalem and here, loudly asserting that he ought not to be allowed to live.
B044C025V025	44	25	25	I found, however, that he had not done anything deserving death; so, as he had himself appealed to his August Majesty, I decided to send him.
B044C025V026	44	25	26	But I have nothing definite to write about him to my Imperial Master; and for that reason I have brought him before you all, and especially before you, King Agrippa, that, after examining him, I may have something to write.
B044C025V027	44	25	27	For it seems to me absurd to send a prisoner, without at the same time stating the charges made against him.”  
B044C026V001	44	26	1	Turning to Paul, Agrippa said: “You are at liberty to speak for yourself.” Then Paul stretched out his hand and began his defence.
B044C026V002	44	26	2	“I have been congratulating myself, King Agrippa,” he said, “that it is before you that I have to make my defence today, with regard to all the charges brought against me by my own people,
B044C026V003	44	26	3	especially as you are so well-versed in all the customs and questions of the Jewish world. I beg you therefore to give me a patient hearing.
B044C026V004	44	26	4	My life, then, from youth upwards, was passed, from the very first, among my own nation, and in Jerusalem, and is within the knowledge of all Jews;
B044C026V005	44	26	5	and they have always known — if they choose to give evidence — that, in accordance with the very strictest form of our religion, I lived a true Pharisee.
B044C026V006	44	26	6	Even now, it is because of my hope in the promise given by God to our ancestors that I stand here on my trial —
B044C026V007	44	26	7	A promise which our twelve tribes, by earnest service night and day, hope to see fulfilled. It is for this hope, your Majesty, that I am accused — and by Jews themselves!
B044C026V008	44	26	8	Why do you all hold it incredible that God should raise the dead?
B044C026V009	44	26	9	I myself, it is true, once thought it my duty to oppose in every way the name of Jesus of Nazareth;
B044C026V010	44	26	10	and I actually did so at Jerusalem. Acting on the authority of the chief priests, I myself threw many of the people of Christ into prison, and, when it was proposed to put them to death, I gave my vote for it.
B044C026V011	44	26	11	Time after time, in every synagogue, I tried by punishments to force them to blaspheme. So frantic was I against them, that I pursued them even to towns beyond our borders.
B044C026V012	44	26	12	It was while I was traveling to Damascus on an errand of this kind, entrusted with full powers by the chief priests,
B044C026V013	44	26	13	that at midday, your Majesty, I saw right in my path, coming from the heavens, a light brighter than the glare of the sun, which shone all round me and those traveling with me.
B044C026V014	44	26	14	We all fell to the ground, and then I heard a voice saying to me in Hebrew —
B044C026V015	44	26	15	‘Who are you, Lord?’ I asked. And the Lord said:
B044C026V019	44	26	19	After that, King Agrippa, I did not fail to obey the heavenly vision;
B044C026V020	44	26	20	on the contrary, first to those at Damascus and Jerusalem, and then through the whole of Judea, and to the Gentiles as well, I began to preach repentance and conversion to God, and a life befitting that repentance.
B044C026V021	44	26	21	This is why some men seized me in the Temple, and made attempts on my life.
B044C026V022	44	26	22	However I have received help from God to this very day, and so stand here, and bear my testimony to high and low alike — without adding a word to what the prophets, as well as Moses, declared should happen —
B044C026V023	44	26	23	That the Christ must suffer, and that, by rising from the dead, he was destined to be the first to bring news of light, not only to our nation, but also to the Gentiles.”
B044C026V024	44	26	24	While Paul was making this defence, Festus called out loudly: “You are mad, Paul; your great learning is driving you mad.”  
B044C026V025	44	26	25	“I am not mad, your Excellency,” he replied; “on the contrary, the statements that I am making are true and sober.
B044C026V026	44	26	26	Indeed, the king knows about these matters, so I speak before him without constraint. I am sure that there is nothing whatever of what I have been telling him that has escaped his attention; for all this has not been done in a corner.
B044C026V027	44	26	27	King Agrippa, do you believe the prophets? I know you do.”  
B044C026V028	44	26	28	But Agrippa said to Paul: “You are soon trying to make a Christian of me!”  
B044C026V029	44	26	29	“Whether it is soon or late,” answered Paul, “I pray to God that not only you, but all who are listening to me, might today become just what I am myself — except for these chains!”
B044C026V030	44	26	30	Then the king rose, with the Governor and Bernice and those who had been sitting with them,
B044C026V031	44	26	31	and, after retiring, discussed the case among themselves. “There is nothing,” they said, “deserving death or imprisonment in this man’s conduct”;
B044C026V032	44	26	32	and, speaking to Festus, Agrippa added: “The man might have been discharged, if he had not appealed to the Emperor.”  
B044C027V001	44	27	1	As it was decided that we were to sail to Italy, Paul and some other prisoners were put in charge of a captain of the Augustan Guard, named Julius.
B044C027V002	44	27	2	We went on board a ship from Adramyttium, which was on the point of sailing to the ports along the coast of Roman Asia, and put to sea. Aristarchus, a Macedonian from Thessalonica, went with us.
B044C027V003	44	27	3	The next day we put in to Sidon, where Julius treated Paul in a friendly manner, and allowed him to go to see his friends and receive their hospitality.
B044C027V004	44	27	4	Putting to sea again, we sailed under the lee of Cyprus, because the wind was against us;
B044C027V005	44	27	5	and, after crossing the sea of Cilicia and Pamphylia, we reached Myra in Lycia.
B044C027V006	44	27	6	There the Roman officer found an Alexandrian ship on her way to Italy, and put us on board of her.
B044C027V007	44	27	7	For several days our progress was slow, and it was only with difficulty that we arrived off Cnidus. As the wind was still unfavourable when we came off Cape Salmone, we sailed under the lee of Crete,
B044C027V008	44	27	8	and with difficulty, by keeping close in shore, we reached a place called ‘Fair Havens,’ near which was the town of Lasea.
B044C027V009	44	27	9	This had taken a considerable time, and sailing was already dangerous, for the Fast was already over; and so Paul gave this warning.
B044C027V010	44	27	10	“My friends,” he said, “I see that this voyage will be attended with injury and much damage, not only to the cargo and the ship, but to our own lives also.”  
B044C027V011	44	27	11	The Roman officer, however, was more influenced by the captain and the owner than by what was said by Paul.
B044C027V012	44	27	12	And, as the harbour was not a suitable one to winter in, the majority were in favour of continuing the voyage, in hope of being able to reach Phoenix, and winter there. Phoenix was a Cretan harbour, open to the north-east and south-east.
B044C027V013	44	27	13	So, when a light wind sprang up from the south, thinking that they had found their opportunity, they weighed anchor and kept along the coast of Crete, close in shore.
B044C027V014	44	27	14	But shortly afterwards a hurricane came down on us off the land — a north-easter, as it is called.
B044C027V015	44	27	15	The ship was caught by it and was unable to keep her head to the wind, so we had to give way and let her drive before it.
B044C027V016	44	27	16	Running under the lee of a small island called Cauda, we only just managed to secure the ship’s boat,
B044C027V017	44	27	17	and, after hoisting it on board, the men frapped the ship. But, afraid of being driven on to the Syrtis Sands, they lowered the yard, and then drifted.
B044C027V018	44	27	18	So violently were we tossed about by the storm, that the next day they began throwing the cargo overboard,
B044C027V019	44	27	19	and, on the following day, threw out the ship’s tackle with their own hands.
B044C027V020	44	27	20	As neither sun nor stars were visible for several days, and, as the gale still continued severe, all hope of our being saved was at last abandoned.  
B044C027V021	44	27	21	It was then, when they had gone a long time without food, that Paul came forward, and said: “My friends, you should have listened to me, and not have sailed from Crete and so incurred this injury and damage.
B044C027V022	44	27	22	Yet, even as things are, I beg you not to lose courage, for there will not be a single life lost among you — only the ship.
B044C027V023	44	27	23	For last night an angel of the God to whom I belong, and whom I serve, stood by me, and said —
B044C027V024	44	27	24	‘Have no fear, Paul; you must appear before the Emperor, and God himself has given you the lives of all your fellow voyagers.’
B044C027V025	44	27	25	Therefore, courage, my friends! For I believe God, that everything will happen exactly as I have been told.
B044C027V026	44	27	26	We will, however, have to be driven on some island.”  
B044C027V027	44	27	27	It was now the fourteenth night of the storm, and we were drifting about in the Adriatic Sea, when, about midnight, the sailors began to suspect that they were drawing near land.
B044C027V028	44	27	28	So they took soundings, and found twenty fathoms of water. After waiting a little, they took soundings again, and found fifteen fathoms.
B044C027V029	44	27	29	Then, as they were afraid of our being driven on some rocky coast, they let go four anchors from the stern, and longed for daylight.
B044C027V030	44	27	30	The sailors wanted to leave the ship, and had lowered the boat, on pretence of running out anchors from the bows,
B044C027V031	44	27	31	when Paul said to the Roman officer and his men: “Unless the sailors remain on board, you cannot be saved.”
B044C027V032	44	27	32	So the soldiers cut the ropes which held the boat, and let her drift away.
B044C027V033	44	27	33	In the interval before daybreak Paul kept urging them all to take something to eat.  “It is a fortnight today,” he said, “that, owing to your anxiety, you have gone without food, taking nothing.
B044C027V034	44	27	34	So I beg you to take something to eat; your safety depends on it, for not one of you will lose even a hair of his head.”
B044C027V035	44	27	35	With these words he took some bread, and, after saying the thanksgiving to God before them all, broke it in pieces, and began to eat;
B044C027V036	44	27	36	and the men all felt cheered and had something to eat themselves.
B044C027V037	44	27	37	There were about seventy-six of us on board, all told.
B044C027V038	44	27	38	After satisfying their hunger, they further lightened the ship by throwing the grain into the sea.
B044C027V039	44	27	39	When daylight came, they could not make out what land it was, but, observing a creek in which there was a beach, they consulted as to whether they could run the ship safely into it.
B044C027V040	44	27	40	Then they cast off, and abandoned the anchors, and at the same time unlashed the gear of the steering oars, hoisted the foresail to the wind, and made for the beach.
B044C027V041	44	27	41	They got, however, into a kind of channel, and there ran the ship aground. The bows stuck fast and could not be moved, while the stern began breaking up under the strain.
B044C027V042	44	27	42	The advice of the soldiers was that the prisoners should be killed, so that none of them could swim away and make their escape.
B044C027V043	44	27	43	But the Roman officer, anxious to save Paul, prevented their carrying out their intention, and ordered that those who could swim should be the first to jump into the sea and try to reach the shore;
B044C027V044	44	27	44	and that the rest should follow, some on planks, and others on different pieces of the ship. In these various ways everyone managed to get safely ashore.  
B044C028V001	44	28	1	When we were all safe, we found that the island was called Malta.
B044C028V002	44	28	2	The island's people showed us marked kindness, for they lit a fire and took us all under shelter, because it had come on to rain and was cold.
B044C028V003	44	28	3	Paul had gathered a quantity of dry sticks and laid them on the fire, when a poisonous snake, driven out by the heat, fastened on his hand.
B044C028V004	44	28	4	When the islanders saw the creature hanging from his hand, they said to one another: “Evidently this man is a murderer, for though he has been saved from the sea, Justice has not allowed him to live.”
B044C028V005	44	28	5	However, Paul shook the creature off into the fire and took no harm.
B044C028V006	44	28	6	The islanders were expecting inflammation to set in, or that he would suddenly fall dead; but, after waiting for a long time, and seeing that there was nothing amiss with him, they changed their minds and said that he was a God.
B044C028V007	44	28	7	In that neighbourhood there was an estate belonging to the Governor of the island, whose name was Publius. He took us up to his house, and for three days entertained us most courteously.
B044C028V008	44	28	8	It happened that the father of Publius was lying ill of fever and dysentery. So Paul went to see him; and, after praying, he placed his hands on him and cured him.
B044C028V009	44	28	9	After this, all the people in the island who had any illness came to Paul, and were cured.
B044C028V010	44	28	10	They also presented us with many gifts, and when we set sail they put supplies of necessaries on board.  
B044C028V011	44	28	11	After three months, we set sail in a ship that had wintered in the island. She was an Alexandrian vessel, and had the Twin sons of Zeus for her figure-head.
B044C028V012	44	28	12	We put in at Syracuse and stayed there three days,
B044C028V013	44	28	13	and from there we worked to windward and so got to Rhegium. A day later a south wind sprang up and took us to Puteoli in two days.
B044C028V014	44	28	14	There we found some of the Lord's followers, and were urged to stay a week with them; after which we went on to Rome.
B044C028V015	44	28	15	The followers there had heard about us, and came out as far as the Market of Appius and the Three Taverns to meet us. At sight of them Paul thanked God and was much cheered.
B044C028V016	44	28	16	On our reaching Rome, Paul was allowed to live by himself, except for the soldier who was in charge of him.
B044C028V017	44	28	17	Three days after our arrival, Paul invited the leading Jews to meet him; and, when they came, he said: “Brothers, although I had done nothing hostile to the interests of our nation or to our ancestral customs, yet I was sent from Jerusalem as a prisoner, and handed over to the Romans.
B044C028V018	44	28	18	The Romans, when they had examined me, were ready to release me, because there was nothing in my conduct deserving death.
B044C028V019	44	28	19	But, as the Jewish leaders opposed my release, I was compelled to appeal to the Emperor — not, indeed, that I had any charge to make against my own nation.
B044C028V020	44	28	20	This, then, is my reason for urging you to come to see me and talk with me; because it is for the sake of the hope of Israel that I am here in chains.”
B044C028V021	44	28	21	“We,” was their reply, “have not had any letter about you from Judea, nor have any of our fellow Jews come and reported or said anything bad about you.
B044C028V022	44	28	22	But we will be glad to hear from you what your views are, for, with regard to this sect, we are well aware that it is spoken against on all sides.”  
B044C028V023	44	28	23	They then fixed a day with him, and came to the place where he was staying, in even larger numbers, when Paul proceeded to lay the subject before them. He bore his testimony to the kingdom of God, and tried to convince them about Jesus, by arguments drawn from the law of Moses and from the prophets — speaking from morning until evening.
B044C028V024	44	28	24	Some were inclined to accept what he said; others, however, rejected it.
B044C028V025	44	28	25	So, as they disagreed among themselves, they began to disperse, Paul adding only —  “True, indeed, was the declaration made by the Holy Spirit, through the prophet Isaiah to your ancestors —
B044C028V026	44	28	26	‘Go to this nation and say —“You will hear with your ears without ever understanding,And, though you have eyes, you will see without ever perceiving.”
B044C028V027	44	28	27	For the mind of this nation has grown dense,And their ears are dull of hearing,Their eyes also have they closed;Otherwise some day they might see with their eyes,And with their ears they might hear,And in their mind they might understand, and might turn —And I might heal them.’
B044C028V028	44	28	28	Understand, then, that this salvation of God was sent for the Gentiles; and they will listen.”  
B044C028V030	44	28	30	For two whole years Paul stayed in a house which he rented for himself, welcoming all who came to see him,
B044C028V031	44	28	31	proclaiming the kingdom of God, and teaching about the Lord Jesus Christ, with perfect fearlessness, unmolested.  
B045C001V001	45	1	1	To all in Rome who are dear to God and have been called to become Christ’s people, from Paul, a servant of Jesus Christ, who has been called to become an apostle, and has been set apart to tell God’s good news.
B045C001V002	45	1	2	This good news God promised long ago through his prophets in the sacred scriptures,
B045C001V003	45	1	3	concerning his Son, Jesus Christ, our Lord; who, as to his human nature, was descended from David,
B045C001V004	45	1	4	but, as to the spirit of holiness within him, was miraculously designated Son of God by his resurrection from the dead.
B045C001V005	45	1	5	Through him we received the gift of the apostolic office, to win submission to the faith among all nations for the glory of his name.
B045C001V006	45	1	6	And among these nations are you — you who have been called to belong to Jesus Christ.
B045C001V007	45	1	7	May God, our Father, and the Lord Jesus Christ bless you and give you peace.  
B045C001V008	45	1	8	First, I thank my God through Jesus Christ about you all, because the report of your faith is spreading throughout the world.
B045C001V009	45	1	9	God, to whom I offer the worship of my soul as I tell the goodness of his Son, is my witness how constantly I mention you when I pray,
B045C001V010	45	1	10	asking that, if he be willing, I may some day at last find the way open to visit you.
B045C001V011	45	1	11	For I long to see you, in order to impart to you some spiritual gift and so give you fresh strength —
B045C001V012	45	1	12	or rather that both you and I may find encouragement in each other’s faith.
B045C001V013	45	1	13	I want you to know, my friends, that I have many times intended coming to see you — but until now I have been prevented — that I might find among you some fruit of my labours, as I have already among the other nations.
B045C001V014	45	1	14	I have a duty to both the Greek and the barbarian, to both the cultured and the ignorant.
B045C001V015	45	1	15	And so, for my part, I am ready to tell the good news to you also who are in Rome.
B045C001V016	45	1	16	For I am not ashamed of the good news; it is the power of God which brings salvation to everyone who believes in Christ, to the Jew first, but also to the Greek.
B045C001V017	45	1	17	For in it there is a revelation of the divine righteousness resulting from faith and leading on to faith; as scripture says — ‘Through faith the righteous will find life.’  
B045C001V018	45	1	18	So, too, there is a revelation from heaven of the divine wrath against every form of ungodliness and wickedness on the part of those people who, by their wicked lives, are stifling the truth.
B045C001V019	45	1	19	This is so, because what can be known about God is plain to them; for God himself has made it plain.
B045C001V020	45	1	20	For ever since the creation of the universe God’s invisible attributes — his everlasting power and divinity — are to be seen and studied in his works, so that people have no excuse;
B045C001V021	45	1	21	because, although they learned to know God, yet they did not offer him as God either praise or thanksgiving. Their speculations about him proved futile, and their undiscerning minds were darkened.
B045C001V022	45	1	22	Professing to be wise, they showed themselves fools;
B045C001V023	45	1	23	and they transformed the glory of the immortal God into the likeness of mortal humans, and of birds, and beasts, and reptiles.  
B045C001V024	45	1	24	Therefore God abandoned them to impurity, letting them follow the cravings of their hearts, until they dishonoured their own bodies;
B045C001V025	45	1	25	for they had substituted a lie for the truth about God, and had reverenced and worshiped created things more than the Creator, who is to be praised for ever. Amen.
B045C001V026	45	1	26	That, I say, is why God abandoned them to degrading passions. Even the women among them perverted the natural use of their bodies to the unnatural;
B045C001V027	45	1	27	while the men, disregarding that for which women were intended by nature, were consumed with passion for one another. Men indulged in vile practices with men, and incurred in their own persons the inevitable penalty for their perverseness.  
B045C001V028	45	1	28	Then, as they would not keep God before their minds, God abandoned them to depraved thoughts, so that they did all kinds of shameful things.
B045C001V029	45	1	29	They revelled in every form of wickedness, evil, greed, vice. Their lives were full of envy, murder, quarrelling, treachery, malice.
B045C001V030	45	1	30	They became back-biters, slanderers, impious, insolent, boastful. They devised new sins. They disobeyed their parents.
B045C001V031	45	1	31	They were undiscerning, untrustworthy, without natural affection or pity.
B045C001V032	45	1	32	Well aware of God’s decree, that those who do such things deserve to die, not only are they guilty of them themselves, but they even applaud those who do them.  
B045C002V001	45	2	1	Therefore you have nothing to say in your own defence, whoever you are who set yourself up as a judge. In judging others you condemn yourself, for you who set yourself up as a judge do the very same things.
B045C002V002	45	2	2	And we know that God’s judgment falls unerringly on those who do them.
B045C002V003	45	2	3	You who judge those that do such things and yet are yourself guilty of them — do you suppose that you of all people will escape God’s judgment?
B045C002V004	45	2	4	Or do you think lightly of his abundant kindness, patience, and forbearance, not realising that his kindness is meant to lead you to repentance?
B045C002V005	45	2	5	Hard-hearted and impenitent as you are, you are storing up for yourself wrath on the ‘day of wrath,’ when God’s justice as a judge will be revealed;
B045C002V006	45	2	6	for ‘he will give to everyone what their actions deserve.’
B045C002V007	45	2	7	To those who, by perseverance in doing good, aim at glory, honour, and all that is imperishable, he will give immortal life;
B045C002V008	45	2	8	while as to those who are factious, and disobedient to truth but obedient to evil, wrath and anger, distress and despair,
B045C002V009	45	2	9	will fall on every human being who persists in wrong-doing — on the Jew first, but also on the Greek.
B045C002V010	45	2	10	But there will be glory, honour, and peace for everyone who does right — for the Jew first, but also for the Greek,
B045C002V011	45	2	11	since God shows no partiality.
B045C002V012	45	2	12	All who, when they sin, are without law will also perish without law; while all who, when they sin, are under law, will be judged as being under law.
B045C002V013	45	2	13	It is not those who hear the words of a law that are righteous before God, but it is those who obey it that will be pronounced righteous.
B045C002V014	45	2	14	When Gentiles, who have no law, do instinctively what the law requires, they, though they have no law, are a law to themselves;
B045C002V015	45	2	15	for they show the demands of the law written on their hearts; their consciences corroborating it, while in their thoughts they argue either in self-accusation or, it may be, in self-defence —
B045C002V016	45	2	16	on the day when God passes judgment on people’s inmost lives, as the good news that I tell declares that he will do through Christ Jesus.
B045C002V017	45	2	17	But, perhaps, you bear the name of ‘Jew,’ and are relying on law, and boast of belonging to God, and understand his will,
B045C002V018	45	2	18	and, having been carefully instructed from the law, have learned to appreciate the finer moral distinctions.
B045C002V019	45	2	19	Perhaps you are confident that you are a guide to the blind, a light to those who are in the dark, an instructor of the unintelligent,
B045C002V020	45	2	20	and a teacher of the childish, because in the law you possess the outline of all knowledge and truth.
B045C002V021	45	2	21	Why, then, you teacher of others, do not you teach yourself? Do you preach against stealing, and yet steal?
B045C002V022	45	2	22	Do you forbid adultery, and yet commit adultery? Do you loathe idols, and yet plunder temples?
B045C002V023	45	2	23	Boasting, as you do, of your law, do you dishonour God by breaking the law?
B045C002V024	45	2	24	For, as scripture says — ‘The Gentiles insult God's name because of you’!
B045C002V025	45	2	25	Circumcision has its value, if you are obeying the law. But, if you are a breaker of the law, your circumcision is no better than uncircumcision.
B045C002V026	45	2	26	If, then, an uncircumcised man pays regard to the requirements of the law, will not he, although not circumcised, be regarded by God as if he were?
B045C002V027	45	2	27	Indeed, the person who, owing to his birth, remains uncircumcised, and yet scrupulously obeys the law, will condemn you, who, for all your written law and your circumcision, are yet a breaker of the law.
B045C002V028	45	2	28	For a man who is only a Jew outwardly is not a real Jew; nor is outward bodily circumcision real circumcision. The real Jew is the person who is a Jew in soul;
B045C002V029	45	2	29	and the real circumcision is the circumcision of the heart, a spiritual and not a literal thing. Such a person wins praise from God, though not from people.  
B045C003V001	45	3	1	What is the advantage, then, of being a Jew? Or what is the good of circumcision?
B045C003V002	45	3	2	Great in every way. First of all, because the Jews were entrusted with God’s utterances.
B045C003V003	45	3	3	What follows then? Some, no doubt, showed a want of faith; but will their want of faith make God break faith? Heaven forbid!
B045C003V004	45	3	4	God must prove true, though everyone prove a liar! As scripture says of God — ‘That you may be pronounced righteous in what you say, and gain your cause when people would judge you.’
B045C003V005	45	3	5	But what if our wrong-doing makes God’s righteousness all the clearer? Will God be wrong in inflicting punishment? (I can but speak as a person.) Heaven forbid!
B045C003V006	45	3	6	Otherwise how can God judge the world?  
B045C003V007	45	3	7	But, if my falsehood redounds to the glory of God, by making his truthfulness more apparent, why am I like others, still condemned as a sinner?
B045C003V008	45	3	8	Why should we not say — as some people slanderously assert that we do say — ‘Let us do evil that good may come’? The condemnation of such people is indeed just!  
B045C003V009	45	3	9	What follows, then? Are we Jews in any way superior to others? Not at all. Our indictment against both Jews and Greeks was that all alike were in subjection to sin.
B045C003V010	45	3	10	As scripture says —  ‘There is not even one who is righteous,
B045C003V011	45	3	11	not one who understands,not one who is searching for God!
B045C003V012	45	3	12	They have all gone astray;they have one and all become depraved;there is no one who is doing good — no, not one!’
B045C003V013	45	3	13	‘Their throats are like opened graves;they deceive with their tongues.’‘The venom of snakes lies behind their lips,’
B045C003V014	45	3	14	‘And their mouths are full of bitter curses.’
B045C003V015	45	3	15	‘Swift are their feet to shed blood.
B045C003V016	45	3	16	Distress and trouble dog their steps,
B045C003V017	45	3	17	and the path of peace they do not know.’
B045C003V018	45	3	18	‘The fear of God is not before their eyes.’ 
B045C003V019	45	3	19	Now we know that everything said in the law is addressed to those who are under its authority, in order that every mouth may be closed, and to bring the whole world under God's judgment.
B045C003V020	45	3	20	For ‘no human being will be pronounced righteous before God’ as the result of obedience to law; for it is law that shows what sin is.
B045C003V021	45	3	21	But now, quite apart from law, the divine righteousness stands revealed, and to it the law and the prophets bear witness —
B045C003V022	45	3	22	the divine righteousness which is bestowed, through faith in Jesus Christ, on all, without distinction, who believe in him.
B045C003V023	45	3	23	For all have sinned, and all fall short of God’s glorious ideal,
B045C003V024	45	3	24	but, in his loving kindness, are being freely pronounced righteous through the deliverance found in Christ Jesus.
B045C003V025	45	3	25	For God set him before the world, to be, by the shedding of his blood, a means of reconciliation through faith. And this God did to prove his righteousness, and because, in his forbearance, he had passed over the sins that people had previously committed;
B045C003V026	45	3	26	as a proof, I repeat, at the present time, of his own righteousness, that he might be righteous in our eyes, and might pronounce righteous the person who takes their stand on faith in Jesus.  
B045C003V027	45	3	27	What, then, becomes of our boasting? It is excluded. By what sort of law? A law requiring obedience? No, a law requiring faith.  
B045C003V028	45	3	28	For we conclude that a person is pronounced righteous on the ground of faith, quite apart from obedience to law.
B045C003V029	45	3	29	Or can it be that God is the God only of the Jews? Is not he also the God of the Gentiles?
B045C003V030	45	3	30	Yes, of the Gentiles also, since there is only one God, and he will pronounce those who are circumcised righteous as the result of faith, and also those who are uncircumcised on their showing the same faith.  
B045C003V031	45	3	31	Do we, then, use this faith to abolish law? Heaven forbid! No, we establish law.  
B045C004V001	45	4	1	What then, it may be asked, are we to say about Abraham, the ancestor of our nation?
B045C004V002	45	4	2	If he was pronounced righteous as the result of obedience, then he has something to boast of. Yes, but not before God.
B045C004V003	45	4	3	For what are the words of scripture? ‘Abraham had faith in God, and his faith was regarded by God as righteousness.’
B045C004V004	45	4	4	Now wages are regarded as due to the person who works, not as a favour, but as a debt;
B045C004V005	45	4	5	while, as for the person who does not rely on their obedience, but has faith in him who can pronounce the godless righteous, their faith is regarded by God as righteousness.
B045C004V006	45	4	6	In precisely the same way David speaks of the blessing pronounced on the person who is regarded by God as righteous apart from actions —
B045C004V007	45	4	7	‘Blessed are those whose wrong-doings have been forgiven and over whose sins a veil has been drawn!
B045C004V008	45	4	8	Blessed the man whom the Lord will never regard as sinful!’
B045C004V009	45	4	9	Is this blessing, then, pronounced on the circumcised only or on the uncircumcised as well? We say that — ‘Abraham’s faith was regarded by God as righteousness.’
B045C004V010	45	4	10	Under what circumstances, then, did this take place? After his circumcision or before it?
B045C004V011	45	4	11	Not after, but before. And it was as a sign of this that he received the rite of circumcision — to show the righteousness due to the faith of an uncircumcised man — in order that he might be the father of all who have faith in God even when uncircumcised, so that they also may be regarded by God as righteous;
B045C004V012	45	4	12	as well as father of the circumcised — to those who are not only circumcised, but who also follow our father Abraham in that faith which he had while still uncircumcised.
B045C004V013	45	4	13	For the promise that he should inherit the world did not come to Abraham or his descendants through law, but through the righteousness due to faith.
B045C004V014	45	4	14	If those who take their stand on law are to inherit the world, then faith is robbed of its meaning and the promise comes to nothing!
B045C004V015	45	4	15	Law entails punishment; but, where no law exists, no breach of it is possible.
B045C004V016	45	4	16	That is why everything is made to depend on faith: so that everything may be God’s gift, and in order that the fulfilment of the promise may be made certain for all Abraham’s descendants — not only for those who take their stand on the law, but also for those who take their stand on the faith of Abraham. (He is the Father of us all;
B045C004V017	45	4	17	as scripture says — ‘I have made you the Father of many nations.’) And this they do in the sight of that God in whom Abraham had faith, and who gives life to the dead, and speaks of what does not yet exist as if it did.
B045C004V018	45	4	18	With no ground for hope, Abraham, sustained by hope, put faith in God; in order that, in fulfilment of the words — ‘So many will your descendants be,’ he might become ‘the Father of many nations.’
B045C004V019	45	4	19	Though he was nearly a hundred years old, yet his faith did not fail him, even when he thought of his own body, then utterly worn out, and remembered that Sarah was past bearing children.
B045C004V020	45	4	20	He was not led by want of faith to doubt God’s promise.
B045C004V021	45	4	21	On the contrary, his faith gave him strength; and he praised God, in the firm conviction that what God has promised he is also able to carry out.
B045C004V022	45	4	22	And therefore his faith ‘was regarded as righteousness.’
B045C004V023	45	4	23	Now these words — ‘it was regarded as righteousness’ — were not written with reference to Abraham only;
B045C004V024	45	4	24	but also with reference to us. Our faith, too, will be regarded by God in the same light, if we have faith in him who raised Jesus, our Lord, from the dead;
B045C004V025	45	4	25	for Jesus ‘was given up to death to atone for our offences,’ and was raised to life that we might be pronounced righteous.  
B045C005V001	45	5	1	Therefore, having been pronounced righteous as the result of faith, let us enjoy peace with God through Jesus Christ, our Lord.
B045C005V002	45	5	2	It is through him that, by reason of our faith, we have obtained admission to that place in God’s favour in which we not stand. So let us exult in our hope of attaining God’s glorious ideal.
B045C005V003	45	5	3	And not only that, but let us also exult in our troubles;
B045C005V004	45	5	4	for we know that trouble develops endurance, and endurance strength of character, and strength of character hope,
B045C005V005	45	5	5	and that ‘hope never disappoints.’ For the love of God has filled our hearts through the Holy Spirit which was given us;
B045C005V006	45	5	6	seeing that, while we were still powerless, Christ, in God’s good time, died on behalf of the godless.
B045C005V007	45	5	7	Even for an upright person scarcely anyone will die. For a really good person perhaps some one might even dare to die.
B045C005V008	45	5	8	But God puts his love for us beyond all doubt by the fact that Christ died on our behalf while we were still sinners.
B045C005V009	45	5	9	Much more, then, now that we have been pronounced righteous by virtue of the shedding of his blood, will we be saved through him from the wrath of God.
B045C005V010	45	5	10	For if, when we were God’s enemies, we were reconciled to him through the death of his Son, much more, now that we have become reconciled, will we be saved by virtue of Christ’s life.
B045C005V011	45	5	11	And not only that, but we exult in God, through Jesus Christ, our Lord, through whom we have now obtained this reconciliation.
B045C005V012	45	5	12	Therefore, just as sin came into the world through one man, and through sin came death; so, also, death spread to all humanity, because every person has sinned.
B045C005V013	45	5	13	Even before the time of the law there was sin in the world; but sin cannot be charged against someone where no law exists.
B045C005V014	45	5	14	Yet, from Adam to Moses, death reigned even over those whose sin was not a breach of a law, as Adam’s was. And Adam foreshadows the One to come.
B045C005V015	45	5	15	But there is a contrast between Adam’s offence and God’s gracious gift. For, if by reason of the offence of the one man the whole race died, far more were the loving kindness of God, and the gift given in the loving kindness of the one man, Jesus Christ, lavished on the whole race.
B045C005V016	45	5	16	There is a contrast, too, between the gift and the results of the one man’s sin. The judgment, which followed on the one man’s sin, resulted in condemnation, but God’s gracious gift, which followed on many offences, resulted in a decree of righteousness.
B045C005V017	45	5	17	For if, by reason of the offence of the one man, death reigned through that one man, far more will those, on whom God’s loving kindness and his gift of righteousness are lavished, find life, and reign through the one man, Jesus Christ.
B045C005V018	45	5	18	Briefly then, just as a single offence resulted for all humanity in condemnation, so, too, a single decree of righteousness resulted for all humanity in that declaration of righteousness which brings life.
B045C005V019	45	5	19	For, as through the disobedience of the one man the whole race was rendered sinful, so, too, through the obedience of the one, the whole race will be rendered righteous.
B045C005V020	45	5	20	law was introduced in order that offences might be multiplied. But, where sins were multiplied, the loving kindness of God was lavished the more,
B045C005V021	45	5	21	in order than, just as sin had reigned in the realm of death, so, too, might Loving-kindness reign through righteousness, and result in eternal life, through Jesus Christ, our Lord.  
B045C006V001	45	6	1	What are we to say, then? Are we to continue to sin, in order that God’s loving kindness may be multiplied?
B045C006V002	45	6	2	Heaven forbid! We became dead to sin, and how can we go on living in it?
B045C006V003	45	6	3	Or can it be that you do not know that all of us, who were baptized into union with Christ Jesus, in our baptism shared his death?
B045C006V004	45	6	4	Consequently, through sharing his death in our baptism, we were buried with him; that, just as Christ was raised from the dead by a manifestation of the Father’s power, so we also may live a new life.
B045C006V005	45	6	5	If we have become united with him by the act symbolic of his death, surely we will also become united with him by the act symbolic of his resurrection.
B045C006V006	45	6	6	We recognise the truth that our old self was crucified with Christ, in order that the body, the stronghold of sin, might be rendered powerless, so that we should no longer be slaves to sin.
B045C006V007	45	6	7	For the man who has so died has been pronounced righteous and released from sin.
B045C006V008	45	6	8	And our belief is, that, as we have shared Christ’s death, we will also share his life.
B045C006V009	45	6	9	We know, indeed, that Christ, having once risen from the dead, will not die again. Death has power over him no longer.
B045C006V010	45	6	10	For the death that he died was a death to sin, once and for all. But the life that he now lives, he lives for God.
B045C006V011	45	6	11	So let it be with you — regard yourselves as dead to sin, but as living for God, through union with Christ Jesus.
B045C006V012	45	6	12	Therefore do not let sin reign in your mortal bodies and compel you to obey its cravings.
B045C006V013	45	6	13	Do not offer any part of your bodies to sin, in the cause of unrighteousness, but once for all offer yourselves to God (as those who, though once dead, now have life), and devote every part of your bodies to the cause of righteousness.
B045C006V014	45	6	14	For sin will not lord it over you. You are living under the reign, not of law, but of love.
B045C006V015	45	6	15	What follows, then? Are we to sin because we are living under the reign of love and not of law? Heaven forbid!
B045C006V016	45	6	16	Surely you know that, when you offer yourselves as servants, to obey anyone, you are the servants of the person whom you obey, whether the service be a service sin which leads to death, or a service Duty which leads to righteousness.
B045C006V017	45	6	17	God be thanked that, though you were once servants of sin, yet you learned to give hearty obedience to that form of doctrine under which you were placed.
B045C006V018	45	6	18	Set free from the control of sin, you became servants to righteousness.
B045C006V019	45	6	19	I can but speak as people do because of the weakness of your earthly nature. Once you offered every part of your bodies to the service of impurity, and of wickedness, which leads to further wickedness. Now, in the same way, offer them to the service of righteousness, which leads to holiness.
B045C006V020	45	6	20	While you were still servants of sin, you were free as regards righteousness.
B045C006V021	45	6	21	But what were the fruits that you reaped from those things of which you are now ashamed? For the end of such things is death.
B045C006V022	45	6	22	But now that you have been set free from the control of sin, and have become servants to God, the fruit that you reap is an ever increasing holiness, and the end eternal life.
B045C006V023	45	6	23	The wages of sin are death, but the gift of God is eternal life, through union with Christ Jesus, our Lord.  
B045C007V001	45	7	1	Surely, friends, you know (for I am speaking to people who know what law means) that law has power over a person only as long as they lives.
B045C007V002	45	7	2	For example, by law a married woman is bound to her husband while he is living; but, if her husband dies, she is set free from the law that bound her to him.
B045C007V003	45	7	3	If, then, during her husband’s lifetime, she unites herself to another man, she will be called an adulteress; but, if her husband dies, the law has no further hold on her, nor, if she unites herself to another man, is she an adulteress.
B045C007V004	45	7	4	And so with you, my friends; as far as the law was concerned, you underwent death in the crucified body of the Christ, so that you might be united to another, to him who was raised from the dead, in order that our lives might bear fruit for God.
B045C007V005	45	7	5	When we were living merely earthly lives, our sinful passions, aroused by the law, were active in every part of our bodies, with the result that our lives bore fruit for death.
B045C007V006	45	7	6	But now we are set free from the law, because we are dead to that which once kept us under restraint; and so we serve under new, spiritual conditions, and not under old, written regulations.
B045C007V007	45	7	7	What are we to say, then? That law and sin are the same thing? Heaven forbid! On the contrary, I should not have learned what sin is, had not it been for law. If the law did not say ‘You must not covet,’ I should not know what it is to covet.
B045C007V008	45	7	8	But sin took advantage of the Commandment to arouse in me every form of covetousness, for where there is no consciousness of law sin shows no sign of life.
B045C007V009	45	7	9	There was a time when I myself, unconscious of law, was alive; but when the Commandment was brought home to me, sin sprang into life, while I died!
B045C007V010	45	7	10	The Commandment that should have meant life I found to result in death!
B045C007V011	45	7	11	sin took advantage of the Commandment to deceive me, and used it to bring about my death.
B045C007V012	45	7	12	And so the law is holy, and each Commandment is also holy, and just, and good.
B045C007V013	45	7	13	Did, then, a thing, which in itself was good, involve death in my case? Heaven forbid! It was sin that involved death; so that, by its use of what I regarded as good to bring about my death, its true nature might appear; and in this way the Commandment showed how intensely sinful sin is.
B045C007V014	45	7	14	We know that the law is spiritual, but I am earthly — sold into slavery to sin.
B045C007V015	45	7	15	I do not understand my own actions. For I am so far from habitually doing what I want to do, that I find myself doing the thing that I hate.
B045C007V016	45	7	16	But when I do what I want not to do, I am admitting that the law is right.
B045C007V017	45	7	17	This being so, the action is no longer my own, but is done by the sin which is within me.
B045C007V018	45	7	18	I know that there is nothing good in me — I mean in my earthly nature. For, although it is easy for me to want to do right, to act rightly is not easy.
B045C007V019	45	7	19	I fail to do the good thing that I want to do, but the bad thing that I want not to do — that I habitually do.
B045C007V020	45	7	20	But, when I do the thing that I want not to do, the action is no longer my own, but is done by the sin which is within me.
B045C007V021	45	7	21	This, then, is the law that I find — when I want to do right, wrong presents itself!
B045C007V022	45	7	22	At heart I delight in the law of God;
B045C007V023	45	7	23	but throughout my body I see a different law, one which is in conflict with the law accepted by my reason, and which endeavours to make me a prisoner to that law of sin which exists throughout my body.
B045C007V024	45	7	24	Miserable man that I am! Who will deliver me from the body that is bringing me to this death?
B045C007V025	45	7	25	Thank God, there is deliverance through Jesus Christ, our Lord! Well then, for myself, with my reason I serve the law of God, but with my earthly nature the law of sin.  
B045C008V001	45	8	1	There is, therefore, now no condemnation for those who are in union with Christ Jesus;
B045C008V002	45	8	2	for through your union with Christ Jesus, the law of the life-giving Spirit has set you free from the law of sin and death.
B045C008V003	45	8	3	What law could not do, in so far as our earthly nature weakened its action, God did, by sending his own Son, with a nature resembling our sinful nature, to atone for sin. He condemned sin in that earthly nature,
B045C008V004	45	8	4	so that the requirements of the law might be satisfied in us who live now in obedience, not to our earthly nature, but to the Spirit.
B045C008V005	45	8	5	They who follow their earthly nature are earthly-minded, while they who follow the Spirit are spiritually minded.
B045C008V006	45	8	6	To be earthly-minded means death, to be spiritually minded means life and peace;
B045C008V007	45	8	7	because to be earthly-minded is to be an enemy to God, for such a mind does not submit to the law of God, nor indeed can it do so.
B045C008V008	45	8	8	They who are earthly cannot please God.
B045C008V009	45	8	9	You, however, are not earthly but spiritual, since the Spirit of God lives within you. Unless a person has the Spirit of Christ, they do not belong to Christ;
B045C008V010	45	8	10	but, if Christ is within you, then, though the body is dead as a consequence of sin, the spirit is life as a consequence of righteousness.
B045C008V011	45	8	11	And, if the Spirit of him who raised Jesus from the dead lives within you, he who raised Christ Jesus from the dead will give life even to your mortal bodies, through his Spirit living within you.
B045C008V012	45	8	12	So then, friends, we owe nothing to our earthly nature, that we should live in obedience to it.
B045C008V013	45	8	13	If you live in obedience to your earthly nature, you will inevitably die; but if, by the power of the Spirit, you put an end to the evil habits of the body, you will live.
B045C008V014	45	8	14	All who are guided by the Spirit of God are sons of God.
B045C008V015	45	8	15	For you did not receive the spirit of a slave, to fill you once more with fear, but the spirit of a son which leads us to cry ‘Abba, Our Father.’
B045C008V016	45	8	16	The Spirit himself unites with our spirits in bearing witness to our being God’s children,
B045C008V017	45	8	17	and if children, then heirs — heirs of God, and joint heirs with Christ, since we share Christ’s sufferings in order that we may also share his glory.  
B045C008V018	45	8	18	I do not count the sufferings of our present life worthy of mention when compared with the glory that is to be revealed and bestowed on us.
B045C008V019	45	8	19	All Nature awaits with eager expectation the appearing of the sons of God.
B045C008V020	45	8	20	For Nature was made subject to imperfection — not by its own choice, but owing to him who made it so —
B045C008V021	45	8	21	yet not without the hope that some day Nature, also, will be set free from enslavement to decay, and will attain to the freedom which will mark the glory of the children of God.
B045C008V022	45	8	22	We know, indeed, that all Nature alike has been groaning in the pains of labour to this very hour.
B045C008V023	45	8	23	And not Nature only; but we ourselves also, though we have already a first gift of the Spirit — we ourselves are inwardly groaning, while we eagerly await our full adoption as sons — the redemption of our bodies.
B045C008V024	45	8	24	By our hope we were saved. But the thing hoped for is no longer an object of hope when it is before our eyes; for who hopes for what is before his eyes?
B045C008V025	45	8	25	But when we hope for what is not before our eyes, then we wait for it with patience.  
B045C008V026	45	8	26	So, also, the Spirit supports us in our weakness. We do not even know how to pray as we should; but the Spirit himself pleads for us in sighs that can find no utterance.
B045C008V027	45	8	27	Yet he who searches all our hearts knows what the Spirit’s meaning is, because the pleadings of the Spirit for Christ’s people are in accordance with his will.
B045C008V028	45	8	28	But we do know that God causes all things to work together for the good of those who love him — those who have received the call in accordance with his purpose.
B045C008V029	45	8	29	For those whom God chose from the first he also destined from the first to be transformed into likeness to his Son, so that his Son might be the eldest among many brothers and sisters.
B045C008V030	45	8	30	And those whom God destined for this he also called; and those whom he called he also pronounced righteous; and those whom he pronounced righteous he also brought to glory.  
B045C008V031	45	8	31	What are we to say, then, in the light of all this?  If God is on our side, who can there be against us?
B045C008V032	45	8	32	God did not withhold his own Son, but gave him up on behalf of us all; will he not, then, with him, freely give us all things?
B045C008V033	45	8	33	Who will bring a charge against any of God’s people? He who pronounces them righteous is God!
B045C008V034	45	8	34	Who is there to condemn them? He who died for us is Christ Jesus! — or, rather, it was he who was raised from the dead, and who is now at God’s right hand and is even pleading on our behalf!
B045C008V035	45	8	35	Who is there to separate us from the love of the Christ? Will trouble, or difficulty, or persecution, or hunger, or nakedness, or danger, or the sword? 
B045C008V036	45	8	36	scripture says — ‘For your sake we are being killed all the day long, We are regarded as sheep to be slaughtered.’
B045C008V037	45	8	37	Yet amidst all these things we more than conquer through him who loved us!
B045C008V038	45	8	38	For I am persuaded that neither death, nor life, nor angels, nor archangels, nor the Present, nor the Future, nor any powers,
B045C008V039	45	8	39	nor Height, nor Depth, nor any other created thing, will be able to separate us from the love of God revealed in Christ Jesus, our Lord!  
B045C009V001	45	9	1	I am speaking the truth as one in union with Christ; it is no lie; and my conscience, enlightened by the Holy Spirit,
B045C009V002	45	9	2	bears me out when I say that there is a great weight of sorrow on me and that my heart is never free from pain.
B045C009V003	45	9	3	I could wish that I were myself accursed and severed from the Christ, for the sake of my people — my own flesh and blood.
B045C009V004	45	9	4	For they are Israelites, and theirs are the adoption as sons, the visible presence, the Covenants, the revealed law, the Temple worship, and the Promises.
B045C009V005	45	9	5	They are descended from the Patriarchs; and, as far as his human nature was concerned, from them came the Christ — he who is supreme over all things, God for ever blessed. Amen.
B045C009V006	45	9	6	Not that God’s Word has failed. For it is not all who are descended from Israel who are true Israelites;
B045C009V007	45	9	7	nor, because they are Abraham’s descendants, are they all his children; but — ‘It is Isaac’s children who will be called your descendants.’
B045C009V008	45	9	8	This means that it is not the children born in the course of nature who are God’s children, but it is the children born in fulfilment of the Promise who are to be regarded as Abraham’s descendants.
B045C009V009	45	9	9	For these words are the words of a promise — ‘About this time I will come, and Sarah will have a son.’
B045C009V010	45	9	10	Nor is that all. There is also the case of Rebecca, when she was about to bear children to our ancestor Isaac.
B045C009V011	45	9	11	For in order that the purpose of God, working through selection, might not fail — a selection depending, not on obedience, but on his call — Rebecca was told, before her children were born and before they had done anything either right or wrong,
B045C009V012	45	9	12	that ‘the elder would be a servant to the younger.’
B045C009V013	45	9	13	The words of scripture are — ‘I loved Jacob, but I hated Esau.’  
B045C009V014	45	9	14	What are we to say, then? Is God guilty of injustice? Heaven forbid!
B045C009V015	45	9	15	For his words to Moses are — ‘I will take pity on whom I take pity, and be merciful to whom I am merciful.’
B045C009V016	45	9	16	So, then, all depends, not on human wishes or human efforts, but on God’s mercy.
B045C009V017	45	9	17	In scripture, again, it is said to Pharaoh — ‘It was for this purpose that I raised you to the throne, to show my power by my dealings with you, and to make my name known throughout the world.’
B045C009V018	45	9	18	So, then, where God wills, he takes pity, and where he wills, he hardens the heart.
B045C009V019	45	9	19	Perhaps you will say to me — ‘How can anyone still be blamed? For who withstands his purpose?’
B045C009V020	45	9	20	I might rather ask ‘Who are you who are arguing with God?’ Does a thing which a person has moulded say to the person who has moulded it ‘Why did you make me like this?’
B045C009V021	45	9	21	Has not the potter absolute power over their clay, so that out of the same lump they make one thing for better, and another for common, use?
B045C009V022	45	9	22	And what if God, intending to reveal his displeasure and make his power known, bore most patiently with the objects of his displeasure, though they were fit only to be destroyed,
B045C009V023	45	9	23	so as to make known his surpassing glory in dealing with the objects of his mercy, whom he prepared beforehand for glory,
B045C009V024	45	9	24	and whom he called — even us — Not only from among the Jews but from among the Gentiles also!
B045C009V025	45	9	25	This, indeed, is what he says in the book of Hosea — ‘Those who were not my people, I will call my people, and those who were unloved I will love.
B045C009V026	45	9	26	And in the place where it was said to them — “You are not my people”, they will be called sons of the living God.’
B045C009V027	45	9	27	And Isaiah cries aloud over Israel — ‘Though the sons of Israel are like the sand of the sea in number, only a remnant of them will escape!
B045C009V028	45	9	28	For the Lord will execute his sentence on the world, fully and without delay.’
B045C009V029	45	9	29	It is as Isaiah foretold — ‘Had not the Lord of Hosts spared some few of our race to us, we should have become like Sodom and been made to resemble Gomorrah.’  
B045C009V030	45	9	30	What are we to say, then? Why, that Gentiles, who were not in search of righteousness, secured it — a righteousness which was the result of faith;
B045C009V031	45	9	31	while Israel, which was in search of a law which would ensure righteousness, failed to discover one.
B045C009V032	45	9	32	And why? Because they looked to obedience, and not to faith, to secure it. They stumbled over ‘the Stumbling-block.’
B045C009V033	45	9	33	As scripture says — ‘See, I place a Stumbling-block in Zion — a Rock which will prove a hindrance; and he who believes in him will have no cause for shame.’  
B045C010V001	45	10	1	My friends, my heart’s desire and prayer to God for my people is for their salvation.
B045C010V002	45	10	2	I can testify that they are zealous for the honour of God; but they are not guided by true insight,
B045C010V003	45	10	3	for, in their ignorance of the divine righteousness, and in their eagerness to set up a righteousness of their own, they refused to accept with submission the divine righteousness.
B045C010V004	45	10	4	For Christ has brought law to an end, so that righteousness may be obtained by everyone who believes in him.
B045C010V005	45	10	5	For Moses writes that, as for the righteousness which results from law, ‘those who practice it will find life through it.’
B045C010V006	45	10	6	But the righteousness which results from faith finds expression in these words — ‘Do not say to yourself “Who will go up into heaven?”’ — which means to bring Christ down —
B045C010V007	45	10	7	‘or “Who will go down into the depths below?”’ — which means to bring Christ up from the dead.
B045C010V008	45	10	8	No, but what does it say? ‘The message of faith’ which we proclaim.
B045C010V009	45	10	9	For, if with your lips you acknowledge the truth of the message that JESUS IS LORD, and believe in your heart that God raised him from the dead, you will be saved.
B045C010V010	45	10	10	For with their hearts people believe and so attain to righteousness, while with their lips they make their Profession of faith and so find salvation.
B045C010V011	45	10	11	As the passage of scripture says — ‘No one who believes in him will have any cause for shame.’
B045C010V012	45	10	12	For no distinction is made between the Jew and the Greek, for all have the same Lord, and he is bountiful to all who invoke him.
B045C010V013	45	10	13	For ‘everyone who invokes the name of the Lord will be saved.’
B045C010V014	45	10	14	But how, it may be asked, are they to invoke one in whom they have not learned to believe? And how are they to believe in one whose words they have not heard? And how are they to hear his words unless some one proclaims him?
B045C010V015	45	10	15	And how is anyone to proclaim him unless they are sent as his messengers? As scripture says — ‘How beautiful are the feet of those who bring good news!’
B045C010V016	45	10	16	Still, it may be said, everyone did not give heed to the good news. No, for Isaiah asks — ‘Lord, who has believed our teaching?’
B045C010V017	45	10	17	And so we gather, faith is a result of teaching, and the teaching comes in the message of Christ.
B045C010V018	45	10	18	But I ask ‘Is it possible that people have never heard?’ No, indeed, for — ‘Their voices spread through all the earth, and their message to the ends of the world.’
B045C010V019	45	10	19	But again I ask ‘Did not the people of Israel understand? First there is Moses, who says — ‘I, the Lord, will stir you to rivalry with a nation which is no nation; Against an undiscerning nation I will arouse your anger.’
B045C010V020	45	10	20	And Isaiah says boldly — ‘I was found by those who were not seeking me; I made myself known to those who were not inquiring of me.
B045C010V021	45	10	21	But of the people of Israel he says — ‘All day long I have stretched out my hands to a people who disobey and contradict.’  
B045C011V001	45	11	1	I ask, then, ‘Has God rejected his people?’ Heaven forbid! For I myself am an Israelite, a descendant of Abraham, of the tribe of Benjamin.
B045C011V002	45	11	2	God has not rejected his people, whom he chose from the first. Have you forgotten the words of scripture in the story of Elijah — how he appeals to God against Israel?
B045C011V003	45	11	3	‘Lord, they have killed your prophets, they have pulled down your altars, and I only am left; and now they are eager to take my life.’
B045C011V004	45	11	4	But what was the divine response? ‘I have kept for myself seven thousand who have never bowed the knee to Baal.’
B045C011V005	45	11	5	And so in our own time, too, there is to be found a remnant of our nation selected by God in love.
B045C011V006	45	11	6	But if in love, then no longer as a result of obedience. Otherwise love would cease to be love.
B045C011V007	45	11	7	What follows from this? Why, that Israel as a nation failed to secure what it was seeking, while those whom God selected did secure it.
B045C011V008	45	11	8	The rest grew callous; as scripture says — ‘God has given them a deadness of mind — eyes that are not to see and ears that are not to hear — and it is so to this very day.’
B045C011V009	45	11	9	David, too, says — ‘May their feasts prove a snare and a trap to them — a hindrance and a retribution;
B045C011V010	45	11	10	may their eyes be darkened, so that they cannot see; and do you always make their backs to bend.’
B045C011V011	45	11	11	I ask then — ‘Was their stumbling to result in their fall?’ Heaven forbid! On the contrary, through their falling away salvation has reached the Gentiles, to stir the rivalry of Israel.
B045C011V012	45	11	12	And, if their falling away has enriched the world, and their failure has enriched the Gentiles, how much more will result from their full restoration!
B045C011V013	45	11	13	But I am speaking to you who were Gentiles.
B045C011V014	45	11	14	Being myself an apostle to the Gentiles, I exalt my office, in the hope that I may stir my countrymen to rivalry, and so save some of them.
B045C011V015	45	11	15	For, if their being cast aside has meant the reconciliation of the world, what will their reception mean, but life from the dead?
B045C011V016	45	11	16	If the first handful of dough in holy, so is the whole mass; and if the root is holy, so are the branches.
B045C011V017	45	11	17	Some, however, of the branches were broken off, and you, who were only a wild olive, were grafted in among them, and came to share with them the root which is the source of the richness of the cultivated olive.
B045C011V018	45	11	18	Yet do not exult over the other branches. But, if you do exult over them, remember that you do not support the root, but that the root supports you.
B045C011V019	45	11	19	But branches, you will say, were broken off, so that I might be grafted in.
B045C011V020	45	11	20	True; it was because of their want of faith that they were broken off, and it is because of your faith that you are standing. Do not think too highly of yourself, but beware.
B045C011V021	45	11	21	For, if God did not spare the natural branches, neither will he spare you.
B045C011V022	45	11	22	See, then, both the goodness and the severity of God — his severity towards those who fell, and his goodness towards you, provided that you continue to confide in that goodness; otherwise you, also, will be cut off.
B045C011V023	45	11	23	And they, too, if they do not continue in their unbelief, will be grafted in; for God has it in his power to graft them in again.
B045C011V024	45	11	24	If you were cut off from your natural stock — a wild olive — and were grafted, contrary to the course of nature, on a good olive, much more will they — the natural branches — be grafted back into their parent tree.  
B045C011V025	45	11	25	My friends, so that you don't think too highly of yourselves, I want you to recognise the truth, hitherto hidden, that the callousness which has come over Israel is only partial, and will continue only until the whole Gentile world has been gathered in.
B045C011V026	45	11	26	And then all Israel will be saved. As scripture says — ‘From Zion will come the Deliverer; he will banish ungodliness from Jacob.
B045C011V027	45	11	27	And they will see the fulfilment of my covenant, when I have taken away their sins.’
B045C011V028	45	11	28	From the standpoint of the good news, the Jews are God’s enemies for your sake; but from the standpoint of God’s selection, they are dear to him for the sake of the Patriarchs.
B045C011V029	45	11	29	For God never regrets his gifts or his call.
B045C011V030	45	11	30	Just as you at one time were disobedient to him, but have now found mercy in the day of their disobedience;
B045C011V031	45	11	31	so, too, they have now become disobedient in your day of mercy, in order that they also in their turn may now find mercy.
B045C011V032	45	11	32	For God has given all alike over to disobedience, that to all alike he may show mercy.
B045C011V033	45	11	33	Oh! The unfathomable wisdom and knowledge of God! How inscrutable are his judgments, how untraceable his ways! Yes —
B045C011V034	45	11	34	‘Who has ever comprehended the mind of the Lord? Who has ever become his counsellor?
B045C011V035	45	11	35	Or who has first given to him, so that he may claim a reward?’
B045C011V036	45	11	36	For all things are from him, through him, and for him. And to him be all glory for ever and ever! Amen.  
B045C012V001	45	12	1	I entreat you, then, friends, by the mercies of God, to offer your bodies as a living and holy sacrifice, acceptable to God, for this is your rational worship.
B045C012V002	45	12	2	Do not conform to the fashion of this world; but be transformed by the complete change that has come over your minds, so that you may discern what God’s will is — all that is good, acceptable, and perfect.
B045C012V003	45	12	3	In fulfilment of the charge with which I have been entrusted, I tell every one of you not to think more highly of himself than he ought to think, but to think until he learns to think soberly — in accordance with the measure of faith that God has allotted to each.
B045C012V004	45	12	4	For, just as in the human body there is a union of many parts, and each part has its own function,
B045C012V005	45	12	5	so we, by our union in Christ, many though we are, form but one body, and individually we are related one to another as its parts.
B045C012V006	45	12	6	Since our gifts differ in accordance with the particular charge entrusted to us, if our gift is to preach, let our preaching correspond to our faith;
B045C012V007	45	12	7	if it is to minister to others, let us devote ourselves to our ministry; the teacher to their teaching,
B045C012V008	45	12	8	the counselor to their counsel. Let the person who gives in charity do so with a generous heart; let the person who is in authority exercise due diligence; let the person who shows kindness do so in a cheerful spirit.
B045C012V009	45	12	9	Let your love be sincere. Hate the wrong; cling to the right.
B045C012V010	45	12	10	In the love of the community of the Lord's followers, be affectionate to one another; in showing respect, set an example of deference to one another;
B045C012V011	45	12	11	never flagging in zeal; fervent in spirit; serving the Master;
B045C012V012	45	12	12	rejoicing in your hope; steadfast under persecution; persevering in prayer;
B045C012V013	45	12	13	relieving the wants of Christ’s people; devoted to hospitality.
B045C012V014	45	12	14	Bless your persecutors — bless and never curse.
B045C012V015	45	12	15	Rejoice with those who are rejoicing, and weep with those who are weeping.
B045C012V016	45	12	16	Let the same spirit of sympathy animate you all, not a spirit of pride; enjoy the company of ordinary people. Do not think too highly of yourselves.
B045C012V017	45	12	17	Never return injury for injury. Aim at doing what everyone will recognise as honourable.
B045C012V018	45	12	18	If it is possible, as far as rests with you, live peaceably with everyone.
B045C012V019	45	12	19	Never avenge yourselves, dear friends, but make way for the wrath of God; for scripture declares — ‘“It is for me to avenge, I will requite,” says the Lord.’
B045C012V020	45	12	20	Rather — ‘If your enemy is hungry, feed him; if he is thirsty, give him to drink. By doing this you will heap coals of fire on his head.’
B045C012V021	45	12	21	Never be conquered by evil, but conquer evil with good.  
B045C013V001	45	13	1	Let everyone obey the supreme Authorities. For no Authority exists except by the will of God, and the existing Authorities have been appointed by God.
B045C013V002	45	13	2	Therefore he who sets himself against the authorities is resisting God’s appointment, and those who resist will bring a judgment on themselves.
B045C013V003	45	13	3	A good action has nothing to fear from Rulers; a bad action has. Do you want to have no reason to fear the Authorities? Then do what is good, and you will win their praise.
B045C013V004	45	13	4	For they are God’s servants appointed for your good. But, if you do what is wrong, you may well be afraid; for the sword they carry is not without meaning! They are God’s servants to inflict his punishments on those who do wrong.
B045C013V005	45	13	5	You are bound, therefore, to obey, not only through fear of God’s punishments, but also as a matter of conscience.
B045C013V006	45	13	6	This, too, is the reason for your paying taxes; for the officials are God’s officers, devoting themselves to this special work.
B045C013V007	45	13	7	In all cases pay what is due from you — tribute where tribute is due, taxes where taxes are due, respect where respect is due, and honour where honour is due.
B045C013V008	45	13	8	Owe nothing to anyone except love; for they who love their neighbour have satisfied the law.
B045C013V009	45	13	9	The commandments, ‘You must not commit adultery, You must not kill, You must not steal, You must not covet,’ and whatever other commandment there is, are all summed up in the words — ‘You must love your neighbour as you love yourself.’
B045C013V010	45	13	10	Love never wrongs a neighbour. Therefore love fully satisfies the law.
B045C013V011	45	13	11	This I say, because you know the crisis that we have reached, for the time has already come for you to rouse yourselves from sleep; our salvation is nearer now than when we accepted the faith.  
B045C013V012	45	13	12	The night is almost gone; the day is near. Therefore let us have done with the deeds of darkness, and arm ourselves with the weapons of light.
B045C013V013	45	13	13	Being in the light of day, let us live becomingly, not in revelry and drunkenness, not in lust and licentiousness, not in quarrelling and jealousy.
B045C013V014	45	13	14	No! Arm yourselves with the spirit of the Lord Jesus Christ, and spend no thought on your earthly nature, to satisfy its cravings.  
B045C014V001	45	14	1	As for those whose faith is weak, always receive them as friends, but not for the purpose of passing judgment on their scruples.
B045C014V002	45	14	2	One person’s faith permits of their eating food of all kinds, while another whose faith is weak eats only vegetable food.
B045C014V003	45	14	3	The person who eats meat must not despise the person who abstains from it; nor must the person who abstains from eating meat pass judgment on the one who eats it, for God himself has received them.
B045C014V004	45	14	4	Who are you, that you should pass judgment on the servant of another? Their standing or falling concerns their own master. And stand they will, for their Master can enable them to stand.
B045C014V005	45	14	5	Again, one person considers some days to be more sacred than others, while another considers all days to be alike. Everyone ought to be fully convinced in their own mind.
B045C014V006	45	14	6	The person who observes a day, observes it to the Master’s honour. They, again, who eat meat eat it to the Master’s honour, for they give thanks to God; while the person who abstains from it abstains from it to the Master’s honour, and also gives thanks to God.
B045C014V007	45	14	7	There is not one of us whose life concerns ourselves alone, and not one of us whose death concerns ourself alone;
B045C014V008	45	14	8	for, if we live, our life is for the Master, and, if we die, our death is for the Master. Whether, then, we live or die we belong to the Master.
B045C014V009	45	14	9	The purpose for which Christ died and came back to life was this — that he might be Lord over both the dead and the living.
B045C014V010	45	14	10	I would ask the one ‘Why do you judge other followers of the Lord?’ And I would ask the other ‘Why do you despise them?’ For we will all stand before the court of God.
B045C014V011	45	14	11	For scripture says — ‘“As surely as I live,” says the Lord, “every knee will bend before me; and every tongue will make acknowledgment to God.”’
B045C014V012	45	14	12	So, then, each one of us will have to render account of himself to God.
B045C014V013	45	14	13	Let us, then, cease to judge one another. Rather let this be your resolve — never to place a stumbling-block or an obstacle in the way of a fellow follower of the Lord.
B045C014V014	45	14	14	Through my union with the Lord Jesus, I know and am persuaded that nothing is ‘defiling in itself.’ A thing is ‘defiling’ only to the person who holds it to be so.
B045C014V015	45	14	15	If, for the sake of what you eat, you wound your fellow follower’s feelings, your life has ceased to be ruled by love. Do not, by what you eat, ruin someone for whom Christ died!
B045C014V016	45	14	16	Do not let what is right for you become a matter of reproach.
B045C014V017	45	14	17	For the kingdom of God does not consist of eating and drinking, but of righteousness and peace and gladness through the presence of the Holy Spirit.
B045C014V018	45	14	18	The person who serves the Christ in this way pleases God, and wins the approval of their fellows.
B045C014V019	45	14	19	Therefore our efforts should be directed towards all that makes for peace and the mutual building up of character.
B045C014V020	45	14	20	Do not undo God’s work for the sake of what you eat. Though everything is ‘clean,’ yet, if a person eats so as to put a stumbling-block in the way of others, they do wrong.
B045C014V021	45	14	21	The right course is to abstain from meat or wine or, indeed, anything that is a stumbling-block to your fellow follower of the Lord.
B045C014V022	45	14	22	As for yourself — keep this faith of yours to yourself, as in the presence of God. Happy the person who never has to condemn themselves in regard to something they think right!
B045C014V023	45	14	23	The person, however, who has misgivings stands condemned if they still eat, because their doing so is not the result of faith. And anything not done as the result of faith is a sin.  
B045C015V001	45	15	1	We, the strong, ought to take on our own shoulders the weaknesses of those who are not strong, and not merely to please ourselves.
B045C015V002	45	15	2	Let each of us please our neighbour for our neighbour’s good, to help in the building up of their character.
B045C015V003	45	15	3	Even the Christ did not please himself! On the contrary, as scripture says of him — ‘The reproaches of those who were reproaching you fell upon me.’
B045C015V004	45	15	4	Whatever was written in the scriptures in days gone by was written for our instruction, so that, through patient endurance, and through the encouragement drawn from the scriptures, we might hold fast to our hope.
B045C015V005	45	15	5	And may God, the giver of this patience and this encouragement, grant you to be united in sympathy in Christ,
B045C015V006	45	15	6	so that with one heart and one voice you may praise the God and Father of Jesus Christ, our Lord.
B045C015V007	45	15	7	Therefore always receive one another as friends, just as the Christ himself received us, to the glory of God.
B045C015V008	45	15	8	For I tell you that Christ, in vindication of God’s truthfulness, has become a minister of the covenant of circumcision, so that he may fulfil the promises made to our ancestors,
B045C015V009	45	15	9	and that the Gentiles also may praise God for his mercy. As scripture says — ‘Therefore will I make acknowledgment to you among the Gentiles and sing in honour of your name.’
B045C015V010	45	15	10	And again it says — ‘Rejoice, you Gentiles, with God’s people.’
B045C015V011	45	15	11	And yet again — ‘Praise the Lord, all you Gentiles, and let all Peoples sing his praises.’
B045C015V012	45	15	12	Again, Isaiah says — ‘There will be a Scion of the house of Jesse, One who is to arise to rule the Gentiles; on him will the Gentiles rest their hopes.’
B045C015V013	45	15	13	May God, who inspires our hope, grant you perfect happiness and peace in your faith, until you are filled with this hope by the power of the Holy Spirit.
B045C015V014	45	15	14	I am persuaded, my friends — yes, I Paul, with regard to you — that you are yourselves full of kindness, furnished with all Christian learning, and well able to give advice to one another.
B045C015V015	45	15	15	But in parts of this letter I have expressed myself somewhat boldly — by way of refreshing your memories —
B045C015V016	45	15	16	because of the charge with which God has entrusted me, that I should be a minister of Christ Jesus to go to the Gentiles — that I should act as a priest of God’s good news, so that the offering up of the Gentiles may be an acceptable sacrifice, consecrated by the Holy Spirit.
B045C015V017	45	15	17	It is, then, through my union with Christ Jesus that I have a proud confidence in my work for God.
B045C015V018	45	15	18	For I will not dare to speak of anything but what Christ has done through me to win the obedience of the Gentiles —
B045C015V019	45	15	19	by my words and actions, through the power displayed in signs and marvels, and through the power of the Holy Spirit. And so, starting from Jerusalem and its neighbourhood, and going as far as Illyria, I have told in full the good news of the Christ;
B045C015V020	45	15	20	yet always with the ambition to tell the good news where Christ’s name had not previously been heard, so as to avoid building on another’s foundations.
B045C015V021	45	15	21	But as scripture says — ‘They to whom he had never been proclaimed will see; and they who have never heard will understand!’  
B045C015V022	45	15	22	That is why I have so often been prevented from coming to you.
B045C015V023	45	15	23	But now there are no further openings for me in these parts, and I have for several years been longing to come to you whenever I may be going to Spain.
B045C015V024	45	15	24	For my hope is to visit you on my journey, and then to be sent on my way by you, after I have first partly satisfied myself by seeing something of you.
B045C015V025	45	15	25	Just now, however, I am on my way to Jerusalem, to take help to Christ’s people there.
B045C015V026	45	15	26	For Macedonia and Greece have been glad to make a collection for the poor among Christ’s people at Jerusalem.
B045C015V027	45	15	27	Yes, they were glad to do so; and indeed it is a duty which they owe to them. For the Gentile converts who have shared their spiritual blessings are in duty bound to minister to them in the things of this world.
B045C015V028	45	15	28	When I have settled this matter, and have secured to the poor at Jerusalem the enjoyment of these benefits, I will go, by way of you, to Spain.
B045C015V029	45	15	29	And I know that, when I come to you, it will be with a full measure of blessing from Christ.
B045C015V030	45	15	30	I beg you, then, friends, by Jesus Christ, our Lord, and by the love inspired by the Spirit, to join me in earnest prayer to God on my behalf.
B045C015V031	45	15	31	Pray that I may be rescued from those in Judea who reject the faith, and that the help which I am taking to Jerusalem may prove acceptable to Christ’s people;
B045C015V032	45	15	32	so that, God willing, I may be able to come to you with a joyful heart, and enjoy some rest among you.
B045C015V033	45	15	33	May God, the giver of peace, be with you all. Amen.  
B045C016V001	45	16	1	I commend to your care our sister, Phoebe, who is a minister of the church at Cenchreae;
B045C016V002	45	16	2	and I ask you to give her a Christian welcome — one worthy of Christ’s people — and to aid her in any matter in which she may need your assistance. She has proved herself a staunch friend and protector and to many others.
B045C016V003	45	16	3	Give my greeting to Prisca and Aquila, my fellow workers in the cause of Christ Jesus,
B045C016V004	45	16	4	who risked their own lives to save mine. It is not I alone who thank them, but all the churches among the Gentiles thank them also.
B045C016V005	45	16	5	Give my greeting, also, to the church that meets at their house, as well as to my dear friend Epaenetus, one of the first in Roman Asia to believe in Christ;
B045C016V006	45	16	6	to Mary, who worked hard for you;
B045C016V007	45	16	7	to Andronicus and Junia, fellow Jews and once my fellow prisoners, who are people of note among the apostles, and who became Christians before I did;
B045C016V008	45	16	8	to my dear Christian friend Ampliatus;
B045C016V009	45	16	9	to Urban, our fellow worker in the cause of Christ, and to my dear friend Stachys;
B045C016V010	45	16	10	to that proved Christian Apelles; to the household of Aristobulus;
B045C016V011	45	16	11	to my countryman Herodion; to the Christians in the household of Narcissus;
B045C016V012	45	16	12	to Tryphaena and Tryphosa, who have worked hard for the Master; to my dear friend Persis, for she has done much hard work for the Master;
B045C016V013	45	16	13	to that eminent Christian, Rufus, and to his mother, who has been a mother to me also;
B045C016V014	45	16	14	to Asyncritus, Phlegon, Hermes, Patrobas, Hermas, and our friends with them;
B045C016V015	45	16	15	also to Philologus and Julia, Nereus and his sister, and Olympas, and to all Christ’s people who are with them.
B045C016V016	45	16	16	Greet one another with a sacred kiss. All the churches of the Christ send you greetings.  
B045C016V017	45	16	17	I beg you, friends, to be on your guard against people who, by disregarding the teaching which you received, cause divisions and create difficulties; dissociate yourselves from them.
B045C016V018	45	16	18	For such persons are not serving Christ, our Master, but are slaves to their own appetites; and, by their smooth words and flattery, they deceive simple-minded people.
B045C016V019	45	16	19	Everyone has heard of your ready obedience. It is true that I am very happy about you, but I want you to be well versed in all that is good, and innocent of all that is bad.
B045C016V020	45	16	20	And God, the giver of peace, will before long crush Satan under your feet. 
B045C016V021	45	16	21	Timothy, my fellow worker, sends you his greetings, and Lucius, Jason, and Sosipater, my countrymen, send theirs.  
B045C016V022	45	16	22	I Tertius, who am writing this letter, send you my Christian greeting.  
B045C016V023	45	16	23	My host Gaius, who extends his hospitality to the whole church, sends you his greeting; and Erastus, the city treasurer, and Quartus, our dear friend, add theirs.  
B045C016V025	45	16	25	Now to him who is able to strengthen you, as promised in the good news entrusted to me and in the proclamation of Jesus Christ, in accordance with the revelation of that hidden purpose, which in past ages was kept secret but now has been revealed
B045C016V026	45	16	26	and, in obedience to the command of the immortal God, made known through the writings of the prophets to all nations, to secure submission to the faith —
B045C016V027	45	16	27	to him, I say, the wise and only God, be ascribed, through Jesus Christ, all glory for ever and ever. Amen.  
B046C001V001	46	1	1	To the church of God in Corinth, to those who have been consecrated by union with Christ Jesus and called to become his people, and also to all, wherever they may be, who invoke the name of our Lord Jesus Christ — their Master and ours,
B046C001V002	46	1	2	from Paul, who has been called to be an apostle of Jesus Christ by the will of God, and from Sosthenes, our fellow follower of the Lord.
B046C001V003	46	1	3	May God, our Father, and the Lord Jesus Christ bless you and give you peace.  
B046C001V004	46	1	4	I always thank God about you for the blessing bestowed on you in Christ Jesus.
B046C001V005	46	1	5	For through union with him you were enriched in every way — in your power to preach, and in your knowledge of the truth;
B046C001V006	46	1	6	and so became yourselves a confirmation of my testimony to the Christ.
B046C001V007	46	1	7	There is no gift in which you are deficient, while waiting for the appearing of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B046C001V008	46	1	8	And God himself will strengthen you to the end, so that at the day of our Lord Jesus Christ you may be found blameless.
B046C001V009	46	1	9	God will not fail you, and it is he who called you into communion with his Son, Jesus Christ, our Lord.
B046C001V010	46	1	10	But I appeal to you, my friends, by the name of our Lord Jesus Christ, to agree in what you profess, and not to allow divisions to exist among you, but to be united — of one mind and of one opinion.
B046C001V011	46	1	11	For I have been informed, my friends, by the members of Chloe’s household, that party feeling exists among you.
B046C001V012	46	1	12	I mean this: that every one of you says either ‘I follow Paul,’ or ‘I Apollos,’ or ‘I Cephas,’ or ‘I Christ.’
B046C001V013	46	1	13	You have torn the Christ in pieces! Was it Paul who was crucified for you? Or were you baptized into the faith of Paul?
B046C001V014	46	1	14	I am thankful that I did not baptize any of you except Crispus and Gaius,
B046C001V015	46	1	15	so that no one can say that you were baptized into my faith.
B046C001V016	46	1	16	I baptized also the household of Stephanas. I do not know that I baptized anyone else.
B046C001V017	46	1	17	My mission from Christ was not to baptize, but to tell the good news; not, however, in the language of philosophy, in case the cross of the Christ should be robbed of its meaning.
B046C001V018	46	1	18	The message of the cross is indeed mere folly to those who are in the path to ruin, but to us who are in the path of salvation it is the power of God.
B046C001V019	46	1	19	For scripture says —  ‘I will bring the philosophy of the philosophers to nought, and the shrewdness of the shrewd I will bring to nothing.’
B046C001V020	46	1	20	Where is the philosopher? Where the teacher of the law? Where the disputant of today? Has not God shown the world’s philosophy to be folly?
B046C001V021	46	1	21	For since the world, in God’s wisdom, did not by its philosophy learn to know God, God saw fit, by the ‘folly’ of our proclamation, to save those who believe in Christ!
B046C001V022	46	1	22	While Jews ask for miraculous signs, and Greeks study philosophy,
B046C001V023	46	1	23	we are proclaiming Christ crucified! — to the Jews an obstacle, to the Gentiles mere folly,
B046C001V024	46	1	24	but to those who have received the call, whether Jews or Greeks, Christ, the power of God and the wisdom of God!
B046C001V025	46	1	25	For God’s ‘folly’ is wiser than people, and God’s ‘weakness’ is stronger than people.
B046C001V026	46	1	26	Look at the facts of your call, friends. There are not many among you who are wise, as people reckon wisdom, not many who are influential, not many who are high-born;
B046C001V027	46	1	27	but God chose what the world counts foolish to put its wise to shame, and God chose what the world counts weak to put its strong to shame,
B046C001V028	46	1	28	and God chose what the world counts poor and insignificant — things that to it are unreal — to bring its ‘realities’ to nothing,
B046C001V029	46	1	29	so that in his presence no one should boast.
B046C001V030	46	1	30	But you, by your union with Christ Jesus, belong to God; and Christ, by God’s will, became not only our wisdom, but also our righteousness, holiness, and deliverance,
B046C001V031	46	1	31	so that — in the words of scripture —  ‘Let him who boasts make his boast of the Lord!’ 
B046C002V001	46	2	1	For my own part, friends, when I came to you, it was with no display of eloquence or philosophy that I came to tell the hidden purpose of God;
B046C002V002	46	2	2	for I had determined that, while with you, I would forget everything Jesus Christ — and him crucified!
B046C002V003	46	2	3	Indeed, when I came among you, I was weak, and full of fears, and in great anxiety.
B046C002V004	46	2	4	My message and my proclamation were not delivered in the persuasive language of philosophy, but were accompanied by the manifestation of spiritual power,
B046C002V005	46	2	5	so that your faith should be based, not on the human wisdom, but on the power of God.
B046C002V006	46	2	6	Yet there is a philosophy that we teach to those whose faith is matured, but it is not the philosophy of today, or of the leaders of today — whose downfall is at hand.
B046C002V007	46	2	7	No, it is a divine philosophy that we teach, one concerned with the hidden purpose of God — that long hidden philosophy which God, before time began, destined for our glory.
B046C002V008	46	2	8	This philosophy is not known to any of the leaders of today; for, had they known it, they would not have crucified our glorified Lord.
B046C002V009	46	2	9	It is what scripture speaks of as —  ‘What eye never saw, nor ear ever heard,what never entered people's minds —even all that God has prepared for those who love him.’
B046C002V010	46	2	10	Yet to us God revealed it through his Spirit; for the Spirit fathoms all things, even the inmost depths of God’s being.
B046C002V011	46	2	11	For what person is there who knows what a person is, except the person’s own spirit within them? So, also, no one comprehends what God is, except the Spirit of God.
B046C002V012	46	2	12	And as for us, it is not the spirit of the world that we have received, but the Spirit that comes from God, so that we may realize the blessings given to us by him.
B046C002V013	46	2	13	And we speak of these gifts, not in language taught by human philosophy, but in language taught by the Spirit, explaining spiritual things in spiritual words.
B046C002V014	46	2	14	The merely intellectual person rejects the teaching of the Spirit of God; for to them it is mere folly; they cannot grasp it, because it is to be understood only by spiritual insight.
B046C002V015	46	2	15	But the person with spiritual insight is able to understand everything, although they themselves are understood by no one.
B046C002V016	46	2	16	For ‘who has so comprehended the mind of the Lord as to be able to instruct him?’ We, however, have the mind of Christ.  
B046C003V001	46	3	1	But I, my friends, could not speak to you as people with spiritual insight, but only as worldly-minded — mere infants in the faith of Christ.
B046C003V002	46	3	2	I fed you with milk, not with solid food, for you were not then able to take it.  No, and even now you are not able; you are still worldly.
B046C003V003	46	3	3	While there exist among you jealousy and party feeling, is it not true that you are worldly, and are acting merely as other people do?
B046C003V004	46	3	4	When one says ‘I follow Paul,’ and another ‘I follow Apollos,’ are not you like other people?
B046C003V005	46	3	5	What, I ask, is Apollos? Or what is Paul? Servants through whom you were led to accept the faith; and that only as the Lord helped each of you.
B046C003V006	46	3	6	I planted, and Apollos watered, but it was God who caused the growth.
B046C003V007	46	3	7	Therefore neither the one who plants, nor the one who waters, counts for anything, but only God who causes the growth.
B046C003V008	46	3	8	In this the person who plants and the person who waters are one; yet each will receive their own reward in proportion to their own labour.
B046C003V009	46	3	9	For we are God’s fellow workers; you are God’s harvest field, God’s building.  
B046C003V010	46	3	10	In fulfilment of the charge which God had entrusted to me, I laid the foundation like a skilful master; but someone else is now building on it. Let everyone take care how they build;
B046C003V011	46	3	11	for no one can lay any other foundation than the one already laid — Jesus Christ.
B046C003V012	46	3	12	Whatever is used by those who build on this foundation, whether gold, silver, costly stones, wood, hay, or straw,
B046C003V013	46	3	13	the quality of each man’s work will become known, for the day will make it plain; because that day is to be ushered in with fire, and the fire itself will test the quality of every man’s work.
B046C003V014	46	3	14	If anyone’s work, which they have built on that foundation, still remains, they will gain a reward.
B046C003V015	46	3	15	If anyone’s work is burnt up, they will suffer loss; though they themselves will escape, but only as one who has passed through fire.  
B046C003V016	46	3	16	Do not you know that you are God’s Temple, and that God’s Spirit has his home in you?
B046C003V017	46	3	17	If any one destroys the Temple of God, God will destroy them; for the Temple of God is sacred, and so also are you.  
B046C003V018	46	3	18	Let no one deceive himself. If any one among you imagines that, as regards this world, they are wise, let them become a ‘fool,’ that they may become wise.
B046C003V019	46	3	19	For in God’s sight this world’s wisdom is folly. Scripture tells of —  ‘One who catches the wise in their own craftiness,’
B046C003V020	46	3	20	And it says again —  ‘The Lord sees how fruitless are the deliberations of the wise.’
B046C003V021	46	3	21	Therefore let no one boast about people; for all things are yours —
B046C003V022	46	3	22	Whether Paul, or Apollos, or Cephas, or the world, or life, or death, or the present, or the future — all things are yours!
B046C003V023	46	3	23	But you are Christ’s and Christ is God’s.
B046C004V001	46	4	1	Let people look on us as Christ’s servants, and as stewards of the hidden truths of God.
B046C004V002	46	4	2	Now what we look for in stewards is that they should be trustworthy.
B046C004V003	46	4	3	But it weighs very little with me that I am judged by you or by any human tribunal. No, I do not even judge myself;
B046C004V004	46	4	4	for, though I am conscious of nothing against myself, that does not prove me innocent. It is the Lord who is my judge.
B046C004V005	46	4	5	Therefore do not pass judgment before the time, but wait until the Lord comes. He will throw light on what is now dark and obscure, and will reveal the motives in people’s minds; and then everyone will receive due praise from God.
B046C004V006	46	4	6	All this, friends, I have, for your sakes, applied to Apollos and myself, so that, from our example, you may learn to observe the precept — ‘Keep to what is written,’ that none of you may speak boastfully of one teacher to the disparagement of another.
B046C004V007	46	4	7	For who makes any one of you superior to others? And what have you that was not given you? But if you received it as a gift, why do you boast as if you had not?
B046C004V008	46	4	8	Are you all so soon satisfied? Are you so soon rich? Have you begun to reign without us? Would indeed that you had, so that we also might reign with you!
B046C004V009	46	4	9	For, as it seems to me, God has exhibited us, the apostles, last of all, as people doomed to death. We are made a spectacle to the universe, both to angels and to people!
B046C004V010	46	4	10	We, for Christ’s sake, are ‘fools,’ but you, by your union with Christ, are people of discernment. We are weak, but you are strong. You are honoured, but we are despised.
B046C004V011	46	4	11	To this very hour we go hungry, thirsty, and naked; we are beaten; we are homeless;
B046C004V012	46	4	12	we work hard, toiling with our own hands. We meet abuse with blessings, we meet persecution with endurance,
B046C004V013	46	4	13	we meet slander with gentle appeals. We have been treated as the scum of the earth, the vilest of the vile, to this very hour.  
B046C004V014	46	4	14	It is with no wish to shame you that I am writing like this; but to warn you as my own dear children.
B046C004V015	46	4	15	Though you may have thousands of instructors in the faith of Christ, yet you have not many fathers. It was I who, through union with Christ Jesus, became your father by means of the good news.
B046C004V016	46	4	16	Therefore I entreat you — Follow my example.
B046C004V017	46	4	17	This is my reason for sending Timothy to you. He is my own dear faithful child in the Master’s service, and he will remind you of my methods of teaching the faith of Christ Jesus — methods which I follow everywhere in every church.  
B046C004V018	46	4	18	Some, I hear, are puffed up with pride, thinking that I am not coming to you.
B046C004V019	46	4	19	But come to you I will, and that soon, if it please the Lord; and then I will find out, not what words these people use who are so puffed up, but what power they possess;
B046C004V020	46	4	20	for the kingdom of God is based, not on words, but on power.
B046C004V021	46	4	21	What do you wish? Am I to come to you with a rod, or in a loving and gentle spirit?  
B046C005V001	46	5	1	There is a wide-spread report respecting a case of immorality among you, and that, too, of a kind that does not occur even among the Gentiles — a man, I hear, is living with his father’s wife!
B046C005V002	46	5	2	Instead of grieving over it and taking steps for the expulsion of the man who has done this thing, is it possible that you are still puffed up?
B046C005V003	46	5	3	For I myself, though absent in body, have been present with you in spirit, and in the name of our Lord Jesus I have already passed judgment, just as if I had been present, on the man who has acted in this way.
B046C005V004	46	5	4	I have decided — having been present in spirit at your meetings, when the power of the Lord Jesus was with us —
B046C005V005	46	5	5	to deliver such a man as this over to Satan, that what is sensual in him may be destroyed, so that his spirit may be saved at the day of the Lord.
B046C005V006	46	5	6	Your boasting is unseemly. Do not you know that even a little leaven leavens all the dough?
B046C005V007	46	5	7	Get rid entirely of the old leaven, so that you may be like new dough — free from leaven, as in truth you are. For our passover lamb is already sacrificed — Christ himself;
B046C005V008	46	5	8	therefore let us keep our festival, not with the leaven of former days, nor with the leaven of vice and wickedness, but with the unleavened bread of sincerity and truth.
B046C005V009	46	5	9	I told you, in my letter, not to associate with immoral people —
B046C005V010	46	5	10	not, of course, meaning people of the world who are in immoral, or who are covetous and grasping, or who worship idols; for then you would have to leave the world altogether.
B046C005V011	46	5	11	But, as things are, I say that you are not to associate with anyone who, although a follower of Christ in name, is immoral, or covetous, or an idolater, or abusive, or a drunkard, or grasping — no, not even to sit down to eat with such people.
B046C005V012	46	5	12	What have I to do with judging those outside the church? Is it not for you to judge those who are within the church,
B046C005V013	46	5	13	while God judges those who are outside? ‘Put away the wicked from among you.’  
B046C006V001	46	6	1	Can it be that, when one of you has a dispute with another, they dare to have their case tried before the heathen, instead of before Christ’s people?
B046C006V002	46	6	2	Do not you know that Christ’s people will try the world? And if the world is to be tried by you, are you unfit to try the most trivial cases?
B046C006V003	46	6	3	Do not you know that we are to try angels — to say nothing of the affairs of this life?
B046C006V004	46	6	4	Why, then, if you have cases relating to the affairs of this life, do you set to try them those who carry no weight with the church? To your shame I ask it.
B046C006V005	46	6	5	Can it be that there is not one among you wise enough to decide between two of their fellow followers?
B046C006V006	46	6	6	Must a follower sue a fellow follower? In front of unbelievers?
B046C006V007	46	6	7	To begin with, it is undoubtedly a loss to you to have lawsuits with one another. Why not rather let yourselves be wronged? Why not rather let yourselves be cheated?
B046C006V008	46	6	8	Instead of this, you wrong and cheat others yourselves — yes, even other followers!
B046C006V009	46	6	9	Do not you know that wrong-doers will have no share in God’s kingdom? Do not be deceived. No one who is immoral, or an idolater, or an adulterer, or licentious, or a sexual pervert,
B046C006V010	46	6	10	or a thief, or covetous, or a drunkard, or abusive, or grasping, will have any share in God’s kingdom.
B046C006V011	46	6	11	Such some of you used to be; but you washed yourselves clean. You became Christ’s people! You were pronounced righteous through the name of our Lord Jesus Christ, and through the Spirit of our God!
B046C006V012	46	6	12	Everything is allowable for me! Yes, but everything is not profitable. Everything is allowable for me! Yes, but for my part, I will not let myself be enslaved by anything.
B046C006V013	46	6	13	Food exists for the stomach, and the stomach for food; but God will put an end to both the one and the other. The body, however, exists, not for immorality, but for the Lord, and the Lord for the body;
B046C006V014	46	6	14	and, as God has raised the Lord, so he will raise up us also by the exercise of his power.
B046C006V015	46	6	15	Do not you know that your bodies are Christ’s members? Am I, then, to take the members that belong to the Christ and make them the members of a prostitute? Heaven forbid!
B046C006V016	46	6	16	Or do not you know that a man who unites himself with a prostitute is one with her in body (for ‘the two,’ it is said, ‘will become one’);
B046C006V017	46	6	17	while a man who is united with the Lord is one with him in spirit?
B046C006V018	46	6	18	Shun all immorality. Every other sin that people commit is something outside the body; but an immoral person sins against their own body.
B046C006V019	46	6	19	Again, do not you know that your body is a shrine of the Holy Spirit that is within you – the Spirit which you have from God?
B046C006V020	46	6	20	Moreover, you are not your own masters; you were bought, and the price was paid. Therefore, honour God in your bodies.
B046C007V001	46	7	1	With reference to the subjects about which you wrote to me: It is good for a man to remain single.
B046C007V002	46	7	2	But, owing to the prevalence of immorality, I advise every man to have his own wife, and every woman her husband.
B046C007V003	46	7	3	A husband should give his wife her due, and a wife her husband.
B046C007V004	46	7	4	It is not the wife, but the husband, who exercises power over her body; and so, too, it is not the husband, but the wife, who exercises power over his body.
B046C007V005	46	7	5	Do not deprive each other of what is due — unless it is only for a time and by mutual consent, so that your minds may be free for prayer until you again live as man and wife — otherwise Satan might take advantage of your want of self-control and tempt you.
B046C007V006	46	7	6	I say this, however, as a concession, not as a command.
B046C007V007	46	7	7	I should wish everyone to be just what I am myself. But everyone has his own gift from God — one in one way, and one in another.
B046C007V008	46	7	8	My advice, then, to those who are not married, and to widows, is this: It would be good for them to remain as I am myself.
B046C007V009	46	7	9	But, if they cannot control themselves, let them marry, for it is better to marry than to be consumed with passion.
B046C007V010	46	7	10	To those who are married my direction is — yet it is not mine, but the Master’s — that a woman is not to leave her husband
B046C007V011	46	7	11	(If she has done so, let her remain as she is, or else be reconciled to her husband) and also that a man is not to divorce his wife.
B046C007V012	46	7	12	To all others I say — I, not the Master — If a follower of the Lord is married to a woman, who is an unbeliever but willing to live with him, he should not divorce her;
B046C007V013	46	7	13	and a woman who is married to a man, who is an unbeliever but willing to live with her, should not divorce her husband.
B046C007V014	46	7	14	For, through his wife, the husband who is an unbeliever has become associated with Christ’s people; and the wife who is an unbeliever has become associated with Christ’s people through the Lord's follower whom she has married. Otherwise your children would be ‘defiled,’ but, as it is, they belong to Christ’s people.
B046C007V015	46	7	15	However, if the unbeliever wishes to be separated, let him be so. Under such circumstances neither is bound; God has called you to live in peace.
B046C007V016	46	7	16	How can you tell, wife, whether you may not save your husband? And how can you tell, husband, whether you may not save your wife?
B046C007V017	46	7	17	In any case, a person should continue to live in the condition which the Lord has allotted to them, and in which they were when God called them. This is the rule that I lay down in every church.
B046C007V018	46	7	18	Was a man already circumcised when he was called? Then he should not efface his circumcision. Has a man been called when uncircumcised? Then he should not be circumcised.
B046C007V019	46	7	19	Circumcision is nothing; the want of it is nothing; but to keep the commands of God is everything.
B046C007V020	46	7	20	Let everyone remain in that condition of life in which they were when the call came to them.
B046C007V021	46	7	21	Were you a slave when you were called? Do not let that trouble you. No, even if you are able to gain your freedom, still do your best.
B046C007V022	46	7	22	For the person who was a slave when they were called to the master’s service is the Master’s freedman; so, too, the person who was free when called is Christ’s slave.
B046C007V023	46	7	23	You were bought, and the price was paid. Do not let yourselves become slaves to people.
B046C007V024	46	7	24	Friends, let everyone remain in the condition in which they were when they were called, in close communion with God.  
B046C007V025	46	7	25	With regard to unmarried women, I have no command from the Master to give you, but I tell you my opinion, and the Master in his mercy has made me worthy to be trusted.
B046C007V026	46	7	26	I think, then, that, in view of the time of suffering that has now come upon us, what I have already said is best — that a man should remain as he is.
B046C007V027	46	7	27	Are you married to a wife? Then do not seek to be separated. Are you separated from a wife? Then do not seek for a wife.
B046C007V028	46	7	28	still, if you should marry, that is not wrong; nor, if a young woman marries, is that wrong. But those who marry will have much trouble to bear, and my wish is to spare you.
B046C007V029	46	7	29	What I mean, friends, is this — The time is short. Meanwhile, let those who have wives live as if they had none,
B046C007V030	46	7	30	those who are weeping as if not weeping, those who are rejoicing as if not rejoicing, those who buy as if not possessing,
B046C007V031	46	7	31	and those who use the good things of the world as using them sparingly; for this world as we see it is passing away.
B046C007V032	46	7	32	I want you to be free from anxiety. The unmarried man is anxious about the Master’s cause, desiring to please him;
B046C007V033	46	7	33	while the married man is anxious about worldly matters, desiring to please his wife;
B046C007V034	46	7	34	and so his interests are divided. Again, the unmarried woman, whether she is old or young, is anxious about the Master’s cause, striving to be pure both in body and in spirit, while the married woman is anxious about worldly matters, desiring to please her husband.
B046C007V035	46	7	35	I say this for your own benefit, not with any intention of putting a halter round your necks, but in order to secure for the Master seemly and constant devotion, free from all distraction.
B046C007V036	46	7	36	If, however, a father thinks that he is not acting fairly by his unmarried daughter, when she is past her youth, and if under these circumstances her marriage ought to take place, let him act as he thinks right. He is doing nothing wrong — let the marriage take place.
B046C007V037	46	7	37	On the other hand, a father, who has definitely made up his mind, and is under no compulsion, but is free to carry out his own wishes, and who has come to the decision, in his own mind, to keep his unmarried daughter at home will be doing right.
B046C007V038	46	7	38	In short, the one who consents to his daughter’s marriage is doing right, and yet the other will be doing better.  
B046C007V039	46	7	39	A wife is bound to her husband as long as he lives; but, if the husband should pass to his rest, the widow is free to marry anyone she wishes, provided he is a believer.
B046C007V040	46	7	40	Yet she will be happier if she remains as she is — in my opinion, for I think that I also have the Spirit of God.  
B046C008V001	46	8	1	With reference to food that has been offered in sacrifice to idols — We are aware that all of us have knowledge! Knowledge breeds conceit, while love builds up character.
B046C008V002	46	8	2	If someone thinks that they know anything, they have not yet reached that knowledge which they ought to have reached.
B046C008V003	46	8	3	On the other hand, if a person loves God, they are known by God.
B046C008V004	46	8	4	With reference, then, to eating food that has been offered to idols — we are aware that an idol is nothing in the world, and that there is no God but one.
B046C008V005	46	8	5	Even supposing that there are so-called ‘gods’ either in heaven or on earth — and there are many such ‘gods’ and ‘lords’ —
B046C008V006	46	8	6	Yet for us there is only one God, the Father, from whom all things come (and for him we live), and one Lord, Jesus Christ, through whom all things come (and through him we live).
B046C008V007	46	8	7	Still, it is not everyone that has this knowledge. Some people, because of their association with idols, continued down to the present time, eat the food as food offered to an idol; and their consciences, while still weak, are dulled.
B046C008V008	46	8	8	What we eat, however, will not bring us nearer to God. We lose nothing by not eating this food, and we gain nothing by eating it.
B046C008V009	46	8	9	But take care that this right of yours does not become in any way a stumbling-block to the weak.
B046C008V010	46	8	10	For if some one should see you who possess this knowledge, feasting in an idol’s temple, will not their conscience, if they are weak, become so hardened that they, too, will eat food offered to idols?
B046C008V011	46	8	11	And so, through this knowledge of yours, the weak person is ruined — someone for whose sake Christ died!
B046C008V012	46	8	12	In this way, by sinning against your fellow followers of the Lord and injuring their consciences, while still weak, you sin against Christ.
B046C008V013	46	8	13	Therefore, if what I eat makes a follower of the Lord fall, rather than make them fall, I will never eat meat again.
B046C009V001	46	9	1	Am I not free? Am I not an apostle? Have I not seen our Lord Jesus? Are not you yourselves my work achieved in union with the Lord?
B046C009V002	46	9	2	If I am not an apostle to others, yet at least I am to you; for you are the seal that stamps me as an apostle in union with the Lord.
B046C009V003	46	9	3	The defence that I make to my critics is this:
B046C009V004	46	9	4	Have not we a right to food and drink?
B046C009V005	46	9	5	Have not we a right to take a wife with us, if she is a Christian, as the other apostles and the Master’s brothers and Cephas all do?
B046C009V006	46	9	6	Or is it only Barnabas and I who have no right to give up working for our bread?
B046C009V007	46	9	7	Does anyone ever serve as a soldier at his own expense? Does anyone plant a vineyard and not eat its produce? Or does anyone look after a herd and not drink the milk?
B046C009V008	46	9	8	Am I, in all this, speaking only from the human standpoint? Does not the law also say the same?
B046C009V009	46	9	9	For in the law of Moses it is said —  ‘You should not muzzle a bullock while it is treading out the grain.’  Is it the bullocks that God is thinking of?
B046C009V010	46	9	10	Or is not is said entirely for our sakes? Surely it was written for our sakes, for the ploughman ought not to plough, nor the thrasher to thrash, without expecting a share of the grain.
B046C009V011	46	9	11	Since we, then, sowed spiritual seed for you, is it too much that we should reap from you an earthly harvest?
B046C009V012	46	9	12	If others share in this right over you, do not we even more? Still we did not avail ourselves of this right. No, we endure anything rather than impede the progress of the good news of the Christ.
B046C009V013	46	9	13	Do not you know that those who do the work of the Temple live on what comes from the Temple, and that those who serve at the altar share the offerings with the altar?
B046C009V014	46	9	14	So, too, the Master has appointed that those who tell the good news should get their living from the good news.
B046C009V015	46	9	15	I, however, have not availed myself of any of these rights. I am not saying this to secure such an arrangement for myself; indeed, I would far rather die — Nobody will make my boast a vain one!
B046C009V016	46	9	16	If I tell the good news, I have nothing to boast of, for I can but do so. Woe is me if I do not tell it!
B046C009V017	46	9	17	If I do this work willingly, I have a reward; but, if unwillingly, I have been charged to perform a duty.
B046C009V018	46	9	18	What is my reward, then? To present the good news free of all cost, and so make but a sparing use of the rights which it gives me.
B046C009V019	46	9	19	Although I was entirely free, yet, to win as many converts as possible, I made myself everyone’s slave.
B046C009V020	46	9	20	To the Jews I became like a Jew, to win Jews. To those who are subject to law I became like a man subject to law — though I was not myself subject to law — to win those who are subject to law.
B046C009V021	46	9	21	To those who have no law I became like a man who has no law — not that I am free from God’s law; no, for I am under Christ’s law — to win those who have no law.
B046C009V022	46	9	22	To the weak I became weak, to win the weak. I have become all things to all people, so as at all costs to save some.
B046C009V023	46	9	23	And I do everything for the sake of the good news, so that with them I may share in its blessings.  
B046C009V024	46	9	24	Do not you know that on a racecourse, though all run, yet only one wins the prize? Run in such a way that you may win.
B046C009V025	46	9	25	Every athlete exercises self-restraint in everything; they, indeed, for a crown that fades, we for one that is unfading.
B046C009V026	46	9	26	I, therefore, run with no uncertain aim. I box — not like a man hitting the air.
B046C009V027	46	9	27	No, I bruise my body and make it my slave, so that I, who have called others to the contest, will not myself be rejected.  
B046C010V001	46	10	1	I want you to bear in mind, friends, that all our ancestors were beneath the cloud, and all passed through the sea;
B046C010V002	46	10	2	that in the cloud and in the sea they all underwent baptism as followers of Moses;
B046C010V003	46	10	3	and that they all ate the same supernatural food,
B046C010V004	46	10	4	and all drank the same supernatural water, for they used to drink from a supernatural rock which followed them, and that rock was the Christ.
B046C010V005	46	10	5	Yet with most of them God was displeased; for they were ‘struck down in the desert.’
B046C010V006	46	10	6	Now these things happened as warnings to us, to teach us not to long for evil things as our forefathers longed.
B046C010V007	46	10	7	Do not become idolaters, as some of them became. Scripture says —  ‘The people sat down to eat and drink, and stood up to dance.’
B046C010V008	46	10	8	Nor let us act immorally, as some of them acted, with the result that twenty-three thousand of them fell dead in a single day.
B046C010V009	46	10	9	Nor let us try the patience of the Lord too far, as some of them tried it, with the result that they ‘were, one after another, destroyed by the snakes.’
B046C010V010	46	10	10	And do not murmur, as some of them murmured, and so ‘were destroyed by the angel of death.’
B046C010V011	46	10	11	These things happened to them by way of warning, and were recorded to serve as a caution to us, in whose days the close of the ages has come.
B046C010V012	46	10	12	Therefore let the person who thinks that they stand take care that they do not fall.
B046C010V013	46	10	13	No temptation has come upon you that is not common to all humanity. God will not fail you, and he will not allow you to be tempted beyond your strength; but, when he sends the temptation, he will also provide the way of escape, so that you may have strength to endure.  
B046C010V014	46	10	14	Therefore, my dear friends, shun the worship of idols.
B046C010V015	46	10	15	I speak to you as man of discernment; form your own judgment about what I am saying.
B046C010V016	46	10	16	In the cup of blessing which we bless, is not there a sharing in the blood of the Christ? And in the bread which we break, is not there a sharing in the body of the Christ?
B046C010V017	46	10	17	The bread is one, and we, though many, are one body; for we all partake of that one bread.
B046C010V018	46	10	18	Look at the people of Israel. Do not those who eat the sacrifices share with the altar?
B046C010V019	46	10	19	What do I mean? That an offering made to an idol, or the idol itself, is anything?
B046C010V020	46	10	20	No; what I say is that the sacrifices offered by the Gentiles ‘are offered to demons and to a being who is no God,’ and I do not want you to share with demons.
B046C010V021	46	10	21	You cannot drink both the Cup of the Lord and the cup of demons. You cannot partake at the Table of the Lord and at the table of demons.
B046C010V022	46	10	22	Or ‘are we to rouse the jealousy of the Lord’? Are we stronger than he?
B046C010V023	46	10	23	Everything is allowable! Yes, but everything is not profitable. Everything is allowable! Yes, but everything does not build up character.
B046C010V024	46	10	24	A person must not study their own interests, but the interests of others.  
B046C010V025	46	10	25	Eat anything that is sold in the market, without making inquiries to satisfy your scruples;
B046C010V026	46	10	26	for ‘the earth, with all that is in it, belongs to the Lord.’
B046C010V027	46	10	27	If an unbeliever invites you to his house and you consent to go, eat anything that is put before you, without making inquiries to satisfy your scruples.
B046C010V028	46	10	28	But, if anyone should say to you ‘This has been offered in sacrifice to an idol,’ then, for the sake of the speaker and his scruples, do not eat it.
B046C010V029	46	10	29	I do not say ‘your’ scruples, but ‘his.’ For why should the freedom that I claim be condemned by the scruples of another?
B046C010V030	46	10	30	If, for my part, I take the food thankfully, why should I be abused for eating that for which I give thanks?  
B046C010V031	46	10	31	Whether, then, you eat or drink or whatever you do, do everything to the honour of God.
B046C010V032	46	10	32	Do not cause offence either to Jews or Greeks or to the church of God;
B046C010V033	46	10	33	for I, also, try to please everybody in everything, not seeking my own advantage, but do what is best for others, so that they may be saved.  
B046C011V001	46	11	1	Imitate me, as I myself imitate Christ.
B046C011V002	46	11	2	I praise you, indeed, because you never forget me, and are keeping my injunctions in mind, exactly as I laid them on you.
B046C011V003	46	11	3	But I am anxious that you should understand that the Christ is the head of every man, that man is the head of woman, and that God is the head of the Christ.
B046C011V004	46	11	4	Any man who keeps his head covered, when praying or preaching in public, dishonours him who is his head;
B046C011V005	46	11	5	while any woman, who prays or preaches in public bare-headed, dishonours him who is her head; for that is to make herself like one of the shameless women who shave their heads.
B046C011V006	46	11	6	Indeed, if a woman does not keep her head covered, she may as well cut her hair short. But, since to cut her hair short, or shave it off, marks her as one of the shameless women, let her keep her head covered.
B046C011V007	46	11	7	A man ought not to have his head covered, for he has been from the beginning ‘the likeness of God’ and the reflection of his glory, but woman is the reflection of man’s glory.
B046C011V008	46	11	8	For it was not man who was taken from woman, but woman who was taken from man.
B046C011V009	46	11	9	Besides, man was not created for the sake of woman, but woman for the sake of man.
B046C011V010	46	11	10	And, therefore, a woman ought to wear on her head a symbol of her subjection, because of the presence of the angels.
B046C011V011	46	11	11	Still, when in union with the Lord, woman is not independent of man, or man of woman;
B046C011V012	46	11	12	for just as woman came from man, so man comes by means of woman; and all things come from God.
B046C011V013	46	11	13	judge for yourselves. Is it fitting that a woman should pray to God in public with her head uncovered?
B046C011V014	46	11	14	Does not nature herself teach us that, while for a man to wear his hair long is degrading to him,
B046C011V015	46	11	15	a woman’s long hair is her glory? Her hair has been given her to serve as a covering.
B046C011V016	46	11	16	If, however, anyone still thinks it right to contest the point — well, we have no such custom, nor have the churches of God.
B046C011V017	46	11	17	In giving directions on the next subject, I cannot praise you; because your meetings do more harm than good.
B046C011V018	46	11	18	To begin with, I hear you and, to some extent, I believe it.
B046C011V019	46	11	19	Indeed, there must be actual parties among you, for so only will the people of real worth become known.
B046C011V020	46	11	20	When you meet together, as I understand, it is not possible to eat the Lord’s Supper;
B046C011V021	46	11	21	for, as you eat, each of you tries to secure his own supper first, with the result that one has too little to eat, and another has too much to drink!
B046C011V022	46	11	22	Have you no houses in which you can eat and drink? Or are you trying to show your contempt for the church of God, and to humiliate the poor? What can I say to you? Should I praise you? In this matter I cannot praise you.
B046C011V023	46	11	23	For I myself received from the Lord the account which I have in turn given to you — how the Lord Jesus, on the very night of his betrayal, took some bread,
B046C011V024	46	11	24	and, after saying the thanksgiving, broke it and said
B046C011V025	46	11	25	And in the same way with the cup, after supper, saying
B046C011V026	46	11	26	For whenever you eat this bread and drink the cup, you proclaim the Lord’s death — until he comes.
B046C011V027	46	11	27	Therefore, whoever eats the bread, or drinks the Lord’s cup, in an irreverent spirit, will have to answer for an offence against the Lord’s body and blood.
B046C011V028	46	11	28	Let everyone look into their own heart, and only then eat of the bread and drink from the cup.
B046C011V029	46	11	29	For the person who eats and drinks brings a judgment on themselves by their eating and drinking, when they do not discern the body.
B046C011V030	46	11	30	That is why so many among you are weak and ill, and why some are sleeping.
B046C011V031	46	11	31	But, if we judged ourselves rightly, we should not be judged.
B046C011V032	46	11	32	Yet, in being judged by the Lord, we are undergoing discipline, so that we may not have judgment passed on us with the rest of the world.
B046C011V033	46	11	33	Therefore, my friends, when you meet together to eat the Supper, wait for one another.
B046C011V034	46	11	34	If anyone is hungry, let them eat at home, so that your meetings may not bring a judgment on you. The other details I will settle when I come.
B046C012V001	46	12	1	In the next place, friends, I do not want you to be ignorant about spiritual gifts.
B046C012V002	46	12	2	You know that there was a time when you were Gentiles, going astray after idols that could not speak, just as you happened to be led.
B046C012V003	46	12	3	Therefore I tell you plainly that no one who speaks under the influence of the Spirit of God says ‘JESUS IS ACCURSED,’ and that no one can say ‘JESUS IS LORD,’ except under the influence of the Holy Spirit.
B046C012V004	46	12	4	Gifts differ, but the Spirit is the same;
B046C012V005	46	12	5	ways of serving differ, yet the Master is the same;
B046C012V006	46	12	6	results differ, yet the God who brings about every result is in every case the same.
B046C012V007	46	12	7	To each of us there is given spiritual illumination for the general good.
B046C012V008	46	12	8	To one is given the power to speak with wisdom through the Spirit; to another the power to speak with knowledge, due to the same Spirit;
B046C012V009	46	12	9	to another faith by the same Spirit; to another power to cure diseases by the one Spirit; to another supernatural powers;
B046C012V010	46	12	10	to another the gift of preaching; to another the gift of distinguishing between true and false inspiration; to another varieties of the gift of ‘tongues’; to another the power to interpret ‘tongues.’
B046C012V011	46	12	11	All these result from one and the same Spirit, who distributes his gifts to each individually as he wills.
B046C012V012	46	12	12	For just as the human body is one whole, and yet has many parts, and all its parts, many though they are, form but one body, so it is with the Christ;
B046C012V013	46	12	13	for it was by one Spirit that we were all baptized to form one body, whether Jews or Greeks, slaves or free, and were all imbued with one Spirit.
B046C012V014	46	12	14	The human body, I repeat, consists not of one part, but of many.
B046C012V015	46	12	15	If the foot says ‘Since I am not a hand, I do not belong to the body,’ it does not because of that cease to belong to the body.
B046C012V016	46	12	16	Or if the ear says ‘Since I am not an eye, I do not belong to the body,’ it does not because of that cease to belong to the body.
B046C012V017	46	12	17	If all the body were an eye, where would the hearing be? If it were all hearing, where would the sense of smell be?
B046C012V018	46	12	18	But in fact God has placed each individual part just where he thought fit in the body.
B046C012V019	46	12	19	If, however, they all made up only one part, where would the body be?
B046C012V020	46	12	20	But in fact, although it has many parts, there is only one body.
B046C012V021	46	12	21	The eye cannot say to the hand ‘I do not need you,’ nor, again, the head to the feet ‘I do not need you.’
B046C012V022	46	12	22	No! Those parts of the body that seem naturally the weaker are indispensable;
B046C012V023	46	12	23	and those parts which we deem less honourable we surround with special honour; and our ungraceful parts receive a special grace which our graceful parts do not require.
B046C012V024	46	12	24	Yes, God has so constructed the body — by giving a special honour to the part that lacks it —
B046C012V025	46	12	25	As to secure that there should be no disunion in the body, but that the parts should show the same care for one another.
B046C012V026	46	12	26	If one part suffers, all the others suffer with it, and if one part has honour done it, all the others share its joy.
B046C012V027	46	12	27	Together you are the body of Christ, and individually its parts.
B046C012V028	46	12	28	In the church God has appointed, first, apostles, secondly preachers, thirdly teachers; then he has given supernatural powers, then power to cure diseases, aptness for helping others, capacity to govern, varieties of the gift of ‘tongues.’
B046C012V029	46	12	29	Can everyone be an apostle? Can everyone be a preacher? Can everyone be a teacher? Can everyone have supernatural powers?
B046C012V030	46	12	30	Can everyone have power to cure diseases? Can everyone speak in ‘tongues’? Can everyone interpret them?
B046C012V031	46	12	31	Strive for the greater gifts.  
B046C013V001	46	13	1	Though I speak in the ‘tongues’ of people, or even of angels, yet have not love, I have become mere echoing brass, or a clanging cymbal!
B046C013V002	46	13	2	Even though I have the gift of preaching, and fathom all hidden truths and all the depths of knowledge; even though I have such faith as might move mountains, yet have not love, I am nothing!
B046C013V003	46	13	3	Even though I dole my substance to the poor, even though I sacrifice my body in order to boast, yet have not love, it avails me nothing!
B046C013V004	46	13	4	love is long-suffering, and kind; love is never envious, never boastful, never conceited, never behaves unbecomingly;
B046C013V005	46	13	5	love is never self-seeking, never provoked, never reckons up her wrongs;
B046C013V006	46	13	6	love never rejoices at evil, but rejoices in the triumph of truth;
B046C013V007	46	13	7	love bears with all things, every trustful, ever hopeful, ever patient.
B046C013V008	46	13	8	love never fails. But, whether it be the gift of preaching, it will be done with; whether it be the gift of ‘tongues,’ it will cease; whether it be knowledge, it, too, will be done with.
B046C013V009	46	13	9	For our knowledge is incomplete, and our preaching is incomplete,
B046C013V010	46	13	10	but, when the perfect has come, that which is incomplete will be done with.
B046C013V011	46	13	11	When I was a child, I talked as a child, I felt as a child, I reasoned as a child; now that I am a man, I have done with childish ways.
B046C013V012	46	13	12	As yet we see, in a mirror, dimly, but then — face to face! As yet my knowledge is incomplete, but then I will know in full, as I have been fully known.
B046C013V013	46	13	13	Meanwhile faith, hope, and love endure — these three, but the greatest of these is love.
B046C014V001	46	14	1	Seek this love earnestly, and strive for spiritual gifts, above all for the gift of preaching.
B046C014V002	46	14	2	The person who, when speaking, uses the gift of ‘tongues’ is speaking, not to people, but to God, for no one understands them; yet in spirit they are speaking of hidden truths.
B046C014V003	46	14	3	But those who preach are speaking to their fellow men and women words that will build up faith, and give them comfort and encouragement.
B046C014V004	46	14	4	Those who, when speaking, use the gift of ‘tongues’ builds up their own faith, while those who preach build up the faith of the church.
B046C014V005	46	14	5	Now I want you all to speak in ‘tongues,’ but much more I wish that you should preach. A preacher is worth more than one who speaks in ‘tongues,’ unless they interprets their words, so that the faith of the church may be built up.
B046C014V006	46	14	6	This being so, friends, what good will I do you, if I come to you and speak in ‘tongues,’ unless my words convey some revelation, or knowledge, or take the form of preaching or teaching?
B046C014V007	46	14	7	Even with inanimate things, such as a flute or a harp, though they produce sounds, yet unless the notes are quite distinct, how can the tune played on the flute or the harp be recognised?
B046C014V008	46	14	8	If the bugle sounds a doubtful call, who will prepare for battle?
B046C014V009	46	14	9	And so with you; unless, in using the gift of ‘tongues,’ you utter intelligible words, how can what you say be understood? You will be speaking to the winds!
B046C014V010	46	14	10	There is, for instance, a certain number of different languages in the world, and not one of them fails to convey meaning.
B046C014V011	46	14	11	If, however, I do not happen to know the language, I will be a foreigner to those who speak it, and they will be foreigners to me.
B046C014V012	46	14	12	And so with you; since your are striving for spiritual gifts, be eager to excel in such as will build up the faith of the church.
B046C014V013	46	14	13	Therefore let him who, when speaking, uses the gift of ‘tongues’ pray for ability to interpret them.
B046C014V014	46	14	14	If, when praying, I use the gift of ‘tongues,’ my spirit indeed prays, but my mind is a blank.
B046C014V015	46	14	15	What, then, is my conclusion? Simply this — I will pray with my spirit, but with my mind as well; I will sing with my spirit, but with my mind as well.
B046C014V016	46	14	16	If you bless God with your spirit only, how can people in the congregation who are without your gift say ‘Amen’ to your thanksgiving? They do not know what you are saying!
B046C014V017	46	14	17	Your thanksgiving may be excellent, but the other is not helped by it.
B046C014V018	46	14	18	Thank God, I use the gift of ‘tongues’ more than any of you.
B046C014V019	46	14	19	But at a meeting of the church I would rather speak five words with my mind, and so teach others, than ten thousand words when using the gift of ‘tongues.’
B046C014V020	46	14	20	My friends, do not show yourselves children in understanding. In wickedness be infants, but in understanding show yourselves adults.
B046C014V021	46	14	21	It is said in the law —  ‘In strange tongues and by the lips of strangers will I speak to this people, but even then they will not listen to me, says the Lord.’
B046C014V022	46	14	22	Therefore the gift of the ‘tongues’ is intended as a sign, not for those who believe in Christ, but for those who do not, while the gift of preaching is intended as a sign, not for those who do not believe in Christ, but for those who do.
B046C014V023	46	14	23	So, when the whole church meets, if all present use the gift of ‘tongues,’ and some people who are without the gift, or who are unbelievers, come in, will not they say that you are mad?
B046C014V024	46	14	24	While, if all those present use the gift of preaching, and an unbeliever, or someone without the gift, comes in, they are convinced of their sinfulness by them all, they are called to account by them all;
B046C014V025	46	14	25	the secrets of their heart are revealed, and then, throwing themselves on their face, they will worship God, and declare ‘God is indeed among you!’  
B046C014V026	46	14	26	What do I suggest, then, friends? Whenever you meet for worship, each of you comes, either with a hymn, or a lesson, or a revelation, or the gift of ‘tongues,’ or the interpretation of them; let everything be directed to the building up of faith.
B046C014V027	46	14	27	If any of you use the gift of ‘tongues,’ not more than two, or at the most three, should do so — each speaking in his turn — and some one should interpret them.
B046C014V028	46	14	28	If there is no one able to interpret what is said, they should remain silent at the meeting of the church, and speak to themselves and to God.
B046C014V029	46	14	29	Of preachers two or three should speak, and the rest should weigh well what is said.
B046C014V030	46	14	30	But, if some revelation is made to another person as he sits there, the first speaker should stop.
B046C014V031	46	14	31	For you can all preach in turn, so that all may learn some lesson and all receive encouragement.
B046C014V032	46	14	32	(The spirit that moves the preachers is within the preachers’ control;
B046C014V033	46	14	33	for God is not a God of disorder, but of peace.) This custom prevails in all the churches of Christ’s people.  
B046C014V034	46	14	34	At the meetings of the church married women should remain silent, for they are not allowed to speak in public; they should take a subordinate place, as the law itself directs.
B046C014V035	46	14	35	If they want information on any point, they should ask their husbands about it at home; for it is unbecoming for a married woman to speak at a meeting of the church.
B046C014V036	46	14	36	What! Did God’s message to the world originate with you? Or did it find its way to none but you?
B046C014V037	46	14	37	If anyone thinks that he has the gift of preaching or any other spiritual gift, let him recognise that what I am now saying to you is a command from the Lord.
B046C014V038	46	14	38	Anyone who ignores it may be ignored.
B046C014V039	46	14	39	Therefore, my friends, strive for the gift of preaching, and yet do not forbid speaking in ‘tongues.’
B046C014V040	46	14	40	Let everything be done in a proper and orderly manner.  
B046C015V001	46	15	1	Next, friends, I would like to remind you of the good news which I told you, and which you received — the good news on which you have taken your stand,
B046C015V002	46	15	2	and by means of which you are being saved. I would like to remind you of the words that I used in telling it to you, since you are still holding fast to it, and since it was not in vain that you became believers in Christ.
B046C015V003	46	15	3	For at the very beginning of my teaching I gave you the account which I had myself received — that Christ died for our sins (as the scriptures had foretold),
B046C015V004	46	15	4	that he was buried, that on the third day he was raised (as the scriptures had foretold),
B046C015V005	46	15	5	and that he appeared to Cephas, and then to the Twelve.
B046C015V006	46	15	6	After that, he appeared to more than five hundred of his followers at one time, most of whom are still alive, though some have gone to their rest.
B046C015V007	46	15	7	After that, he appeared to James, and then to all the apostles.
B046C015V008	46	15	8	Last of all, he appeared even to me, who am, as it were, the abortion.
B046C015V009	46	15	9	For I am the meanest of the apostles, I who am unworthy of the name of ‘apostle,’ because I persecuted the church of God.
B046C015V010	46	15	10	But it is through the love of God that I am what I am, and the love that he showed me has not been wasted. No, I have toiled harder than any of them, and yet it was not I, but the love of God working with me.
B046C015V011	46	15	11	Whether, then, it was I or whether it was they, this we proclaim, and this you believed.
B046C015V012	46	15	12	Now, if it is proclaimed of Christ that he has been raised from the dead, how is it that some of you say that there is no such thing as a resurrection of the dead?
B046C015V013	46	15	13	But, if there is no such thing as a resurrection of the dead, then even Christ has not been raised;
B046C015V014	46	15	14	and, if Christ has not been raised, then our proclamation is without meaning, and our faith without meaning also!
B046C015V015	46	15	15	Yes, and we are being proved to have borne false testimony about God; for we testified of God that he raised the Christ, whom he did not raise, if, indeed, the dead do not rise!
B046C015V016	46	15	16	For, if the dead do not rise, then even Christ himself has not been raised,
B046C015V017	46	15	17	and, if Christ has not been raised, your faith is folly — your sins are on you still!
B046C015V018	46	15	18	Yes, and they, who have passed to their rest in union with Christ, perished!
B046C015V019	46	15	19	If all that we have done has been to place our hope in Christ for this life, then we of all people are the most to be pitied.
B046C015V020	46	15	20	But, in truth, Christ has been raised from the dead, the first-fruits of those who are at rest.
B046C015V021	46	15	21	For, since through a man there is death, so, too, through a man there is a resurrection of the dead.
B046C015V022	46	15	22	For, as through union with Adam all die, so through union with the Christ will all be made to live.
B046C015V023	46	15	23	But each in their proper order — Christ the first-fruits; afterwards, at his coming, those who belong to the Christ.
B046C015V024	46	15	24	Then will come the end — when he surrenders the kingdom to his God and Father, having overthrown all other rule and all other authority and power.
B046C015V025	46	15	25	For he must reign until God ‘has put all his enemies under his feet.’
B046C015V026	46	15	26	The last enemy to be overthrown is death;
B046C015V027	46	15	27	for God has placed all things under Christ’s feet. (But, when it is said that all things have been placed under Christ, it is plain that God is excepted who placed everything under him.)
B046C015V028	46	15	28	And, when everything has been placed under him, the Son will place himself under God who placed everything under him, so that God may be all in all!
B046C015V029	46	15	29	Again, what good will they be doing who are baptized on behalf of the dead? If it is true that the dead do not rise, why are people baptized on their behalf?
B046C015V030	46	15	30	Why, too, do we risk our lives every hour?
B046C015V031	46	15	31	Daily I face death — I swear it, friends, by the pride in you that I feel through my union with Christ Jesus, our Lord.
B046C015V032	46	15	32	If with only human hopes I had fought in the arena at Ephesus, what should I have gained by it? If the dead do not rise, then — ‘Let us eat and drink, for tomorrow we will die’!
B046C015V033	46	15	33	Do not be deceived.  ‘Good character is marred by evil company.’
B046C015V034	46	15	34	Wake up to a righteous life, and cease to sin. There are some who have no true knowledge of God. I speak in this way to shame you.  
B046C015V035	46	15	35	Some one, however, may ask ‘How do the dead rise? And in what body will they come?’
B046C015V036	46	15	36	You foolish person! The seed you yourself sow does not come to life, unless it dies!
B046C015V037	46	15	37	And when you sow, you sow not the body that will be, but a mere grain — perhaps of wheat, or something else.
B046C015V038	46	15	38	God gives it the body that he pleases — to each seed its special body.
B046C015V039	46	15	39	All forms of life are not the same; there is one for people, another for beasts, another for birds, and another for fishes.
B046C015V040	46	15	40	There are heavenly bodies, and earthly bodies; but the beauty of the heavenly bodies is not the beauty of the earthly.
B046C015V041	46	15	41	There is a beauty of the sun, and a beauty of the moon, and a beauty of the stars; for even star differs from star in beauty.
B046C015V042	46	15	42	It is the same with the resurrection of the dead. Sown a mortal body, it rises immortal; sown disfigured, it rises beautiful;
B046C015V043	46	15	43	sown weak, it rises strong; sown a human body, it rises a spiritual body.
B046C015V044	46	15	44	As surely as there is a human body, there is also a spiritual body.
B046C015V045	46	15	45	That is what is meant by the words — ‘Adam, the first man, became a human being’; the last Adam became a life-giving spirit.
B046C015V046	46	15	46	That which comes first is not the spiritual, but the human; afterwards comes the spiritual;
B046C015V047	46	15	47	the first man was from the dust of the earth; the second man from heaven.
B046C015V048	46	15	48	Those who are of the dust are like him who came from the dust; and those who are of heaven are like him who came from heaven.
B046C015V049	46	15	49	And as we have borne the likeness of him who came from the dust, so let us bear the likeness of him who came from heaven.
B046C015V050	46	15	50	This I say, friends — Flesh and blood can have no share in the kingdom of God, nor can the perishable share the imperishable.
B046C015V051	46	15	51	Listen, I will tell you God’s hidden purpose! We will not all have passed to our rest, but we will all be transformed — in a moment, in the twinkling of an eye,
B046C015V052	46	15	52	at the last trumpet-call; for the trumpet will sound, and the dead will rise immortal, and we, also, will be transformed.
B046C015V053	46	15	53	For this perishable body of ours must put on an imperishable form, and this dying body a deathless form.
B046C015V054	46	15	54	And, when this dying body has put on its deathless form, then indeed will the words of scripture come true —
B046C015V055	46	15	55	‘death has been swallowed up in victory! Where, Death, is your victory? Where, death, is your sting?’
B046C015V056	46	15	56	It is sin that gives death its sting, and it is the law that gives sin its power.
B046C015V057	46	15	57	But thanks be to God, who gives us the victory, through Jesus Christ, our Lord.
B046C015V058	46	15	58	Therefore, my dear friends, stand firm, unshaken, always diligent in the Lord’s work, for you know that, in union with him, your toil is not in vain.
B046C016V001	46	16	1	With reference to the collection for Christ’s people, I want you to follow the instructions that I gave to the churches in Galatia.
B046C016V002	46	16	2	On the first day of every week each of you should put by what he can afford, so that no collections need be made after I have come.
B046C016V003	46	16	3	On my arrival, I will send any persons, whom you may authorise by letter, to carry your gift to Jerusalem;
B046C016V004	46	16	4	and, if it appears to be worth while for me to go also, they will go with me.
B046C016V005	46	16	5	I will come to you as soon as I have been through Macedonia — for I am going through Macedonia —
B046C016V006	46	16	6	And I will probably make some stay with you or, perhaps, remain for the winter, so that you may yourselves send me on my way, wherever I may be going.
B046C016V007	46	16	7	I do not propose to pay you a visit in passing now, for I hope to stay with you for some time, if the Lord permits.
B046C016V008	46	16	8	I intend, however, staying at Ephesus until the Festival at the close of the Harvest;
B046C016V009	46	16	9	for a great opening for active work has presented itself, and there are many opponents.  
B046C016V010	46	16	10	If Timothy comes, take care that he has no cause for feeling anxious while he is with you. He is doing the Master’s work no less than I am.
B046C016V011	46	16	11	No one, therefore, should slight him. See him safely on his way to me, for I am expecting him with some of our friends.  
B046C016V012	46	16	12	As for our friend Apollos, I have often urged him to go to you with the others. He has, however, been very unwilling to do so as yet; but he will go as soon as he finds a good opportunity.  
B046C016V013	46	16	13	Be watchful; stand firm in your faith; be brave; be strong.
B046C016V014	46	16	14	Let everything you do be done in a loving spirit.  
B046C016V015	46	16	15	I have another request to make of you, friends. You remember Stephanas and his household, and that they were the first-fruits gathered in from Greece, and set themselves to serve Christ’s people.
B046C016V016	46	16	16	I want you, on your part, to show deference to such people as these, as well as to every fellow labourer and earnest worker.
B046C016V017	46	16	17	I am glad Stephanas and Fortunatus and Achaicus have come, for they have made up for your absence;
B046C016V018	46	16	18	they have cheered my heart, and your hearts also. Recognise the worth of such people as these.  
B046C016V019	46	16	19	The churches in Roman Asia send you their greetings. Aquila and Prisca and the church that meets at their house send you many Christian greetings.
B046C016V020	46	16	20	All of the Lord's followers send you greetings. Greet one another with a sacred kiss.
B046C016V021	46	16	21	I, Paul, add this greeting in my own handwriting.
B046C016V022	46	16	22	Accursed be anyone who has no love for the Lord. THE LORD IS COMING.
B046C016V023	46	16	23	May the blessing of the Lord Jesus be with you.
B046C016V024	46	16	24	My love to all of you who are in union with Christ Jesus.  
B047C001V001	47	1	1	To the church of God in Corinth, and to all Christ’s people throughout Greece, from Paul, an apostle of Christ Jesus, by the will of God, and from Timothy, who is also a follower.
B047C001V002	47	1	2	May God, our Father, and the Lord Jesus Christ bless you and give you peace.
B047C001V003	47	1	3	Blessed is the God and Father of Jesus Christ our Lord, the all-merciful Father, the God ever ready to console,
B047C001V004	47	1	4	who consoles us in all our troubles, so that we may be able to console those who are in any trouble with the consolation that we ourselves receive from him.
B047C001V005	47	1	5	It is true that we have our full share of the sufferings of the Christ, but through the Christ we have also our full share of consolation.
B047C001V006	47	1	6	If we meet with trouble, it is for the sake of your consolation and salvation; and, if we find consolation, it is for the sake of the consolation that you will experience when you are called to endure the sufferings that we ourselves are enduring;
B047C001V007	47	1	7	and our hope for you remains unshaken. We know that, as you are sharing our sufferings, you will also share our consolation.
B047C001V008	47	1	8	We want you, friends, to know that, in the troubles which befell us in Roman Asia, we were burdened altogether beyond our strength, so much so that we even despaired of life.
B047C001V009	47	1	9	Indeed, we had the presentiment that we must die, so that we might rely, not on ourselves, but on God who raises the dead.
B047C001V010	47	1	10	And from so imminent a death God delivered us, and will deliver us again; for in him we have placed our hopes of future deliverance, while you, also, help us by your prayers.
B047C001V011	47	1	11	And then many lips will give thanks on our behalf for the blessing granted us in answer to many prayers.
B047C001V012	47	1	12	Indeed, our main ground for satisfaction is this — Our conscience tells us that our conduct in the world, and still more in our relations with you, was marked by a purity of motive and a sincerity that were inspired by God, and was based, not on worldly policy, but on the help of God.
B047C001V013	47	1	13	We never write anything to you other than what you will acknowledge to the very end —
B047C001V014	47	1	14	And, indeed, you have already partly acknowledged it about us — that you have a right to be proud of us, as we will be proud of you, on the day of our Lord Jesus.
B047C001V015	47	1	15	With this conviction in my mind, I planned to come to see you first, so that your pleasure might be doubled —
B047C001V016	47	1	16	To visit you both on my way to Macedonia, and to come to you again on my return from Macedonia, and then to get you to send me on my way into Judea.
B047C001V017	47	1	17	As this was my plan, where, pray, did I show any fickleness of purpose? Or do you think that my plans are formed on mere impulse, so that in the same breath I say ‘Yes’ and ‘No’?
B047C001V018	47	1	18	As God is true, the message that we brought you does not waver between ‘Yes’ and ‘No’!
B047C001V019	47	1	19	The Son of God, Christ Jesus, whom we — Silas, Timothy, and I — proclaimed among you, never wavered between ‘Yes’ and ‘No.’ With him it has always been ‘Yes.’
B047C001V020	47	1	20	For, many as were the promises of God, in Christ is the ‘Yes’ that fulfils them. Therefore, through Christ again, let the ‘Amen’ rise, through us, to the glory of God.
B047C001V021	47	1	21	God who brings us, with you, into close union with Christ, and who consecrated us,
B047C001V022	47	1	22	also set his seal on us, and gave us his Spirit in our hearts as a pledge of future blessings.
B047C001V023	47	1	23	But, as my life will answer for it, I call God to witness that it was to spare you that I deferred my visit to Corinth.
B047C001V024	47	1	24	I do not mean that we are to dictate to you with regard to your faith; on the contrary, we work with you for your true happiness; indeed, it is through your faith that you are standing firm.  
B047C002V001	47	2	1	For my own sake, as well, I decided not to pay you another painful visit.
B047C002V002	47	2	2	If it is I who cause you pain, why, who is there to cheer me, except the person whom I am paining?
B047C002V003	47	2	3	So I wrote as I did because I was afraid that if I had come, I should have been pained by those who ought to have made me glad; for I felt sure that it was true of you all that my joy was in every case yours also.
B047C002V004	47	2	4	I wrote to you in sore trouble and distress of heart and with many tears, not to give you pain, but to let you see how intense a love I have for you.
B047C002V005	47	2	5	Now whoever has caused the pain has not so much pained me, as he has, to some extent — not to be too severe — pained every one of you.
B047C002V006	47	2	6	The man to whom I refer has been sufficiently punished by the penalty inflicted by the majority of you;
B047C002V007	47	2	7	so that now you must take the opposite course, and forgive and encourage him, or else he may be overwhelmed by the intensity of his pain.
B047C002V008	47	2	8	So I entreat you to assure him of your love.
B047C002V009	47	2	9	I had this further object, also, in what I wrote — to find out whether you might be relied on to be obedient in everything.
B047C002V010	47	2	10	Anyone you forgive, I forgive them, too. Indeed, for my part, whatever I have forgiven (if I have had to forgive anything), I have forgiven for your sakes, in the presence of Christ,
B047C002V011	47	2	11	so as to prevent Satan from taking advantage of us; for we are not ignorant of his devices.  
B047C002V012	47	2	12	When I went to the district round Troas to tell the good news of the Christ, even though there was an opening for serving the Master,
B047C002V013	47	2	13	I could get no peace of mind because I failed to find Titus, my friend; so I took leave of the people there, and went on to Macedonia.
B047C002V014	47	2	14	All thanks to God, who, through our union with the Christ, leads us in one continual triumph, and uses us to spread the sweet perfume of the knowledge of him in every place.
B047C002V015	47	2	15	For we are the fragrance of Christ ascending to God — both among those who are in the path of salvation and among those who are in the path to ruin.
B047C002V016	47	2	16	To the latter we are a stench which arises from death and tells of death; to the former a fragrance which arises from life and tells of life. But who is equal to such a task?
B047C002V017	47	2	17	Unlike many people, we are not in the habit of making profit out of God’s message; but in all sincerity, and bearing God’s commission, we speak before him in union with Christ.  
B047C003V001	47	3	1	Are we beginning to commend ourselves again? Or are we like some who need letters of commendation to you, or from you?
B047C003V002	47	3	2	You yourselves are our letter — a letter written on our hearts, and one which everybody can read and understand.
B047C003V003	47	3	3	All can see that you are a letter from Christ delivered by us, a letter written, not with ink, but with the Spirit of the living God, not on ‘tablets of stone,’ but on ‘tablets of human hearts.’
B047C003V004	47	3	4	This, then, is the confidence in regard to God that we have gained through the Christ.
B047C003V005	47	3	5	I do not mean that we are fit to form any judgment by ourselves, as if on our own authority;
B047C003V006	47	3	6	our fitness comes from God, who himself made us fit to be ministers of a new covenant, of which the substance is, not a written law, but a Spirit. For the written law means death, but the Spirit gives life.
B047C003V007	47	3	7	If the system of religion which involved death, embodied in a written law and engraved on stones, began amid such glory, that the Israelites were unable to gaze at the face of Moses because of its glory, though it was but a passing glory,
B047C003V008	47	3	8	will not the religion that confers the Spirit have still greater glory?
B047C003V009	47	3	9	For, if there was a glory in the religion that involved condemnation, far greater is the glory of the religion that confers righteousness!
B047C003V010	47	3	10	Indeed, that which then had glory has lost its glory, because of the glory which surpasses it.
B047C003V011	47	3	11	And, if that which was to pass away was attended with glory, far more will that which is to endure be surrounded with glory!  
B047C003V012	47	3	12	With such a hope as this, we speak with all plainness;
B047C003V013	47	3	13	unlike Moses, who covered his face with a veil, to prevent the Israelites from gazing at the disappearance of what was passing away.
B047C003V014	47	3	14	But their minds were slow to learn. Indeed, to this very day, at the public reading of the old covenant, the same veil remains ; only for those who are in union with Christ does it pass away.
B047C003V015	47	3	15	But, even to this day, whenever Moses is read, a veil lies on their hearts.
B047C003V016	47	3	16	‘Yet, whenever someone turns to the Lord, the veil is removed.’
B047C003V017	47	3	17	And the ‘Lord’ is the Spirit, and, where the Spirit of the Lord is, there is freedom.
B047C003V018	47	3	18	And all of us, with faces from which the veil is lifted, seeing, as if reflected in a mirror, the glory of the Lord, are being transformed into his likeness, from glory to glory, as it is given by the Lord, the Spirit.  
B047C004V001	47	4	1	Therefore, since it is by God’s mercy that we are engaged in this ministry, we do not lose heart.
B047C004V002	47	4	2	No, we have renounced the secrecy prompted by shame, refusing to adopt crafty ways, or to tamper with God’s message, and commending ourselves to everyone’s conscience, in the sight of God, by our exhibition of the truth.
B047C004V003	47	4	3	And, even if the good news that we bring is veiled, it is veiled only in the case of those who are on the path to ruin —
B047C004V004	47	4	4	people whose minds have been blinded by the God of this age, unbelievers as they are, so that the light from the good news of the glory of the Christ, who is the incarnation of God, should not shine for them.
B047C004V005	47	4	5	(For it is not ourselves that we proclaim, but Christ Jesus, as Lord, and ourselves as your servants for Jesus’ sake.)
B047C004V006	47	4	6	Indeed, the same God who said ‘Out of darkness light will shine,’ has shone in on our hearts, so that we should bring out into the light the knowledge of the glory of God, seen in the face of Christ.
B047C004V007	47	4	7	This treasure we have in these earthen vessels, so that its all-prevailing power may be seen to come from God, and not to be our own.
B047C004V008	47	4	8	Though hard pressed on every side, we are never hemmed in; through perplexed, never driven to despair;
B047C004V009	47	4	9	though pursued, never abandoned; though struck down, never killed!
B047C004V010	47	4	10	We always bear on our bodies the marks of the death that Jesus died, so that the life also of Jesus may be exhibited in our bodies.
B047C004V011	47	4	11	Indeed, we who still live are continually being given over to death for Jesus’ sake, so that the life also of Jesus may be exhibited in our mortal nature.
B047C004V012	47	4	12	And so, while death is at work within us, life is at work within you.
B047C004V013	47	4	13	But, in the same spirit of faith as that expressed in the words — ‘I believed, and therefore I spoke,’ we, also believe, and therefore speak.
B047C004V014	47	4	14	For we know that he who raised the Lord Jesus will raise us also with him, and will bring us, with you, into his presence.
B047C004V015	47	4	15	For all this is for your sakes, so that the loving kindness of God, spreading from heart to heart, may cause yet more hearts to overflow with thanksgiving, to his glory.
B047C004V016	47	4	16	Therefore, as I said, we do not lose heart. No, even though outwardly we are wasting away, yet inwardly we are being renewed day by day.
B047C004V017	47	4	17	The light burden of our momentary trouble is preparing for us, in measure transcending thought, a weight of imperishable glory;
B047C004V018	47	4	18	we, all the while, gazing not on what is seen, but on what is unseen; for what is seen is transient, but what is unseen is imperishable.  
B047C005V001	47	5	1	For we know that if our tent — that earthly body which is now our home — is taken down, we have a house of God’s building, a home not made by hands, imperishable, in heaven.
B047C005V002	47	5	2	Even while in our present body we sigh, longing to put over it our heavenly house,
B047C005V003	47	5	3	sure that, when we have put it on, we will never be found discarnate.
B047C005V004	47	5	4	For we who are in this ‘tent’ sigh under our burden, unwilling to take it off, yet wishing to put our heavenly body over it, so that all that is mortal may be absorbed in life.
B047C005V005	47	5	5	And he who has prepared us for this change is God, who has also given us his Spirit as a pledge.
B047C005V006	47	5	6	Therefore we are always confident, knowing that, while our home is in the body, we are absent from our home with the Lord.
B047C005V007	47	5	7	For we guide our lives by faith, and not by what we see.
B047C005V008	47	5	8	And in this confidence we would gladly leave our home in the body, and make our home with the Lord.
B047C005V009	47	5	9	Therefore, whether in our home or absent from our home, our one ambition is to please him.
B047C005V010	47	5	10	For at the court of the Christ we must all appear in our true characters, so that each may reap the results of the life which he has lived in the body, in accordance with his actions — whether good or worthless.  
B047C005V011	47	5	11	Therefore, because we know the fear inspired by the Lord, it is true that we are trying to win people over, but our motives are plain to God; and I hope that in your inmost hearts they are plain to you also.
B047C005V012	47	5	12	We are not “commending ourselves” again to you, but rather are giving you cause for pride in us, so that you may have an answer ready for those who pride themselves on appearances and not on character.
B047C005V013	47	5	13	For, if we were “beside ourselves,” it was in God’s service! If we are not in our senses, it is in yours!
B047C005V014	47	5	14	It is the love of the Christ which compels us, when we reflect that, as one died for all, therefore all died;
B047C005V015	47	5	15	and that he died for all, so that the living should no longer live for themselves, but for him who died and rose for them.
B047C005V016	47	5	16	For ourselves, then, from this time forward, we refuse to regard anyone from the world’s standpoint. Even if we once thought of Christ from the standpoint of the world, yet now we do so no longer.
B047C005V017	47	5	17	Therefore, if anyone is in union with Christ, he is a new being! His old life has passed away; a new life has begun!
B047C005V018	47	5	18	But all this is the work of God, who reconciled us to himself through Christ, and gave us the Ministry of Reconciliation —
B047C005V019	47	5	19	To proclaim that God, in Christ, was reconciling the world to himself, not reckoning people’s offences against them, and that he had entrusted us with the message of this reconciliation.  
B047C005V020	47	5	20	It is, then, on Christ’s behalf that we are acting as ambassadors, God, as it were, appealing to you through us. We implore you on Christ’s behalf — Be reconciled to God.
B047C005V021	47	5	21	For our sake God made Christ, who was innocent of sin, one with our sinfulness, so that in him we might be made one with the righteousness of God.  
B047C006V001	47	6	1	Therefore, as God’s fellow workers, we also appeal to you not to receive his loving kindness in vain.
B047C006V002	47	6	2	For he says —  ‘At the time for acceptance I listened to you,And on the day of deliverance I helped you.’  Now is the time for acceptance! Now is the day of deliverance!
B047C006V003	47	6	3	Never do we put an obstacle in anyone’s way, so that no fault may be found with our ministry.
B047C006V004	47	6	4	No, we are trying to commend ourselves under all circumstances, as God’s ministers should — in many an hour of endurance, in troubles, in hardships, in difficulties,
B047C006V005	47	6	5	in floggings, in imprisonments, in riots, in toils, in sleepless nights, in fastings;
B047C006V006	47	6	6	by purity, by knowledge, by patience, by kindliness, by holiness of spirit, by unfeigned love;
B047C006V007	47	6	7	by the message of truth, and by the power of God; by the weapons of righteousness in the right hand and in the left;
B047C006V008	47	6	8	amid honour and disrepute, amid slander and praise; regarded as deceivers, yet proved to be true;
B047C006V009	47	6	9	as unknown, yet well-known; as at death’s door, yet, see, we are living; as chastised, yet not killed;
B047C006V010	47	6	10	as saddened, yet always rejoicing; as poor, yet enriching many; as having nothing, and yet possessing all things!
B047C006V011	47	6	11	We have been speaking freely to you, dear friends in Corinth; we have opened our heart;
B047C006V012	47	6	12	there is room there for you, yet there is not room, in your love, for us.
B047C006V013	47	6	13	Can you not in return — I appeal to you as I should to children — open your hearts to us?
B047C006V014	47	6	14	Do not enter into inconsistent relations with those who reject the faith. For what partnership can there be between righteousness and lawlessness? Or what has light to do with darkness?
B047C006V015	47	6	15	What harmony can there be between Christ and Belial? Or what can those who accept the faith have in common with those who reject it?
B047C006V016	47	6	16	What agreement can you be between a temple of God and idols? And we are a temple of the living God. That is what God meant when he said —  ‘I will live among them, and walk among them;And I will be their God, and they will be my people.
B047C006V017	47	6	17	Therefore “Come out from among the nations, and separate yourselves from them,” says the Lord,“And touch nothing impure;And I will welcome you;
B047C006V018	47	6	18	and I will be a father to you, and you will be my sons and daughters,”says the Lord, the Ruler of all.’ 
B047C007V001	47	7	1	With these promises, dear friends, let us purify ourselves from everything that pollutes either body or spirit, and, in deepest respect for God, aim at perfect holiness.
B047C007V002	47	7	2	Make room for us in your hearts. In no instance have we ever wronged, or harmed, or taken advantage of, anyone.
B047C007V003	47	7	3	I am not saying this to condemn you. Indeed, I have already said that you are in our heart, to live and die together.
B047C007V004	47	7	4	I have the utmost confidence in you; I am always boasting about you. I am full of encouragement and, in spite of all our troubles, my heart is overflowing with happiness.  
B047C007V005	47	7	5	Ever since we reached Macedonia, we have had no rest in body or mind; on every side there have been troubles — conflicts without, anxieties within.
B047C007V006	47	7	6	But God, who encourages the downcast, has encouraged us by the arrival of Titus.
B047C007V007	47	7	7	And it is not only by his arrival that we are encouraged, but also by the encouragement which he received from you; for he tells us of your strong affection, your penitence, and your zeal on my behalf — so that I am happier still.
B047C007V008	47	7	8	For, though I caused you sorrow by my letter, I do not regret it. Even if I were inclined to regret it — for I see that my letter did cause you sorrow though only for a time —
B047C007V009	47	7	9	I am glad now; not because of the sorrow it caused you, but because your sorrow brought you to repentance. For it was God’s will that you should feel sorrow, in order that you should not suffer loss in any way at our hands.
B047C007V010	47	7	10	For, when sorrow is in accordance with God’s will, it results in a repentance leading to salvation, and which will never be regretted. The sure result of the sorrow that the world knows is death.
B047C007V011	47	7	11	For see what results that other sorrow — sorrow in accordance with God’s will — has had in your case. What earnestness it produced! What explanations! What strong feeling! What alarm! What longing! What eagerness! What readiness to punish! You have proved yourselves altogether free from guilt in that matter.
B047C007V012	47	7	12	So, then, even though I did write to you, it was not for the sake of the wrong-doer, or of the man who was wronged, but to make you conscious, in the sight of God, of your own earnest care for us. And it is this that has encouraged us.  
B047C007V013	47	7	13	In addition to the encouragement that this gave us, we were made far happier still by the happiness of Titus for his heart has been cheered by you all.
B047C007V014	47	7	14	Although I have been boasting a little to him about you, you did not put me to shame; but, just as every thing we had said to you was true, so our boasting to Titus about you has also proved to be the truth.
B047C007V015	47	7	15	And his affection for you is all the greater, as he remembers the deference that you all showed him, and recalls how you received him with anxious care.
B047C007V016	47	7	16	I am glad that I can feel perfect confidence in you.  
B047C008V001	47	8	1	We want to remind you, friends, of the love that God has shown to the churches in Macedonia —
B047C008V002	47	8	2	How, tired though they were by many a trouble, their overflowing happiness, and even their deep poverty, resulted in a flood of generosity.
B047C008V003	47	8	3	I can bear witness that to the full extent of their power, and even beyond their power, spontaneously,
B047C008V004	47	8	4	and with many an appeal to us for permission, they showed their love, and contributed their share towards the fund for their fellow Christians.
B047C008V005	47	8	5	And that, not only in the way we had expected; but first they gave themselves to the Lord, and to us also, in accordance with God’s will.
B047C008V006	47	8	6	And this led us beg Titus, since he had started the work for you, he should also see to the completion of this expression of your love.
B047C008V007	47	8	7	And, remembering how you excel in everything — in faith, in teaching, in knowledge, in unfailing earnestness, and in the affection that we have awakened in you — I ask you to excel also in this expression of your love.
B047C008V008	47	8	8	I am not laying a command on you, but I am making use of the earnestness shown by others to test the genuineness of your affection.
B047C008V009	47	8	9	For you do not forget the loving kindness of our Lord Jesus Christ — how that for your sakes, although he was rich, he became poor, so that you also might become rich through his poverty.
B047C008V010	47	8	10	I am only making suggestions on this matter; for this is the best course for you, since you were a year before others, not only in taking action, but also in showing your readiness to do so.
B047C008V011	47	8	11	And now I want you to complete the work, so that its completion may correspond with your willing readiness — in proportion, of course, to your means.
B047C008V012	47	8	12	For, where there is willingness, a person’s gift is valued by its comparison with what they have, and not with what they do not have.
B047C008V013	47	8	13	For our object is not to give relief to others and bring distress on you. It is a matter of a fair balance.
B047C008V014	47	8	14	On this occasion what you can spare will supply what they need, at another time what they can spare may supply your need, and so things will be equal.
B047C008V015	47	8	15	As scripture says —  ‘Those who had much had nothing over, and those who had little did not lack!’
B047C008V016	47	8	16	I thank God for inspiring Titus with the same keen interest in your welfare that I have;
B047C008V017	47	8	17	for Titus has responded to my appeals and, in his great earnestness, is starting to go to you of his own accord.
B047C008V018	47	8	18	We are sending with him one of the Lord's followers whose fame in the service of the good news has spread through all the churches;
B047C008V019	47	8	19	and not only that, but he has been elected by the churches to accompany us on our journey, in connexion with this expression of your love, which we are personally administering to the honour of the Lord, and to show our deep interest.
B047C008V020	47	8	20	What we are specially guarding against is that any fault should be found with us in regard to our administration of this charitable fund;
B047C008V021	47	8	21	for we are trying to make arrangements which will be right, not only in the eyes of the Lord, but also in the eyes of people.
B047C008V022	47	8	22	We are also sending with them another of our friends, whose earnestness we have many a time proved in many ways, and whom we now find made even more earnest by his great confidence in you.
B047C008V023	47	8	23	If I must say anything about Titus, he is my intimate companion, and he shares my work for you; if it is our friends, they are delegates of the churches, an honour to Christ.
B047C008V024	47	8	24	Show them, therefore — so that the churches may see it — the proof of your affection, and the ground for our boasting to them about you.  
B047C009V001	47	9	1	With reference, indeed, to the Fund for your fellow Christians, it is quite superfluous for me to say anything to you.
B047C009V002	47	9	2	I know, of course, your willingness to help, and I am always boasting of it to the Macedonians. I tell them that you in Greece have been ready for a year past; and it was really your zeal that stimulated most of them.
B047C009V003	47	9	3	So my reason for sending our friends is to prevent what we said about you from proving, in this particular matter, an empty boast, and to enable you to be as well prepared as I have been saying that you are.
B047C009V004	47	9	4	Otherwise, if any Macedonians were to come with me, and find you unprepared, we — to say nothing of you — should feel ashamed of our present confidence.
B047C009V005	47	9	5	Therefore I think it necessary to beg the friends to go to you in advance, and to complete the arrangements for the gift, which you have already promised, so that it may be ready, as a gift, before I come, and not look as if it were being given under pressure.
B047C009V006	47	9	6	Remember the saying — ‘Scanty sowing, scanty harvest; plentiful sowing, plentiful harvest.’
B047C009V007	47	9	7	Let everyone give as he has determined before hand, not grudgingly or under compulsion; for God loves ‘a cheerful giver.’
B047C009V008	47	9	8	God has power to shower all kinds of blessings on you, so that, having, under all circumstances and on all occasions, all that you can need, you may be able to shower all kinds of benefits on others.
B047C009V009	47	9	9	(As scripture says —  ‘He scattered broadcast, he gave to the poor; His righteousness continues for ever.’
B047C009V010	47	9	10	And he who supplies ‘seed to the sower, and bread for eating,’ will supply you with seed, and cause it to increase, and will multiply ‘the fruits of your righteousness’).
B047C009V011	47	9	11	Rich in all things yourselves, you will be able to show liberality to all, which, with our help, will cause thanksgiving to be offered to God.
B047C009V012	47	9	12	For the rendering of a public service such as this, not only relieves the needs of your fellow Christians, but also results in the offering to God of many a thanksgiving.
B047C009V013	47	9	13	Through the evidence afforded by the service rendered, you cause people to praise God for your fidelity to your profession of faith in the good news of the Christ, as well as for the liberality of your contributions for them and for all others.
B047C009V014	47	9	14	And they also, in their prayers for you, express their longing to see you, because of the surpassing love of God displayed toward you.
B047C009V015	47	9	15	All thanks to God for his inestimable gift!  
B047C010V001	47	10	1	Now, I, Paul, make a personal appeal to you by the meekness and gentleness of the Christ — I who, “in your presence, am humble in my bearing towards you, but, when absent, am bold in my language to you” —
B047C010V002	47	10	2	I implore you not to drive me to “show my boldness,” when I do come, by the confident tone which I expect to have to adopt towards some of you, who are expecting to find us influenced in our conduct by earthly motives.
B047C010V003	47	10	3	For, though we live an earthly life, we do not wage an earthly war.
B047C010V004	47	10	4	The weapons for our warfare are not earthly, but, under God, are powerful enough to pull down strongholds.
B047C010V005	47	10	5	We are engaged in confuting arguments and pulling down every barrier raised against the knowledge of God. We are taking captive every hostile thought, to bring it into submission to the Christ,
B047C010V006	47	10	6	and are fully prepared to punish every act of rebellion, when once your submission is complete.
B047C010V007	47	10	7	You look at the outward appearance of things! Let anyone, who is confident that he belongs to Christ, reflect, for himself, again on the fact — that we belong to Christ no less than he does.
B047C010V008	47	10	8	Even if I boast extravagantly about our authority — which the Lord gave us for building up your faith and not for overthrowing it — still I have no reason to be ashamed.
B047C010V009	47	10	9	I say this so that it doesn't seem as if I am trying to overawe you by my letters.
B047C010V010	47	10	10	For people say “His letters are impressive and vigorous, but his personal appearance is insignificant and his speaking contemptible.”
B047C010V011	47	10	11	Let such a person be assured of this — that our words in our letters show us to be, when absent, just what our deeds will show us to be, when present.
B047C010V012	47	10	12	We have not indeed the audacity to class or compare ourselves with some of those who indulge in self-commendation! But, when such persons measure themselves by themselves, and compare themselves with themselves, they show a want of wisdom.
B047C010V013	47	10	13	We, however, will not give way to unlimited boasting, but will confine ourselves to the limits of the sphere to which God limited us, when he permitted us to come as far as Corinth.
B047C010V014	47	10	14	For it is not the case, as it would be if we were not in the habit of coming to you, that we are exceeding our bounds! Why, we were the very first to reach you with the good news of the Christ!
B047C010V015	47	10	15	Our boasting, therefore, is not unlimited, nor does it extend to the labours of others; but our hope is that, as your faith grows, our influence among you may be very greatly increased — though still confined to our sphere —
B047C010V016	47	10	16	So that we will be able to tell the good news in the districts beyond you, without trespassing on the sphere assigned to others, or boasting of what has been already done.
B047C010V017	47	10	17	‘Let anyone who boasts make their boast of the Lord.’
B047C010V018	47	10	18	For it is not those who commend themselves that stand the test, but those who are commended by the Lord.
B047C011V001	47	11	1	I could wish that you would tolerate a little folly in me! But indeed you do tolerate me.
B047C011V002	47	11	2	I am jealous over you with the jealousy of God. For I engaged you to one husband so that I might present you to the Christ a pure bride.
B047C011V003	47	11	3	Yet I fear that it may turn out that, just as the snake by his craftiness deceived Eve, so your minds may have lost the loyalty and purity due from you to the Christ.
B047C011V004	47	11	4	For, if some newcomer is proclaiming a Jesus other than him whom we proclaimed, or if you are receiving a Spirit different from the Spirit which you received, or a good news different from that which you welcomed, then you are marvellously tolerant!
B047C011V005	47	11	5	I do not regard myself as in any way inferior to the most eminent apostles!
B047C011V006	47	11	6	Though I am no trained orator, yet I am not without knowledge; indeed we made this perfectly clear to you in every way.
B047C011V007	47	11	7	Perhaps you say that I did wrong in humbling myself that you might be exalted — I mean because I told you God’s good news without payment.
B047C011V008	47	11	8	I robbed other churches by taking pay from them, so that I might serve you!
B047C011V009	47	11	9	And, when I was with you in need, I did not become a burden to any of you; for our friends, on coming from Macedonia, supplied my needs. I kept myself, and will keep myself from being an expense to you in any way.
B047C011V010	47	11	10	As surely as I know anything of the truth of Christ, this boast, as far as I am concerned, will not be stopped in any part of Greece.
B047C011V011	47	11	11	Why? Because I do not love you? God knows that I do!  
B047C011V012	47	11	12	What I am doing now I will continue to do in order to cut away the ground from under those who are wishing for some ground for attacking me, so that as regards the thing of which they boast they may appear in their true characters, just as we do.
B047C011V013	47	11	13	Such people are false apostles, treacherous workers, disguising themselves as apostles of Christ!
B047C011V014	47	11	14	And no wonder; for even Satan disguises himself as an angel of light.
B047C011V015	47	11	15	It is not surprising, therefore, if his servants also disguise themselves as servants of righteousness. But their end will be in accordance with their actions.  
B047C011V016	47	11	16	I say again — Let no one think me a fool! Yet, if you do, at least welcome me as you would a fool, so that I, too may indulge in a little boasting.
B047C011V017	47	11	17	When I speak like this, I am not speaking as the Master would, but as a fool might, in boasting so confidently.
B047C011V018	47	11	18	As so many are boasting of earthly things, I, too, will boast.
B047C011V019	47	11	19	For all your cleverness, you tolerate fools willingly enough!
B047C011V020	47	11	20	You tolerate a person even when they enslave you, when they plunder you, when they get you into their power, when they put on airs of superiority, when they strike you in the face!
B047C011V021	47	11	21	I admit, to my shame, that we have been weak. But whatever the subject on which others are not afraid to boast — though it is foolish to say so — I am not afraid either!
B047C011V022	47	11	22	Are they Hebrews? So am I! Are they Israelites? So am I! Are they descendants of Abraham? So am I!
B047C011V023	47	11	23	Are they ‘Servants of Christ’? Though it is madness to talk like this, I am more so than they! I have had more of toil, more of imprisonment! I have been flogged times without number. I have been often at death’s door.
B047C011V024	47	11	24	Five times I received at the hands of my own people forty lashes, all but one.
B047C011V025	47	11	25	Three times I was beaten with rods. Once I was stoned. Three times I was shipwrecked. I have spent a whole day and night in the deep.
B047C011V026	47	11	26	My journeys have been many. I have been through dangers from rivers, dangers from robbers, dangers from my own people, dangers from the Gentiles, dangers in towns, dangers in the country, dangers on the sea, dangers among people pretending to be followers of the Lord.
B047C011V027	47	11	27	I have been through toil and hardship. I have passed many a sleepless night; I have endured hunger and thirst; I have often been without food; I have known cold and nakedness.
B047C011V028	47	11	28	And, not to speak of other things, there is my daily burden of anxiety about all the churches.
B047C011V029	47	11	29	Who is weak without my being weak? Who is led astray without my burning with indignation?
B047C011V030	47	11	30	If I must boast, I will boast of things which show my weakness!
B047C011V031	47	11	31	The God and Father of the Lord Jesus — he who is for ever blessed — knows that I am speaking the truth.
B047C011V032	47	11	32	When I was in Damascus, the Governor under King Aretas had the gates of that city guarded, so as to arrest me,
B047C011V033	47	11	33	but I was let down in a basket through a window in the wall, and so escaped his hands.
B047C012V001	47	12	1	I must boast! It is unprofitable; but I will pass to visions and revelations given by the Lord.
B047C012V002	47	12	2	I know a man in union with Christ, who, fourteen years ago — whether in the body or out of the body I do not know; God knows — was caught up (this man of whom I am speaking) to the third heaven.
B047C012V003	47	12	3	And I know that this man — whether in the body or separated from the body I do not know; God knows —
B047C012V004	47	12	4	Was caught up into Paradise, and heard unspeakable things of which no human being may tell.
B047C012V005	47	12	5	About such a man I will boast, but about myself I will not boast except as regards my weaknesses.
B047C012V006	47	12	6	Yet if I choose to boast, I will not be a fool; for I will be speaking no more than the truth. But I refrain, in case anyone should credit me with more than he can see in me or hear from me, and because of the marvellous character of the revelations.
B047C012V007	47	12	7	It was for this reason, and to prevent my thinking too highly of myself, that a thorn was sent to pierce my flesh — an instrument of Satan to discipline me — so that I should not think too highly of myself.
B047C012V008	47	12	8	About this I three times entreated the Lord, praying that it might leave me.
B047C012V009	47	12	9	But his reply has been —  Most gladly, then, will I boast all the more of my weaknesses, so that the strength of the Christ may overshadow me.
B047C012V010	47	12	10	That is why I delight in weakness, ill treatment, hardship, persecution, and difficulties, when borne for Christ. For, when I am weak, then it is that I am strong!  
B047C012V011	47	12	11	I have been “playing the fool!” It is you who drove me to it. For it is you who ought to have been commending me! Although I am nobody, in no respect did I prove inferior to the most eminent apostles.
B047C012V012	47	12	12	The marks of the true apostle were exhibited among you in constant endurance, as well as by signs, by marvels, and by miracles.
B047C012V013	47	12	13	In what respect, I ask, were you treated worse than the other churches, unless it was that, for my part, I refused to become a burden to you? Forgive me the wrong I did to you!
B047C012V014	47	12	14	Remember, this is the third time that I have made every preparation to come to see you, and I will refuse to be a burden to you; I want, not your money, but you. It is not the duty of children to put by for their parents, but of parents to put by for their children.
B047C012V015	47	12	15	For my part, I will most gladly spend, and be spent, for your welfare. Can it be that the more intensely I love you the less I am to be loved?
B047C012V016	47	12	16	You will admit that I was not a burden to you but you say that I was “crafty” and caught you “by a trick”!
B047C012V017	47	12	17	Do you assert that I took advantage of you through any of those whom I have sent to you?
B047C012V018	47	12	18	I urged Titus to go, and I sent another follower with him. Did Titus take any advantage of you? Did not we live in the same Spirit, and tread in the same footsteps?  
B047C012V019	47	12	19	Have you all this time been fancying that it is to you that we are making our defence? No, it is in the sight of God, and in union with Christ, that we are speaking. And all this, dear friends, is to build up your characters;
B047C012V020	47	12	20	for I am afraid that perhaps, when I come, I may find that you are not what I want you to be, and, on the other hand, that you may find that I am what you do not want me to be. I am afraid that I may find quarrelling, jealousy, ill feeling, rivalry, slandering, backbiting, self-assertion, and disorder.
B047C012V021	47	12	21	I am afraid that, on my next visit, my God may humble me in regard to you, and that I may have to mourn over many who have long been sinning, and have not repented of the impurity, immorality, and sensuality, in which they have indulged.  
B047C013V001	47	13	1	For the third time I am coming to see you. ‘By the word of two or three witnesses each statement will be established.’
B047C013V002	47	13	2	I have said it, and I say it again before I come, just as if I were with you on my second visit, though for the moment absent, I say to those who have been long sinning, as well as to all others — that if I come again, I will spare no one.
B047C013V003	47	13	3	And that will be the proof, which you are looking for, that the Christ speaks through me. There is no weakness in his dealings with you. No, he shows his power among you.
B047C013V004	47	13	4	For though his crucifixion was due to weakness, his life is due to the power of God. And we, also, are weak in his weakness, but with him we will live for you through the power of God.
B047C013V005	47	13	5	Put yourselves to the proof, to see whether you are holding to the faith. Test yourselves. Surely you recognise this fact about yourselves — that Jesus Christ is in you! Unless indeed you cannot stand the test!
B047C013V006	47	13	6	But I hope that you will recognise that we can stand the test.
B047C013V007	47	13	7	We pray God that you may do nothing wrong, not that we may be seen to stand the test, but that you may do what is right, even though we may seem not to stand the test.
B047C013V008	47	13	8	We have no power at all against the truth, but we have power in the service of the truth.
B047C013V009	47	13	9	We are glad when we are weak, if you are strong. And what we pray for is that you may become perfect.
B047C013V010	47	13	10	This is my reason for writing as I am now doing, while I am away from you, so that, when I am with you, I may not act harshly in the exercise of the authority which the Lord gave me — and gave me for building up and not for pulling down.
B047C013V011	47	13	11	And now, friends, goodbye. Aim at perfection; take courage; agree together; live in peace. And then God, the source of all love and peace, will be with you.
B047C013V012	47	13	12	Greet one another with a sacred kiss.
B047C013V013	47	13	13	All Christ’s people here send you their greetings.
B047C013V014	47	13	14	May the blessing of the Lord Jesus Christ, and the love of God, and the communion with the Holy Spirit, be with you all.
B048C001V001	48	1	1	To the churches in Galatia, from Paul, an apostle whose commission is not from any human authority and is given, not by human beings, but by Jesus Christ and God the Father who raised him from the dead;
B048C001V002	48	1	2	and from all the followers of the Lord here.
B048C001V003	48	1	3	May God, our Father, and the Lord Jesus Christ, bless you and give you peace. For Christ, to rescue us from this present wicked age,
B048C001V004	48	1	4	gave himself for our sins, in accordance with the will of God and Father,
B048C001V005	48	1	5	to whom be ascribed all glory for ever and ever. Amen.
B048C001V006	48	1	6	I am astonished at your so soon deserting him, who called you through the love of Christ, for a different ‘good news,’
B048C001V007	48	1	7	Which is really no good news at all. But then, I know that there are people who are harassing you, and who want to pervert the good news of the Christ.
B048C001V008	48	1	8	Yet even if we — or if an angel from heaven were to tell you any other ‘good news’ than that which we told you, may he be accursed!
B048C001V009	48	1	9	We have said it before, and I repeat it now — If anyone tells you a ‘good news’ other than that which you received, may he be accursed!
B048C001V010	48	1	10	Is this, I ask, trying to conciliate people, or God? Am I seeking to please people? If I were still trying to please people, I should not be a servant of Christ.
B048C001V011	48	1	11	I remind you, friends, that the good news which I told is no mere human invention.
B048C001V012	48	1	12	I, at least, did not receive it from any human being, nor was I taught it, but it came to me through a revelation made by Jesus Christ.
B048C001V013	48	1	13	You heard, no doubt, of my conduct when I was devoted to Judaism — how I persecuted the church of God to an extent beyond belief, and made havoc of it,
B048C001V014	48	1	14	and how, in my devotion to Judaism, I surpassed many of my contemporaries among my own people in my intense earnestness in upholding the traditions of my ancestors.
B048C001V015	48	1	15	But when God, who had set me apart even before my birth, and who called me by his love,
B048C001V016	48	1	16	saw fit to reveal his Son in me, so that I might tell the good news of him among the Gentiles, then at once, instead of consulting any human being,
B048C001V017	48	1	17	or even going up to Jerusalem to see those who were apostles before me, I went to Arabia, and came back again to Damascus.
B048C001V018	48	1	18	Three years afterwards I went up to Jerusalem to make the acquaintance of Peter, and I stayed a fortnight with him.
B048C001V019	48	1	19	I did not, however, see any other apostle, except James, the Master’s brother.
B048C001V020	48	1	20	(As to what I am now writing to you, I call God to witness that I am speaking the truth).
B048C001V021	48	1	21	Afterwards I went to the districts of Syria and Cilicia.
B048C001V022	48	1	22	But I was still unknown even by sight to the Christian churches in Judea;
B048C001V023	48	1	23	all that they had heard was — ‘The man who once persecuted us is now telling the good news of the faith of which he once made havoc.’
B048C001V024	48	1	24	And they praised God for my sake.  
B048C002V001	48	2	1	Fourteen years afterwards I went up to Jerusalem again with Barnabas, and I took Titus also with me.
B048C002V002	48	2	2	It was in obedience to a revelation that I went; and I laid before the apostles the good news that I am proclaiming among the Gentiles. I did this privately before those who are thought highly of because I was afraid that I might possibly be taking, or might have already taken, a course which would prove useless.
B048C002V003	48	2	3	Yet even my companion, Titus, though a Greek, was not compelled to be circumcised.
B048C002V004	48	2	4	But, because of those who pretended to be followers who had stolen in, the intruders who had crept in to spy on the liberty which we have through union with Christ Jesus, in order to bring us back to slavery —
B048C002V005	48	2	5	Why, we did not for a moment yield submission to them, so that the truth of the good news might be yours always!
B048C002V006	48	2	6	Of those who are thought somewhat highly of — what they once were makes no difference to me; God does not recognise human distinctions — those, I say, who are thought highly of added nothing to my message.
B048C002V007	48	2	7	On the contrary, they saw that I had been entrusted with the good news for the Gentiles, just as Peter had been for the Jews.
B048C002V008	48	2	8	For he who gave Peter power for his mission to the Jews gave me, also, power to go to the Gentiles.
B048C002V009	48	2	9	Recognising the charge entrusted to me, James, Peter, and John, who were regarded as pillars of the church, openly acknowledged Barnabas and me as fellow workers, agreeing that we should go to the Gentiles, and they to the Jews.
B048C002V010	48	2	10	Only we were to remember the poor — the thing I was myself anxious to do.
B048C002V011	48	2	11	But, when Peter came to Antioch, I opposed him to his face; for he stood self-condemned.
B048C002V012	48	2	12	Before certain persons came from James, he had been in the habit of eating with the Gentile converts; but, when they came, he began to withdraw and hold aloof, because he was afraid of offending those who still held to circumcision.
B048C002V013	48	2	13	The rest of the Jewish converts were guilty of the same hypocrisy, so that even Barnabas was led away by it.
B048C002V014	48	2	14	But, when I saw that they were not dealing straightforwardly with the truth of the good news, I said to Peter, before them all, “If you, who were born a Jew, adopt Gentile customs, instead of Jewish, why are you trying to compel the Gentile converts to adopt Jewish customs?”
B048C002V015	48	2	15	We, though we are Jews by birth and not outcasts of Gentile origin, know that no one is pronounced righteous as the result of obedience to law, but only through faith in Christ Jesus.
B048C002V016	48	2	16	So we placed our faith in Christ Jesus, in order that we might be pronounced righteous, as the result of faith in Christ, and not of obedience to law; for such obedience ‘will not result in even one soul’s being pronounced righteous.’
B048C002V017	48	2	17	If, while seeking to be pronounced righteous through union with Christ, we were ourselves seen to be outcasts, would that make Christ an agent of sin? Heaven forbid!
B048C002V018	48	2	18	For, if I rebuild the things that I pulled down, I prove myself to have done wrong.
B048C002V019	48	2	19	I, indeed, through law became dead to law, in order to live for God.
B048C002V020	48	2	20	I have been crucified with Christ. So it is no longer I that live, but it is Christ who lives in me; and, as for my present earthly life, I am living it by faith in the Son of God, who loved me and gave himself for me.
B048C002V021	48	2	21	I do not reject the love of God. If righteousness comes through law, then there was no need for Christ to die!
B048C003V001	48	3	1	Foolish Galatians! Who has been fascinating you — you before whose eyes Jesus Christ was depicted on the cross?
B048C003V002	48	3	2	Here is the one thing that I want to find out from you — Did you receive the Spirit as the result of obedience to law, or of your having listened with faith?
B048C003V003	48	3	3	Can you be so foolish? After beginning with what is spiritual, do you now end with what is external?
B048C003V004	48	3	4	Did you go through so much to no purpose? — if indeed it really was to no purpose!
B048C003V005	48	3	5	He who supplies you abundantly with his Spirit and endows you with such powers — does he do this as the result of obedience to law? Or as the result of your having listened with faith?
B048C003V006	48	3	6	It is just as it was with Abraham —  ‘He had faith in God, and his faith was regarded by God as righteousness.’
B048C003V007	48	3	7	You see, then, that those whose lives are based on faith are the sons of Abraham.
B048C003V008	48	3	8	And scripture, foreseeing that God would pronounce the Gentiles righteous as the result of faith, foretold the good news to Abraham in the words —  ‘Through you all the Gentiles will be blessed.’
B048C003V009	48	3	9	And, therefore, those whose lives are based on faith share the blessings bestowed on the faith of Abraham.
B048C003V010	48	3	10	All who rely on obedience to law are under a curse, for scripture says —  ‘Cursed is everyone who does not abide by all that is written in the book of the law, and do it.’
B048C003V011	48	3	11	Again, it is evident that no one is pronounced righteous before God through law, for we read —  ‘Through faith the righteous will find life.’
B048C003V012	48	3	12	But the law is not based on faith; no, its words are —  ‘Those who practice these precepts will find life through them.’
B048C003V013	48	3	13	Christ ransomed us from the curse pronounced in the law, by taking the curse on himself for us, for scripture says —  ‘Cursed is anyone who is hanged on a tree.’
B048C003V014	48	3	14	And this he did that the blessing given to Abraham might be extended to the Gentiles through their union with Jesus Christ; that so, through our faith, we also might receive the promised gift of the Spirit.
B048C003V015	48	3	15	To take an illustration, friends, from daily life — No one sets aside even an agreement between two people, when once it has been confirmed, nor do they add conditions to it.
B048C003V016	48	3	16	Now it was to Abraham that the promises were made, ‘and to his offspring.’ It was not said ‘to his offsprings,’ as if many persons were meant, but the words were ‘to your offspring,’ showing that one person was meant — and that was Christ.
B048C003V017	48	3	17	My point is this — An agreement already confirmed by God cannot be canceled by the law, which came four hundred and thirty years later, so as to cause the promise to be set aside.
B048C003V018	48	3	18	If our heritage is the result of law, then it has ceased to be the result of a promise. Yet God conferred it on Abraham by a promise.  
B048C003V019	48	3	19	What, then, you ask, was the use of the law? It was a later addition, to make people conscious of their wrong-doings, and intended to last only until the coming of that ‘offspring’ to whom the promise had been made; and it was delivered through angels by a mediator.
B048C003V020	48	3	20	Now mediation implies more than one person, but God is one only.
B048C003V021	48	3	21	Does that set the law in opposition to God’s promises? Heaven forbid! For, if a law had been given capable of bestowing life, then righteousness would have actually owed its existence to law.
B048C003V022	48	3	22	But the words of scripture represent the whole world as being in bondage to sin, so that the promised blessing, dependent, as it is, on faith in Jesus Christ, may be given to those who have faith in him.  
B048C003V023	48	3	23	Before the coming of faith, we were kept under the guard of the law, in bondage, awaiting the faith that was destined to be revealed.
B048C003V024	48	3	24	Thus the law has proved a guide to lead us to Christ, in order that we may be pronounced righteous as the result of faith.
B048C003V025	48	3	25	But now that faith has come we no longer need a guide.
B048C003V026	48	3	26	For you are all sons of God, through your faith in Christ Jesus.
B048C003V027	48	3	27	For all of you who were baptized into union with Christ clothed yourselves with Christ.
B048C003V028	48	3	28	All distinctions between Jew and Greek, slave and free, male and female, have vanished; for in union with Christ Jesus you are all one.
B048C003V029	48	3	29	And, since you belong to Christ, it follows that you are Abraham’s offspring and, under the promise, sharers in the inheritance.  
B048C004V001	48	4	1	My point is this — As long as the heir is under age, there is no difference between him and a slave, though he is master of the whole estate.
B048C004V002	48	4	2	He is subject to the control of guardians and stewards, during the period for which his father has power to appoint them.
B048C004V003	48	4	3	And so is it with us; when we were under age, as it were, we were slaves to the puerile teaching of this world;
B048C004V004	48	4	4	but, when the full time came, God sent his Son — born a woman’s child, born subject to law —
B048C004V005	48	4	5	To ransom those who were subject to law, so that we might take our position as sons.
B048C004V006	48	4	6	And it is because you are sons that God sent into our hearts the Spirit of his Son, with the cry — ‘Abba, our Father.’
B048C004V007	48	4	7	You, therefore, are no longer a slave, but a son; and, if a son, then an heir also, by God’s appointment.  
B048C004V008	48	4	8	Yet formerly, in your ignorance of God, you became slaves to ‘gods’ which were no gods.
B048C004V009	48	4	9	But now that you have found God — or, rather, have been found by him — how is it that you are turning back to that poor and feeble puerile teaching, to which yet once again you are wanting to become slaves?
B048C004V010	48	4	10	You are scrupulous in keeping days and months and seasons and years!
B048C004V011	48	4	11	You make me fear that the labour which I have spent on you may have been wasted.
B048C004V012	48	4	12	I entreat you, friends, to become like me, as I became like you. You have never done me any wrong.
B048C004V013	48	4	13	You remember that it was owing to bodily infirmity that on the first occasion I told you the good news.
B048C004V014	48	4	14	And as for what must have tried you in my condition, it did not inspire you with scorn or disgust, but you welcomed me as if I had been an angel of God — or Christ Jesus himself!
B048C004V015	48	4	15	What has become then, of your blessings? For I can bear witness that, had it been possible, you would have torn out your eyes and given them to me!
B048C004V016	48	4	16	Am I to think, then, that I have become your enemy by telling you the truth?
B048C004V017	48	4	17	Certain people are seeking your favour, but with no honourable object. No, indeed, they want to isolate you, so that you will have to seek their favour.
B048C004V018	48	4	18	It is always honourable to have your favour sought in an honourable cause, and not only when I am with you, my dear children —
B048C004V019	48	4	19	You for whom I am again enduring a mother’s pains, until a likeness to Christ will have been formed in you.
B048C004V020	48	4	20	But I could wish to be with you now and speak in a different tone, for I am perplexed about you.
B048C004V021	48	4	21	Tell me, you who want to be still subject to law — Why do not you listen to the law?
B048C004V022	48	4	22	scripture says that Abraham had two sons, one the child of the slave-woman and the other the child of the free woman.
B048C004V023	48	4	23	But the child of the slave-woman was born in the course of nature, while the child of the free woman was born in fulfilment of a promise.
B048C004V024	48	4	24	This story may be taken as an allegory. The women stand for two Covenants. One covenant, given from Mount Sinai, produces a race of slaves and is represented by Hagar
B048C004V025	48	4	25	(The word Hagar meaning in Arabia Mount Sinai) and it ranks with the Jerusalem of today, for she and her children are in slavery.
B048C004V026	48	4	26	But the Jerusalem above is free, and she it is who is our mother.
B048C004V027	48	4	27	For scripture says —  ‘Rejoice, you barren one, who does never bear,Break into shouts, you who are never in labour,For many are the children of her who is desolate —aye, more than of her who has a husband.’
B048C004V028	48	4	28	As for ourselves, friends, we, like Isaac, are children born in fulfilment of a promise.
B048C004V029	48	4	29	Yet at that time the child born in the course of nature persecuted the child born by the power of the Spirit; and it is the same now.
B048C004V030	48	4	30	But what does the passage of scripture say?  ‘Send away the slave-woman and her son; for the slave’s son will not be coheir with the son of the free woman.’
B048C004V031	48	4	31	And so, friends, we are not children of a slave, but of her who is free.
B048C005V001	48	5	1	It is for freedom that Christ set us free; stand firm therefore, and do not again be held under the yoke of slavery.
B048C005V002	48	5	2	Understand that I, Paul, myself tell you that if you allow yourselves to be circumcised, Christ will avail you nothing.
B048C005V003	48	5	3	I again declare to everyone who receives circumcision, that he binds himself to obey the whole law.
B048C005V004	48	5	4	You have severed yourselves from Christ — you who are seeking to be pronounced righteous through law; you have fallen away from love.
B048C005V005	48	5	5	For we, by the help of the Spirit, are eagerly waiting for the fulfilment of our hope — that we may be pronounced righteous as the result of faith.
B048C005V006	48	5	6	If we are in union with Christ Jesus, neither is circumcision nor the omission of it anything, but faith, working through love, is everything.
B048C005V007	48	5	7	You were once making good progress! Who has hindered you from obeying the truth?
B048C005V008	48	5	8	The persuasion brought to bear on you does not come from him who calls you.
B048C005V009	48	5	9	A little leaven leavens all the dough.
B048C005V010	48	5	10	I, through my union with the Lord, am persuaded that you will learn to think with me. But the man who is disturbing your minds will have to bear his punishment, whoever he may be.
B048C005V011	48	5	11	If I, friends, am still proclaiming circumcision, why am I still persecuted? It seems that the cross has ceased to be an obstacle!
B048C005V012	48	5	12	I could even wish that the people who are unsettling you would go further still and mutilate themselves.
B048C005V013	48	5	13	Remember, friends, to you the call came to give you freedom. Only do not make your freedom an opportunity for self-indulgence, but serve one another in a loving spirit.
B048C005V014	48	5	14	Indeed, the whole law has been summed up in this one precept —  ‘You must love your neighbour as you love yourself.’
B048C005V015	48	5	15	But, if you are continually wounding and preying on one another, take care that you are not destroyed by one another.
B048C005V016	48	5	16	This is what I have to say — Let your steps be guided by the Spirit, and then you will never gratify the cravings of your earthly nature.
B048C005V017	48	5	17	For these cravings of our earthly nature conflict with the Spirit, and the Spirit with our earthly nature — they are two contrary principles — so that you cannot do what you wish.
B048C005V018	48	5	18	But, if you follow the guidance of the Spirit, you are not subject to law.
B048C005V019	48	5	19	The sins of our earthly nature are unmistakable. They are sins like these — sexual immorality, impurity, indecency,
B048C005V020	48	5	20	idolatry, sorcery, quarrels, strife, jealousy, outbursts of passion, rivalries, dissensions, divisions,
B048C005V021	48	5	21	feelings of envy, drunkenness, revelry, and the like. And I warn you, as I warned you before, that those who indulge in such things will have no place in the kingdom of God.
B048C005V022	48	5	22	But the fruit produced by the Spirit is love, joy, peace, forbearance, kindliness, generosity, trustfulness, gentleness, self-control.
B048C005V023	48	5	23	Against such things there is no law!
B048C005V024	48	5	24	And those who belong to Jesus, the Christ, have already crucified their earthly nature, with its passions and its cravings.  
B048C005V025	48	5	25	Since our life is due to the Spirit, let us rule our conduct also by the Spirit.
B048C005V026	48	5	26	Do not let us grow vain, and provoke or envy one another.  
B048C006V001	48	6	1	My friends, even if someone should be caught committing a sin, you who are spiritually minded should, in a gentle spirit, help them to recover themselves, taking care that you yourselves are not tempted.
B048C006V002	48	6	2	Bear one another’s burdens, and so carry out the law of the Christ.
B048C006V003	48	6	3	If a person imagines themselves to be somebody, when they are really nobody, they deceive themselves.
B048C006V004	48	6	4	Let everyone test their own work, and then their cause for satisfaction will be in themselves and not in a comparison with their neighbour;
B048C006V005	48	6	5	for everyone must bear their own load.
B048C006V006	48	6	6	The person, however, who is being instructed in the message ought always to share their blessings with their teacher.
B048C006V007	48	6	7	Do not be deceived. God cannot be mocked. What a person sows that they will reap.
B048C006V008	48	6	8	For the person who sows the field of their earthly nature will from that earthly nature reap corruption; while the one who sows the field of the spirit will from that spirit reap eternal life.
B048C006V009	48	6	9	Let us never tire of doing right, for at the proper season we will reap our harvest, if we do not grow weary.
B048C006V010	48	6	10	Therefore, I say, as the opportunity occurs, let us treat everyone with kindness, and especially members of the Household of the faith.  
B048C006V011	48	6	11	See in what large letters I am writing with my own hand.
B048C006V012	48	6	12	Those who wish to appear to advantage in regard to outward observances are the people who are trying to compel you to be circumcised; and they do it only to avoid being persecuted for the cross of Jesus, the Christ.
B048C006V013	48	6	13	Even these men who are circumcised do not themselves keep the law; yet they want you to be circumcised, so that they may boast of your observance of the rite.
B048C006V014	48	6	14	But, for my part, may I never boast of anything except the cross of Jesus Christ, our Master, through whom the world has been crucified to me, and I to the world.
B048C006V015	48	6	15	For neither is circumcision nor the omission of it anything; but a new nature is everything.
B048C006V016	48	6	16	May all who rule their conduct by this principle find peace and mercy — they who are the Israel of God.
B048C006V017	48	6	17	For the future let no one trouble me; for I bear the marks of Jesus branded on my body.
B048C006V018	48	6	18	May the blessing of Jesus Christ, our Lord, rest on your souls, friends. Amen.
B049C001V001	49	1	1	To Christ’s people at Ephesus who are faithful to him, from Paul, an apostle of Christ Jesus, by the will of God.
B049C001V002	49	1	2	May God, our Father, and the Lord Jesus Christ bless you and give you peace.
B049C001V003	49	1	3	Blessed is the God and Father of Jesus Christ, our Lord, who has blessed us on high with every spiritual blessing, in Christ.
B049C001V004	49	1	4	For he chose us in our union with Christ before the creation of the universe, so that we might be holy and blameless in his sight, living in the spirit of love.
B049C001V005	49	1	5	From the first he destined us, in his goodwill towards us, to be adopted as sons through Jesus Christ,
B049C001V006	49	1	6	and so to enhance that glorious manifestation of his loving kindness which he gave us in the one he loves;
B049C001V007	49	1	7	for in him, and through the shedding of his blood, we have found redemption in the pardon of our offences.
B049C001V008	49	1	8	All this accords with the loving kindness which God lavished on us, accompanied by countless gifts of wisdom and discernment,
B049C001V009	49	1	9	when he made known to us his hidden purpose. And it also accords with the goodwill which God purposed to exhibit in Christ,
B049C001V010	49	1	10	in view of that divine order which was to mark the completion of the ages, when he should make everything, both in heaven and on earth, centre in him.
B049C001V011	49	1	11	In him, I say, for by our union with him we became God’s heritage, having from the first been destined for this in the intention of him who, in all that happens, is carrying out his own fixed purpose;
B049C001V012	49	1	12	that we should enhance his glory — we who have been the first to rest our hopes on the Christ.
B049C001V013	49	1	13	And you, too, by your union with him, after you had heard the message of the truth, the good news of your salvation — you believed in him and were sealed as his by receiving the holy Spirit, which he had promised.
B049C001V014	49	1	14	And the Spirit is a pledge of our future heritage, foreshadowing the full redemption of God’s own people — to enhance his glory.
B049C001V015	49	1	15	And therefore I, ever since I heard of the faith in the Lord Jesus which prevails among you, and of your confidence in all Christ’s people,
B049C001V016	49	1	16	have never omitted to thank God on your behalf, whenever I make mention of you in my prayers.
B049C001V017	49	1	17	My prayer is that the God of Jesus Christ our Lord, the all-glorious Father, may inspire you with wisdom and true insight through a fuller knowledge of himself;
B049C001V018	49	1	18	that your minds may be so enlightened that you may realise the hope given by God’s call, the wealth of the glory of his heritage among Christ’s people,
B049C001V019	49	1	19	and the transcendent greatness of the power which he is able to exercise in dealing with us who believe in him.
B049C001V020	49	1	20	The same mighty power was exerted on the Christ, when he raised the Christ from the dead and ‘caused him to sit at his right hand’ on high, exalting him above all angels and archangels of every rank,
B049C001V021	49	1	21	and above every name that can be named, whether in the present age, or in the age to come.
B049C001V022	49	1	22	And God placed ‘all things under Christ’s feet,’ and gave him to the church as its supreme head;
B049C001V023	49	1	23	for the church is Christ’s body, and is filled by him who fills all things everywhere with his presence.
B049C002V001	49	2	1	You yourselves were once dead because of your offences and sins.
B049C002V002	49	2	2	For at one time you lived in sin, following the ways of the world, in subjection to the Ruler of the powers of the air — the Spirit who is still at work among the disobedient.
B049C002V003	49	2	3	And it was among them that we all once lived our lives, indulging the cravings of our earthly nature, and carrying out the desires prompted by that earthly nature and by our own thoughts. Our nature exposed us to the divine wrath, like the rest of humanity.
B049C002V004	49	2	4	Yet God, in his abundant compassion, and because of the great love with which he loved us,
B049C002V005	49	2	5	even though we were ‘dead’ because of our offences, gave life to us in giving life to the Christ. (By God’s loving kindness you have been saved.)
B049C002V006	49	2	6	And, through our union with Christ Jesus, God raised us with him, and caused us to sit with him on high,
B049C002V007	49	2	7	in order that, by his goodness to us in Christ Jesus, he might display in the ages to come the boundless wealth of his loving kindness.
B049C002V008	49	2	8	For it is by God’s loving kindness that you have been saved, through your faith. It is not due to yourselves; the gift is God’s.
B049C002V009	49	2	9	It is not due to obedience to law, so that no one can boast.
B049C002V010	49	2	10	For we are God’s handiwork, created, by our union with Christ Jesus, for the good actions in doing which God had pre-arranged that we should spend our lives.
B049C002V011	49	2	11	Remember, therefore, that you were once Gentiles yourselves, as your bodies showed; you were called ‘The Uncircumcised’ by those who were called ‘The Circumcised’ — circumcised only by human hands!
B049C002V012	49	2	12	Remember that you were at that time far from Christ; you were shut out from the citizenship of Israel; you were strangers to the Covenants founded on God’s Promise; you were in the world without hope and without God.
B049C002V013	49	2	13	But now, through your union with Christ Jesus, you who once were ‘far off’ have, by the shedding of the blood of the Christ, been brought ‘near.’
B049C002V014	49	2	14	He it is who is our peace. He made the two divisions of humanity one, broke down the barrier that separated them,
B049C002V015	49	2	15	and in his human nature put an end to the cause of enmity between them — the law with its injunctions and ordinances — in order to create, through union with himself, from Jew and Gentile, one new humanity and so make peace.
B049C002V016	49	2	16	And when, on the cross, he had destroyed their mutual enmity, he sought by means of his cross to reconcile them both to God, united in one body.
B049C002V017	49	2	17	He came with the good news of peace for you who were ‘far off,’ and of peace for those who were ‘near’;
B049C002V018	49	2	18	for it is through him that we, the Jews and the Gentiles, united in the one Spirit, are now able to approach the Father.
B049C002V019	49	2	19	It follows, then, that you are no longer strangers and aliens, but are fellow citizens with Christ’s people and members of God’s Household.
B049C002V020	49	2	20	You have been built up on the foundation laid by the apostles and prophets, Christ Jesus himself being ‘the corner-stone.’
B049C002V021	49	2	21	United in him, every part of the building, closely joined together, will grow into a Temple, consecrated by its union with the Lord.
B049C002V022	49	2	22	And, through union in him, you also are being built up together, to be a place where God lives through the Spirit.  
B049C003V001	49	3	1	For this reason I, Paul, the prisoner of Jesus, the Christ, for the sake of you Gentiles —
B049C003V002	49	3	2	For you have heard, I suppose, of the responsible charge with which God entrusted me for your benefit,
B049C003V003	49	3	3	and also that it was by direct revelation that the hidden purpose of God was made known to me, as I have already briefly told you.
B049C003V004	49	3	4	And, by reading what I have written, you will be able to judge how far I understand this hidden purpose of God in Christ.
B049C003V005	49	3	5	In former generations it was not made known to humanity, as fully as it has now been revealed by the Spirit to the apostles and prophets among Christ’s people —
B049C003V006	49	3	6	That, by union with Christ Jesus and through the good news, the Gentiles are coheirs with us and members of one body, and that they share with us in God’s Promise.
B049C003V007	49	3	7	Of this good news I became a minister, in virtue of the charge with which God entrusted me in the exercise of his power —
B049C003V008	49	3	8	Yes, to me, who am less than the least of all Christ’s people, was this charge entrusted! — to tell the Gentiles the good news of the boundless wealth to be found in the Christ,
B049C003V009	49	3	9	and to make clear what is God’s way of working out that hidden purpose which from the first has been concealed in the mind of the Creator of all things;
B049C003V010	49	3	10	so that now to the archangels and to all the powers on high should be made known, through the church, the all-embracing wisdom of God,
B049C003V011	49	3	11	in accordance with that purpose which runs through all the ages and which he has now accomplished in Jesus, the Christ, our Master.
B049C003V012	49	3	12	And in union with him, and through our trust in him, we find courage to approach God with confidence.
B049C003V013	49	3	13	Therefore I beg you not to be disheartened at the sufferings that I am undergoing for your sakes; for they redound to your honour.
B049C003V014	49	3	14	For this reason, then, I kneel before the Father —
B049C003V015	49	3	15	From whom all ‘fatherhood’ in heaven and on earth derives its name —
B049C003V016	49	3	16	And pray that, in proportion to the wealth of his glory, he will strengthen you with his power by breathing his Spirit into your inmost soul,
B049C003V017	49	3	17	so that the Christ, through your faith, may make his home within your hearts in love; And I pray that you, now firmly rooted and established, may, with all Christ’s people,
B049C003V018	49	3	18	have the power to comprehend in all its width and length and height and depth,
B049C003V019	49	3	19	and to understand — though it surpasses all understanding — the love of the Christ; and so be filled to the full with God himself.
B049C003V020	49	3	20	To him who, through his power which is at work within us, is able to do far more than anything that we can ask or conceive —
B049C003V021	49	3	21	To him be all glory through the church and through Christ Jesus, for all generations, age after age. Amen.
B049C004V001	49	4	1	I beg you, then — I who am a prisoner in the Master’s cause — to live lives worthy of the call that you have received;
B049C004V002	49	4	2	always humble and gentle, patient, bearing lovingly with one another,
B049C004V003	49	4	3	and striving to maintain in the bond of peace the unity given by the Spirit.
B049C004V004	49	4	4	There is but one body and one Spirit, just as there was but one hope set before you when you received your call.
B049C004V005	49	4	5	There is but one Lord, one faith, one baptism.
B049C004V006	49	4	6	There is but one God and Father of all — the God who is over all, pervades all, and is in all.
B049C004V007	49	4	7	Everyone of us, however, has been entrusted with some charge, each in accordance with the extent of the gift of the Christ.
B049C004V008	49	4	8	That is why it is said —  ‘When he went up on high, he led his captives into captivity. And gave gifts to humanity.’
B049C004V009	49	4	9	Now surely this ‘going up’ must imply that he had already gone down into the world beneath.
B049C004V010	49	4	10	He who went down is the same as he who went up — up beyond the highest heaven, so that he might fill all things with his presence.
B049C004V011	49	4	11	And he it is who gave to the church apostles, prophets, Missionaries, Pastors, and teachers,
B049C004V012	49	4	12	to fit his people for the work of the ministry, for the building up of the body of the Christ.
B049C004V013	49	4	13	And this will continue, until we all attain to that unity which is given by faith and by a fuller knowledge of the Son of God; until we reach maturity — the full standard of the perfection of the Christ.
B049C004V014	49	4	14	Then we will no longer be like infants, tossed backward and forward, blown about by every breath of human teaching and by people's trickery and craftiness;
B049C004V015	49	4	15	but holding the truth in a spirit of love, we will grow into complete union with him who is our head — Christ himself.
B049C004V016	49	4	16	For from him the whole body, closely joined and knit together by the contact of every part with the source of its life, derives its power to grow, in proportion to the vigour of each individual part; and so is being built up in a spirit of love.
B049C004V017	49	4	17	This, then, as one in union with the Lord, I implore: Do not continue to live such purposeless lives as the Gentiles live,
B049C004V018	49	4	18	with their powers of discernment darkened, cut off from the life of God, owing to the ignorance that prevails among them and to the hardness of their hearts.
B049C004V019	49	4	19	Lost to all sense of shame, they have abandoned themselves to licentiousness, in order to practice every kind of impurity without restraint.
B049C004V020	49	4	20	But far different is the lesson you learned from the Christ — if, that is, you really listened to him,
B049C004V021	49	4	21	and through union with him were taught the truth, as it is to be found in Jesus.
B049C004V022	49	4	22	For you learned with regard to your former way of living that you must cast off your old nature, which, yielding to deluding passions, grows corrupt;
B049C004V023	49	4	23	that the spirit of your minds must be constantly renewed;
B049C004V024	49	4	24	and that you must clothe yourselves in that new nature which was created to resemble God, with the righteousness and holiness springing from the truth.
B049C004V025	49	4	25	Since, therefore, you have cast off what is false, ‘you must every one of you speak the truth to your neighbours.’ For we are united to one another like the parts of a body.
B049C004V026	49	4	26	‘Be angry, yet do not sin.’ Do not let the sun go down on your anger;
B049C004V027	49	4	27	and give no opportunity to the devil.
B049C004V028	49	4	28	Let the person who steals steal no longer, but rather let them toil with their hands at honest work, so that they may have something to share with anyone in need.
B049C004V029	49	4	29	Never let any foul word pass your lips, but only such good words as the occasion demands, so that they may be a help to those who hear them.
B049C004V030	49	4	30	And do not grieve God’s Holy Spirit; for it was through that Spirit that God sealed you as his, against the day of Redemption.
B049C004V031	49	4	31	Let all bitterness, passion, anger, brawling, and abusive language be banished from among you, as well as all malice.
B049C004V032	49	4	32	Be kind to one another, tenderhearted, ready to forgive one another, just as God, in Christ, forgave you.  
B049C005V001	49	5	1	Therefore imitate God, as his dear children,
B049C005V002	49	5	2	and live a life of love, following the example of the Christ, who loved you and gave himself for you as ‘an offering and a sacrifice to God, that should be fragrant and acceptable.’
B049C005V003	49	5	3	As for sexual immorality and every kind of impurity, or greed, do not let them even be mentioned among you, as befits Christ’s people,
B049C005V004	49	5	4	nor shameful conduct, nor foolish talk or jesting, for they are wholly out of place among you; but rather thanksgiving.
B049C005V005	49	5	5	For of this you may be sure — that no one who is unchaste or impure or greedy of gain (for to be greedy of gain is idolatry) has any place awaiting him in the kingdom of the Christ and God.  
B049C005V006	49	5	6	Do not let anyone deceive you with specious arguments. Those are the sins that bring down the wrath of God on the disobedient.
B049C005V007	49	5	7	Therefore have nothing to do with such people.
B049C005V008	49	5	8	For, although you were once in darkness, now, by your union with the Lord, you are in the light. Live as ‘children of light’ —
B049C005V009	49	5	9	For the outcome of life in the light may be seen in every form of goodness, righteousness, and sincerity —
B049C005V010	49	5	10	Always trying to find out what is pleasing to the Lord.
B049C005V011	49	5	11	Take no part in deeds of darkness, from which no good can come; on the contrary, expose them.
B049C005V012	49	5	12	It is degrading even to speak of the things continually done by them in secret.
B049C005V013	49	5	13	All such actions, when exposed, have their true character made manifest by the light.
B049C005V014	49	5	14	For everything that has its true character made manifest is clear as light. And that is why it is said —  ‘Sleeper, awake!Arise from the dead,And the Christ will give you light!’
B049C005V015	49	5	15	Take great care, then, how you live — not unwisely but wisely,
B049C005V016	49	5	16	making the most of every opportunity; for these are evil days.
B049C005V017	49	5	17	Therefore do not grow thoughtless, but try to understand what the Lord’s will is.
B049C005V018	49	5	18	Do not drink wine to excess, for that leads to profligacy; but seek to be filled with the Spirit of God, and speak to one another in psalms and hymns and sacred songs.
B049C005V019	49	5	19	Sing and make music in your hearts to the Lord.
B049C005V020	49	5	20	Always give thanks for everything to our God and Father, in the name of our Lord Jesus Christ;
B049C005V021	49	5	21	and submit to one another because you honour and respect him.  
B049C005V022	49	5	22	Wives should submit to their husbands as submitting to the Lord.
B049C005V023	49	5	23	For a man is the head of his wife, as the Christ is the head of the church — being indeed himself the Saviour of his body.
B049C005V024	49	5	24	But as the church submits to the Christ, so also should wives submit to their husbands in everything.
B049C005V025	49	5	25	Husbands, love your wives, just as the Christ loved the church, and gave himself for her,
B049C005V026	49	5	26	to make her holy, after purifying her by the washing with the water, according to his promise;
B049C005V027	49	5	27	so that he might himself bring the church, in all her beauty, into his own presence, with no spot or wrinkle or blemish of any kind, but that she might be holy and faultless.
B049C005V028	49	5	28	That is how husbands ought to love their wives — as if they were their own bodies. A man who loves his wife is really loving himself;
B049C005V029	49	5	29	for no one ever yet hated his own body. But everyone feeds his body and cares for it, just as the Christ for the church;
B049C005V030	49	5	30	for we are members of his body.
B049C005V031	49	5	31	‘For this cause a man will leave his father and mother, and be united to his wife; and the man and his wife will become one.’
B049C005V032	49	5	32	In this there is a profound truth — I am speaking of Christ and his church.
B049C005V033	49	5	33	However, for you individually, let each love his wife as if she were himself; and the wife be careful to respect her husband.  
B049C006V001	49	6	1	children, obey your parents, as children of the Lord; for that is but right.
B049C006V002	49	6	2	‘Honour your father and mother’ — this is the first Commandment with a promise —
B049C006V003	49	6	3	‘So that you may prosper and have a long life on earth.’
B049C006V004	49	6	4	And fathers, do not irritate your children, but bring them up with Christian discipline and instruction.
B049C006V005	49	6	5	Slaves, obey your earthly masters, with anxious care, giving them ungrudging service, as if obeying the Christ;
B049C006V006	49	6	6	not only when their eyes are on you, as if you had merely to please people, but as slaves of Christ, who are trying to carry out the will of God.
B049C006V007	49	6	7	Give your service heartily and cheerfully, as working for the Master and not for people;
B049C006V008	49	6	8	for you know that everyone will be rewarded by the Master for any honest work that he has done, whether he is a slave or free.
B049C006V009	49	6	9	And masters, treat your slaves in the same spirit. Give up threatening them; for you know that he who is both their Master and yours is in heaven, and that before him there is no distinction of rank.  
B049C006V010	49	6	10	For the future, find strength in your union with the Lord, and in the power which comes from his might.
B049C006V011	49	6	11	Put on the full armour of God, so that you may be able to stand your ground against the stratagems of the devil.
B049C006V012	49	6	12	For ours is no struggle against enemies of flesh and blood, but against all the various powers of evil that hold sway in the darkness around us, against the spirits of Wickedness on high.
B049C006V013	49	6	13	Therefore take up the full armour of God, so that when the evil day comes, you may be able to withstand the attack, and, having fought to the end, still to stand your ground.
B049C006V014	49	6	14	Stand your ground, then, ‘with truth for your belt,’ and ‘with righteousness for your breast-plate,’
B049C006V015	49	6	15	And with the readiness to serve the good news of peace as shoes for your feet.
B049C006V016	49	6	16	At every onslaught take up faith for your shield; for with it you will be able to extinguish all the flaming darts of the evil one.
B049C006V017	49	6	17	And receive ‘the helmet of salvation,’ and ‘the sword of the Spirit’ — which is the message of God — always with prayer and supplication.
B049C006V018	49	6	18	Pray in spirit at all times. Be intent on this, with unwearying perseverance and supplication for all Christ’s people —
B049C006V019	49	6	19	And on my behalf also, so that when I begin to speak, words may be given me, so that I may fearlessly make known the inmost truth of the good news,
B049C006V020	49	6	20	on behalf of which I am an ambassador — in chains! Pray that, in telling it, I may speak fearlessly as I ought.  
B049C006V021	49	6	21	To enable you, as well as others, to know all that concerns me and what I am doing, Tychicus, our dear friend and faithful helper in the Master’s cause, will tell you everything.
B049C006V022	49	6	22	I am sending him to you on purpose that you may learn all about us, and that he may cheer your hearts.
B049C006V023	49	6	23	May God, the Father, and the Lord Jesus Christ give every follower peace, and love linked with faith.
B049C006V024	49	6	24	May God’s blessing be with all who love our Lord Jesus Christ with an undying love.
B050C001V001	50	1	1	To all Christ’s people at Philippi, with the presiding officers and assistants, from Paul and Timothy, servants of Christ Jesus.
B050C001V002	50	1	2	May God, our Father, and the Lord Jesus Christ bless you, and give you peace.
B050C001V003	50	1	3	Every recollection that I have of you is a cause of thankfulness to God,
B050C001V004	50	1	4	always, in every prayer that I offer for you all — my prayers are full of joy —
B050C001V005	50	1	5	Because of the share that you have had in spreading the good news, from the first day that you received it until now.
B050C001V006	50	1	6	For of this I am confident, that he who began a good work in you will complete it in readiness for the day of Jesus Christ.
B050C001V007	50	1	7	And, indeed, I am justified in feeling like this about you all; because you have a warm place in my heart — you who all, both in my imprisonment and in the work of defending and establishing the good news, shared my privilege with me.
B050C001V008	50	1	8	God will bear me witness how I yearn over you all with the tenderness of Christ Jesus.
B050C001V009	50	1	9	And what I pray for is this — that your love may grow yet stronger and stronger, with increasing knowledge and all discernment,
B050C001V010	50	1	10	until you are able to appreciate all moral distinctions. And I pray, too, that you may be kept pure and blameless against the day of Christ,
B050C001V011	50	1	11	bearing a rich harvest of that righteousness which comes through Jesus Christ, to the glory and praise of God.
B050C001V012	50	1	12	Friends, I want you to realise that what has happened to me has actually served to forward the good news.
B050C001V013	50	1	13	It has even become evident, not only to all the imperial guard, but to everyone else, that it is for Christ’s sake that I am in chains.
B050C001V014	50	1	14	And besides this, most of our fellow followers have gained confidence in the Lord through my chains, and now venture with far greater freedom to speak of God’s message fearlessly.
B050C001V015	50	1	15	It is true that some do proclaim the Christ out of Jealousy and opposition; but there are others who proclaim him from goodwill.
B050C001V016	50	1	16	The latter do it from love for me, knowing that I have been appointed to plead the cause of the good news.
B050C001V017	50	1	17	The former spread the news of the Christ in a factious spirit, and not sincerely, thinking to add to the pain of my chains.
B050C001V018	50	1	18	But what of that? Only that in some way or other, either with assumed or with real earnestness, Christ is being made known; and at that I rejoice.
B050C001V019	50	1	19	Yes, and I will rejoice, for I know that, through your prayers and through a rich supply of the Spirit of Jesus Christ, ‘all this will make for my salvation.’
B050C001V020	50	1	20	And this will fulfil my earnest expectation and hope that I will have no cause for shame, but that, with unfailing courage, now as hitherto, Christ will be honoured in my body, whether by my life or by my death,
B050C001V021	50	1	21	for to me life is Christ, and death is gain.
B050C001V022	50	1	22	But what if the life here in the body — if this brings me fruit from my labours? Then which to choose I cannot tell! I am sorely perplexed either way!
B050C001V023	50	1	23	My own desire is to depart and be with Christ, for this would be far better.
B050C001V024	50	1	24	But, for your sakes, it may be more needful that I should still remain here in the body.
B050C001V025	50	1	25	Yes, I am confident that this is so, and therefore I am sure that I will stay, and stay near you all, to promote your progress and joy in the faith;
B050C001V026	50	1	26	so that, when you once more have me among you, you, in your union with Christ Jesus, may find in me fresh cause for exultation.
B050C001V027	50	1	27	Under all circumstances let your lives be worthy of the good news of the Christ: so that, whether I come and see you, or whether I hear of your affairs at a distance, I may know that you are standing firm, animated by one spirit, and joining with one heart in a common struggle for the faith taught by the good news,
B050C001V028	50	1	28	without ever shrinking from your opponents. To them this will be a sign of their destruction and of your salvation — a sign from God.
B050C001V029	50	1	29	For, on behalf of Christ, you have had the privilege granted you, not only of trusting in him, but also of suffering on his behalf.
B050C001V030	50	1	30	You will be engaged in the same hard struggle as that which you once saw me waging, and which you hear that I am waging still.  
B050C002V001	50	2	1	If, then, any encouragement comes through union with Christ, if there is any persuasive power in love, if there is any communion with the Spirit, if there is any tenderness or pity,
B050C002V002	50	2	2	I entreat you to make my happiness complete — Live together animated by the same spirit and in mutual love, one in heart, animated by one Spirit.
B050C002V003	50	2	3	Nothing should be done in a factious spirit or from vanity, but each of you should with all humility regard others as better than himself,
B050C002V004	50	2	4	and one and all should consider, not only their own interests, but also the interests of others.
B050C002V005	50	2	5	Let the spirit of Christ Jesus be yours also.
B050C002V006	50	2	6	Though the divine nature was his from the beginning, yet he did not look on equality with God as above all things to be clung to,
B050C002V007	50	2	7	but impoverished himself by taking the nature of a servant and becoming like one of us;
B050C002V008	50	2	8	he appeared among us as a man, and still further humbled himself by submitting even to death — to death on a cross!
B050C002V009	50	2	9	And that is why God raised him to the very highest place, and gave him the name which stands above all other names,
B050C002V010	50	2	10	so that in adoration of the name of Jesus every knee should bend, in heaven, on earth, and under the earth,
B050C002V011	50	2	11	and that every tongue should acknowledge JESUS CHRIST as LORD — to the glory of God the Father.
B050C002V012	50	2	12	Therefore, my dear friends, as you have always been obedient in the past, so now work out your own salvation with anxious care, not only when I am with you, but all the more now that I am absent.
B050C002V013	50	2	13	Remember it is God who, in his kindness, is at work within you, enabling you both to will and to work.
B050C002V014	50	2	14	In all that you do, avoid murmuring and dissension,
B050C002V015	50	2	15	so as to prove yourselves blameless and innocent — ‘faultless children of God, in the midst of an evil-disposed and perverse generation,’ in which you are seen shining like stars in a dark world,
B050C002V016	50	2	16	offering to them the message of life; and then I will be able at the day of Christ to boast that I did not run my course for nothing, or toil for nothing.
B050C002V017	50	2	17	And yet, even if, when your faith is offered as a sacrifice to God, my lifeblood must be poured out in addition, still I will rejoice and share the joy of you all;
B050C002V018	50	2	18	and you must also rejoice and share my joy.
B050C002V019	50	2	19	I hope, however, as one who trusts in the Lord Jesus, to send Timothy to you before long, so that I may myself be cheered by receiving news of you.
B050C002V020	50	2	20	For I have no one but him to send — no one of kindred spirit who would take the same genuine interest in your welfare.
B050C002V021	50	2	21	They are all pursuing their own aims and not those of Christ Jesus.
B050C002V022	50	2	22	But you know what Timothy has proved himself to be, and how, like a child working for his father, he worked hard with me in spreading the good news.
B050C002V023	50	2	23	It is Timothy, then, whom I hope to send, as soon as ever I can foresee how it will go with me.
B050C002V024	50	2	24	And I am confident, as one who trusts in the Lord Jesus, that before long I myself will follow.
B050C002V025	50	2	25	Still I think it necessary to send Epaphroditus to you now, for he is my dear friend, fellow worker, and fellow soldier, and he was also your messenger to help me in my need.
B050C002V026	50	2	26	For he has been longing to see you all, and has been distressed because you heard of his illness.
B050C002V027	50	2	27	And I can assure you that his illness very nearly proved fatal. But God had pity on him, and not on him only but also on me, so that I might not have sorrow on sorrow.
B050C002V028	50	2	28	I am all the more ready, therefore, to send him, so that the sight of him may revive your spirits and my own sorrow be lightened.
B050C002V029	50	2	29	Give him, then, the heartiest of Christian welcomes, and hold such people in great honour.
B050C002V030	50	2	30	For it was owing to his devotion to the Master’s work that he was at the point of death, having risked his own life in the effort to supply what was wanting in the help that you sent me.
B050C003V001	50	3	1	In conclusion, my friends, all joy be yours in your union with the Lord. To repeat what I have already written does not weary me, and is the safe course for you.
B050C003V002	50	3	2	Beware of those ‘dogs’! Beware of those mischievous workers! Beware of the men who mutilate themselves!
B050C003V003	50	3	3	For it is we who are the circumcised — we whose worship is prompted by the Spirit of God, who exult in Christ Jesus, and who do not rely on external privileges;
B050C003V004	50	3	4	though I, if anyone, have cause to rely even on them. If anyone thinks he can rely on external privileges, far more can I!
B050C003V005	50	3	5	I was circumcised when eight days old; I am an Israelite by race, and of the tribe of Benjamin; I am a Hebrew, and the child of Hebrews. As to the law, I was a Pharisee;
B050C003V006	50	3	6	as to zeal, I was a persecutor of the church; as to such righteousness as is due to law, I proved myself blameless.
B050C003V007	50	3	7	But all the things which I once held to be gains I have now, for the Christ’s sake, come to count as loss.
B050C003V008	50	3	8	More than that, I count everything as loss, for the sake of the exceeding value of the knowledge of Christ Jesus my Lord. And for his sake I have lost everything, and count it as refuse, if I may but gain Christ and be found in union with him;
B050C003V009	50	3	9	any righteousness that I have being, not the righteousness that results from law, but the righteousness which comes through faith in Christ — the righteousness which is derived from God and is founded on faith.
B050C003V010	50	3	10	Then indeed I will know Christ, and the power of his resurrection, and all that it means to share his sufferings,
B050C003V011	50	3	11	in the hope that, if I become like him in death, I may possibly attain to the resurrection from the dead.
B050C003V012	50	3	12	Not that I have already laid hold of it, or that I am already made perfect. But I press on, in the hope of actually laying hold of that for which indeed I was laid hold of by Christ Jesus.
B050C003V013	50	3	13	For I, friends, do not regard myself as having yet laid hold of it. But this one thing I do — forgetting what lies behind, and straining every nerve for that which lies in front,
B050C003V014	50	3	14	I press on to the goal, to gain the prize of that heavenward call which God gave me through Christ Jesus.
B050C003V015	50	3	15	Let all of us, then, whose faith is mature, think this way. Then, if on any matter you think otherwise, God will make that also plain to you.
B050C003V016	50	3	16	Only we are bound to order our lives by what we have already attained.
B050C003V017	50	3	17	My friends, unite in following my example, and fix your eyes on those who are living by the pattern which we have set you.
B050C003V018	50	3	18	For there are many — of whom I have often told you, and now tell you even with tears — who are living in enmity to the cross of the Christ.
B050C003V019	50	3	19	The end of such people is ruin; for their appetites are their God, and they glory in their shame; their minds are given up to earthly things.
B050C003V020	50	3	20	But the State of which we are citizens is in heaven; and it is from heaven that we are eagerly looking for a Saviour, the Lord Jesus Christ,
B050C003V021	50	3	21	who, by the exercise of his power to bring everything into subjection to himself, will make this body that we have in our humiliation like to that body which he has in his glory.  
B050C004V001	50	4	1	So then, my dear friends, whom I am longing to see — you who are my joy and my crown, stand fast in union with the Lord, dear friends.
B050C004V002	50	4	2	I entreat Euodia, and I entreat Syntyche, to live in harmony, in union with the Lord;
B050C004V003	50	4	3	yes, and I ask you, my true comrade, to help them, remembering that they toiled by my side in spreading the good news; and so, too, did Clement and my other fellow workers, whose names are ‘in the book of life.’
B050C004V004	50	4	4	All joy be yours at all times in your union with the Lord. Again I repeat — All joy be yours.
B050C004V005	50	4	5	Let your forbearing spirit be plain to everyone. The Lord is near.
B050C004V006	50	4	6	Do not be anxious about anything; but under all circumstances, by prayer and entreaty joined with thanksgiving, make your needs known to God.
B050C004V007	50	4	7	Then the peace of God, which is beyond all human understanding, will stand guard over your hearts and thoughts, through your union with Christ Jesus.
B050C004V008	50	4	8	In conclusion, friends, whenever you find things that are true or honourable, righteous or pure, loveable or praiseworthy, or if ‘virtue’ and ‘honour’ have any meaning, let them fill your thoughts.
B050C004V009	50	4	9	All that you learned and received and heard and saw in me put into practice continually; and then God, the giver of peace, will be with you.
B050C004V010	50	4	10	It was a matter of great joy to me, as one in union with the Lord, that at length your interest in me had revived. The interest indeed you had, but not the opportunity.
B050C004V011	50	4	11	Do not think that I am saying this under the pressure of want. For I, however I am placed, have learned to be independent of circumstances.
B050C004V012	50	4	12	I know how to face humble circumstances, and I know how to face prosperity. Into all and every human experience I have been initiated — into plenty and hunger, into prosperity and want.
B050C004V013	50	4	13	I can do everything in the strength of him who makes me strong!
B050C004V014	50	4	14	Yet you have acted nobly in sharing my troubles.
B050C004V015	50	4	15	And you at Philippi know, as well as I, that in the early days of the good news — at the time when I had just left Macedonia — no church, with the one exception of yourselves, had anything to do with me as far as giving and receiving are concerned.
B050C004V016	50	4	16	Indeed, even while I was still in Thessalonica, you sent more than once to relieve my wants.
B050C004V017	50	4	17	It is not that I am anxious for your gifts, but I am anxious to see the abundant return that will be placed to your account. I have enough of everything, and to spare.
B050C004V018	50	4	18	My wants are fully satisfied, now that I have received from Epaphroditus the gifts which you sent me — the sweet fragrance of a sacrifice acceptable and pleasing to God.
B050C004V019	50	4	19	And my God, out of the greatness of his wealth, will, in glory, fully satisfy your every need, through your union with Christ Jesus.
B050C004V020	50	4	20	To him, our God and Father, be ascribed all glory for every and ever. Amen.
B050C004V021	50	4	21	Give my greeting to everyone of the people of Christ Jesus. The Lord's followers who are with me send your their greetings.
B050C004V022	50	4	22	All Christ’s people here, and especially those who belong to the Emperor’s household, send theirs.  
B050C004V023	50	4	23	May the blessing of the Lord Jesus Christ rest on your souls.
B051C001V001	51	1	1	From Paul, an apostle of Christ Jesus, by the will of God, and from Timothy, also a follower of the Lord.
B051C001V002	51	1	2	To Christ’s people at Colossae — the followers who are faithful to him: May God, our Father, bless you and give you peace.
B051C001V003	51	1	3	Whenever we pray, we never fail to thank God, the Father of our Lord, Jesus Christ, about you,
B051C001V004	51	1	4	now that we have heard of your faith in Christ Jesus and of the love that you have for all his people,
B051C001V005	51	1	5	because of the hope which awaits its fulfilment in heaven. Of this hope you heard long ago in the true message of the good news which reached you —
B051C001V006	51	1	6	Bearing fruit and growing, as it does, through all the world, just as it did among you, from the very day that you heard of God’s loving kindness, and understood what that loving kindness really is.
B051C001V007	51	1	7	It is just what you learned from Epaphras, our dear fellow servant, who, as a minister of the Christ, faithfully represents us,
B051C001V008	51	1	8	and who told us of the love with which the Spirit has inspired you.
B051C001V009	51	1	9	And therefore we, from the very day that we heard this, have never ceased praying for you, or asking that you may possess that deeper knowledge of the will of God, which comes through all true spiritual wisdom and insight.
B051C001V010	51	1	10	Then you will live lives worthy of the Master, and so please God in every way. Your lives will be fruitful in every kind of good action, and your characters will grow through a fuller knowledge of God;
B051C001V011	51	1	11	you will be made strong at all points with a strength worthy of the power manifested in his glory — strong to endure with patience, and even with gladness, whatever may happen to you;
B051C001V012	51	1	12	and you will give thanks to the Father who made you fit to share the lot which awaits Christ’s people in the realms of light.
B051C001V013	51	1	13	For God has rescued us from the tyranny of darkness, and has removed us into the kingdom of his Son, who is the embodiment of his love,
B051C001V014	51	1	14	and through whom we have found deliverance in the forgiveness of our sins.
B051C001V015	51	1	15	For Christ is the incarnation of the invisible God — first-born and head of all creation;
B051C001V016	51	1	16	for in him was created all that is in heaven and on earth, the visible and the invisible — angels and archangels and all the powers of heaven.
B051C001V017	51	1	17	All has been created through him and for him. He was before all things, and all things unite in him;
B051C001V018	51	1	18	and he is the head of the church, which is his body. The first-born from the dead, he is to the church the Source of its life, that he, in all things, may stand first.
B051C001V019	51	1	19	For it pleased the Father that in him the divine nature in all its fulness should live,
B051C001V020	51	1	20	and through him to reconcile all things to himself (making peace by the shedding of Christ’s blood offered on the cross) — whether on earth or in heaven.
B051C001V021	51	1	21	And it pleased God that you, once estranged from him and hostile towards him in your thoughts, intent only on wickedness —
B051C001V022	51	1	22	But now he has reconciled you to himself by the sacrifice of Christ’s earthly body in death — it has pleased God that you should stand in his presence holy, pure, and blameless,
B051C001V023	51	1	23	if only you remain true to your faith, firm and immovable, never abandoning the hope held out in the good news to which you listened, which has been proclaimed among all created things under heaven, and of which I, Paul, was made a minister.  
B051C001V024	51	1	24	Now at last I can rejoice in my sufferings on your behalf, and in my own person I supplement the afflictions endured by the Christ, for the sake of his body, the church;
B051C001V025	51	1	25	of which I myself became a minister in virtue of the office with which God entrusted me for your benefit, to declare the message of God in all its fulness —
B051C001V026	51	1	26	That truth which has been hidden from former ages and generations. But now it has been revealed to God’s people,
B051C001V027	51	1	27	to whom it was his pleasure to make known the surpassing glory of that hidden truth when proclaimed among the Gentiles — ‘Christ among you! Your hope of glory!’
B051C001V028	51	1	28	This is the Christ whom we proclaim, warning everyone, and instructing everyone, with all the wisdom that we possess, in the hope of bringing everyone into God’s presence perfected by union with Christ.
B051C001V029	51	1	29	It is for that I toil, struggling with all the energy which he inspires and which works powerfully within me.
B051C002V001	51	2	1	I want you to know in how great a struggle I am engaged for you and for Christ’s people at Laodicea, and for all who have not yet seen me;
B051C002V002	51	2	2	in the hope that they, being bound to one another by love, and keeping in view the full blessedness of a firm conviction, may be encouraged to strive for a perfect knowledge of God’s hidden truth,
B051C002V003	51	2	3	even Christ himself, in whom all treasures of wisdom and knowledge lie hidden.
B051C002V004	51	2	4	I say this to prevent anyone from deceiving you by plausible arguments.
B051C002V005	51	2	5	It is true that I am not with you in person, but I am with you in spirit, and am glad to see the good order and the unbroken front resulting from your faith in Christ.
B051C002V006	51	2	6	Since, therefore, you have received Jesus, the Christ, as your Lord, live your lives in union with him —
B051C002V007	51	2	7	rooted in him, building up your characters through union with him, growing stronger through your faith, as you were taught, overflowing with faith and thanksgiving.
B051C002V008	51	2	8	Take care there is not some one who will carry you away by his ‘philosophy’ — a hollow sham! — following, as it does, mere human traditions, and dealing with puerile questions of this world, and not with Christ.
B051C002V009	51	2	9	For in Christ the Godhead in all its fulness dwells incarnate;
B051C002V010	51	2	10	and, by your union with him, you also are filled with it. He is the head of all archangels and powers of heaven.
B051C002V011	51	2	11	By your union with him you received a circumcision that was not performed by human hands, when you threw off the tyranny of the earthly body, and received the circumcision of the Christ.
B051C002V012	51	2	12	For in baptism you were buried with Christ; and in baptism you were also raised to life with him, through your faith in the omnipotence of God, who raised him from the dead.
B051C002V013	51	2	13	And to you, who once were ‘dead,’ by reason of your sins and your uncircumcised nature — to you God gave life in giving life to Christ! He pardoned all our sins!
B051C002V014	51	2	14	He canceled the bond which stood against us — the bond that consisted of ordinances — and which was directly hostile to us! He has taken it out of our way by nailing it to the cross!
B051C002V015	51	2	15	He rid himself of all the powers of evil, and held them up to open contempt, when he celebrated his triumph over them on the cross!
B051C002V016	51	2	16	Do not, then, allow anyone to take you to task on questions of eating or drinking, or in the matter of annual or monthly or weekly festivals.
B051C002V017	51	2	17	These things are only the shadow of what is to come; the substance is in the Christ.
B051C002V018	51	2	18	Do not let anyone defraud you of the reality by affecting delight in so-called ‘humility’ and angel-worship. Such a person busies themselves with their visions, and without reason are rendered conceited by their merely human intellect.
B051C002V019	51	2	19	They fail to maintain union with the head, to whom it is due that the whole body, nourished and knit together by the contact and connexion of every part, grows with a divine growth.  
B051C002V020	51	2	20	Since, with Christ, you became dead to the puerile teaching of this world, why do you submit, as as if you still belonged to the world,
B051C002V021	51	2	21	to such ordinances as ‘Do not handle, or taste, or touch’?
B051C002V022	51	2	22	For all the things referred to in them cease to exist when used. You are following mere human directions and instructions.
B051C002V023	51	2	23	Such prohibitions appear reasonable where there is a desire for self-imposed service, and so-called ‘humility,’ and harsh treatment of the body, but are of no real value against the indulgence of our earthly nature.
B051C003V001	51	3	1	Since, therefore, you were raised to life with the Christ, seek for the things that are above; for it is there that the Christ is ‘seated at the right hand of God.’
B051C003V002	51	3	2	Fix your thoughts on the things that are above, not on those that are on earth.
B051C003V003	51	3	3	For you died, and your life now lies hidden, with the Christ, in God.
B051C003V004	51	3	4	When the Christ, who is our life, appears, then you also will appear with him in glory.
B051C003V005	51	3	5	Therefore destroy all that is earthly in you — immorality, uncleanness, passions, evil desires, and that greed which is idolatry.
B051C003V006	51	3	6	These are the things because of which the wrath of God comes,
B051C003V007	51	3	7	and to which you, like others, once devoted your lives, when you lived for them.
B051C003V008	51	3	8	You, however, must now lay aside all such things — anger, passion, malice, slander, abuse.
B051C003V009	51	3	9	Never lie to one another. Get rid of your old self and its habits,
B051C003V010	51	3	10	and clothe yourselves with that new self, which, as it gains in knowledge, is being constantly renewed ‘in resemblance to him who made it.’
B051C003V011	51	3	11	In that new life there is no distinction between Greek and Jew, circumcised and uncircumcised, barbarian, Scythian, slave, free; but Christ is all! — and in all!
B051C003V012	51	3	12	Therefore, as God’s people, consecrated and dear to him, clothe yourselves with tenderness of heart, kindliness, humility, gentleness, forbearance;
B051C003V013	51	3	13	bearing with one another, and, when there is any ground for complaint, forgiving one another freely. As the Master freely forgave you, so you must forgive one another.
B051C003V014	51	3	14	Over all these virtues put on love; for that is the girdle which makes all complete.
B051C003V015	51	3	15	Let the peace that the Christ gives decide all doubts within your hearts; for you also were called to the enjoyment of peace as members of one body. And show yourselves thankful.
B051C003V016	51	3	16	Let the message of the Christ be alive in your minds in all its wealth, bringing all wisdom with it. Teach and admonish one another with psalms, and hymns, and sacred songs, full of the loving kindness of God, lifting your hearts in song to him.
B051C003V017	51	3	17	And, whatever you say or do, do everything in the name of the Lord Jesus; and through him offer thanksgiving to God the father.  
B051C003V018	51	3	18	Wives, submit to your husbands, as befits those who belong to the Lord.
B051C003V019	51	3	19	Husbands, love your wives, and never treat them harshly.
B051C003V020	51	3	20	children, always obey your parents; for that is pleasant to see in those who belong to the Lord.
B051C003V021	51	3	21	Fathers, never irritate your children, otherwise they might become disheartened.
B051C003V022	51	3	22	Slaves, always obey your earthly masters, not only when their eyes are on you, as if you had but to please people alone, but giving them ungrudging service, in your respect for the Master.
B051C003V023	51	3	23	Whatever you do, do it with all your heart, as if working for the Master and not for people,
B051C003V024	51	3	24	since you know that it is from the Master that you will receive the inheritance which will be your reward. You are serving Christ, the Master.
B051C003V025	51	3	25	Those who do wrong will reap the wrong they have done; and there will be no partiality.
B051C004V001	51	4	1	Masters, do what is right and fair by your slaves, for you know that you also have a Master — in heaven.
B051C004V002	51	4	2	Devote yourselves to prayer. Give your whole mind to it, and also offer thanksgiving;
B051C004V003	51	4	3	and at the same time pray for us, so that God may give us an opening for our message, so that we may speak of the truths hidden in the Christ — the truths for which I am in chains!
B051C004V004	51	4	4	Then I will make them known, as I ought to do.
B051C004V005	51	4	5	Show tact in your behaviour to the outside world, making the most of every opportunity.
B051C004V006	51	4	6	Let your conversation always be kindly, but not bland, season it, as it were, with salt; be aware in each case of the answer you should be giving.
B051C004V007	51	4	7	Our dear friend, Tychicus, will tell you all about me. He is a faithful minister, and a fellow servant in the Master’s cause.
B051C004V008	51	4	8	I send him to you expressly that you may learn our circumstances, and that he may give you encouragement.
B051C004V009	51	4	9	With him will be Onesimus, our dear faithful friend, who is one of yourselves. They will tell you all that is going on here.
B051C004V010	51	4	10	My fellow prisoner, Aristarchus, sends you his greeting, and Barnabas’s cousin, Mark, sends his. (You have received directions about him. If he comes to you, make him welcome.)
B051C004V011	51	4	11	Joshua, who is called Justus, also sends his greeting. These are the only converts from Judaism who have worked with me for the kingdom of God; I have found them a great comfort.
B051C004V012	51	4	12	Epaphras, who is one of yourselves, sends you his greeting. He is a servant of Christ Jesus, and is always most earnest in your behalf in his prayers, praying that you may stand firm, with a matured faith and with a sure conviction of all that is in accordance with God’s will.
B051C004V013	51	4	13	I can bear testimony to the deep interest he takes in you, as well as in the followers at Laodicea and at Hierapolis.
B051C004V014	51	4	14	Luke, our dear doctor, sends you his greeting, and Demas sends his.
B051C004V015	51	4	15	Give my greeting to the followers at Laodicea, and to Nymphe, and to the church that meets at her house.
B051C004V016	51	4	16	And when this letter has been read to you, see that it is also read before the church at Laodicea, and that you yourselves read the letter which will be forwarded from there.
B051C004V017	51	4	17	Give this message to Archippus — ‘Take care to discharge to the best of your ability the office to which you were appointed in the Master’s cause.’
B051C004V018	51	4	18	I, Paul, add this greeting in my own handwriting. Remember these chains of mine. God’s blessing be with you.
B052C001V001	52	1	1	To the Thessalonian church in union with God the Father and the Lord Jesus Christ, from Paul, Silas, and Timothy. May God bless you and give you peace.
B052C001V002	52	1	2	We always mention you in our prayers and thank God for you all;
B052C001V003	52	1	3	recalling continually before our God and Father the efforts that have resulted from your faith, the toil prompted by your love, and the patient endurance sustained by your hope in our Lord Jesus Christ.
B052C001V004	52	1	4	Friends, whom God loves, we know that he has chosen you,
B052C001V005	52	1	5	because the good news that we brought came home to you, not merely as so many words, but with a power and a fulness of conviction due to the Holy Spirit. For you know the life that we lived among you for your good.
B052C001V006	52	1	6	And you yourselves began to follow, not only our example, but the Master’s also; and, in spite of much suffering, you welcomed the message with a joy inspired by the Holy Spirit,
B052C001V007	52	1	7	and so became a pattern to all who believed in Christ throughout Macedonia and Greece.
B052C001V008	52	1	8	For it was from you that the Lord’s message resounded throughout Macedonia and Greece; and, more than that, your faith in God has become known far and wide; so that there is no need for us to say another word.
B052C001V009	52	1	9	Indeed, in speaking about us, the people themselves tell of the reception you gave us, and how, turning to God from your idols, you became servants of the true and living God,
B052C001V010	52	1	10	and are now awaiting the return from heaven of his Son whom he raised from the dead — Jesus, our deliverer from the coming wrath.
B052C002V001	52	2	1	Yes, friends, you yourselves know that your reception of us was not without result.
B052C002V002	52	2	2	For, although we had experienced suffering and ill treatment, as you know, at Philippi, we had the courage, by the help of our God, to tell you God’s good news in spite of great opposition.
B052C002V003	52	2	3	Our appeal to you was not based on a delusion, nor was it made from unworthy motives, or with any intention of misleading you.
B052C002V004	52	2	4	But, having been found worthy by God to be entrusted with the good news, therefore we tell it; with a view to please, not people, but God who proves our hearts.
B052C002V005	52	2	5	Never at any time, as you know, did we use the language of flattery, or make false professions in order to hide selfish aims. God will bear witness to that.
B052C002V006	52	2	6	Nor did we seek to win honour from people, whether from you or from others, although, as apostles of Christ, we might have burdened you with our support.
B052C002V007	52	2	7	But we lived among you with the simplicity of a child; we were like a woman nursing her own children.
B052C002V008	52	2	8	In our strong affection for you, that seemed to us the best way of sharing with you, not only God’s Good news, but our lives as well — so dear had you become to us.
B052C002V009	52	2	9	You will not have forgotten, friends, our labour and toil. Night and day we used to work at our trades, so as not be a burden to any of you, while we proclaimed to you God’s good news.
B052C002V010	52	2	10	You will bear witness, and God also, that our relations with you who believed in Christ were pure, and upright, and beyond reproach.
B052C002V011	52	2	11	Indeed, you know that, like a father with his own children, we used to encourage and comfort every one of you, and solemnly plead with you;
B052C002V012	52	2	12	so that you should make your daily lives worthy of God who is calling you into the glory of his kingdom.
B052C002V013	52	2	13	This, too, is a reason why we, on our part, are continually thanking God — because, in receiving the teaching that you had from us, you accepted it, not as the teaching of humans, but as what it really is — the teaching of God, which is even now doing its work within you who believe in Christ.
B052C002V014	52	2	14	For you, friends, began to follow the example of the churches of God in Judea which are in union with Jesus Christ; you, in your turn, suffering at the hands of your fellow citizens, in the same way as those churches did at the hands of of their people —
B052C002V015	52	2	15	who killed both the Lord Jesus and the prophets, and persecuted us also. They do not try to please God, and they are enemies to all humanity,
B052C002V016	52	2	16	for they try to prevent us from speaking to the Gentiles with a view to their salvation, and so are always ‘filling up the measure of their iniquity.’ But the wrath of God has come upon them to the full!
B052C002V017	52	2	17	As for ourselves, friends, our having been bereaved of you even for a short time — though in body only, and not in spirit — made us all the more eager to see your faces again; and the longing to do so was strong on us.
B052C002V018	52	2	18	That was why we made up our minds to go and see you — at least I, Paul, did, more than once — but Satan put difficulties in our way.
B052C002V019	52	2	19	For what hope or joy will be ours, or what crown will we have to boast of, in the presence of our Lord Jesus, at his coming, if it be not you?
B052C002V020	52	2	20	You are our pride and our delight!  
B052C003V001	52	3	1	And so, as we could bear it no longer, we made up our minds to remain behind alone at Athens,
B052C003V002	52	3	2	and sent Timothy, our dear friend and God’s minister of the good news of the Christ, to strengthen you, and to encourage you in your faith,
B052C003V003	52	3	3	so that none of you should be shaken by the troubles through which you are passing. You yourselves know that we are destined to meet with such things.
B052C003V004	52	3	4	For, even while we were with you, we warned you beforehand that we were certain to encounter trouble. And so it proved, as you know.
B052C003V005	52	3	5	Therefore, since I could no longer endure the uncertainty, I sent to make inquiries about your faith, fearing that the Tempter had tempted you, and that our toil might prove to have been in vain.
B052C003V006	52	3	6	But, when Timothy recently returned to us from you with good news of your faith and love, and told us how kindly you think of us — always longing, he said, to see us, just as we are longing to see you —
B052C003V007	52	3	7	on hearing this, we felt encouraged about you, friends, in the midst of all our difficulties and troubles, by your faith.
B052C003V008	52	3	8	For it is new life to us to know that you are holding fast to the Lord.
B052C003V009	52	3	9	How can we thank God enough for all the happiness that you are giving us in the sight of our God?
B052C003V010	52	3	10	Night and day we pray most earnestly that we may see you face to face, and make good any deficiency in your faith.
B052C003V011	52	3	11	May our God and Father himself, and Jesus, our Lord, make the way plain for us to come to you.
B052C003V012	52	3	12	And for you, may the Lord fill you to overflowing with love for one another and for everyone, just as we are filled with love for you;
B052C003V013	52	3	13	and so make your hearts strong, and your lives pure beyond reproach, in the sight of our God and Father, at the coming of our Lord Jesus, with all his Holy Ones.  
B052C004V001	52	4	1	Further, friends, we beg and urge you in the name of our Lord Jesus to carry out more fully than ever — as indeed you are already doing — all that you have heard from us as to what your daily life must be, if it is to please God.
B052C004V002	52	4	2	For you have not forgotten the directions that we gave you on the authority of our Lord Jesus.
B052C004V003	52	4	3	For this is God’s purpose — that you should be pure; abstaining from all immorality;
B052C004V004	52	4	4	each of you learning to gain control over your own body, in a way that is holy and honourable,
B052C004V005	52	4	5	and not for the mere gratification of your passions, like the Gentiles who know nothing of God;
B052C004V006	52	4	6	none of you overreaching or taking advantage of their fellow follower of the Lord in such matters. ‘The Lord takes vengeance’ on all who do such things, as we have already warned you and solemnly declared.
B052C004V007	52	4	7	For God’s call to us does not permit of an impure life, but demands purity.
B052C004V008	52	4	8	Therefore the person who disregards this warning disregards, not people, but God who gives you his Holy Spirit.  
B052C004V009	52	4	9	As to love for each other there is no need to write to you; for you have yourselves been taught by God to love one another;
B052C004V010	52	4	10	and indeed you do act in this spirit towards all his people throughout Macedonia.  Yet, friends, we beg you to do even more.
B052C004V011	52	4	11	Make it your ambition to live quietly, and to attend to your own business, and to work with your hands, as we directed you;
B052C004V012	52	4	12	so that your conduct may win respect from those outside the church, and that you may not want for anything.  
B052C004V013	52	4	13	We don't want you to be ignorant, friends, about those who have passed to their rest. We don't want you to grieve like other people who have no hope.
B052C004V014	52	4	14	For, as we believe that Jesus died and rose again, so also we believe that God will bring, with Jesus, those who through him have passed to their rest.
B052C004V015	52	4	15	This we tell you on the authority of the Lord — that those of us who are still living at the coming of the Lord will not anticipate those who have passed to their rest.
B052C004V016	52	4	16	For, with a loud summons, with the shout of an archangel, and with the trumpet-call of God, the Lord himself will come down from heaven.
B052C004V017	52	4	17	Then those who died in union with Christ will rise first; and afterwards we who are still living will be caught up in the clouds, with them, to meet the Lord in the air; and so we will be for ever with the Lord.
B052C004V018	52	4	18	Therefore, comfort one another with what I have told you.
B052C005V001	52	5	1	But as to the times and the moments, there is no need, friends, for anyone to write to you.
B052C005V002	52	5	2	You yourselves know well that the day of the Lord will come just as a thief comes in the night.
B052C005V003	52	5	3	When people are saying ‘All is quiet and safe,’ it is then that, like birth pains on a pregnant woman, ruin comes suddenly upon them, and there will be no escape!
B052C005V004	52	5	4	You, however, friends, are not in darkness, that the daylight should take you by surprise as if you were thieves.
B052C005V005	52	5	5	For you all are ‘sons of light’ and ‘sons of the day.’  We have nothing to do with night, or darkness.
B052C005V006	52	5	6	Therefore let us not sleep as others do. No, let us be watchful and self-controlled.
B052C005V007	52	5	7	It is at night that people sleep, and at night that drunkards get drunk.
B052C005V008	52	5	8	But let us, who belong to the day, control ourselves, and put on faith and love as a breast plate, and the hope of salvation as a helmet.
B052C005V009	52	5	9	For God destined us, not for wrath, but to win salvation through our Lord Jesus Christ, who died for us,
B052C005V010	52	5	10	that, whether we are still watching or have fallen asleep, we may live with him.
B052C005V011	52	5	11	Therefore encourage one another, and try to build up one another’s characters, as indeed you are doing.  
B052C005V012	52	5	12	We beg you, friends, to value those who toil among you, and are your leaders in the Lord’s service, and give you counsel.
B052C005V013	52	5	13	Hold them in the very greatest esteem and affection for the sake of their work. Live at peace with one another.
B052C005V014	52	5	14	We entreat you also, friends — warn the disorderly, comfort the faint-hearted, give a helping hand to the weak, and be patient with everyone.
B052C005V015	52	5	15	Take care that none of you ever pays back wrong for wrong, but always follow the kindest course with one another and with everyone.
B052C005V016	52	5	16	Always be joyful;
B052C005V017	52	5	17	never cease to pray;
B052C005V018	52	5	18	under all circumstances give thanks to God. For this is his will for you as made known in Christ Jesus.
B052C005V019	52	5	19	Do not quench the Spirit;
B052C005V020	52	5	20	do not make light of preaching.
B052C005V021	52	5	21	Bring everything to the test; cling to what is good;
B052C005V022	52	5	22	shun every form of evil.
B052C005V023	52	5	23	May God himself, the giver of peace, make you altogether holy; and may your spirits, souls, and bodies be kept altogether faultless until the coming of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B052C005V024	52	5	24	He who calls you will not fail you; he will complete his work.
B052C005V025	52	5	25	Friends, pray for us.  
B052C005V026	52	5	26	Greet all the Lord's followers with a sacred kiss.
B052C005V027	52	5	27	I order you in the Lord’s name to have this letter read to all the brethren.
B052C005V028	52	5	28	May the blessing of our Lord Jesus Christ be with you.
B053C001V001	53	1	1	To the Thessalonian church in union with God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ, From Paul, Silas, and Timothy.
B053C001V002	53	1	2	May God, the Father, and the Lord Jesus Christ bless you and give you peace.
B053C001V003	53	1	3	Friends, it is our duty always to thank God about you, as is but right, considering the wonderful growth of your faith, and because, without exception, your love for one another is continually increasing.
B053C001V004	53	1	4	So much is this the case that we ourselves speak with pride, before the churches of God, of the patience and faith which you have shown, in spite of all the persecutions and troubles that you are enduring.
B053C001V005	53	1	5	These persecutions will vindicate the justice of God’s judgment, and will result in your being reckoned worthy of God’s kingdom, for the sake of which you are now suffering;
B053C001V006	53	1	6	since God deems it just to inflict suffering on those who are now inflicting suffering on you,
B053C001V007	53	1	7	and to give relief to you who are suffering, as well as to us, at the appearing of the Lord Jesus from heaven with his mighty angels, ‘in flaming fire.’
B053C001V008	53	1	8	Then he will ‘inflict punishment on those who refuse to know God, and on those who turn a deaf ear’ to the good news of Jesus, our Lord.
B053C001V009	53	1	9	They will pay the penalty of unutterable ruin — banished ‘from the presence of the Lord and from the glorious manifestation of his might,
B053C001V010	53	1	10	when he comes to be honour ed in his people,’ and to be revered in all who have learned to believe in him (for you also believed our testimony) — as he will be on ‘that day.’
B053C001V011	53	1	11	With this in view, our constant prayer for you is that our God may count you worthy of the call that you have received, and by his power make perfect your delight in all goodness and the efforts that have resulted from your faith.
B053C001V012	53	1	12	Then, in the loving kindness of our God and the Lord Jesus Christ, will the name of Jesus, our Lord, be honoured in you, and you in him.
B053C002V001	53	2	1	As to the coming of our Lord Jesus Christ, and our being gathered to meet him, we beg you, friends,
B053C002V002	53	2	2	not lightly to let your minds become unsettled, or disturbed by any revelation, or by any message, or by any letter, purporting to come from us, to the effect that the day of the Lord is come.
B053C002V003	53	2	3	Do not let anyone deceive you, whatever he may do. For it will not come until after the Great Apostasy, and the appearing of that Incarnation of Wickedness, that the Lost soul,
B053C002V004	53	2	4	who so opposes himself to everyone that is spoken of as a God or as an object of worship, and so exalts himself above them, that he seats himself in the Temple of God, and displays himself as God!
B053C002V005	53	2	5	Do not you remember how, when I was with you, I used to speak to you of all this?
B053C002V006	53	2	6	And you know now what the restraining influence is which prevents his appearing before his appointed time.
B053C002V007	53	2	7	Wickedness, indeed, is already at work in secret; but only until he who at present restrains it is removed out of the way.
B053C002V008	53	2	8	Then will ‘Wickedness Incarnate’ appear, but the Lord Jesus will destroy him with the breath of his lips, and annihilate him by the splendour of his coming.
B053C002V009	53	2	9	For at the coming of the Lord there will be great activity on the part of Satan, in the form of all kinds of deceptive miracles, signs, and marvels, as well as of wicked attempts to delude —
B053C002V010	53	2	10	to the ruin of those who are on the path to destruction, because they have never received and loved the truth to their own salvation.
B053C002V011	53	2	11	That is why God places them under the influence of a delusion, to cause them to believe a lie;
B053C002V012	53	2	12	so that sentence may be passed on all those who refuse to believe the truth, but delight in wickedness.
B053C002V013	53	2	13	But, friends, whom the Lord loves, it is our duty always to thank God about you, for, from the first, God chose you for salvation through the purifying influence of the Spirit, and your belief in the truth.
B053C002V014	53	2	14	To this you were called by the good news which we brought you, to attain to the glory of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B053C002V015	53	2	15	Stand firm then, friends, and hold fast to the truths that we taught you, whether by word or by letter.
B053C002V016	53	2	16	And may our Lord Jesus Christ himself, and God our Father, who loved us and, in his loving kindness, gave us unfailing consolation and good ground for hope,
B053C002V017	53	2	17	console your hearts, and strengthen you to do and to say all that is right.
B053C003V001	53	3	1	In conclusion, friends, pray for us — pray that the Lord’s message may spread rapidly, and be received everywhere with honour, as it was among you;
B053C003V002	53	3	2	and that we may be preserved from wrong-headed and wicked people — for it is not everyone who believes in Christ.
B053C003V003	53	3	3	But the Lord will not fail you; he will give you strength, and guard you from evil.
B053C003V004	53	3	4	Yes, and the confidence that our union with the Lord enables us to place in you leads us to believe that you are doing, and will do, what we direct you.
B053C003V005	53	3	5	May the Lord bring you to the love of God, and to the patience of the Christ.
B053C003V006	53	3	6	We beg you, friends, in the name of the Lord Jesus Christ, to avoid any follower who is living an ill-ordered life, which is not in agreement with the teaching that you received from us.
B053C003V007	53	3	7	For you know well that you ought to follow our example. When we were with you, our life was not ill-ordered,
B053C003V008	53	3	8	nor did we eat anyone’s bread without paying for it. Night and day, labouring and toiling, we used to work at our trades, so as not to be a burden on any of you.
B053C003V009	53	3	9	This was not because we had not a right to receive support, but our object was to give you a pattern for you to copy.
B053C003V010	53	3	10	Indeed, when we were with you, the rule we laid down was — ‘Whoever does not choose to work will not get to eat.’
B053C003V011	53	3	11	We hear that there are among you people who are living ill-ordered lives, and who, instead of attending to their own business, are mere busybodies.
B053C003V012	53	3	12	All such people we beg, and implore,, in the name of the Lord Jesus Christ, to attend quietly to their business, and earn their own living.
B053C003V013	53	3	13	You, friends, must not grow weary of doing what is right.
B053C003V014	53	3	14	If anyone disregards what we have said in this letter, take note of them and avoid their company, so that they may feel ashamed.
B053C003V015	53	3	15	Yet do not think of them as an enemy, but caution them as you would a brother or sister.
B053C003V016	53	3	16	May the Lord, from whom all peace comes, himself give you his peace at all times and in all ways. May he be with you all.
B053C003V017	53	3	17	I, Paul, add this greeting in my own handwriting. It is my signature to every letter. This is how I write.
B053C003V018	53	3	18	May the blessing of our Lord Jesus Christ be with you all.
B054C001V001	54	1	1	From Paul, an apostle of Christ Jesus by the appointment of God, our Saviour, and Christ Jesus, our hope.
B054C001V002	54	1	2	To Timothy, my true child in the faith: May God, the Father, and Christ Jesus, our Lord, bless you, and be merciful to you, and give you peace.
B054C001V003	54	1	3	I beg you, as I did when I was on my way into Macedonia, to remain at Ephesus; that you may instruct certain people there not to teach new and strange doctrines,
B054C001V004	54	1	4	nor to devote their attention to legends and interminable genealogies, which tend to give rise to argument rather than to further that divine plan which is revealed in the faith.
B054C001V005	54	1	5	The object of all instruction is to call forth that love which comes from a pure heart, a clear conscience, and a sincere faith.
B054C001V006	54	1	6	And it is because they have not aimed at these things that the attention of certain people has been diverted to unprofitable subjects.
B054C001V007	54	1	7	They want to be teachers of the law, and yet do not understand either the words they use, or the subjects on which they speak so confidently.
B054C001V008	54	1	8	We know, of course, that the law is excellent, when used legitimately,
B054C001V009	54	1	9	by one who recognises that laws were not made for good people, but for the lawless and disorderly, for irreligious and wicked people, for those who are irreverent and profane, for those who ill-treat their fathers or mothers, for murderers,
B054C001V010	54	1	10	for the immoral, for perverts, for slave-dealers, for liars, for perjurers, and for whatever else is opposed to sound Christian teaching —
B054C001V011	54	1	11	as is taught in the glorious good news of the ever-blessed God, with which I was entrusted.
B054C001V012	54	1	12	I am thankful to Christ Jesus, our Lord, who has been my strength, for showing that he thought me worthy of trust by appointing me to his ministry,
B054C001V013	54	1	13	though I once used to blaspheme, and to persecute, and to insult. Yet mercy was shown me, because I acted in ignorance, while still an unbeliever;
B054C001V014	54	1	14	and the loving kindness of our Lord was boundless, and filled me with that faith and love which come from union with Christ Jesus.
B054C001V015	54	1	15	How true the saying is, and worthy of the fullest acceptance, that ‘Christ Jesus came into the world to save sinners’! And there is no greater sinner than I!
B054C001V016	54	1	16	Yet mercy was shown me for the express purpose that Christ Jesus might exhibit in my case, beyond all others, his exhaustless patience, as an example for those who were afterwards to believe on him and attain eternal life.
B054C001V017	54	1	17	To the eternal King, ever-living, invisible, the one God, be ascribed honour and glory for ever and ever. Amen.  
B054C001V018	54	1	18	This, then, is the charge that I lay on you, Timothy, my child, in accordance with what was predicted of you — Fight the good fight in the spirit of those predictions,
B054C001V019	54	1	19	with faith, and with a clear conscience; and it is because they have thrust this aside, that, as regards the faith, some have wrecked their lives.
B054C001V020	54	1	20	Hymenaeus and Alexander are instances — the men whom I delivered over to Satan so that they might be taught not to blaspheme.  
B054C002V001	54	2	1	First of all, then, I ask that petitions, prayers, intercessions, and thanksgivings should be offered for everyone,
B054C002V002	54	2	2	especially for kings and all who are in high positions, in order that we may lead a quiet and peaceful life in a deeply religious and reverent spirit.
B054C002V003	54	2	3	This will be good and acceptable in the eyes of God, our Saviour,
B054C002V004	54	2	4	whose will is that everyone should be saved, and attain to a full knowledge of the truth.
B054C002V005	54	2	5	There is but one God, and one mediator between God and men — the man, Christ Jesus,
B054C002V006	54	2	6	who gave himself as a ransom on behalf of all men.  This must be our testimony, as opportunities present themselves;
B054C002V007	54	2	7	and it was for this that I was myself appointed a herald and an apostle (I am telling the simple truth and no lie) — a teacher of the Gentiles in the faith and truth.  
B054C002V008	54	2	8	My desire, then, is that it should be the custom everywhere for the men to lead the prayers, with hands reverently uplifted, avoiding heated controversy.  
B054C002V009	54	2	9	I also desire that women should adorn themselves with appropriate dress, worn quietly and modestly, and not with wreaths or gold ornaments for the hair, or pearls, or costly clothing,
B054C002V010	54	2	10	but — as is proper for women who profess to be religious — with good actions.
B054C002V011	54	2	11	They must learn, listening quietly to their teachers and showing them all deference.
B054C002V012	54	2	12	I do not consent to them becoming teachers, or exercising authority over men; they ought to not make a fuss.
B054C002V013	54	2	13	Adam was formed first, not Eve.
B054C002V014	54	2	14	And it was not Adam who was deceived; it was the woman who was entirely deceived and fell into sin.
B054C002V015	54	2	15	But she will be saved by the birth of a child, if they never abandon faith, love, or holiness, and behave with modesty.  
B054C003V001	54	3	1	
         How true is this saying: ‘To aspire to be to be a presiding officer in the church is to be ambitious for a noble task.’
B054C003V002	54	3	2	The presiding officer should be of blameless character; a faithful partner; living a temperate, discreet, and well-ordered life; hospitable, and a skilful teacher,
B054C003V003	54	3	3	not addicted to drink or brawling, but of a forbearing and peaceable disposition, and not a lover of money;
B054C003V004	54	3	4	they should provide for own household well, and their children should kept under control and be well-behaved.
B054C003V005	54	3	5	If someone does not know how to provide for their own household, how can they take charge of the church of God?
B054C003V006	54	3	6	The presiding officer should not be a recent convert, or they might become blinded by pride and fall under the same condemnation as the devil.
B054C003V007	54	3	7	They should also be well spoken of by outsiders, so that they may not incur censure and so fall into the devil's trap.
B054C003V008	54	3	8	So, too, assistant officers should be serious and straightforward, not given to taking much drink or to questionable money-making,
B054C003V009	54	3	9	but people who hold the deep truths of the faith and have a clear conscience.
B054C003V010	54	3	10	They should be tested first, and only appointed to their office if no objection is raised against them.
B054C003V011	54	3	11	It should be the same with the women in this office. They should be serious, not gossips, sober, and trustworthy in all respects.
B054C003V012	54	3	12	Assistant officers should be faithful partners who manage their children and their households well.
B054C003V013	54	3	13	Those who have filled that post with honour gain for themselves an honourable position, as well as great confidence through the faith that they place in Christ Jesus.  
B054C003V014	54	3	14	I am writing this to you, though I hope that I will come to see you before long;
B054C003V015	54	3	15	but in case I should be delayed, I want you to know what your conduct ought to be in the Household of God, which is the church of the living God — the pillar and stay of the truth.
B054C003V016	54	3	16	Yes, and confessedly wonderful are the deep truths of our religion; for —  ‘He was revealed in our nature,Pronounced righteous in spirit,Seen by angels,Proclaimed among the Gentiles,Believed on in the world,Taken up into glory.’
B054C004V001	54	4	1	But the Spirit distinctly says that in later times there will be some who will fall away from the faith, and devote their attention to misleading spirits, and to the teaching of demons,
B054C004V002	54	4	2	who will make use of the hypocrisy of lying teachers. These people’s consciences are seared,
B054C004V003	54	4	3	and they discourage marriage and enjoin abstinence from certain kinds of food; though God created these foods to be enjoyed thankfully by those who hold the faith and have attained a full knowledge of the truth.
B054C004V004	54	4	4	Everything created by God is good, and there in nothing that need be rejected — provided only that it is received thankfully;
B054C004V005	54	4	5	for it is consecrated by God’s blessing and by prayer.
B054C004V006	54	4	6	Put all this before the followers, and you will be a good servant of Christ Jesus, sustained by the precepts of the faith and of that good teaching by which you have guided your life.
B054C004V007	54	4	7	As for profane legends and old wives’ tales, leave them alone. Train yourself to lead a religious life;
B054C004V008	54	4	8	for while the training of the body is of service in some respects, religion is of service in all, carrying with it, as it does, a promise of life both here and hereafter.
B054C004V009	54	4	9	How true that saying is and worthy of the fullest acceptance!
B054C004V010	54	4	10	With that aim we toil and struggle, for we have set our hopes on the living God, who is the Saviour of all, and especially of those who hold the faith.  
B054C004V011	54	4	11	Remember these things in your teaching.
B054C004V012	54	4	12	Do not let anyone look down on you because you are young, but, by your conversation, your conduct, your love, your faith, and your purity, be an example to those who hold the faith.
B054C004V013	54	4	13	Until I come, apply yourself to public reading, preaching, and teaching.
B054C004V014	54	4	14	Do not neglect the divine gift within you, which was given you, amid many a prediction, when the hands of the officers of the church were laid on your head.
B054C004V015	54	4	15	Practice these things, devote yourself to them, so that your progress may be plain to everyone.
B054C004V016	54	4	16	Look to yourself as well as to your teaching. Persevere in this, for your doing so will mean salvation for yourself as well as for your hearers.
B054C005V001	54	5	1	Do not reprimand an older man, but plead with him as if he were your father. Treat the young men as brothers,
B054C005V002	54	5	2	the older women as mothers, and the younger women as sisters — with all purity.
B054C005V003	54	5	3	Show consideration for widows — I mean those who are really widowed.
B054C005V004	54	5	4	but, if a widow has children or grandchildren, let them learn to show proper regard for the members of their own family first, and to make some return to their parents; for that is pleasing in God’s sight.
B054C005V005	54	5	5	As for the woman who is really widowed and left quite alone, her hopes are fixed on God, and she devotes herself to prayers and supplications night and day.
B054C005V006	54	5	6	But the life of a widow who is devoted to pleasure is a living death.
B054C005V007	54	5	7	Those are the points you should teach, so that there may be no call for your censure.
B054C005V008	54	5	8	Anyone who fails to provide for their own relations, and especially for those under their own roof, has disowned the faith, and is worse than an unbeliever.
B054C005V009	54	5	9	A widow, when her name is added to the list, should not be less than sixty years old; she should have been a faithful wife,
B054C005V010	54	5	10	and be well spoken of for her kind actions. She should have brought up children, have shown hospitality to strangers, have washed the feet of her fellow Christians, have relieved those who were in distress, and devoted herself to every kind of good action.
B054C005V011	54	5	11	But you should exclude the younger widows from the list; for, when they grow restive under the yoke of the Christ, they want to marry,
B054C005V012	54	5	12	and so they bring condemnation on themselves for having broken their previous promise.
B054C005V013	54	5	13	And not only that, but they learn to be idle as they go about from house to house. Nor are they merely idle, but they also become gossips and busybodies, and talk of what they ought not.
B054C005V014	54	5	14	Therefore I advise young widows to marry, bear children, and attend to their homes, and so avoid giving the enemy an opportunity for scandal.
B054C005V015	54	5	15	There are some who have already left us, to follow Satan.
B054C005V016	54	5	16	Any Christian woman, who has relations who are widows, ought to relieve them and not allow them to become a burden to the church, so that the church may relieve those widows who are really widowed.
B054C005V017	54	5	17	Those officers of the church who fill their office well should be held deserving of especial consideration, particularly those whose work lies in preaching and teaching.
B054C005V018	54	5	18	The words of scripture are —  ‘You should not muzzle the ox while it is treading out the grain.’  and again —
B054C005V019	54	5	19	Do not receive a charge against an officer of the church, unless it is supported by two or three witnesses;
B054C005V020	54	5	20	but rebuke offenders publicly, so that others may take warning.
B054C005V021	54	5	21	I charge you solemnly, before God and Christ Jesus and the chosen angels, to carry out these directions, unswayed by prejudice, never acting with partiality.
B054C005V022	54	5	22	Never ordain anyone hastily, and take no part in the wrong-doing of others. Keep your life pure.
B054C005V023	54	5	23	Do not continue to drink water only, but take a little wine because of the weakness of your stomach, and your frequent ailments.
B054C005V024	54	5	24	There are some people whose sins are conspicuous and lead on to judgment, while there are others whose sins dog their steps.
B054C005V025	54	5	25	In the same way noble deeds become conspicuous, and those which are otherwise cannot be concealed.  
B054C006V001	54	6	1	All who are in the position of slaves should regard their masters as deserving of the greatest respect, so that the name of God, and our teaching, may not be maligned.
B054C006V002	54	6	2	Those who have Christian masters should not think less of them because they are also followers of Christ, but on the contrary they should serve them all the better, because those who are to benefit by their good work are dear to them as their fellow Christians.
B054C006V003	54	6	3	Anyone who teaches otherwise, and refuses their assent to sound instruction — the instruction of our Lord Jesus Christ — and to the teaching of religion,
B054C006V004	54	6	4	is puffed up with conceit, not really knowing anything, but having a morbid craving for discussions and arguments. Such things only give rise to envy, quarrelling, recriminations, base suspicions,
B054C006V005	54	6	5	and incessant wrangling on the part of these corrupt-minded people who have lost all hold on the truth, and who think of religion only as a source of gain.
B054C006V006	54	6	6	And a great source of gain religion is, when it brings contentment with it!
B054C006V007	54	6	7	For we brought nothing into the world, because we cannot even carry anything out of it.
B054C006V008	54	6	8	So, with food and shelter, we will be content.
B054C006V009	54	6	9	Those who want to be rich fall into the net of temptation, and become the prey of many foolish and harmful ambitions, which plunge people into destruction and ruin.
B054C006V010	54	6	10	Love of money is a source of all kinds of evil; and in their eagerness to be rich some have wandered away from the faith, and have been pierced to the heart by many a regret.
B054C006V011	54	6	11	But you must, servant of God, avoid all this. Aim at righteousness, piety, faith, love, endurance, gentleness.
B054C006V012	54	6	12	Run the great race of the faith, and win the eternal life. It was for this that you received the call, and, in the presence of many witnesses, made the great profession of faith.
B054C006V013	54	6	13	I beg you, as in the sight of God, the source of all life, and of Christ Jesus who before Pontius Pilate made the great profession of faith —
B054C006V014	54	6	14	I implore you to keep his command free from stain or reproach, until the appearing of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B054C006V015	54	6	15	This will be brought about in his own time by the one ever-blessed Potentate, the king of all kings and Lord of all lords,
B054C006V016	54	6	16	who alone is possessed of immortality and dwells in unapproachable light, whom no one has ever seen or ever can see — to whom be ascribed honour and power for ever. Amen.  
B054C006V017	54	6	17	Teach those who are wealthy in this life not to pride themselves, or fix their hopes, on so uncertain a thing as wealth, but on God, who gives us a wealth of enjoyment on every side.
B054C006V018	54	6	18	Teach them to show kindness, to exhibit a wealth of good actions, to be open-handed and generous,
B054C006V019	54	6	19	storing up for themselves what in the future will prove to be a good foundation, so that they may gain the only true life.  
B054C006V020	54	6	20	Timothy, guard what has been entrusted to you. Avoid the profane prattle and contradictions of what some miscall ‘theology,’
B054C006V021	54	6	21	for there are those who, while asserting their proficiency in it, have yet, as regards the faith, gone altogether astray. 
B055C001V001	55	1	1	To Timothy, my dear child, from Paul who, by the will of God, is an apostle of Christ Jesus, charged to proclaim the life that comes from union with Christ Jesus. May God, the Father, and Christ Jesus, our Lord, bless you, and be merciful to you, and give you peace.
B055C001V003	55	1	3	I am thankful to God, whom I serve, as my ancestors did, with a clear conscience, when I remember you, as I never fail to do, in my prayers — night and day alike,
B055C001V004	55	1	4	as I think of your tears, longing to see you, that my happiness may be completed,
B055C001V005	55	1	5	now that I have been reminded of the sincere faith that you have shown. That faith was seen first in your grandmother Lois and your mother Eunice, and is now, I am convinced, in you also.
B055C001V006	55	1	6	And that is my reason for reminding you to stir into flame that gift of God, which is yours through your ordination at my hands.
B055C001V007	55	1	7	For the Spirit which God gave us was not a spirit of cowardice, but a spirit of power, love, and self-control.
B055C001V008	55	1	8	Do not, therefore, be ashamed of the testimony which we have to bear to our Lord, or of me imprisoned for his sake; but join with me in suffering for the good news, as far as God enables you.
B055C001V009	55	1	9	It was God who saved us, and from him we received our solemn call — not as a reward for anything that we had done, but in fulfilment of his own loving purpose. For that love was extended to us, through Christ Jesus, before time began,
B055C001V010	55	1	10	and has now been made apparent through the appearing of our Saviour, Christ Jesus; who has made an end of death, and has brought life and Immortality to light by that good news,
B055C001V011	55	1	11	of which I was myself appointed a herald and apostle, and teacher.
B055C001V012	55	1	12	That is why I am undergoing these sufferings; yet I feel no shame, for I know in whom I have put my faith, and am convinced that he is able to guard what I have entrusted to him until ‘that day.’
B055C001V013	55	1	13	Keep before you, as an example of sound teaching, all that you learnt from me as you listened with that faith and love which come from union with Christ Jesus.
B055C001V014	55	1	14	Guard by the help of the Holy Spirit, who is within us, the glorious trust that has been committed to you.
B055C001V015	55	1	15	You know, of course, that all our friends in Roman Asia turned their backs on me, and among them Phygellus and Hermogenes.
B055C001V016	55	1	16	May the Lord show mercy to the household of Onesiphorus; for he often cheered me and was not ashamed of my chains.
B055C001V017	55	1	17	On the contrary, when he arrived in Rome, he sought eagerly for me until he found me.
B055C001V018	55	1	18	The Lord grant that he may find mercy at the hands of the Lord on ‘that day.’ The many services that he rendered at Ephesus you have the best means of knowing.  
B055C002V001	55	2	1	You must, then, my child, find strength in the help which comes from the union with Christ Jesus;
B055C002V002	55	2	2	and what you learnt from me, in the presence of many listeners, entrust to reliable people, who will be able in their turn to teach others.
B055C002V003	55	2	3	Share hardships with me, as a true soldier of Christ Jesus.
B055C002V004	55	2	4	A soldier on active service, to please his superior officer, always avoids entangling himself in the affairs of ordinary life.
B055C002V005	55	2	5	No athlete is ever awarded the wreath of victory unless they have kept the rules.
B055C002V006	55	2	6	The labourer who does the work should be the first to receive a share of the fruits of the earth.
B055C002V007	55	2	7	Reflect on what I say; the Lord will always help you to understand.
B055C002V008	55	2	8	Keep before your mind Jesus Christ, raised from the dead, a descendant of David, as told in the good news entrusted to me;
B055C002V009	55	2	9	in the service of which I am suffering hardships, even to being put in fetters as a criminal. But the message of God is not fettered;
B055C002V010	55	2	10	and that is why I submit to anything for the sake of God’s people: so that they also may obtain the salvation which comes from union with Christ Jesus, and imperishable glory.
B055C002V011	55	2	11	How true this saying is — ‘If we have shared his death, we will also share his life.
B055C002V012	55	2	12	If we continue to endure, we will also share his throne. If we should ever disown him, he, too, will disown us.
B055C002V013	55	2	13	If we lose our trust, he is still to be trusted, for he cannot be false to himself!’
B055C002V014	55	2	14	Remind people of all this; tell them solemnly, as in the sight of God, to avoid controversy, a useless thing and the ruin of those who listen to it.
B055C002V015	55	2	15	Do your utmost to show yourself true to God, a worker with no reason to be ashamed, accurate in delivering the message of the truth.
B055C002V016	55	2	16	Avoid profane prattle. Those who indulge in it only get deeper into irreligious ways,
B055C002V017	55	2	17	and their teaching will spread like a cancer. Hymenaeus and Philetus are instances of this.
B055C002V018	55	2	18	They have gone completely astray as regards the truth; they say that a resurrection has already taken place, and so upset some people’s faith.
B055C002V019	55	2	19	Yet God’s firm foundation still stands unmoved, and it bears this inscription —  ‘THE LORD KNOWS THOSE WHO ARE HIS’;  and this —  ‘LET ALL THOSE WHO USE THE NAME OF THE LORD TURN AWAY FROM WICKEDNESS.’
B055C002V020	55	2	20	Now in a large house there are not only things of gold and silver, but also others of wood and earthenware, some for better and some for common use.
B055C002V021	55	2	21	If, then, a person has escaped from the pollution of such errors as I have mentioned, they will be like a thing kept for better use, set apart, serviceable to its owner, ready for any good purpose.
B055C002V022	55	2	22	Flee from the passions of youth, but pursue righteousness, faith, love, and peace, in the company of those who, with a pure heart, invoke the Lord.
B055C002V023	55	2	23	Shun foolish and ignorant discussions, for you know that they only breed quarrels;
B055C002V024	55	2	24	and a servant of the Lord should never quarrel. They ought, on the contrary, to be courteous to everyone, skilful teachers, and forbearing.
B055C002V025	55	2	25	They should instruct their opponents in a gentle spirit; for, possibly, God may give those opponents a repentance that will lead to a fuller knowledge of truth,
B055C002V026	55	2	26	and they may yet come to a sober mind, and escape from the devil's net, when captured by the Lord’s servant to do the will of God.  
B055C003V001	55	3	1	Be sure of this, that in the last days difficult times will come.
B055C003V002	55	3	2	People will be selfish, mercenary, boastful, haughty, and blasphemous; disobedient to their parents, ungrateful, impure,
B055C003V003	55	3	3	incapable of affection, merciless, slanderous, wanting in self-control, brutal, careless of the right,
B055C003V004	55	3	4	treacherous, reckless, and puffed up with pride; they will love pleasure more than they love God;
B055C003V005	55	3	5	and while they retain the outward form of religion, they will not allow it to influence them. Turn your back on such people as these.
B055C003V006	55	3	6	For among them are to be found those who creep into homes and captivate weak women — women who, loaded with sins, and slaves to all kinds of passions,
B055C003V007	55	3	7	are always learning, and yet never able to attain to a real knowledge of the truth.
B055C003V008	55	3	8	Just as Jannes and Jambres opposed Moses, so do these people, in their turn, oppose the truth. Their minds are corrupted, and, as regards the faith, they are utterly worthless.
B055C003V009	55	3	9	They will not, however, make further progress; for their wicked folly will be plain to everyone, just as the folly Jannes and Jambres was.
B055C003V010	55	3	10	But you, Timothy, were a close observer of my teaching, my conduct, my purposes, my faith, my forbearance, my love, and my patient endurance,
B055C003V011	55	3	11	as well as of my persecutions, and of the sufferings which I met with at Antioch, Iconium, and Lystra. You know what persecutions I underwent; and yet the Lord brought me safe out of all!
B055C003V012	55	3	12	Yes, and all who aim at living a religious life in union with Christ Jesus will have to suffer persecution;
B055C003V013	55	3	13	but wicked people and impostors will go from bad to worse, deceiving others and deceived themselves.
B055C003V014	55	3	14	You, however, must stand by what you learnt and accepted as true. You know who they were from whom you learnt it;
B055C003V015	55	3	15	and that, from your childhood, you have known the sacred writings, which can give you the wisdom that, through belief in Christ Jesus, leads to salvation.
B055C003V016	55	3	16	All scripture is God-breathed: helpful for teaching, for refuting error, for giving guidance, and for training others in righteousness;
B055C003V017	55	3	17	so that God’s people may be capable and equipped for good work of every kind.
B055C004V001	55	4	1	I solemnly charge you, in the sight of God and of Christ Jesus, who will one day judge the living and the dead — I charge you by his appearing and by his kingdom: —
B055C004V002	55	4	2	Proclaim the message, be ready in season and out of season, convince, rebuke, encourage, never failing to instruct with forbearance.
B055C004V003	55	4	3	For a time will come when people will not tolerate sound teaching. They will follow their own wishes, and, in their itching for novelty, procure themselves a crowd of teachers.
B055C004V004	55	4	4	They will turn a deaf ear to the truth, and give their attention to legends instead.
B055C004V005	55	4	5	But you, Timothy, must always be temperate. Face hardships; do the work of a missionary; discharge all the duties of your office.
B055C004V006	55	4	6	As for me, my life blood is already being poured out; the time of my departure is close at hand.
B055C004V007	55	4	7	I have run the great race; I have finished the course; I have kept the faith.
B055C004V008	55	4	8	And now the crown of righteousness awaits me, which the Lord, the just judge, will give me on ‘that day’ — and not only to me, but to all who have loved his appearing.  
B055C004V009	55	4	9	Do your utmost to come to me soon;
B055C004V010	55	4	10	for Demas, in his love for the world, has deserted me. He has gone to Thessalonica, Crescens to Galatia, and Titus to Dalmatia.
B055C004V011	55	4	11	There is no one but Luke with me. Pick up Mark on your way, and bring him with you, for he is useful to me in my work.
B055C004V012	55	4	12	I have sent Tychicus to Ephesus.
B055C004V013	55	4	13	Bring with you, when you come, the cloak which I left at Troas with Carpus, and the books, especially the parchments.
B055C004V014	55	4	14	Alexander, the coppersmith, showed much ill feeling towards me. ‘The Lord will give him what his actions deserve.’
B055C004V015	55	4	15	You must also on your guard against him, for he is strongly opposed to our teaching.
B055C004V016	55	4	16	At my first trial no one stood by me. They all deserted me. May it never be counted against them!
B055C004V017	55	4	17	But the Lord came to my help and strengthened me, in order that, through me, the proclamation should be made so widely that all the Gentiles should hear it; and I was rescued ‘out of the Lion’s mouth.’
B055C004V018	55	4	18	The Lord will rescue me from all evil, and bring me safe into his Heavenly kingdom. All glory to him for ever and ever! Amen.
B055C004V019	55	4	19	Give my greeting to Prisca and Aquila, and to the household of Onesiphorus.
B055C004V020	55	4	20	Erastus remained at Corinth, and I left Thophimus ill at Miletus.
B055C004V021	55	4	21	Do your utmost to come before winter. Eubulus, Pudens, Linus and Claudia send you their greetings, and so do the rest of the Lord's followers.
B055C004V022	55	4	22	May the Lord be with your soul. God bless you all.
B056C001V001	56	1	1	From Paul, a servant of God, and an apostle of Jesus Christ, charged to strengthen the faith of God’s chosen people, and their knowledge of that truth which makes for godliness
B056C001V002	56	1	2	and is based on the hope of eternal life, which God, who never lies, promised before the ages began,
B056C001V003	56	1	3	and has revealed at his own time in his message, with the proclamation of which I was entrusted by the command of God our Saviour.
B056C001V004	56	1	4	To Titus, my true child in our one faith: May God, the Father, and Christ Jesus, our Saviour, bless you and give you peace.
B056C001V005	56	1	5	My reason for leaving you in Crete was that you might put in order what had been left unsettled, and appoint officers of the church in the various towns, as I myself directed you.
B056C001V006	56	1	6	They are to be of irreproachable character, faithful to their partners, whose children are Christians and have never been charged with dissolute conduct or have been unruly.
B056C001V007	56	1	7	For a presiding officer, as God’s steward, ought to be of irreproachable character; not self-willed or quick-tempered, nor addicted to drink or to brawling or to questionable money-making.
B056C001V008	56	1	8	On the contrary, they should be hospitable, eager for the right, discreet, upright, people of holy life and capable of self-restraint,
B056C001V009	56	1	9	who hold doctrine that can be relied on as being in accordance with the accepted teaching; so that they may be able to encourage others by sound teaching, as well as to refute our opponents.
B056C001V010	56	1	10	There are, indeed, many unruly persons — great talkers who deceive themselves, principally converts from Judaism,
B056C001V011	56	1	11	whose mouths ought to be stopped; for they upset whole households by teaching what they ought not to teach, merely to make questionable gains.
B056C001V012	56	1	12	It was a Cretan — one of their own teachers — who said: ‘Cretans are always liars, base brutes, and gluttonous idlers’; and his statement is true.
B056C001V013	56	1	13	Therefore rebuke them sharply, so that they may be sound in the faith,
B056C001V014	56	1	14	and may pay no attention to Jewish legends, or to the directions of those who turn their backs on the truth.
B056C001V015	56	1	15	Everything is pure to the pure-minded, but to those whose minds are polluted and who are unbelievers nothing is pure. Their minds and consciences are alike polluted.
B056C001V016	56	1	16	They profess to know God, but by their actions they disown him. They are degraded and self-willed; and, as far as anything good is concerned, they are utterly worthless.  
B056C002V001	56	2	1	You should, however, speak of such subjects as properly have a place in sound Christian teaching.
B056C002V002	56	2	2	Teach that the older men should be temperate, serious, and discreet; strong in faith, love, and endurance.
B056C002V003	56	2	3	So, too, that the older women should be reverent in their demeanour, and that they should avoid scandal, and beware of becoming slaves to drink;
B056C002V004	56	2	4	that they should teach what is right, so as to train the younger women to love their husbands and children,
B056C002V005	56	2	5	and to be discreet, pure-minded, domesticated, good women, respecting the authority of their husbands, in order that God’s message may not be maligned.
B056C002V006	56	2	6	And so again with the younger men — impress on them the need of discretion.
B056C002V007	56	2	7	Above all, set an example of doing good. Show sincerity in your teaching, and a serious spirit;
B056C002V008	56	2	8	let the instruction that you give be sound and above reproach, so that the enemy may be ashamed when he fails to find anything bad to say about us.
B056C002V009	56	2	9	Tell slaves to respect their owner's authority in all circumstances, and to try their best to please them.
B056C002V010	56	2	10	Teach them not to contradict or to pilfer, but to show such praiseworthy fidelity in everything, as to recommend the teaching about God our Saviour by all that they do.
B056C002V011	56	2	11	For the loving kindness of God has been revealed, bringing salvation for all;
B056C002V012	56	2	12	leading us to renounce irreligious ways and worldly ambitions, and to live discreet, upright, and religious lives here in this present world,
B056C002V013	56	2	13	while we are awaiting our blessed hope — the appearing in glory of our great God and Saviour, Christ Jesus.
B056C002V014	56	2	14	For he gave himself on our behalf, to deliver us from all wickedness, and to purify for himself a people who should be peculiarly his own and eager to do good.
B056C002V015	56	2	15	Speak of all this, and encourage and rebuke with all authority. Do not let anyone despise you.  
B056C003V001	56	3	1	Remind your hearers to respect and obey the powers that be, to be ready for every kind of good work, to speak ill of no one, to avoid quarrelling,
B056C003V002	56	3	2	to be forbearing, and under all circumstances to show a gentle spirit in dealing with others, whoever they may be.
B056C003V003	56	3	3	There was, you remember, a time when we ourselves were foolish, disobedient, misled, slaves to all kinds of passions and vices, living in a spirit of malice and envy, detested ourselves and hating one another.
B056C003V004	56	3	4	But, when the kindness of God our Saviour and his love for humanity were revealed, he saved us,
B056C003V005	56	3	5	not as the result of any righteous actions that we had done, but in fulfilment of his merciful purposes. He saved us by that washing which was a new birth to us, and by the renewing power of the Holy Spirit,
B056C003V006	56	3	6	which he poured out on us abundantly through Jesus Christ our Saviour;
B056C003V007	56	3	7	that, having been pronounced righteous through his loving kindness, we might enter on our inheritance with the hope of eternal life.
B056C003V008	56	3	8	How true that saying is! And it is on these subjects that I desire you to lay especial stress, so that those who have learned to trust in God may be careful to devote themselves to doing good. Such subjects are excellent in themselves, and of real use to humanity.
B056C003V009	56	3	9	But have nothing to do with foolish discussions, or with genealogies, or with controversy, or disputes about the law. They are useless and futile.
B056C003V010	56	3	10	If someone is causing divisions among you, after warning them once or twice, have nothing more to say to them.
B056C003V011	56	3	11	You may be sure that such a person has forsaken the truth and is in the wrong; they stand self-condemned.
B056C003V012	56	3	12	As soon as I send Artemas or Tychicus to you, join me as quickly as possible at Nicopolis, for I have arranged to spend the winter there.
B056C003V013	56	3	13	Do your best to help Zenas, the teacher of the law, and Apollos, on their way, and see that they want for nothing.
B056C003V014	56	3	14	Let all our people learn to devote themselves to doing good, so as to meet the most pressing needs, and that their lives may not be unfruitful.
B056C003V015	56	3	15	All who are with me here send you their greeting. Give my greeting to our friends in the faith.   
B057C001V001	57	1	1	From Paul, now a prisoner for Christ Jesus, and from Timothy, a fellow follower of the Lord.
B057C001V002	57	1	2	To our dear friend and fellow worker Philemon, to our sister Apphia, to our fellow soldier Archippus; and to the church that meets at Philemon’s house;
B057C001V003	57	1	3	may God, our Father, and the Lord Jesus Christ bless you and give you peace.
B057C001V004	57	1	4	I always mention you in my prayers and thank God for you,
B057C001V005	57	1	5	because I hear of the love and the faith which you show, not only to the Lord Jesus, but also to all his people;
B057C001V006	57	1	6	and I pray that your participation in the faith may result in action, as you come to a fuller realisation of everything that is good and Christlike in us.
B057C001V007	57	1	7	I have indeed found great joy and encouragement in your love, knowing, as I do, how the hearts of Christ’s People have been cheered, friend, by you.
B057C001V008	57	1	8	And so, though my union with Christ enables me, with all confidence, to dictate the course that you should adopt,
B057C001V009	57	1	9	yet the claims of love make me prefer to plead with you — yes, even me, Paul, though I am an ambassador for Christ Jesus and, now a prisoner for him as well.
B057C001V010	57	1	10	I plead with you for this child of mine, Onesimus, to whom, in my prison, I have become a father.
B057C001V011	57	1	11	Once he was of little service to you, but now he has become of great service, not only to you, but to me as well;
B057C001V012	57	1	12	and I am sending him back to you with this letter — though it is like tearing out of my heart.
B057C001V013	57	1	13	For my own sake I should like to keep him with me, so that, while I am in prison for the good news, he might attend to my wants on your behalf.
B057C001V014	57	1	14	But I do not wish to do anything without your consent, because I want your generosity to be voluntary and not, as it were, compulsory.
B057C001V015	57	1	15	It may be that he was separated from you for an hour, for this reason, so that you might have him back for ever,
B057C001V016	57	1	16	no longer as a slave, but as something better — a dearly loved friend and follower of the Lord, especially dear to me, and how much more so to you, not only as a person, but as your fellow Christian!
B057C001V017	57	1	17	If, then, you count me your friend, receive him as you would me.
B057C001V018	57	1	18	If he has caused you any loss, or owes you anything, charge it to me.
B057C001V019	57	1	19	I, Paul, put my own hand to it — I will repay you myself. I say nothing about your owing me your self.
B057C001V020	57	1	20	Yes, friend, let me gain something from you because of your union with the Lord. Cheer my heart by your Christlike spirit.  
B057C001V021	57	1	21	Even as I write, I have such confidence in your compliance with my wishes, that I am sure that you will do even more than I am asking.
B057C001V022	57	1	22	Please also get a lodging ready for me, for I hope that I will be given back to you all in answer to your prayers.
B057C001V023	57	1	23	Epaphras, who is my fellow prisoner for Christ Jesus, sends you his greeting;
B057C001V024	57	1	24	and Marcus, Aristarchus, Demas, and Luke, my fellow workers, send theirs.
B057C001V025	57	1	25	May the blessing of the Lord Jesus Christ rest on your souls.
B058C001V001	58	1	1	God, who, of old, at many times and in many ways, spoke to our ancestors, by the prophets,
B058C001V002	58	1	2	has in these latter days spoken to us by the Son, whom he appointed the heir of all things, and through whom he made the universe.
B058C001V003	58	1	3	For he is the radiance of the glory of God and the expression of his being, upholding all creation by the power of his word; and, when he had made an expiation for the sins of humanity, he ‘took his seat at the right hand’ of God’s Majesty on high,
B058C001V004	58	1	4	having shown himself as much greater than the angels as the name that he has inherited surpasses theirs.
B058C001V005	58	1	5	For to which of the angels did God ever say —  ‘You are my Son; this day I have become your Father’?  or again —  ‘I will be to him a Father, and he will be to me a Son’?
B058C001V006	58	1	6	And again, when God brought the first-born into the world, he said —  ‘Let all the angels of God bow down before him.’
B058C001V007	58	1	7	Speaking of the angels, he said —  ‘He makes the winds his angelsAnd the flames of fire his servants’;
B058C001V008	58	1	8	while of the Son he said —  ‘God is your throne for ever and ever;The sceptre of his kingdom is the sceptre of Justice;
B058C001V009	58	1	9	You love righteousness and hates iniquity;Therefore God, your God, has anointed you with the festal oil more abundantly than your peers.’
B058C001V010	58	1	10	Again —  ‘You, Lord, in the beginning did lay the foundation of the earth,And the heavens are the work of your hands.
B058C001V011	58	1	11	They will perish, but you remain;As a garment they will all grow old;
B058C001V012	58	1	12	As a mantle you will fold them up,And as a garment they will be changed,But you are the same, and your years will know no end.’
B058C001V013	58	1	13	To which of the angels has God ever said —  ‘Sit you at my right handUntil I put your enemies as a stool for your feet’?
B058C001V014	58	1	14	Are not all the angels spirits in the service of God, sent out to minister for the sake of those who are destined to obtain salvation?  
B058C002V001	58	2	1	Therefore we must give still more heed to what we were taught, so we do not drift away.
B058C002V002	58	2	2	For, if the message which was delivered by angels had its authority confirmed, so that every offence against it, or neglect of it, met with a fitting requital,
B058C002V003	58	2	3	how can we, of all people, expect to escape, if we disregard so great a salvation? It was the Master who at the outset spoke of this salvation, and its authority was confirmed for us by those who heard him,
B058C002V004	58	2	4	while God himself added his testimony to it by signs, and marvels, and many different miracles, as well as by imparting the Holy Spirit as he saw fit.
B058C002V005	58	2	5	God has not given to angels the control of that future world of which we are speaking!
B058C002V006	58	2	6	No; a writer has declared somewhere —  ‘What are mere mortals that you should remember them?Or human beings that you should care for them?
B058C002V007	58	2	7	You have made them, for a while, lower than angels;With glory and honour you have crowned them;You have set them over all that your hands have made;
B058C002V008	58	2	8	You have placed all things beneath their feet.’  This ‘placing of everything’ under humanity means that there was nothing which was not placed under them. As yet, however, we do not see everything placed under humanity.
B058C002V009	58	2	9	What our eyes do see is Jesus, who was made for a while lower than angels, now, because of his sufferings and death, crowned with glory and honour; so that his tasting the bitterness of death should, in God’s loving kindness, be on behalf of all humanity.
B058C002V010	58	2	10	It was, indeed, fitting that God, for whom and through whom all things exist, should, when leading many children to glory, make the author of their salvation perfect through suffering.
B058C002V011	58	2	11	For he who purifies, and those whom he purifies, all spring from One; and therefore he is not ashamed to call them his brothers and sisters.’
B058C002V012	58	2	12	He says —  ‘I will tell of your name to my brothers and sisters,In the midst of the congregation I will sing your praise.’
B058C002V013	58	2	13	And again —  ‘As for me, I will put my trust in God.’  And yet again —  ‘See, here am I and the children whom God gave me.’
B058C002V014	58	2	14	Therefore, since human nature is the common heritage of ‘the children,’ Jesus also shared it, in order that by death he might render powerless him whose power lies in death — that is, the devil —
B058C002V015	58	2	15	and so might deliver all those who, from fear of death, had all their lives been living in slavery.
B058C002V016	58	2	16	It was not, surely, to the help of the angels that Jesus came, but ‘to the help of the descendants of Abraham.’
B058C002V017	58	2	17	And consequently it was necessary that he should in all points be made like ‘his brothers and sisters,’ in order that he might prove a merciful as well as a faithful high priest in humanity’s relations with God, for the purpose of expiating the sins of his people.
B058C002V018	58	2	18	The fact that he himself suffered under temptation enables him to help those who are tempted.
B058C003V001	58	3	1	Therefore, my Christian friends, you who, all alike, have received the call from heaven, fix your attention on Jesus, the apostle and high priest of our religion.
B058C003V002	58	3	2	See how faithful he was to the God who appointed him, as Moses was in the whole house of God.
B058C003V003	58	3	3	He has been deemed worthy of far higher honour than Moses, just as the founder of the house is held in greater regard than the house itself.
B058C003V004	58	3	4	For every house has its founder, and the founder of the universe is God.
B058C003V005	58	3	5	While the faithful service of Moses in the whole house of God was that of a servant, whose duty was to bear testimony to a message still to come,
B058C003V006	58	3	6	the faithfulness of Christ was that of a son set over the house of God. And we are his house — if only we retain, unshaken to the end, the courage and confidence inspired by our hope.
B058C003V007	58	3	7	Therefore, as the Holy Spirit says —  ‘If today you hear God’s voice,
B058C003V008	58	3	8	harden not your hearts, as when Israel provoked meOn the day when they tried my patience in the desert,
B058C003V009	58	3	9	Where your ancestors tried my forbearance,And saw my mighty deeds for forty years.
B058C003V010	58	3	10	Therefore I was sorely vexed with that generation,And I said — “Their hearts are always straying;They have never learned my ways”;
B058C003V011	58	3	11	While in my wrath I swore —“They will never enter upon my rest.”’
B058C003V012	58	3	12	Be careful, friends, that there is never found in anyone of you a wicked and faithless heart, shown by that person separating themselves from the living God.
B058C003V013	58	3	13	Rather encourage one another daily — while there is a ‘Today’ — to prevent anyone among you from being hardened by the deceitfulness of sin.
B058C003V014	58	3	14	For we now all share in the Christ, if indeed we retain, unshaken to the end, the confidence that we had at the first.
B058C003V015	58	3	15	To use the words of scripture —  ‘If today you hear God’s voice,Harden not your hearts, as when Israel provoked me.’
B058C003V016	58	3	16	Who were they who heard God speak and yet provoked him? Were not they all those who left Egypt under the leadership of Moses?
B058C003V017	58	3	17	And with whom was it that God was sorely vexed for forty years? Was not it with those who had sinned, and who fell dead in the desert?
B058C003V018	58	3	18	And who were they to whom God swore that they should not enter upon his rest, if not those who had proved faithless?
B058C003V019	58	3	19	We see, then, that they failed to enter upon it because of their want of faith.  
B058C004V001	58	4	1	We must, therefore, be very careful, though there is a promise still standing that we will enter upon God’s rest, that none of you even appear to have missed it.
B058C004V002	58	4	2	For we have had the good news told us just as they had. But the message which they heard did them no good, since they did not share the faith of those who were attentive to it.
B058C004V003	58	4	3	Upon that rest we who have believed are now entering. As God has said —  ‘In my wrath I swore —“They will never enter upon my rest;”’  Although God’s work was finished at the creation of the world;
B058C004V004	58	4	4	for, in a passage referring to the seventh day, you will find these words —  ‘God rested on the seventh day after all his work.’
B058C004V005	58	4	5	On the other hand, we read in that passage —  ‘They will never enter upon my rest.’
B058C004V006	58	4	6	Since, then, there is still a promise that some will enter upon this rest, and since those who were first told the good news did not enter upon it, because of their disbelief,
B058C004V007	58	4	7	again God fixed a day. ‘Today,’ he said, speaking after a long interval through the mouth of David, in the passage already quoted —  ‘If today you hear God’s voiceHarden not your hearts.’
B058C004V008	58	4	8	Now if Joshua had given ‘rest’ to the people, God would not have spoken of another and later day.
B058C004V009	58	4	9	There is, then, a Sabbath rest still awaiting God’s people.
B058C004V010	58	4	10	For the person who enters upon God’s rest do themselves rest after their work, just as God did.
B058C004V011	58	4	11	Let us, therefore, make every effort to enter upon that rest, so that none of us fall through such disbelief as that of which we have had an example.
B058C004V012	58	4	12	God’s message is a living and active power, sharper than any two-edged sword, piercing its way until it penetrates soul and spirit — not the joints only but the marrow — and detecting the inmost thoughts and purposes of the mind.
B058C004V013	58	4	13	There is no created thing that can hide itself from the sight of God. Everything is exposed and laid bare before the eyes of him to whom we have to give account.
B058C004V014	58	4	14	We have, then , in Jesus, the Son of God, a great high priest who has passed into the highest heaven; let us, therefore, hold fast to the faith which we have professed.
B058C004V015	58	4	15	Our high priest is not one unable to sympathise with our weaknesses, but one who has in every way been tempted, exactly as we have been, but without sinning.
B058C004V016	58	4	16	Therefore, let us draw near boldly to the throne of love, to find pity and love for the hour of need.  
B058C005V001	58	5	1	Every high priest, taken from among the people, is appointed as their representative in their relations with God, to offer both gifts and sacrifices in expiation of sins.
B058C005V002	58	5	2	And he is able to sympathise with the ignorant and deluded, since he is himself subject to weakness,
B058C005V003	58	5	3	and is therefore bound to offer sacrifices for sins, not only for the people, but equally so for himself.
B058C005V004	58	5	4	Nor does anyone take that high office on themselves, until they have been called to do so by God, as Aaron was.
B058C005V005	58	5	5	In the same way, even the Christ did not take the honour of the high priesthood on himself, but he was appointed by him who said to him —  ‘You are my Son; this day I have become your Father’;
B058C005V006	58	5	6	and on another occasion also —  ‘You are a priest for all time of the order of Melchizedek.’
B058C005V007	58	5	7	Jesus, in the days of his earthly life, offered prayers and supplications, with earnest cries and with tears, to him who was able to save him from death; and he was heard because of his devout submission.
B058C005V008	58	5	8	Son though he was, he learned obedience from his sufferings;
B058C005V009	58	5	9	and, being made perfect, he became to all those who obey him the source of eternal salvation,
B058C005V010	58	5	10	while God himself pronounced him a high priest of the order of Melchizedek.
B058C005V011	58	5	11	Now on this subject I have much to say, but it is difficult to explain it to you, because you have shown yourselves so slow to learn.
B058C005V012	58	5	12	For whereas, considering the time that has elapsed, you ought to be teaching others, you still need some one to teach you the alphabet of the divine revelation, and need again to be fed with ‘milk’ instead of with ‘solid food.’
B058C005V013	58	5	13	For everyone who still has to take ‘milk’ knows nothing of the teaching of righteousness; they are a mere infant.
B058C005V014	58	5	14	But ‘solid food’ is for Christians of mature faith — those whose faculties have been trained by practice to distinguish right from wrong.
B058C006V001	58	6	1	Therefore, let us leave behind the elementary teaching about the Christ and press on to perfection, not always laying over again a foundation of repentance for a lifeless formality, of faith in God —
B058C006V002	58	6	2	teaching concerning baptisms and the laying on of hands, the resurrection of the dead and a final judgment.
B058C006V003	58	6	3	Yes and, with God’s help, we will.
B058C006V004	58	6	4	For if those who were once for all brought into the light, and learned to appreciate the gift from heaven, and came to share in the Holy Spirit,
B058C006V005	58	6	5	and learned to appreciate the beauty of the divine message, and the new powers of the coming age —
B058C006V006	58	6	6	if those, I say, fell away, it would be impossible to bring them again to repentance; they would be crucifying the Son of God over again for themselves, and exposing him to open contempt.
B058C006V007	58	6	7	Ground that drinks in the showers that from time to time fall on it, and produces vegetation useful to those for whom it is tilled, receives a blessing from God;
B058C006V008	58	6	8	but, if it ‘bears thorns and thistles,’ it is regarded as worthless, it is in danger of being ‘cursed,’ and its end will be the fire.
B058C006V009	58	6	9	But about you, dear friends, even though we speak in this way, we are confident of better things — of things that point to your salvation.
B058C006V010	58	6	10	For God is not unjust; he will not forget the work that you did, and the love that you showed for his name, in sending help to your fellow Christians — as you are still doing.
B058C006V011	58	6	11	But our great desire is that every one of you should be equally earnest to attain to a full conviction that our hope will be fulfilled, and that you should keep that hope to the end.
B058C006V012	58	6	12	Then you will not show yourselves slow to learn, but you will copy those who, through faith and patience, are now entering upon the enjoyment of God’s promises.  
B058C006V013	58	6	13	When God gave his promise to Abraham, since there was no one greater by whom he could swear, he swore by himself.
B058C006V014	58	6	14	His words were —  ‘I will assuredly bless you and increase your numbers.’
B058C006V015	58	6	15	And so, after patiently waiting, Abraham obtained the fulfilment of God’s promise.
B058C006V016	58	6	16	People, of course, swear by what is greater than themselves, and with them an oath is accepted as putting a matter beyond all dispute.
B058C006V017	58	6	17	And therefore God, in his desire to show, with unmistakable plainness, to those who were to enter on the enjoyment of what he had promised, the unchangeableness of his purpose, bound himself with an oath.
B058C006V018	58	6	18	For he intended us to find great encouragement in these two unchangeable things, which make it impossible for God to prove false — we, I mean, who fled for safety where we might lay hold on the hope set before us.
B058C006V019	58	6	19	This hope is an anchor for our souls, secure and strong, and it ‘reaches into the sanctuary that lies behind the curtain,’
B058C006V020	58	6	20	where Jesus, our forerunner, has entered on our behalf, after being made for all time a high priest of the order of Melchizedek.  
B058C007V001	58	7	1	It was this Melchizedek, king of Salem and priest of the Most High God, who met Abraham returning from the slaughter of the kings, and gave him his blessing;
B058C007V002	58	7	2	and it was to him that Abraham allotted a tithe of all the spoil. The meaning of his name is ‘king of righteousness,’ and besides that, he was also king of Salem, which means ‘king of peace.’
B058C007V003	58	7	3	There is no record of his father, or mother, or lineage, nor again of any beginning of his days, or end of his life. In this he resembles the Son of God, and stands before us as a priest whose priesthood is continuous.
B058C007V004	58	7	4	Consider, then the importance of this Melchizedek, to whom even the patriarch Abraham himself gave a tithe of the choicest spoils.
B058C007V005	58	7	5	Those descendants of Levi, who are from time to time appointed to the priesthood, are directed to collect tithes from the people in accordance with the law — that is from their own kindred, although they also are descended from Abraham.
B058C007V006	58	7	6	But Melchizedek, although not of this lineage, received tithes from Abraham, and gave his blessing to the man who had God’s promises.
B058C007V007	58	7	7	Now no one can dispute that it is the superior who blesses the inferior.
B058C007V008	58	7	8	In the one case the tithes are received by people who are mortal; in the other case by one about whom there is the statement that his life still continues.
B058C007V009	58	7	9	Moreover, in a sense, even Levi, who is the receiver of the tithes, has, through Abraham, paid tithes;
B058C007V010	58	7	10	for Levi was still in the body of his ancestor when Melchizedek met Abraham.  
B058C007V011	58	7	11	If, then, perfection had been attainable through the Levitical priesthood — and it was under this priesthood that the people received the law — why was it still necessary that a priest of a different order should appear, a priest of the order of Melchizedek and not of the order of Aaron?
B058C007V012	58	7	12	With the change of the priesthood a change of the law became a necessity.
B058C007V013	58	7	13	And he of whom all this is said belonged to quite a different tribe, no member of which has ever served at the altar.
B058C007V014	58	7	14	For it is plain that our Lord had sprung from the tribe of Judah, though of that tribe Moses said nothing about their being priests.
B058C007V015	58	7	15	All this becomes even yet plainer when we remember that a new priest has appeared, resembling Melchizedek,
B058C007V016	58	7	16	and that he was appointed, not under a law regulating only earthly matters, but by virtue of a life beyond the reach of death;
B058C007V017	58	7	17	for that is the meaning of the declaration —  ‘You are for all time a priest of the order of Melchizedek.’
B058C007V018	58	7	18	On the one hand, we have the abolition of a previous regulation as being both inefficient and useless
B058C007V019	58	7	19	(for the law never brought anything to perfection); and, on the other hand, we have the introduction of a better hope, which enables us to draw near to God.
B058C007V020	58	7	20	Then again, the appointment of this new priest was ratified by an oath, which is not so with the Levitical priests,
B058C007V021	58	7	21	but his appointment was ratified by an oath, when God said to him —  ‘The Lord has sworn, and will not change, “You are a priest for all time.”’
B058C007V022	58	7	22	And the oath shows the corresponding superiority of the covenant of which Jesus is appointed the surety.
B058C007V023	58	7	23	Again, new Levitical priests are continually being appointed, because death prevents their remaining in office;
B058C007V024	58	7	24	but Jesus remains for all time, and therefore the priesthood that he holds will never pass to another.
B058C007V025	58	7	25	And that is why he is able to save perfectly those who come to God through him, living for ever, as he does, to intercede of their behalf.  
B058C007V026	58	7	26	This was the high priest that we needed — holy, innocent, spotless, withdrawn from sinners, exalted above the highest heaven,
B058C007V027	58	7	27	one who has no need to offer sacrifices daily as those high priests have, first for their own sins, and then for those of the people. For this he did once and for all, when he offered himself as the sacrifice.
B058C007V028	58	7	28	The law appoints as high priests men who are weak, but the words of God’s oath, which was later than the law, name the Son as, for all time, the perfect priest.  
B058C008V001	58	8	1	To sum up what I have been saying: — Such is the high priest that we have, one who ‘has taken his seat at the right hand’ of the throne of God’s Majesty in heaven,
B058C008V002	58	8	2	where he ministers in the sanctuary, in that true tent set up by the Lord and not by man.
B058C008V003	58	8	3	Every high priest is appointed for the purpose of offering gifts and sacrifices to God; it follows, therefore, that this high priest must have some offering to make.
B058C008V004	58	8	4	If he were, however, still on earth, he would not even be a priest, since there are already priests who offer the gifts as the law directs.
B058C008V005	58	8	5	(These priests, it is true, are engaged in a service which is only a copy and shadow of the heavenly realities, as is shown by the directions given to Moses when he was about to construct the tent. ‘Look to it,’ are the words, ‘that you make every part in accordance with the pattern shown you on the mountain.’)
B058C008V006	58	8	6	But Jesus, as we see, has obtained a ministry as far excelling theirs, as the covenant of which he is the intermediary, based, as it is, on better promises, excels the former covenant.
B058C008V007	58	8	7	If that first covenant had been faultless, there would have been no occasion for a second.
B058C008V008	58	8	8	But, finding fault with the people, God says —  ‘“A time is coming,” says the Lord,“When I will ratify a new covenant with the people of Israel and with the people of Judah —
B058C008V009	58	8	9	Not such a covenant as I made with their ancestorsOn the day when I took them by the hand to lead them out of the land of Egypt.For they did not abide by their covenant with me,And therefore I disregarded them,” says the Lord.
B058C008V010	58	8	10	“This is the covenant that I will make with the people of IsraelAfter those days,” says the Lord.“I will impress my laws on their minds,And will inscribe them on their hearts;And I will be their God,And they will be my people.
B058C008V011	58	8	11	There will be no need for anyone to instruct their fellow citizen,Or for a person to say to their relatives ‘Learn to know the Lord’;For everyone will know me,From the lowest to the highest.
B058C008V012	58	8	12	For I will be merciful to their wrong-doings,And I will no longer remember their sins.”’
B058C008V013	58	8	13	By speaking of a ‘new’ covenant, God at once renders the former covenant obsolete; and whatever becomes obsolete and loses its force is virtually annulled.
B058C009V001	58	9	1	It is true that even the first covenant had its regulations for divine worship, and its sanctuary — though only a material one.
B058C009V002	58	9	2	For a tent was constructed, with an outer part which contained the stand for the lamps, and the table, and the consecrated bread. This is called the sanctuary.
B058C009V003	58	9	3	The part of the tent behind the second curtain is called the inner sanctuary.
B058C009V004	58	9	4	In it is the gold incense-altar, and the ark containing the covenant, completely covered with gold. In the ark is a gold casket containing the manna, Aaron’s rod that budded, and the tablets on which the covenant was written;
B058C009V005	58	9	5	while above it, and overshadowing the cover on which atonement was made, are the cherubim of the presence. Now is not the time to discuss these things in detail.
B058C009V006	58	9	6	Such, then, was the arrangement of the tent. Into the outer part priests are constantly going, in the discharge of their sacred duties;
B058C009V007	58	9	7	but into the inner only the high priest goes, and that but once a year, and never without taking the blood of a victim, which he offers on his own behalf, and on behalf of the errors of the people.
B058C009V008	58	9	8	By this the Holy Spirit is teaching that the way into the sanctuary was hidden, as long as the outer part of the tent still remained.
B058C009V009	58	9	9	For that was only a type, to continue down to the present time; and, in keeping with it, both gifts and sacrifices are offered, though incapable of satisfying the conscience of the worshiper;
B058C009V010	58	9	10	the whole system being concerned only with food and drink and various ablutions — external ceremonials imposed until the coming of the new order.
B058C009V011	58	9	11	But, when Christ came, he appeared as high priest of that better system which was established; and he entered through that nobler and more perfect ‘tent,’ not made by human hands — that is to say, not a part of this present creation.
B058C009V012	58	9	12	Nor was it with the blood of goats and calves, but with his own blood, that he entered, once and for all, into the sanctuary, and obtained our eternal deliverance.
B058C009V013	58	9	13	For, if the blood of goats and bulls, and the sprinkling of the ashes of a heifer, purify those who have been defiled (as far as ceremonial purification goes),
B058C009V014	58	9	14	how much more will the blood of the Christ, who, through his eternal Spirit, offered himself up to God, as a victim without blemish, purify our consciences from a lifeless formality, and fit us for the service of the living God!
B058C009V015	58	9	15	And that is why he is the intermediary of a new covenant; in order that, as a death has taken place to effect a deliverance from the offences committed under the first covenant, those who have received the call may obtain the eternal inheritance promised to them.
B058C009V016	58	9	16	Whenever such a covenant as a will is in question, the death of the testator must of necessity be alleged.
B058C009V017	58	9	17	For such a covenant takes effect only on death, it does not come into force as long as the testator is alive.
B058C009V018	58	9	18	This explains why even the first covenant was not ratified without the shedding of blood.
B058C009V019	58	9	19	For, when every command had been announced to all the people by Moses in accordance with the law, he took the blood of the calves and of the goats, with water, scarlet wool, and a bunch of hyssop, and sprinkled even the book of the law, as well as all the people,
B058C009V020	58	9	20	saying, as he did so — “This is the blood that renders valid the covenant which God has commanded to be made with you.”
B058C009V021	58	9	21	And in the same way he also sprinkled with the blood the tent and all the things that were used in public worship.
B058C009V022	58	9	22	Indeed, under the law, almost everything is purified with blood; and, unless blood is shed, no forgiveness is to be obtained.  
B058C009V023	58	9	23	While, then, it was necessary for the copies of the heavenly realities to be purified by such means as these, the heavenly realities themselves required better sacrifices.
B058C009V024	58	9	24	For it was not into a sanctuary made by human hands, which merely foreshadowed the true one, that Christ entered, but into heaven itself, so that he might now appear in the presence of God on our behalf.
B058C009V025	58	9	25	Nor yet was it to offer himself may times, as year after year the high priest entered the sanctuary with an offering of blood — but not his own blood;
B058C009V026	58	9	26	for then Christ would have had to undergo death many times since the creation of the world. But now, once and for all, at the close of the age, he has appeared, in order to abolish sin by the sacrifice of himself.
B058C009V027	58	9	27	And, as it is ordained for people to die but once (death being followed by judgment),
B058C009V028	58	9	28	so it is with the Christ. He was offered up once and for all, to ‘bear away the sins of many’; and the second time he will appear — but without any burden of sin — to those who are waiting for him, to bring salvation.  
B058C010V001	58	10	1	The law, though able to foreshadow the better system which was coming, never had its actual substance. Its priests, with those sacrifices which they offer continuously year after year, can never make those who come to worship perfect.
B058C010V002	58	10	2	Otherwise, would not the offering of these sacrifices have been abandoned, as the worshipers, having been once purified, would have had their consciences clear from sins?
B058C010V003	58	10	3	But, on the contrary, these sacrifices recall their sins to mind year after year.
B058C010V004	58	10	4	For the blood of bulls and goats is powerless to remove sins.
B058C010V005	58	10	5	That is why, when he was coming into the world, the Christ declared —  ‘Sacrifice and offering you do not desire, but you provide for me a body;
B058C010V006	58	10	6	You take no pleasure in burnt offerings and sacrifices for sin.
B058C010V007	58	10	7	So I said, “See, I have come’ (as is written of me in the pages of the book),“To do your will, God.”’
B058C010V008	58	10	8	First come the words — ‘You do not desire, nor do you take pleasure in, sacrifices, offerings, burnt offerings, and sacrifices for sin’ (offerings regularly made under the law),
B058C010V009	58	10	9	and then there is added — ‘See, I have come to do your will.’ The former sacrifices are set aside to be replaced by the latter.
B058C010V010	58	10	10	And it is in the fulfilment of the will of God that we have been purified by the sacrifice, once and for all, of the body of Jesus Christ.
B058C010V011	58	10	11	Every other priest stands day after day at his ministrations, and offers the same sacrifices over and over again — sacrifices that can never take sins away.
B058C010V012	58	10	12	But, this priest, after he had offered one sacrifice for sins, which should serve for all time, ‘took his seat at the right hand of God,’
B058C010V013	58	10	13	and has since then been waiting ‘for his enemies to be put as a stool for his feet.’
B058C010V014	58	10	14	By a single offering he has made perfect for all time those who are being purified.
B058C010V015	58	10	15	We have also the testimony of the Holy Spirit. For, after saying —
B058C010V016	58	10	16	‘“This is the covenant that I will make with themAfter those days,” says the Lord;“I will impress my laws on their hearts,And will inscribe them on their minds,”’
B058C010V017	58	10	17	then we have —  ‘And their sins and their iniquities I will no longer remember.’
B058C010V018	58	10	18	And, when these are forgiven, there is no further need of an offering for sin.
B058C010V019	58	10	19	Therefore, friends, since we may enter the sanctuary with confidence, in virtue of the blood of Jesus,
B058C010V020	58	10	20	by the way which he inaugurated for us — a new and living way, a way through the sanctuary curtain (that is, his human nature);
B058C010V021	58	10	21	and, since we have in him ‘a great priest set over the house of God,’
B058C010V022	58	10	22	let us draw near to God in all sincerity of heart and in perfect faith, with our hearts purified by the sprinkled blood from all consciousness of wrong, and with our bodies washed with pure water.
B058C010V023	58	10	23	Let us maintain the confession of our hope unshaken, for he who has given us his promise will not fail us.
B058C010V024	58	10	24	Let us vie with one another in a rivalry of love and noble actions.
B058C010V025	58	10	25	And let us not, as some do, cease to meet together; but, on the contrary, let us encourage one another, and all the more, now that you see the day drawing near.
B058C010V026	58	10	26	Remember, if we sin wilfully after we have gained a full knowledge of the truth, there can be no further sacrifice for sin;
B058C010V027	58	10	27	there is only a fearful anticipation of judgment, and a burning indignation which will destroy all opponents.
B058C010V028	58	10	28	When someone disregarded the law of Moses, they were, on the evidence of two or three witnesses, put to death without pity.
B058C010V029	58	10	29	How much worse then, think you, will be the punishment deserved by those who have trampled underfoot the Son of God, who have treated the blood that rendered the covenant valid — the blood by which they were purified — as if it were not holy, and who have outraged the Spirit of love?
B058C010V030	58	10	30	We know who it was that said —  ‘It is for me to avenge, I will requite’;  and again —  ‘The Lord will judge his people.’
B058C010V031	58	10	31	It is a fearful thing to fall into the hands of the living God.
B058C010V032	58	10	32	Call to mind those early days in which, after you had received the light, you patiently underwent a long and painful conflict.
B058C010V033	58	10	33	Sometimes, in consequence of the taunts and injuries heaped on you, you became a public spectacle; and sometimes you suffered through having shown yourselves to be the friends of people who were in the same position in which you had been.
B058C010V034	58	10	34	For you not only sympathised with those who were in prison, but you even took the confiscation of your possessions joyfully, knowing, as you did, that you had in yourselves a greater possession and a lasting one.
B058C010V035	58	10	35	Do not, therefore, abandon the confidence that you have gained, for it has a great reward awaiting it.
B058C010V036	58	10	36	You still have need of patient endurance, in order that, when you have done God’s will, you may obtain the fulfilment of his promise.
B058C010V037	58	10	37	‘For there is indeed but a very little whileEre He who is coming will have come, without delay;
B058C010V038	58	10	38	And through faith the righteous will find life,But, if anyone draws back, my heart can find no pleasure in them.’
B058C010V039	58	10	39	But we do not belong to those who draw back, to their ruin, but to those who have faith, to the saving of their souls.  
B058C011V001	58	11	1	Faith is the realisation of things hoped for — the proof of things not seen.
B058C011V002	58	11	2	And it was for faith that the people of old were renowned.
B058C011V003	58	11	3	Faith enables us to perceive that the universe was created at the bidding of God — so that we know that what we see was not made out of visible things.
B058C011V004	58	11	4	Faith made the sacrifice which Abel offered to God a better sacrifice than Cain’s, and won him renown as a righteous man, God himself establishing his renown by accepting his gifts; and it is by the example of his faith that Abel, though dead, still speaks.
B058C011V005	58	11	5	Faith led to Enoch’s removal from earth, so that he might not experience death. ‘He could not be found because God had removed him.’ For, before his removal, he was renowned as having pleased God;
B058C011V006	58	11	6	but without faith it is impossible to please him, for he who comes to God must believe that God exists, and that he rewards those who seek for him.
B058C011V007	58	11	7	It was faith that enabled Noah, after he had received the divine warning about what could not then be foreseen, to build, in reverent obedience, an ark in which to save his family. By his faith he condemned the world, and became possessed of that righteousness which follows on faith.  
B058C011V008	58	11	8	It was faith that enabled Abraham to obey the call that he received, and to set out for the place which he was afterwards to obtain as his own; and he set out not knowing where he was going.
B058C011V009	58	11	9	It was faith that made him go to live as an emigrant in the promised land — as in a strange country — living there in tents with Isaac and Jacob, who shared the promise with him.
B058C011V010	58	11	10	For he was looking for the city with the sure foundations, whose architect and builder is God.  
B058C011V011	58	11	11	Again, it was faith that enabled Sarah to conceive (though she was past the age for child-bearing), because she felt sure that he who had given her the promise would not fail her.
B058C011V012	58	11	12	And so from one man — and that when his powers were dead — there sprang a people as numerous ‘as the stars in the heavens or the countless grains of sand on the shore.’  
B058C011V013	58	11	13	All these died sustained by faith. They did not obtain the promised blessings, but they saw them from a distance and welcomed the sight, and they acknowledged themselves to be only aliens and strangers on the earth.
B058C011V014	58	11	14	Those who speak like this show plainly that they are seeking their homeland.
B058C011V015	58	11	15	If they had been thinking of the land that they had left, they could have found opportunities to return.
B058C011V016	58	11	16	But no, they were longing for a better, a heavenly, land! And therefore God was not ashamed to be called their God; indeed he had already prepared them a city.
B058C011V017	58	11	17	It was faith that enabled Abraham, when put to the test, to offer Isaac as a sacrifice — he who had received the promises offering up his only son,
B058C011V018	58	11	18	of whom it had been said —  ‘It is through Isaac that there will be descendants to bear your name.’
B058C011V019	58	11	19	For he argued that God was even able to raise a man from the dead — and indeed, figuratively speaking, Abraham did receive Isaac back from the dead.
B058C011V020	58	11	20	It was faith that enabled Isaac to bless Jacob and Esau, even with regard to the future.
B058C011V021	58	11	21	Faith enabled Jacob, when dying, to give his blessing to each of the sons of Joseph, and ‘to bow himself in worship as he leant on the top of his staff.’
B058C011V022	58	11	22	Faith caused Joseph, when his end was near, to speak of the future migration of the Israelites, and to give instructions with regard to his bones.
B058C011V023	58	11	23	Faith caused the parents of Moses to hide the child for three months after his birth, for they saw that he was a beautiful child; and they would not respect the king’s order.
B058C011V024	58	11	24	It was faith that caused Moses, when he was grown up, to refuse the title of ‘son of a daughter of Pharaoh.’
B058C011V025	58	11	25	He preferred sharing the hardships of God’s people to enjoying the short-lived pleasures of sin.
B058C011V026	58	11	26	For he counted ‘the reproaches that are heaped on the Christ’ of greater value than the treasures of Egypt, looking forward, as he did, to the reward awaiting him.
B058C011V027	58	11	27	Faith caused him to leave Egypt, though undaunted by the king’s anger, for he was strengthened in his endurance by the vision of the invisible God.
B058C011V028	58	11	28	Faith led him to institute the Passover and the sprinkling of the blood, so that the Destroyer might not touch the eldest children of the Israelites.
B058C011V029	58	11	29	Faith enabled the people to cross the Red Sea, as if it had been dry land, while the Egyptians, when they attempted to do so, were drowned.
B058C011V030	58	11	30	Faith caused the walls of Jericho to fall after being encircled for seven days.
B058C011V031	58	11	31	Faith saved Rahab, the prostitute, from perishing with the unbelievers, after she had entertained the spies with friendliness.  
B058C011V032	58	11	32	Need I add anything more? Time would fail me if I attempted to relate the stories of Gideon, Barak, Samson, and Jephthah, and those of David, Samuel, and the prophets.
B058C011V033	58	11	33	By their faith they subdued kingdoms, ruled righteously, gained the fulfilment of God’s promises, ‘shut the mouths of lions,’
B058C011V034	58	11	34	quelled the fury of the flames, escaped the edge of the sword, found strength in the hour of weakness, displayed their prowess in war, and routed hostile armies.
B058C011V035	58	11	35	Women received back their dead raised to life. Some were tortured on the wheel, and refused release in order that they might rise to a better life.
B058C011V036	58	11	36	Others had to face taunts and blows, and even chains and imprisonment.
B058C011V037	58	11	37	They were stoned to death, they were tortured, they were swan asunder, they were put to the sword; they wandered about clothed in the skins of sheep or goats, destitute, persecuted, ill-used —
B058C011V038	58	11	38	people of whom the world was not worthy — roaming in lonely places, and on the mountains, and in caves and holes in the ground.
B058C011V039	58	11	39	Yet, though they all won renown by their faith, they did not obtain the final fulfilment of God’s promise;
B058C011V040	58	11	40	since God had in view some better thing for us, so that they would only reach perfection together with us.  
B058C012V001	58	12	1	Seeing, therefore, that there is on every side of us such a throng of witnesses, let us also lay aside everything that hinders us, and the sin that clings about us, and run with patient endurance the race that lies before us,
B058C012V002	58	12	2	our eyes fixed on Jesus, the leader and perfect example of our faith, who, for the joy that lay before him, endured the cross, heedless of its shame, and now ‘has taken his seat at the right hand’ of the throne of God.
B058C012V003	58	12	3	Weigh well the example of him who had to endure such opposition from ‘people who were sinning against themselves,’ so that you should not grow weary or faint-hearted.
B058C012V004	58	12	4	You have not yet, in your struggle with sin, resisted to the death;
B058C012V005	58	12	5	and you have forgotten the encouraging words which are addressed to you as God’s children —  ‘My child, think not lightly of the Lord’s discipline,Do not despond when he rebukes you;
B058C012V006	58	12	6	For it is him whom he loves that he disciplines,And he chastises every child whom he acknowledges.’
B058C012V007	58	12	7	It is for your discipline that you have to endure all this. God is dealing with you as his children. For where is there a child whom his father does not discipline?
B058C012V008	58	12	8	If you are left without that discipline, in which all children share, it shows that you are bastards, and not true children.
B058C012V009	58	12	9	Further, when our earthly fathers disciplined us, we respected them. Should we not, then, much rather yield submission to the Father of souls, and live?
B058C012V010	58	12	10	Our fathers disciplined us for only a short time and as seemed best to them; but God disciplines us for our true good, to enable us to share his holiness.
B058C012V011	58	12	11	No discipline is pleasant at the time; on the contrary, it is painful. But afterwards its fruit is seen in the peacefulness of a righteous life which is the lot of those who have been trained under it.
B058C012V012	58	12	12	Therefore ‘lift again the down-dropped hands and straighten the weakened knees;
B058C012V013	58	12	13	make straight paths for your feet,’ so that the lame limb may not be put out of joint, but rather be cured.
B058C012V014	58	12	14	Try earnestly to live at peace with everyone, and to attain to that purity without which no one will see the Lord.
B058C012V015	58	12	15	Take care that no one fails to use the loving help of God, ‘that no bitterness is allowed to take root and spring up, and cause trouble,’ and so poison the whole community.
B058C012V016	58	12	16	Take care that no one becomes immoral, or irreligious like Esau, who sold his birthright for a single meal.
B058C012V017	58	12	17	For you know that even afterwards, when he wished to claim his father’s blessing, he was rejected — for he never found an opportunity to repair his error — though he begged for the blessing with tears.
B058C012V018	58	12	18	It is not to tangible ‘flaming fire’ that you have drawn near, nor to ‘gloom, and darkness, and storm,
B058C012V019	58	12	19	and the blast of a trumpet, and an audible voice.’ Those who heard that voice entreated that they might hear no more,
B058C012V020	58	12	20	for they could not bear to think of the command — ‘If even an animal touches the mountain, it is to be stoned to death;’
B058C012V021	58	12	21	and so fearful was the sight that Moses said — ‘I tremble with fear.’
B058C012V022	58	12	22	No, but it is to Mount Zion that you have drawn near, the city of the living God, the heavenly Jerusalem, to countless hosts of angels,
B058C012V023	58	12	23	to the festal gathering and assemblage of God’s firstborn whose names are enrolled in heaven, to God the judge of all people, to the spirits of the righteous who have attained perfection,
B058C012V024	58	12	24	to Jesus, the intermediary of a new covenant, and to the sprinkled blood that tells of better things than the blood of Abel.
B058C012V025	58	12	25	Beware how you refuse to hear him who is speaking. For, if the Israelites did not escape punishment, when they refused to listen to him who taught them on earth the divine will, far worse will it be for us, if we turn away from him who is teaching us from heaven.
B058C012V026	58	12	26	Then his voice shook the earth, but now his declaration is —  ‘Still once more I will cause not only the earth to tremble, but also the heavens.’
B058C012V027	58	12	27	And those words ‘still once more’ indicate the passing away of all that is shaken — that is, of all created things — in order that only what is unshaken may remain.
B058C012V028	58	12	28	Therefore, let us, who have received a kingdom that cannot be shaken, be thankful, and so offer acceptable worship to God, with awe and the deepest respect.
B058C012V029	58	12	29	For our God is ‘a consuming fire.’  
B058C013V001	58	13	1	Let your love for the Lord's followers continue.
B058C013V002	58	13	2	Do not neglect to show hospitality; for, through being hospitable, people have all unawares entertained angels.
B058C013V003	58	13	3	Remember the prisoners, as if you were their fellow prisoners, and the oppressed, not forgetting that you also are still in the body.
B058C013V004	58	13	4	Let marriage be honoured by all and the married life be pure; for God will judge those who are immoral and those who commit adultery.
B058C013V005	58	13	5	Do not let your conduct be ruled by the love of money. Be content with what you have, for God himself has said —  ‘I will never forsake you, nor will I ever abandon you.’
B058C013V006	58	13	6	Therefore we may say with confidence —  ‘The Lord is my helper, I will not be afraid.What can mere people do to me?’
B058C013V007	58	13	7	Do not forget your leaders, who told you God’s message. Recall the close of their lives, and imitate their faith.
B058C013V008	58	13	8	Jesus Christ is the same yesterday and today — yes, and for ever!
B058C013V009	58	13	9	Do not let yourselves be carried away by the various novel forms of teaching. It is better to rely for spiritual strength on the divine help, than on regulations regarding food; for those whose lives are guided by such regulations have not found them of service.
B058C013V010	58	13	10	We are not without an altar; but it is one at which those who still worship in the tent have no right to eat.
B058C013V011	58	13	11	The bodies of those animals whose blood is brought by the high priest into the sanctuary, as an offering for sin, are burnt outside the camp.
B058C013V012	58	13	12	And so Jesus, also, to purify the people by his own blood, suffered outside the gate.
B058C013V013	58	13	13	Therefore let us go out to him ‘outside the camp,’ bearing the same reproaches as he;
B058C013V014	58	13	14	for here we have no permanent city, but are looking for the city that is to be.
B058C013V015	58	13	15	Through him let us offer, as our sacrifice, continual praise to God — an offering from lips that glorify his name.
B058C013V016	58	13	16	Never forget to do kindly acts and to share what you have with others, for such sacrifices are acceptable to God.
B058C013V017	58	13	17	Obey your leaders, and submit to their control, for they are watching over your souls, since they will have to render an account, so that they may do it with joy, and not in sorrow. That would not be to your advantage.  
B058C013V018	58	13	18	Pray for us, for we are sure that our consciences are clear, since our wish is to be occupied with what is good.
B058C013V019	58	13	19	And I the more earnestly ask for your prayers, so that I may be restored to you the sooner.
B058C013V020	58	13	20	May God, the source of all peace, who brought back from the dead him who, ‘by virtue of the blood that rendered valid the unchangeable covenant, is the great shepherd of God’s Sheep,’ Jesus, our Lord —
B058C013V021	58	13	21	may God make you perfect in everything that is good, so that you may be able to do his will. May he bring out in us all that is pleasing in his sight, through Jesus Christ, to whom be all glory for ever and ever. Amen.  
B058C013V022	58	13	22	I beg you, friends, to bear with these words of advice. For I have written only very briefly to you.  
B058C013V023	58	13	23	You will be glad to hear that our friend, Timothy, has been set free. If he comes here soon, we will visit you together.  
B058C013V024	58	13	24	Give our greeting to all your leaders, and to all Christ’s people. Our friends from Italy send their greetings to you.
B058C013V025	58	13	25	May God bless you all.
B059C001V001	59	1	1	James, a servant of God and of the Lord Jesus Christ, greets the twelve tribes that are living abroad.
B059C001V002	59	1	2	My friends, whatever may be the temptations that beset you from time to time, always regard them as a reason for rejoicing,
B059C001V003	59	1	3	knowing, as you do, that the testing of your faith develops endurance.
B059C001V004	59	1	4	And let endurance do its work perfectly, so that you may be altogether perfect, and in no respect deficient.
B059C001V005	59	1	5	If one of you is deficient in wisdom, let them ask wisdom from the God who gives freely to everyone without reproaches, and it will be given to them.
B059C001V006	59	1	6	But let them ask with confidence, never doubting; for the person who doubts is like a wave of the sea driven here and there at the mercy of the wind —
B059C001V007	59	1	7	Such a person must not expect that they will receive anything from the Lord,
B059C001V008	59	1	8	vacillating as they are, irresolute at every turn.  
B059C001V009	59	1	9	Let a follower in humble circumstances be proud of their exalted position, but a rich follower of their humiliation;
B059C001V010	59	1	10	for the rich will pass away ‘like the flower of the grass.’
B059C001V011	59	1	11	As the sun rises, and the hot wind blows, ‘the grass withers, its flower fades,’ and all its beauty is gone. So is it with the rich . In the midst of their pursuits they will come to an untimely end.  
B059C001V012	59	1	12	Blessed is the person who remains firm under temptation, for, when they have stood the test, they will receive the crown of life, which the Lord has promised to those who love him.
B059C001V013	59	1	13	Let no one say, when they are tempted, “It is God who is tempting me!” For God, who cannot be tempted to do wrong, does not himself tempt anyone.
B059C001V014	59	1	14	A person is in every case tempted by their own passions — allured and enticed by them.
B059C001V015	59	1	15	Then passion conceives and gives birth to sin, and sin, on reaching maturity, brings forth death.
B059C001V016	59	1	16	Do not be deceived, my dear friends.
B059C001V017	59	1	17	Every good thing given us, and every perfect gift, is from above, and comes down to us from the Maker of the lights in the heavens, who is himself never subject to change or to eclipse.
B059C001V018	59	1	18	Because he so willed, he gave us life, through the message of the truth, so that we should be, as it were, an earnest of still further creations.  
B059C001V019	59	1	19	Mark this, my dear friends — Let everyone be quick to listen, slow to speak, and slow to get angry;
B059C001V020	59	1	20	for human anger does not forward the righteous purpose of God.
B059C001V021	59	1	21	Therefore, have done with all filthiness and whatever wickedness still remains, and in a humble spirit receive that message which has been planted in your hearts and is able to save your souls.
B059C001V022	59	1	22	Put that message into practice, and do not merely listen to it — deceiving yourselves.
B059C001V023	59	1	23	For, when anyone listens to it and does not practice it, they like a person looking at their own face in a mirror.
B059C001V024	59	1	24	They look at themselves, then go on their way,
B059C001V025	59	1	25	but the person who looks carefully into the perfect law, the law of freedom, and continues to do so, not listening to it and then forgetting it, but putting it into practice — that person will be blessed in what they do.
B059C001V026	59	1	26	When a person appears to be religious, yet does not bridle their tongue, but imposes on their own conscience, that person’s religious observances are valueless.
B059C001V027	59	1	27	That religious observance which is pure and spotless in the eyes of God our Father is this — to visit orphans and widows in their trouble, and to keep oneself uncontaminated by the world.
B059C002V001	59	2	1	My friends, are you really trying to combine faith in Jesus Christ, our glorified Lord, with the worship of rank?
B059C002V002	59	2	2	Suppose a visitor should enter your synagogue, with gold rings and in grand clothes, and suppose a poor man should come in also, in shabby clothes,
B059C002V003	59	2	3	and you are deferential to the visitor who is wearing grand clothes, and say — “There is a good seat for you here,” but to the poor man — “You must stand; or sit down there by my footstool,”
B059C002V004	59	2	4	Is not that to make distinctions among yourselves, and show yourselves prejudiced judges?
B059C002V005	59	2	5	Listen, my dear friends. Has not God chosen those who are poor in the things of this world to be rich through their faith, and to possess the kingdom which he has promised to those who love him?
B059C002V006	59	2	6	But you — you insult the poor man! Is not it the rich who oppress you? Is not it they who drag you into law courts?
B059C002V007	59	2	7	Is not it they who malign that honourable name which has been bestowed on you?
B059C002V008	59	2	8	Yet, if you keep the royal law which runs — ‘You must love your neighbour as you love yourself,’ you are doing right;
B059C002V009	59	2	9	but, if you worship rank, you commit a sin, and stand convicted by that same law of being offenders against it.
B059C002V010	59	2	10	For a person who has laid the law, as a whole, to heart, but has failed in one particular, is accountable for breaking all its provisions.
B059C002V011	59	2	11	He who said ‘You must not commit adultery’ also said ‘You must not murder.’ If, then, you commit murder but not adultery, you are still an offender against the law.
B059C002V012	59	2	12	Therefore, speak and act as people who are to be judged by the ‘law of freedom.’
B059C002V013	59	2	13	For there will be justice without mercy for the person who has not acted mercifully. Mercy triumphs over Justice.
B059C002V014	59	2	14	My friends, what is the good of a person’s saying that they have faith, if they do not prove it by actions? Can such faith save them?
B059C002V015	59	2	15	Suppose some brother or sister should be in need of clothes and of daily bread,
B059C002V016	59	2	16	and one of you were to say to them — “Go, and peace be with you; find warmth and food for yourselves,” and yet you were not to give them the necessaries of life, what good would it be to them?
B059C002V017	59	2	17	In just the same way faith, if not followed by actions, is, by itself, a lifeless thing.
B059C002V018	59	2	18	Some one, indeed, may say — “You are a man of faith, and I am a man of action.”  “Then show me your faith,” I reply, “apart from any actions, and I will show you my faith by my actions.”
B059C002V019	59	2	19	It is a part of your faith, is it not, that there is one God? Good; yet even the demons have that faith, and tremble at the thought.
B059C002V020	59	2	20	Now do you really want to understand, fool, how it is that faith without actions leads to nothing?
B059C002V021	59	2	21	Look at our ancestor, Abraham. Was not it the result of his actions that he was pronounced righteous after he had offered his son, Isaac, on the altar?
B059C002V022	59	2	22	You see how, in his case, faith and actions went together; that his faith was perfected as the result of his actions;
B059C002V023	59	2	23	and that in this way the words of scripture came true — “Abraham believed God, and that was regarded by God as righteousness,” and “He was called the friend of God.”
B059C002V024	59	2	24	You see, then, that it is as the result of their actions that a person is pronounced righteous, and not of their faith only.
B059C002V025	59	2	25	Was not it the same with the prostitute, Rahab? Was not it as the result of her actions that she was pronounced righteous, after she had welcomed the messengers and helped them escape by?
B059C002V026	59	2	26	Exactly as a body is dead without a spirit, so faith is dead without actions.  
B059C003V001	59	3	1	I do not want many of you, my friends, to become teachers, knowing, as you do, that we who teach will be judged by a more severe standard than others.
B059C003V002	59	3	2	We often make mistakes, every one of us. Anyone who does not make mistakes when speaking is indeed a perfect person, able to bridle their whole body as well.
B059C003V003	59	3	3	When we put bits into horses’ mouths, to make them obey us, we control the rest of their bodies so.
B059C003V004	59	3	4	Again, think of ships. Large as they are, and even when driven by fierce winds, they are controlled by a very small rudder and steered in whatever direction the man at the helm may determine.
B059C003V005	59	3	5	So is it with the tongue. Small as it is, it is a great boaster. Think how tiny a spark may set the largest forest ablaze!
B059C003V006	59	3	6	And the tongue is like a spark. Among the members of our body it proves itself a world of mischief; it contaminates the whole body; it sets the wheels of life on fire, and is itself set on fire by the flames of Gehenna.
B059C003V007	59	3	7	For while all sorts of beasts and birds, and of reptiles and creatures in the sea, are tameable, and actually have been tamed by man,
B059C003V008	59	3	8	no human being can tame the tongue. It is a restless plague! It is charged with deadly poison!
B059C003V009	59	3	9	With it we bless our Lord and Father, and with it we curse people who are made ‘in God’s likeness.’
B059C003V010	59	3	10	From the very same mouth come blessings and curses! My friends, it is not right that this should be so.
B059C003V011	59	3	11	Does a spring give both good and bad water from the same source?
B059C003V012	59	3	12	Can a fig tree, my friends, bear olives? Or a vine bear figs? No, nor can a brackish well give good water.
B059C003V013	59	3	13	Who among you claims to be wise and intelligent? Let them show that their actions are the outcome of a good life lived in the humility of true wisdom.
B059C003V014	59	3	14	But, while you harbour envy and bitterness and a spirit of rivalry in your hearts, do not boast or lie to the detriment of the truth.
B059C003V015	59	3	15	That is not the wisdom which comes from above; no, it is earthly, animal, devilish.
B059C003V016	59	3	16	For, where envy and rivalry exist, there you will also find disorder and all kinds of base actions.
B059C003V017	59	3	17	But the wisdom from above is, before every thing else, pure; then peace-loving, gentle, open to conviction, rich in compassion and good deeds, and free from partiality and insincerity.
B059C003V018	59	3	18	And righteousness, its fruit, is sown in peace by those who work for peace.  
B059C004V001	59	4	1	What is the cause of the fighting and quarrelling that goes on among you? Is not it to be found in the desires which are always at war within you?
B059C004V002	59	4	2	You crave, yet do not obtain. You murder and rage, yet cannot gain your end. You quarrel and fight. You do not obtain, because you do not ask.
B059C004V003	59	4	3	You ask, yet do not receive, because you ask for a wrong purpose — to spend what you get on your pleasures.
B059C004V004	59	4	4	Unfaithful people! Do not you know that to be friends with the world means to be at enmity with God? Therefore whoever chooses to be friends with the world makes himself an enemy to God.
B059C004V005	59	4	5	Do you suppose there is no meaning in the passage of scripture which asks — ‘Is envy to result from the longings of the Spirit which God has implanted within you?’
B059C004V006	59	4	6	No; the gift that God gives is for a nobler end; and that is why it is said — ‘God is opposed to the haughty, but gives help to the humble.’
B059C004V007	59	4	7	Therefore submit to God; but resist the devil, and he will flee from you.
B059C004V008	59	4	8	Draw near to God, and he will draw near to you. Make your hands clean, you sinners; and your hearts pure, you vacillator!
B059C004V009	59	4	9	Grieve, mourn, and lament! Let your laughter be turned to mourning, and your happiness to gloom!
B059C004V010	59	4	10	Humble yourselves before the Lord, and he will exalt you.
B059C004V011	59	4	11	Do not disparage one another, friends. The person who disparages others, or passes judgment on them, disparages the law and passes judgment on the law. But, if you pass judgment on the law, you are not obeying it, but judging it.
B059C004V012	59	4	12	There is only one lawgiver and judge — he who has the power both to save and to destroy. But who are you that pass judgment on your neighbour?
B059C004V013	59	4	13	Listen to me, you who say ‘Today or tomorrow we will go to such and such a town, spend a year there, and trade, and make money,’
B059C004V014	59	4	14	And yet you do not know what your life will be like tomorrow! For you are but a mist appearing for a little while and then disappearing.
B059C004V015	59	4	15	You ought, rather, to say ‘If the Lord wills, we will live and do this or that.’
B059C004V016	59	4	16	But, as it is, you are constantly boasting presumptuously! All such boasting is wicked.
B059C004V017	59	4	17	The person, then, who knows what is right but fails to do it — that is sin in them.
B059C005V001	59	5	1	Listen to me, you rich people, weep and wail for the miseries that are coming upon you!
B059C005V002	59	5	2	Your riches have wasted away, and your clothes have become moth-eaten.
B059C005V003	59	5	3	Your gold and silver are rusted; and the rust on them will be evidence against you, and will eat into your flesh. It was fire, so to speak, that you stored up for yourselves in these last days.
B059C005V004	59	5	4	I tell you, the wages of the labourers who mowed your fields, which you have been fraudulently keeping back, are crying out against you, and the outcries of your reapers have reached the ears of the Lord of Hosts!
B059C005V005	59	5	5	You have lived on earth a life of extravagance and luxury; you have indulged your fancies in a time of bloodshed.
B059C005V006	59	5	6	You have condemned, you have murdered, the righteous one! Must not God be opposed to you?
B059C005V007	59	5	7	Be patient, then, friends, until the coming of the Lord. Even the farmer has to wait for the precious fruit of the earth, watching over it patiently, until it has had the spring and summer rains.
B059C005V008	59	5	8	And you must be patient also, and not be discouraged; for the Lord’s coming is near.
B059C005V009	59	5	9	Do not make complaints against one another, friends, or judgment will be passed on you. The judge is already standing at the door!
B059C005V010	59	5	10	Friends, as an example of the patient endurance of suffering, take the prophets who spoke in the name of the Lord.
B059C005V011	59	5	11	We count those who displayed such endurance blessed! You have heard, too, of Job’s endurance, and have seen what the Lord’s purpose was, for ‘the Lord is full of pity and compassion.’
B059C005V012	59	5	12	Above all things, my friends, never take an oath, either by heaven, or by earth, or by anything else. With you let ‘Yes’ suffice for yes, and ‘No’ for no, so that you may escape condemnation.  
B059C005V013	59	5	13	If any of you is in trouble, let them pray; if anyone is happy, let them sing hymns.
B059C005V014	59	5	14	If anyone of you is ill, let him send for the officers of the church, and let them pray over them, after anointing them with oil in the name of the Lord.
B059C005V015	59	5	15	The prayer offered in faith will save the person who is sick, and the Lord will raise them from their bed; and if they have committed sins, they will be forgiven.
B059C005V016	59	5	16	Therefore, confess your sins to one another and pray for one another, so that you may be cured. Great is the power of a good person’s fervent prayer.
B059C005V017	59	5	17	Elijah was only human like ourselves, but, when he prayed fervently that it might not rain, no rain fell on the land for three years and a half.
B059C005V018	59	5	18	And, when he prayed again, the clouds brought rain, and the land bore crops.
B059C005V019	59	5	19	My friends, should one of you be led astray from the truth, and someone bring them back again,
B059C005V020	59	5	20	be sure that the person who brings a sinner back from their mistaken ways will save that person’s soul from death, and throw a veil over countless sins.  
B060C001V001	60	1	1	To the people of God who are living abroad, dispersed throughout Pontus, Galatia, Cappadocia, Roman Asia, and Bithynia,
B060C001V002	60	1	2	and who were chosen in accordance with the foreknowledge of God the Father, through the consecration of the Spirit, to learn obedience, and to be purified by the sprinkling of the blood of Jesus Christ, from Peter, an apostle of Jesus Christ. May blessing and peace be yours in ever increasing measure.
B060C001V003	60	1	3	Blessed is the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ, who has, in his great mercy, through the resurrection of Jesus Christ from the dead,
B060C001V004	60	1	4	given us the new life of undying hope, that promises an inheritance, imperishable, stainless, unfading, which has been reserved for you in heaven —
B060C001V005	60	1	5	for you who, through faith, are being guarded by the power of God, awaiting a salvation that is ready to be revealed in the last days.
B060C001V006	60	1	6	At the thought of this you are full of exultation, though (if it has been necessary) you have suffered for the moment somewhat from various trials;
B060C001V007	60	1	7	that the genuineness of your faith — a thing far more precious than gold, which is perishable, yet has to be tested by fire — may win praise and glory and honour at the appearing of Jesus Christ.
B060C001V008	60	1	8	Though you have never seen him, yet you love him; though you do not even now see him, yet you believe in him, and exalt with a triumphant happiness too great for words,
B060C001V009	60	1	9	as you receive the reward of your faith in the salvation of your souls!
B060C001V010	60	1	10	It was this salvation that the prophets, who spoke long ago of the blessing intended for you, sought, and strove to comprehend;
B060C001V011	60	1	11	as they strove to discern what that time could be, to which the Spirit of Christ within them was pointing, when foretelling the sufferings that Christ would have to endure, and the glories that would follow.
B060C001V012	60	1	12	And it was revealed to them that it was not for themselves, but for you, that they were acting as Ministers of the truths which have now been told to you, by those who, with the help of the Holy Spirit sent from heaven, have brought you the good news — truths into which even angels long to look.
B060C001V013	60	1	13	Therefore concentrate your minds, with the strictest self-control, and fix your hopes on the blessing that is coming for you at the appearing of Jesus Christ.
B060C001V014	60	1	14	Be like obedient children; do not let your lives be shaped by the passions which once swayed you in the days of your ignorance,
B060C001V015	60	1	15	but in your whole life show yourselves to be holy, after the pattern of the Holy One from whom you received your call.
B060C001V016	60	1	16	For scripture says —  ‘You will be holy, because I am holy.’
B060C001V017	60	1	17	And since you call on him as ‘Father,’ who judges everyone impartially by what he has done, let respectful awe be the spirit of your lives during the time of your stay on earth.
B060C001V018	60	1	18	For you know that it was not by perishable things, such as silver and gold, that you were ransomed from the aimless way of living which was handed down to you from your ancestors,
B060C001V019	60	1	19	but by precious blood, as it were of a lamb, unblemished and spotless, the blood of Christ.
B060C001V020	60	1	20	Destined for this before the beginning of the world, he has been revealed in these last days for your sakes,
B060C001V021	60	1	21	who, through him, are faithful to God who raised him from the dead and gave him honour, so that your faith and hope are now in God.
B060C001V022	60	1	22	Now that, by your obedience to the truth, you have purified your lives, so that there is growing up among you a genuine affection, love one another earnestly with all your hearts;
B060C001V023	60	1	23	since your new life has come, not from perishable, but imperishable, seed, through the message of the Everliving God.
B060C001V024	60	1	24	For —  ‘All earthly life is but as grass,and all its splendour as the flower of grass.The grass fades,its flower falls,
B060C001V025	60	1	25	but the teaching of the Lord remains for ever.’  And that is the teaching of the good news which has been told to you.  
B060C002V001	60	2	1	Now that you have done with all malice, all deceitfulness, insincerity, jealous feelings, and all backbiting,
B060C002V002	60	2	2	like newly born infants, crave pure spiritual milk, so that you may be enabled by it to grow until you attain salvation —
B060C002V003	60	2	3	since ‘you have found by experience that the Lord is kind.’
B060C002V004	60	2	4	Come to him, then, as to a living stone, rejected, indeed, by men, but in God’s eyes choice and precious;
B060C002V005	60	2	5	and, as living stones, form yourselves into a spiritual house, to be a consecrated priesthood, for the offering of spiritual sacrifices that will be acceptable to God through Jesus Christ.
B060C002V006	60	2	6	For there is a passage of scripture that runs —  ‘See, I am placing in Zion a choice and precious corner-stone;And those who believe in him will have no cause for shame.’
B060C002V007	60	2	7	It is to you, then, who believe in him that he is precious, but to those who do not believe he is ‘a stone which, though rejected by the builders, has now itself become the corner-stone,’
B060C002V008	60	2	8	and ‘a stumbling-block, and a rock which will prove a hindrance.’ They stumble because they do not accept the message. This was the fate destined for them.
B060C002V009	60	2	9	But you are ‘a chosen race, a royal priesthood, a consecrated nation, God’s own people,’ entrusted with the proclamation of the goodness of him who called you out of darkness into his wonderful light.
B060C002V010	60	2	10	Once you were ‘not a people,’ but now you are ‘God’s people’; once you ‘had not found mercy,’ but now you ‘have found mercy.’
B060C002V011	60	2	11	Dear friends, I beg you, as pilgrims and strangers on earth, to refrain from indulging the cravings of your earthly nature, for they make war on the soul.
B060C002V012	60	2	12	Let your daily life among the Gentiles be so upright, that, whenever they malign you as evil-doers, they may learn, as they watch, from the uprightness of your conduct, to praise God ‘at the time when he will visit them.’
B060C002V013	60	2	13	Submit to all human institutions for the Lord’s sake, alike to the emperor as the supreme authority,
B060C002V014	60	2	14	and to governors as sent by him to punish evil-doers and to commend those who do right.
B060C002V015	60	2	15	For God’s will is this — that you should silence the ignorance of foolish people by doing what is right.
B060C002V016	60	2	16	Act as free people, yet not using your freedom as those do who make it a cloak for wickedness, but as Servants of God.
B060C002V017	60	2	17	Show honour to everyone, love the Lord's followers, ‘revere God, honour the emperor.’  
B060C002V018	60	2	18	Those of you who are domestic servants should always be submissive and respectful to their masters, not only to those who are good and considerate, but also to those who are arbitrary.
B060C002V019	60	2	19	For this wins God’s approval when, because conscious of God’s presence, a person who is suffering unjustly bears their troubles patiently.
B060C002V020	60	2	20	What credit can you claim when, after doing wrong, you take your punishment for it patiently? But, on the other hand, if, after doing right, you take your sufferings patiently, that does win the approval of God.
B060C002V021	60	2	21	For it was to this that you were called! For Christ, too, suffered — on your behalf — and left you an example, that you should follow in his steps.
B060C002V022	60	2	22	He ‘never sinned, nor was anything deceitful ever heard from his lips.’
B060C002V023	60	2	23	He was abused, but he did not answer with abuse; he suffered, but he did not threaten; he entrusted himself to him whose judgments are just.
B060C002V024	60	2	24	And he ‘himself carried our sins’ in his own body to the cross, so that we might die to our sins, and live for righteousness. ‘His bruising was your healing.’
B060C002V025	60	2	25	Once you were straying like sheep, but now you have returned to the shepherd and guardian of your souls.  
B060C003V001	60	3	1	Again, you married women should submit to your husbands, so that if any of them reject the message, they may, apart from the message, be won over, by the conduct of their wives,
B060C003V002	60	3	2	as they watch your submissive and blameless conduct.
B060C003V003	60	3	3	Yours should be, not the external adornment of the arrangement of the hair, the wearing of jewellery, or the putting on of dresses,
B060C003V004	60	3	4	but the inner life with the imperishable beauty of a quiet and gentle spirit; for this is very precious in God’s sight.
B060C003V005	60	3	5	It was by this that the holy women of old, who rested their hopes on God, adorned themselves; submitting to their husbands,
B060C003V006	60	3	6	as Sarah did, who obeyed Abraham, and called him master. And you are her true children, as long as you live good lives, and let nothing terrify you.
B060C003V007	60	3	7	Again, those of you who are married men should live considerately with their wives, showing due regard to their sex, as physically weaker than their own, and not forgetting that they share with you in the gift of life. Then you will be able to pray without hindrance.  
B060C003V008	60	3	8	Lastly, you should all be united, sympathetic, full of love for each other, kind-hearted, humble-minded;
B060C003V009	60	3	9	never returning evil for evil, or abuse for abuse, but, on the contrary, blessing. It was to this that you were called — to obtain a blessing!
B060C003V010	60	3	10	‘The person who wants to enjoy lifeAnd see happy days —Let them keep their tongue from evilAnd their lips from deceitful words,
B060C003V011	60	3	11	let them turn from evil and do good,Let them seek for peace and follow after it;
B060C003V012	60	3	12	For the eyes of the Lord are on the righteous,And his ears are attentive to their prayers,But the face of the Lord is set against those who do wrong.’ 
B060C003V013	60	3	13	Who, indeed, is there to harm you, if you prove yourselves to be eager for what is good?
B060C003V014	60	3	14	Even if you should suffer for righteousness, count yourselves blessed! ‘Do not let people terrify you, or allow yourselves to be dismayed.’
B060C003V015	60	3	15	Revere the Christ as Lord in your hearts; always ready to give an answer to anyone who asks your reason for the hope that you cherish, but giving it with courtesy and respect,
B060C003V016	60	3	16	and keeping your consciences clear, so that, whenever you are maligned, those who vilify your good and Christian conduct may be put to shame.
B060C003V017	60	3	17	It is better that you should suffer, if that should be God’s will, for doing right, than for doing wrong.
B060C003V018	60	3	18	For Christ himself died to atone for sins once for all — the good on behalf of the bad — that he might bring you to God; his body being put to death, but his spirit entering on new life.
B060C003V019	60	3	19	And it was then that he went and preached to the imprisoned spirits,
B060C003V020	60	3	20	who once were disobedient, at the time when God patiently waited, in the days of Noah, while the ark was being prepared; in which some few lives, eight in all, were saved by means of water.
B060C003V021	60	3	21	And baptism, which this foreshadowed, now saves you — not the mere cleansing of the body, but the search of a clear conscience after God — through the resurrection of Jesus Christ,
B060C003V022	60	3	22	who has gone into heaven, and is at God’s right hand, where angels and archangels and the powers of heaven now yield submission to him.
B060C004V001	60	4	1	Since, then, Christ suffered in body, arm yourselves with the same resolve as he; for he who has suffered in body has ceased to sin,
B060C004V002	60	4	2	and so will live the rest of his earthly life guided, not by human passions, but by the will of God.
B060C004V003	60	4	3	Surely in the past you have spent time enough living as the Gentiles delight to live. For your path has lain among scenes of debauchery, licentiousness, drunkenness, revelry, hard-drinking, and profane idolatry.
B060C004V004	60	4	4	And, because you do not run to the same extremes of profligacy as others, they are astonished, and malign you.
B060C004V005	60	4	5	But they will have to answer for their conduct to him who is ready to judge both the living and the dead.
B060C004V006	60	4	6	For that was why the good news was told to the dead also — that, after they have been judged in the body, as people are judged, they might live in the spirit, as God lives.
B060C004V007	60	4	7	But the end of all things is near. Therefore exercise self-restraint and be calm, so that you may be able to pray.
B060C004V008	60	4	8	Above all things, let your love for one another be earnest, for ‘love throws a veil over countless sins.’
B060C004V009	60	4	9	Never grudge hospitality to one another.
B060C004V010	60	4	10	Whatever the gift that each has received, use it in the service of others, as good stewards of the varied bounty of God.
B060C004V011	60	4	11	When anyone speaks, let them speak as one who is delivering the oracles of God. When anyone is endeavouring to serve others, let them do so in reliance on the strength which God supplies; so that in everything God may be honour ed through Jesus Christ — to whom be ascribed all honour and might for ever and ever. Amen.
B060C004V012	60	4	12	Dear friends, do not be astonished at the trial of fire that you are passing through, to test you, as though something strange were happening to you.
B060C004V013	60	4	13	No, the more you share the sufferings of the Christ, the more may you rejoice, that, when the time comes for the manifestation of his glory, you may rejoice and exult.
B060C004V014	60	4	14	If you are insulted for bearing the name of Christ, count yourselves blessed; because the divine glory and the Spirit of God are resting on you.
B060C004V015	60	4	15	I need hardly say that no one among you must suffer as a murderer, or a thief, or a criminal, or for interfering in matters which do not concern Christians.
B060C004V016	60	4	16	But, if someone suffers as a Christian, do not let them be ashamed of it; let them bring honour to God even though they bear that name.
B060C004V017	60	4	17	For the time has come for judgment to begin with the house of God; and, if it begins with us, what will be the end of those who reject God’s good news?
B060C004V018	60	4	18	If ‘a good person is saved only with difficulty, what will become of the godless and the sinful?’
B060C004V019	60	4	19	Therefore, I say, let those who suffer, because God wills it so, commit their lives into the hands of a faithful Creator, and persevere in doing right.
B060C005V001	60	5	1	As for the older ones among you, who bear office in the church, I, their fellow officer, and a witness to the sufferings of the Christ, who will also share in the glory that is to be revealed —
B060C005V002	60	5	2	I beg you to be true shepherds of the flock of God among you, not because you are compelled, but of your own free will; not from a base love of gain, but with a ready spirit;
B060C005V003	60	5	3	not as lords of your charges, but as examples to your flock.
B060C005V004	60	5	4	Then, when the chief shepherd appears, you will win the crown of glory that never fades.
B060C005V005	60	5	5	Again, you younger ones should show deference to the older. And all of you should put on the badge of humility in mutual service, for ‘God is opposed to the proud, but gives his help to the humble.’
B060C005V006	60	5	6	Humble yourselves, therefore, under the mighty hand of God, so that he may exalt you in his good time,
B060C005V007	60	5	7	laying all your anxieties on him, for he makes you his care.
B060C005V008	60	5	8	Exercise self-control, be watchful. Your adversary, the devil, like a roaring lion, is prowling about, eager to devour you.
B060C005V009	60	5	9	Stand firm against him, strong in your faith; knowing, as you do, that the sufferings which you are undergoing are being endured to the full by the Lord's followers throughout the world.
B060C005V010	60	5	10	God, from whom all help comes, and who called you, by your union with Christ, into his eternal glory, will, when you have suffered for a little while, himself perfect, establish, strengthen you.
B060C005V011	60	5	11	To him be ascribed dominion for ever. Amen.
B060C005V012	60	5	12	I have been writing to you briefly by the hand of Silas, our true-hearted friend (for so I regard him), to encourage you, and to bear my testimony that in what I have written is to be found the true love of God. On that take your stand.
B060C005V013	60	5	13	Your sister church in ‘Babylon’ sends you greeting, and so does Mark, who is as a son to me.
B060C005V014	60	5	14	Greet one another with the kiss of love.
B061C001V001	61	1	1	To those to whom, through the justice of our God and Saviour Jesus Christ, there has been granted faith equally privileged with our own, from Simon Peter, a servant and an apostle of Jesus Christ.
B061C001V002	61	1	2	May blessing and peace be yours in ever increasing measure, as you advance in the knowledge of God and of Jesus, our Lord.
B061C001V003	61	1	3	For his divine power has given us everything that is needful for a life of piety, as we advance in the knowledge of him who called us by a glorious manifestation of his goodness.
B061C001V004	61	1	4	For it was through this that he gave us what we prize as the greatest of his promises, that through them you might participate in the divine nature, now that you have fled from the corruption in the world, resulting from human passions.
B061C001V005	61	1	5	Yes, and for this reason do your best to supplement your faith by goodness, goodness by knowledge,
B061C001V006	61	1	6	knowledge by self-control, self-control by endurance, endurance by piety,
B061C001V007	61	1	7	piety by mutual affection, and mutual affection by love.
B061C001V008	61	1	8	For, when these virtues are yours, in increasing measure, they prevent your being indifferent to, or destitute of, a fuller knowledge of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B061C001V009	61	1	9	Surely the person who has not these virtues is shortsighted even to blindness, and has chosen to forget that they have been purified from their sins of the past!
B061C001V010	61	1	10	Therefore, friends, do your best to put God’s call and selection of you beyond all doubt; for, if you do this, you will never fall.
B061C001V011	61	1	11	For in this way you will be given a triumphant admission into the eternal kingdom of our Lord and Saviour, Jesus Christ.
B061C001V012	61	1	12	I will, therefore, always be ready to remind you of all this, even though you know it and are firmly established in the truth that you now hold.
B061C001V013	61	1	13	But I think it my duty, as long as I live in this ‘tent,’ to rouse you by awakening memories of the past;
B061C001V014	61	1	14	for I know that the time for this ‘tent’ of mine to be put away is soon coming, as our Lord Jesus Christ himself assured me.
B061C001V015	61	1	15	So I will do my best to enable you, at any time after my departure, to call these truths to mind.
B061C001V016	61	1	16	For we were not following cleverly devised stories when we told you of the coming in power of our Lord Jesus Christ, but we had been eye-witnesses of his majesty.
B061C001V017	61	1	17	For he received honour and glory from God the Father, when from the glory of the Divine Majesty there were borne to his ears words such as these — ‘This is my dearly loved son, who brings me great joy.’
B061C001V018	61	1	18	These were the words that we heard, borne to our ears from heaven, when we were with him on that sacred mountain.
B061C001V019	61	1	19	And still stronger is the assurance that we have in the teaching of the prophets; to which you will do well to pay attention (as if it were a lamp shining in a gloomy place), until the day dawns and the morning star rises in your hearts.
B061C001V020	61	1	20	But first be assured of this: — There is no prophetic teaching found in scripture that can be interpreted by a person’s unaided reason;
B061C001V021	61	1	21	for no prophetic teaching ever came in the old days at the mere wish of people, but people, moved by the Holy Spirit, spoke direct from God.
B061C002V001	61	2	1	But there were false prophets also in the nation, just as there will be false teachers among you, people who will secretly introduce ruinous divisions, disowning even the Lord who bought them, and bringing speedy ruin on themselves.
B061C002V002	61	2	2	There will be many, too, who will follow their licentious courses, and cause the way of the truth to be maligned.
B061C002V003	61	2	3	In their covetousness they will try to make you a source of profit by their fabrications; but for a long time past their sentence has not been standing idle, nor their ruin slumbering.
B061C002V004	61	2	4	Remember, God did not spare angels when they sinned, but sent them down to Tartarus, and consigned them to caverns of darkness, to be kept under guard for judgment.
B061C002V005	61	2	5	Nor did he spare the world of old; though he preserved Noah, the preacher of righteousness, and seven others, when he brought a flood on the godless world.
B061C002V006	61	2	6	He condemned the cities of Sodom and Gomorrah and reduced them to ashes, holding them up as a warning to the godless of what was in store for them;
B061C002V007	61	2	7	but he rescued righteous Lot, whose heart was vexed by the wanton licentiousness of his neighbours;
B061C002V008	61	2	8	for, seeing and hearing what he did, as he lived his righteous life among them, day after day, Lot’s righteous soul was tortured by their wicked doings.
B061C002V009	61	2	9	The Lord, therefore, knows how to deliver the pious from temptation, and to keep the wicked, who are even now suffering punishment, in readiness for ‘the day of judgment’ —
B061C002V010	61	2	10	especially those who, following the promptings of their lower nature, indulge their polluting passions and despise all control. Audacious and self-willed, they feel no awe of the celestial beings, maligning them,
B061C002V011	61	2	11	even where angels, though excelling them in strength and power, do not bring against them a malignant charge before the Lord.
B061C002V012	61	2	12	These people, however, like animals without reason, intended by nature to be caught and killed — these people, I say, malign those of whom they know nothing, and will assuredly perish through their own corruption,
B061C002V013	61	2	13	suffering themselves, as the penalty for the suffering that they have inflicted. They think that pleasure consists in the self-indulgence of the moment. They are a stain and a disgrace, indulging, as they do, in their wanton revelry, even while joining you at your feasts.
B061C002V014	61	2	14	They have eyes only for adulteresses, eyes never tired of sin; they entice weak souls; their minds are trained to covet; they live under a curse.
B061C002V015	61	2	15	Leaving the straight road, they have gone astray and followed in the steps of Balaam, the son of Beor, who set his heart on the reward for wrong-doing,
B061C002V016	61	2	16	but was rebuked for his offence. A dumb animal spoke with a human voice, and checked the prophet’s madness.
B061C002V017	61	2	17	These people are like springs without water, or mists driven before a gale; and for them the blackest darkness has been reserved.
B061C002V018	61	2	18	With boastful and foolish talk, they appeal to the passions of people’s lower nature, and, by their profligacy, entice those who are just escaping from the people who live such misguided lives.
B061C002V019	61	2	19	They promise them freedom, while they themselves are slaves to corrupt habits; for a person is the slave of anything to which they give way.
B061C002V020	61	2	20	If, after having escaped the polluting influences of the world, through knowing our Lord and Saviour, Jesus Christ, people are again entangled in them, and give way to them, their last state has become worse than their first.
B061C002V021	61	2	21	It would, indeed, have been better for them not to have known the way of righteousness, than, after knowing it, to turn away from the holy command delivered to them.
B061C002V022	61	2	22	In their case is seen the truth of the proverb — ‘A dog returns to what it has vomited’ and ‘A sow after washing to her wallowing-place in the mud.’
B061C003V001	61	3	1	This, dear friends, is my second letter to you. In both of them I have tried, by appealing to your remembrance, to arouse your better feelings.
B061C003V002	61	3	2	I want you to recall what was foretold by the holy prophets, as well as the command of our Lord and Saviour given to you through your apostles.
B061C003V003	61	3	3	First be assured of this, that, as the age draws to an end, scoffers, led by their own passions,
B061C003V004	61	3	4	will come and ask scoffingly — ‘Where is his promised coming? Ever since our ancestors passed to their rest, everything remains just as it was when the world was first created!’
B061C003V005	61	3	5	For they wilfully shut their eyes to the fact that long ago the heavens existed; and the earth, also — formed out of water and by the action of water, by the fiat of God;
B061C003V006	61	3	6	and that by the same means the world which then existed was destroyed in a deluge of water.
B061C003V007	61	3	7	But the present heavens and earth, by the same fiat, have been reserved for fire, and are being kept for the day of the judgment and destruction of the godless.
B061C003V008	61	3	8	But you, dear friends, must never shut your eyes to the fact that, to the Lord, one day is the same as a thousand years, and a thousand years as one day.
B061C003V009	61	3	9	The Lord is not slow to fulfil his promise, as some count slowness; but he is forbearing with you, as it is not his will that any of you should perish, but that all should be brought to repentance.
B061C003V010	61	3	10	The day of the Lord will come like a thief; and on that day the heavens will pass away with a crash, the elements will be burnt up and dissolved, and the earth and all that is in it will be disclosed.
B061C003V011	61	3	11	Now, since all these things are in the process of dissolution, think what you yourselves ought to be — what holy and pious lives you ought to lead,
B061C003V012	61	3	12	while you wait for the coming of the day of God and strive to make it come soon. At its coming the heavens will be dissolved in fire, and the elements melted by heat,
B061C003V013	61	3	13	but we look for ‘new heavens and a new earth,’ where righteousness will have its home, in fulfilment of the promise of God.  
B061C003V014	61	3	14	Therefore, dear friends, in expectation of these things, make every effort to be found by him spotless, blameless, and at peace.
B061C003V015	61	3	15	Regard our Lord’s forbearance as your one hope of salvation. This is what our dear friend Paul wrote to you, with the wisdom that God gave him.
B061C003V016	61	3	16	It is the same in all his letters, when he speaks in them about these subjects. There are some things in them difficult to understand, which untaught and weak people distort, just as they do all other writings, to their own ruin.
B061C003V017	61	3	17	You must, therefore, dear friends, now that you know this beforehand, be on your guard against being led away by the errors of reckless people, and so lapsing from your present steadfastness;
B061C003V018	61	3	18	and advance in the love and knowledge of our Lord and Saviour, Jesus Christ. All glory be to him now and for ever.  
B062C001V001	62	1	1	It is of what has been in existence from the beginning, of what we have heard, of what we have seen with our eyes, of what we watched reverently and touched with our hands — it is about the Word who is the life that we are now writing.
B062C001V002	62	1	2	That life was made visible, and we have seen it, and now bear our testimony to it, and tell you of that eternal life, which was with the Father and was made visible to us.
B062C001V003	62	1	3	It is of what we have seen and heard that we now tell you, so that you may have communion with us. And our communion is with the Father and with his Son, Jesus Christ.
B062C001V004	62	1	4	And we are writing all this to you that our joy may be complete.
B062C001V005	62	1	5	These, then, are the tidings that we have heard from him and now tell you — ‘God is light, and darkness has no place at all in him.’
B062C001V006	62	1	6	If we say that we have communion with him, and yet continue to live in the darkness, we lie, and are not living the truth.
B062C001V007	62	1	7	But, if our lives are lived in the light, as God himself is in the light, we have communion with one another, and the blood of Jesus, his Son, purifies us from all sin.
B062C001V008	62	1	8	If we say that there is no sin in us, we are deceiving ourselves, and the truth has no place in us.
B062C001V009	62	1	9	If we confess our sins, God may be trusted, in his righteousness, to forgive us our sins and purify us from all wickedness.
B062C001V010	62	1	10	If we say that we have not sinned, we are making God a liar, and his message has no place in us.
B062C002V001	62	2	1	My children, I am writing to you to keep you from sinning; but if anyone should sin, we have one who can plead for us with the Father — Jesus Christ, the righteous —
B062C002V002	62	2	2	and he is the atoning sacrifice for our sins, and not for ours only, but for those of the whole world besides.
B062C002V003	62	2	3	And by this we know that we have learned to know him — by our laying his commands to heart.
B062C002V004	62	2	4	The person who says ‘I know Jesus,’ but does not lay his commands to heart, is a liar, and the truth has no place in them;
B062C002V005	62	2	5	but, whenever a person lays his message to heart, in that person the love of God has indeed reached its perfection. By this we know that we are in union with God —
B062C002V006	62	2	6	He who professes to maintain union with God is himself bound to live as Christ lived.
B062C002V007	62	2	7	Dear friends, it is no new command that I am writing to you, but an old command, which you have had from the first. That old command is the message to which you listened.
B062C002V008	62	2	8	Yet, in a way, it is a new command that I am writing to you — manifest in Christ’s life and in your own — for the darkness is passing away and the true light is already shining.
B062C002V009	62	2	9	The person who says that they are in the light, and yet hates others, is in the darkness even now.
B062C002V010	62	2	10	The person who loves others is always in the light, and there is nothing within them to cause them to stumble;
B062C002V011	62	2	11	while the person who hates others is in the darkness, and is living in the darkness, and does not know where they are going, because the darkness prevents them seeing.
B062C002V012	62	2	12	I am writing, God's children, to you, because your sins have been forgiven you for Christ’s sake.
B062C002V013	62	2	13	I am writing, adults in the faith, to you, because you have learned to know him who has been from the beginning. I am writing, young ones in the faith, to you, because you have conquered the evil one. I write, children, to you, because you have learned to know the Father.
B062C002V014	62	2	14	I write, adults in the faith, to you, because you have learned to know him who has been from the beginning. I write, young ones in the faith, to you, because you are strong, and God’s message is always in your hearts, and you have conquered the evil one.
B062C002V015	62	2	15	Do not love the world or what the world can offer. When anyone loves the world, there is no love for the Father in them;
B062C002V016	62	2	16	for all that the world can offer — the gratification of the earthly nature, the gratification of the eye, the pretentious life — belongs, not to the Father, but to the world.
B062C002V017	62	2	17	And the world, and all that it gratifies, is passing away, but they who do God’s will remains for ever.  
B062C002V018	62	2	18	My children, these are the last days. You were told that an antichrist was coming; and many antichrists have already arisen. By that we know that these are the last days.
B062C002V019	62	2	19	From us, it is true, they went out, but they had never belonged to us; for, if they had belonged to us, they would have remained among us. They left us that it might be made clear that they do not, any of them, belong to us.
B062C002V020	62	2	20	You, however, have received consecration from the Holy One.
B062C002V021	62	2	21	You all know — But I am not writing to you because you do not know the truth, but because you do know it, and because nothing false can come from the truth.
B062C002V022	62	2	22	Who is a liar, if not the person who rejects the truth that Jesus is the Christ? That person is the antichrist — the person who rejects the Father and the Son.
B062C002V023	62	2	23	No one who rejects the Son has found the Father; the person who acknowledges the Son has found the Father also.
B062C002V024	62	2	24	As for you, let what you were told at the first be always in your thoughts. If, then, what you were told at the first is always in your thoughts, you yourselves will maintain your union both with the Son and with the Father.
B062C002V025	62	2	25	And this is what he himself promised us — eternal life!  
B062C002V026	62	2	26	In writing this this to you, I have in mind those who are trying to mislead you.
B062C002V027	62	2	27	But you — you still retain in your hearts that consecration which you received from the Christ, and are not in need of anyone to teach you; but, since his consecration of you teaches you about everything, and since it is a real consecration, and no lie, then, as it has taught you, maintain your union with him.
B062C002V028	62	2	28	Yes, my children, maintain your union with Christ, so that, whenever he appears, our confidence may not fail us, and we may not be ashamed to meet him at his coming.
B062C002V029	62	2	29	Knowing him to be righteous, you realise that everyone who lives righteously has received the new life from him.  
B062C003V001	62	3	1	Think what love the Father has shown us in allowing us to be called ‘children of God’; as indeed we are. The reason why the world does not know us is that it has not learned to know him.
B062C003V002	62	3	2	Dear friends, we are God’s children now; what we will be has not yet been revealed. What we do know is that, when it is revealed, we will be like Christ; because we will see him as he is.
B062C003V003	62	3	3	And everyone who has this hope with regard to Christ tries to make themselves pure — as Christ is pure.
B062C003V004	62	3	4	Everyone who lives sinfully is living in violation of law. Sin is violation of law.
B062C003V005	62	3	5	And you know that Christ appeared to take away our sins; and in him sin has no place.
B062C003V006	62	3	6	No one who maintains union with him lives in sin; no one who lives in sin has ever really seen him or learned to know him.
B062C003V007	62	3	7	My children, do not let anyone mislead you. The person who lives righteously is righteous — as Christ is righteous.
B062C003V008	62	3	8	The person who lives sinfully belongs to the devil, for the devil has sinned from the first. It was for this that the Son of God appeared, that he might undo the devil’s work.  
B062C003V009	62	3	9	No one who has received the new life from God lives sinfully, because the nature of God dwells within them; and they cannot live in sin, because they have received the new life from God.
B062C003V010	62	3	10	By this the children of God are distinguished from the children of the devil — No one who lives unrighteously comes from God, and especially the person who does not love others.
B062C003V011	62	3	11	For these are the tidings that we heard from the first — that we are to love one another.
B062C003V012	62	3	12	We must not be like Cain, who belonged to the evil one and killed his brother. And why did he kill him? It was because his life was bad while his brother’s was good.  
B062C003V013	62	3	13	Do not wonder, friends, if the world hates you.
B062C003V014	62	3	14	We know that we have passed out of death into life, because we love each other. The person who does not love remains in a state of death.
B062C003V015	62	3	15	The person who hates another is a murderer; and you know that no murderer has eternal life within them.
B062C003V016	62	3	16	We have learned to know what love is from this — that Christ laid down his life on our behalf. Therefore we also ought to lay down our lives for each other.
B062C003V017	62	3	17	But, if anyone has worldly possessions, and yet looks on while one of our own is in need, and steels their heart against that person, how can it be said that the love of God is within them?
B062C003V018	62	3	18	My children, do not let our love be mere words, or end in talk; let it be true and show itself in acts.  
B062C003V019	62	3	19	By that we will know that we are on the side of the truth; and we will satisfy ourselves in God’s sight,
B062C003V020	62	3	20	that if our conscience condemns us, yet God is greater than our conscience and knows everything.
B062C003V021	62	3	21	Dear friends, if our conscience does not condemn us, then we approach God with confidence,
B062C003V022	62	3	22	and we receive from him whatever we ask, because we are laying his commands to heart, and are doing what is pleasing in his sight.
B062C003V023	62	3	23	His command is this — that we should put our trust in the name of his Son, Jesus Christ, and love one another, in accordance with the command that he gave us.
B062C003V024	62	3	24	And the person who lays his commands to heart maintains union with Christ, and Christ with them. And by this we know that Christ maintains union with us — by our possession of the Spirit which he gave us.  
B062C004V001	62	4	1	Dear friends, do not trust every inspiration, but test each inspiration, to see whether it proceeds from God; because many false prophets have gone out into the world.
B062C004V002	62	4	2	This is the way by which to know the inspiration of God — All inspiration that acknowledges Jesus Christ as come in our human nature is from God;
B062C004V003	62	4	3	while all inspiration that does not acknowledge Jesus is not inspiration from God. It is the inspiration of the Antichrist; you have heard that it was to come, and it is now already in the world.  
B062C004V004	62	4	4	You, my children, come from God, and you have successfully resisted such people as these, because he who is in you is greater than the one who is in the world.
B062C004V005	62	4	5	Those people belong to the world; and therefore they speak as the world speaks, and the world listens to them.
B062C004V006	62	4	6	We come from God. He who knows God listens to us; the person who does not come from God does not listen to us. By that we may know the true inspiration from the false.  
B062C004V007	62	4	7	Dear friends, let us love one another, because love comes from God; and everyone who loves has received the new life from God and knows God.
B062C004V008	62	4	8	The person who does not love has not learned to know God; for God is love.
B062C004V009	62	4	9	The love of God was revealed to us by his sending his only Son into the world, so that we might find life through him.
B062C004V010	62	4	10	His love is seen in this — not in our having loved God, but in his loving us and sending his Son to be an atoning sacrifice for our sins.
B062C004V011	62	4	11	Dear friends, since God loved us in this way, we, surely, ought to love one another.
B062C004V012	62	4	12	No human eyes have ever seen God, yet, if we love one another, God remains in union with us, and his love attains its perfection in us.
B062C004V013	62	4	13	We know that we remain in union with him, and he with us, by this — by his having given us some measure of his Spirit.
B062C004V014	62	4	14	Moreover, our eyes have seen — and we are testifying to the fact — that the Father has sent the Son to be the Saviour of the world.
B062C004V015	62	4	15	Whoever acknowledges that Jesus Christ is the Son of God — God remains in union with that man, and he with God.
B062C004V016	62	4	16	And, moreover, we have learned to know, and have accepted as a fact, the love which God has for us.  God is love; and whoever lives in love lives in God, and God in them.
B062C004V017	62	4	17	It is through this that love has attained its perfection in us, so that we may have confidence on the day of judgment, because what Christ is that we also are in this world.
B062C004V018	62	4	18	There is no fear in love. No! Love, when perfect, drives out fear, because fear implies punishment, and the person who feels fear has not attained to perfect love.
B062C004V019	62	4	19	We love, because God first loved us.
B062C004V020	62	4	20	If someone says ‘I love God,’ and yet hates another person, they are a liar; for the person who does not love their fellow, whom they have seen, cannot love God, whom they have not seen.
B062C004V021	62	4	21	Indeed, we have this command from God — ‘Those who love God must also love each other.’  
B062C005V001	62	5	1	Everyone who believes that Jesus is the Christ has received the new life from God; and everyone who loves him who gave that life loves him who has received it.
B062C005V002	62	5	2	By this we know that we love God’s children — when we love God and carry out his commands.
B062C005V003	62	5	3	For to love God is to lay his commands to heart; and his commands are not burdensome,
B062C005V004	62	5	4	because all that has received the new life from God conquers the world. And this is the power that has conquered the world — our faith!
B062C005V005	62	5	5	Who is the person that conquers the world but the person who believes that Jesus is the Son of God?
B062C005V006	62	5	6	He it is whose coming was by water and blood — Jesus Christ himself; not by water only, but by water and by blood. And there is the Spirit also to bear testimony, and the Spirit is truth itself.
B062C005V007	62	5	7	It is a threefold testimony —
B062C005V008	62	5	8	that of the Spirit, the water, and the blood — and these three are at one.
B062C005V009	62	5	9	We accept the testimony of people, but God’s testimony is still stronger; and there is the testimony of God — the fact that he has already borne testimony about his Son.
B062C005V010	62	5	10	The person who believes in the Son of God has that testimony within them. The person who does not believe God has made God a liar, by refusing to believe in that testimony which he has borne about his Son.
B062C005V011	62	5	11	And that testimony is that God gave us eternal life, and that this life is in his Son.
B062C005V012	62	5	12	The person who finds the Son finds life; the person who does not find the Son of God does not find life.
B062C005V013	62	5	13	I write this to you so that you may realise that you have found eternal life — you who believe in the name of the Son of God.
B062C005V014	62	5	14	And this is the confidence with which we approach him, that whenever we ask anything that is in accordance with his will, he listens to us.
B062C005V015	62	5	15	And if we realise that he listens to us — whatever we ask — we realise that we have what we have asked from him.
B062C005V016	62	5	16	If anyone sees one of our people committing some sin that is not a deadly sin, they will ask, and so be the means of giving life to them — to any whose sin is not deadly. There is such a thing as deadly sin; about that I do not say that a person should pray.
B062C005V017	62	5	17	Every wrong action is sin, and there is sin that is not deadly.  
B062C005V018	62	5	18	We know that no one who has received the new life from God lives in sin. No, the person who has received the new life from God keeps the thought of God in their heart, and then the evil one does not touch them.
B062C005V019	62	5	19	We realise that we come from God, while all the world is under the influence of the evil one.
B062C005V020	62	5	20	We realise, too, that the Son of God has come among us, and has given us the discernment to know the true God; and we are in union with the true God by our union with his Son, Jesus Christ. He is the true God and he is eternal life.
B062C005V021	62	5	21	My children, guard yourselves against false ideas of God.  
B063C001V001	63	1	1	To an eminent Christian Lady, and to her children, from the officer of the church. I sincerely love you all, and not I only, but also all those who have learned to know the truth.
B063C001V002	63	1	2	We love you for the sake of that truth which is always in our hearts; yes, and it will be ours for ever.
B063C001V003	63	1	3	Blessing, mercy, and peace will be ours — the gift of God, the Father, and of Jesus Christ, the Father’s Son — in a life of truth and love.
B063C001V004	63	1	4	It was a great joy to me to find the lives of some of your children guided by the truth, in obedience to the command that we received from the Father.
B063C001V005	63	1	5	And now, I pray you, Lady — not as though I were writing a new command for you; no, it is the command which we had from the first — Let us love one another.
B063C001V006	63	1	6	And this is love — to live in obedience to the Father’s commands. This is the command as you learned from the first, to live in a spirit of love.
B063C001V007	63	1	7	I say this because many impostors have left us to go into the world — people who do not acknowledge Jesus as Christ come in our human nature. It is that which marks someone as an impostor and an antichrist.
B063C001V008	63	1	8	Take care that you do not lose the fruit of all our work; rather, reap the benefit of it in full.
B063C001V009	63	1	9	Everyone who goes beyond the limits of the teaching of the Christ has failed to find God; the person who keeps to that teaching — they have found both the Father and the Son.
B063C001V010	63	1	10	If anyone comes to you and does not bring this teaching, do not receive them into your house or welcome them;
B063C001V011	63	1	11	for the person who welcomes them is sharing with them in his wicked work.
B063C001V012	63	1	12	Though I have a great deal to say to you, I would rather not trust it to paper and ink, but I am hoping to come and see you, and to speak with you face to face, so that your joy may be complete.
B063C001V013	63	1	13	The children of your eminent sister send you their greetings.
B064C001V001	64	1	1	To his dear friend Gaius, whom he sincerely loves, From the officer of the church.
B064C001V002	64	1	2	Dear friend, I pray that all may be well with you and that you may have good health — I know that all is well with your soul.
B064C001V003	64	1	3	For it was a great joy to me, when some followers of the Lord came and testified to your fidelity to the truth — I know that your own life is guided by the truth.
B064C001V004	64	1	4	Nothing gives me greater pleasure than to hear from time to time that the lives of my children are guided by the truth.  
B064C001V005	64	1	5	Dear friend, whatever you do for other followers is done in a Christian spirit — even when they are strangers to you.
B064C001V006	64	1	6	They themselves have testified before the church to your love; and you will do well to help them on their way in a manner worthy of the service of God.
B064C001V007	64	1	7	For it was on behalf of the name that they left their homes, and refused to take anything from the Gentiles.
B064C001V008	64	1	8	We, therefore, ought to give such people a hearty welcome, and so take our share in their work for the truth.  
B064C001V009	64	1	9	I wrote a few lines to the church; but Diotrephes, who loves to be first among them, declines to recognise us.
B064C001V010	64	1	10	Therefore, when I come, I will not forget his conduct in ridiculing us with his wicked tongue. Not content with that, he not only declines to recognise our friends who are followers himself, but actually prevents those who would, and expels them from the church.
B064C001V011	64	1	11	Dear friend, take what is good for your example, not what is bad. The person who does what is good is from God; the person who does what is bad has never seen God.
B064C001V012	64	1	12	Everyone has always had a good word for Demetrius, and the truth itself speaks for him. Yes, and we also add our good word, and you know that what we say about him is true.
B064C001V013	64	1	13	I have a great deal to say to you, but I do not care to trust it to pen and ink in a letter.
B064C001V014	64	1	14	I hope, however, it will not be long before I see you, and then we will speak face to face. Peace be with you. Our friends here send you their greetings. Greet each one of our friends.
B065C001V001	65	1	1	To those who, having received the call, have been loved by God the Father and protected by Jesus Christ, From Jude, a servant of Jesus Christ, and the brother of James.
B065C001V002	65	1	2	May mercy, peace, and love be yours in ever increasing measure.
B065C001V003	65	1	3	Dear friends, while I was making every effort to write to you about our common salvation, I felt that I must write to you at once to encourage you to fight in defence of the faith that has once for all been entrusted to the keeping of Christ’s people.
B065C001V004	65	1	4	For there have crept in among you certain godless people, whose sentence has long since been pronounced, and who make the mercy of God an excuse for profligacy, and disown our only lord and master, Jesus Christ.
B065C001V005	65	1	5	Now I want to remind you — but you already know it all — that, though the Lord delivered the people from Egypt, yet he afterwards destroyed those who refused to believe in him;
B065C001V006	65	1	6	and that even those angels, who did not keep to their appointed spheres, but left their proper homes, have been kept by him for the judgment of the great day in everlasting chains and black darkness.
B065C001V007	65	1	7	Like Sodom and Gomorrah and the towns near them, which gave themselves up to fornication, and fell into unnatural vice, these angels now stand out as a warning, undergoing, as they are, punishment in eternal fire.  
B065C001V008	65	1	8	Yet in the same way these people, too, cherishing vain dreams, pollute our human nature, reject control, and malign the celestial beings.
B065C001V009	65	1	9	Yet even Michael, the archangel, when, in his dispute with the devil, he was arguing about the body of Moses, did not venture to charge him with maligning, but said merely ‘The Lord rebuke you!’
B065C001V010	65	1	10	But these people malign whatever they do not understand; while they use such things as they know by instinct (like the animals that have no reason) for their own corruption.
B065C001V011	65	1	11	Alas for them! They walk in the steps of Cain; led astray by Balaam’s love of gain, they plunge into sin, and meet their ruin through rebellion like Korah.
B065C001V012	65	1	12	These are the people who are blots on your ‘love-feasts,’ when they feast together and provide without scruple for themselves alone. They are clouds without rain, driven before the winds; they are leafless trees without a vestige of fruit, dead through and through, torn up by the roots;
B065C001V013	65	1	13	they are wild sea waves, foaming with their own shame; they are ‘wandering stars,’ for which the blackest darkness has been reserved for ever.  
B065C001V014	65	1	14	To these people, as to others, Enoch, the seventh in descent from Adam, declared — ‘See! The Lord has come with his hosts of holy ones around him,
B065C001V015	65	1	15	to execute judgment on all people, and to convict all godless people of all their godless acts, which in their ungodliness they have committed, and of all the harsh words which they have spoken against him, godless sinners that they are!’  
B065C001V016	65	1	16	These people are always murmuring, and complaining of their lot; they follow where their passions lead them; they have arrogant words on their lips; and they flatter others for the sake of what they can get from them.  
B065C001V017	65	1	17	But you should, dear friends, recall what was foretold by the apostles of our Lord Jesus Christ;
B065C001V018	65	1	18	how they used to say to you — ‘As time draws to an end, there will be scoffers, who will be led by their godless passions.’
B065C001V019	65	1	19	These are the people — animal and unspiritual — who cause divisions.
B065C001V020	65	1	20	But you must, dear friends, build up your characters on the foundation of your most holy faith, pray under the guidance of the Holy Spirit,
B065C001V021	65	1	21	and keep within the love of God, while waiting for the mercy of our Lord Jesus Christ, to bring you to eternal life.
B065C001V022	65	1	22	To some show pity, because they are in doubt. ‘Drag them out of the fire,’ and save them.
B065C001V023	65	1	23	To others show pity, but with caution, hating the clothing polluted by their touch.
B065C001V024	65	1	24	To him who is able to guard you from falling, and to bring you into his glorious presence, blameless and rejoicing —
B065C001V025	65	1	25	to the one God, our Saviour, be ascribed, through Jesus Christ, our Lord, glory, majesty, power, and dominion, as it was before time began, is now, and will be for all time to come. Amen.
B066C001V001	66	1	1	The Revelation of Jesus Christ, which God gave to him to make known to his servants, concerning what must shortly take place, and which he sent and revealed by his angel to his servant John,
B066C001V002	66	1	2	who testified to the message of God and to the testimony to Jesus Christ, omitting nothing of what he had seen.
B066C001V003	66	1	3	Blessed is the one who reads, and blessed are they who listen to, the words of this prophecy, and lay to heart what is here written; for the time is near.
B066C001V004	66	1	4	From John, to the seven churches which are in Roman Asia. Blessing and peace be yours from him who is, and who was, and who will be, and from the seven spirits that are before his throne,
B066C001V005	66	1	5	and from Jesus Christ, ‘the faithful witness, the first-born from the dead, and the Ruler of all the kings of the earth.’ To him who loves us and freed us from our sins by his own blood —
B066C001V006	66	1	6	and he made us ‘a kingdom of priests in the service of God,’ his Father! — to Him be ascribed glory and dominion for ever. Amen.
B066C001V007	66	1	7	‘He is coming among the clouds!’ Every eye will see him, even those who pierced him; ‘and all the nations of the earth will mourn over him.’ So will it be. Amen.
B066C001V008	66	1	8	says the Lord,
B066C001V009	66	1	9	I, John, who am your brother, and who share with you in the suffering and kingship and endurance of Jesus, found myself on the island called Patmos, for the sake of the message of God and the testimony to Jesus.
B066C001V010	66	1	10	I fell into a trance on the Lord’s day, and I heard behind me a loud voice, like the blast of a trumpet.
B066C001V011	66	1	11	It said —
B066C001V012	66	1	12	I turned to see what voice it was that spoke to me; and when I turned, I saw seven golden lamps,
B066C001V013	66	1	13	and in the midst of the lamps one ‘like a man, in a robe reaching to his feet,’ and with a golden girdle across his breast.
B066C001V014	66	1	14	‘The hair of his head was as white as wool, as white as snow; his eyes were like flaming fire;
B066C001V015	66	1	15	and his feet were like brass’ as when molten in a furnace; ‘his voice was like the sound of many streams,’
B066C001V016	66	1	16	in his right hand he held seven stars, from his mouth came a sharp two-edged sword, and his face was like ‘the sun in the fulness of its power.’
B066C001V017	66	1	17	And, when I saw him, I fell at his feet like one dead. He laid his hand on me and said —
B066C004V001	66	4	1	After this, in my vision, I saw an open door in the heavens, and the first voice that I heard was like the blast of a trumpet speaking to me. It said — ‘Come up here and I will show you what must take place.’
B066C004V002	66	4	2	Immediately after this I fell into a trance. There stood a throne in heaven, and on the throne was One seated.
B066C004V003	66	4	3	He who was seated on it was in appearance like a jasper and a sardius; and ‘round the throne there was a rainbow’ of the colour of an emerald.
B066C004V004	66	4	4	And round the throne were twenty-four other thrones, and on these I saw twenty-four councillors sitting clothed in white robes; and on their heads they had crowns of gold.
B066C004V005	66	4	5	Out from the throne ‘come flashes of lightning, cries, and peals of thunder’! There are seven torches burning in front of the throne, which are the seven spirits of God;
B066C004V006	66	4	6	and in front of the throne is what seemed to be a sea of glass, ‘resembling crystal, while within the space before the throne and round the throne are four Creatures full of eyes’ in front and behind.
B066C004V007	66	4	7	The first Creature is like a lion, the second Creature like a calf, the third Creature has a face like a man’s, and the fourth Creature is like an eagle on the wing.
B066C004V008	66	4	8	These four Creatures have each of them six wings, and all round, and within, they are full of eyes; and day and night they never cease to say —  ‘Holy, holy, holy is the Lord, our God, the Almighty, who was, and who is, and who will be.’
B066C004V009	66	4	9	And, whenever these Creatures give praise and honour and thanks to him who is ‘seated on the throne, to him who lives for ever and ever,’
B066C004V010	66	4	10	the twenty-four councillors prostrate themselves before him who is seated on the throne, and worship him who lives for ever and ever, and throw down their crowns before the throne, saying —
B066C004V011	66	4	11	‘Worthy are you, our Lord and God, to receive all praise, and honour, and power, for you did create all things, and at your bidding they came into being and were created.’
B066C005V001	66	5	1	Then I saw at the right hand of him who was ‘seated on the throne a book, with writing inside and out, and sealed’ with seven seals;
B066C005V002	66	5	2	and I saw a mighty angel who was proclaiming in a loud voice — ‘Who is worthy to open the book and break its seals?’
B066C005V003	66	5	3	But no one either in heaven or on earth or under the earth was able to open the book or look within it.
B066C005V004	66	5	4	At this I wept long, because no one could be found who was worthy to open the book or look within it.
B066C005V005	66	5	5	But one of the councillors said to me — ‘Do not weep. The Lion conquered — the Lion of the tribe of Judah, the Scion of David — and can therefore open the book with its seven seals.’
B066C005V006	66	5	6	Then, within the space between the throne and the four Creatures, and in the midst of the councillors, I saw, standing, a Lamb, which seemed to have been sacrificed. It had seven horns and seven eyes. (These eyes are the seven spirits of God, and they are sent into all the world.)
B066C005V007	66	5	7	The Lamb came forward; and he has taken the book from the right hand of him who was seated on the throne.
B066C005V008	66	5	8	And, when he had taken the book, the four Creatures and the twenty-four councillors prostrated themselves before the Lamb, each of them holding a harp and golden bowls full of incense. (These are the prayers of Christ’s people.)
B066C005V009	66	5	9	And they are singing a new song —  ‘You are worthy to take the book and break its seals, for you were sacrificed, and with your blood you did buy for God people of every tribe, and language, and people, and nation,
B066C005V010	66	5	10	and did make them a kingdom of priests in the service of our God, and they are reigning on the earth.’
B066C005V011	66	5	11	Then, in my vision, I heard the voices of many angels round the throne, and of the Creatures, and of the councillors. In number they were ‘ten thousand times ten thousand and thousands of thousands,’
B066C005V012	66	5	12	and they cried in a loud voice —  ‘Worthy is the Lamb that was sacrificed to receive all power, and wealth, and wisdom, and might, and honour, and praise, and blessing.’
B066C005V013	66	5	13	And I heard every created thing in the air, and on the earth, and under the earth, and on the sea, and all that is in them crying —  ‘To him who is seated on the throne and to the Lamb be ascribed all blessing, and honour, and praise, and dominion for ever and ever.’
B066C005V014	66	5	14	And the four Creatures said ‘Amen,’ and the councillors prostrated themselves and worshiped.  
B066C006V001	66	6	1	Then I saw the Lamb break one of the seven seals, and I heard one of the four Creatures crying with a voice like thunder — ‘Come.’
B066C006V002	66	6	2	And in my vision I saw ‘a white horse.’ Its rider held a bow, and he was given a crown, and he went out conquering and to conquer.
B066C006V003	66	6	3	When the Lamb broke the second seal, I heard the second Creature crying — ‘Come.’
B066C006V004	66	6	4	Then there went out another horse, ‘a red horse,’ and to its rider was given the power to deprive the earth of peace, so that people should kill one another; and he was given a great sword.  
B066C006V005	66	6	5	When the Lamb broke the third seal, I heard the third Creature crying — ‘Come.’ And in my vision I saw ‘a black horse.’ Its rider held scales in his hand.
B066C006V006	66	6	6	And I heard what seemed to be a voice, coming from among the four Creatures, crying — ‘A quart of wheat for a silver coin, and three quarts of barley for a silver coin! But do not harm the oil and the wine.’  
B066C006V007	66	6	7	When the Lamb broke the fourth seal, I heard the voice of the fourth Creature crying — ‘Come.’
B066C006V008	66	6	8	And in my vision I saw a grey horse. His rider’s name was Death, and the Lord of the place of Death rode behind him; and power was given them over the fourth part of the earth, so that they might ‘destroy with sword and famine and death, and by means of the wild beasts of the earth.’  
B066C006V009	66	6	9	When the Lamb opened the fifth seal, I saw under the altar the souls of those who had been killed for the sake of God’s message and for the testimony which they had borne.
B066C006V010	66	6	10	They cried in a loud voice — ‘How long, Sovereign Lord, holy and true, before you will give judgment and avenge our blood on all who are living on the earth?’
B066C006V011	66	6	11	Then to each of them was given a white robe, and they were told to rest yet a little longer, until the number of their fellow servants and of their friends in Christ's service who were about to be put to death, as they had been, should be complete.  
B066C006V012	66	6	12	And I saw the Lamb break the sixth seal, and then there was a great earthquake. The sun became black, like sackcloth, and the moon, which was at its full, like blood.
B066C006V013	66	6	13	‘The stars of the heavens fell’ to the earth, as when a fig-tree, shaken by a strong wind, drops its unripe fruit.
B066C006V014	66	6	14	The heavens disappeared like a scroll when it is rolled up, and every mountain and island was moved from its place.
B066C006V015	66	6	15	Then all the kings of the earth, and the princes, and the generals, and the rich, and the powerful, and every slave and free person, ‘hid themselves in the caves and under the rocks’ of the mountains;
B066C006V016	66	6	16	and they are crying to the mountains and the rocks — ‘Fall on us, and hide us from the eyes of him who is seated on the throne, and from the wrath of the Lamb,
B066C006V017	66	6	17	for the great day of their wrath is come, and who can stand to meet it?’  
B066C007V001	66	7	1	After this, I saw four angels standing ‘on the four corners of the earth,’ restraining the four winds of the earth, so that no wind should blow over the earth, or over the sea, or against any tree.
B066C007V002	66	7	2	And, in the east, I saw another angel, ascending, holding the seal of the living God; and he cried in a loud voice to the four angels, to whom there had been given power to harm the earth and the sea —
B066C007V003	66	7	3	‘Do not harm the earth, or the sea, or the trees, until we have sealed the servants of our God on their foreheads.’
B066C007V004	66	7	4	I heard, too, the number of those who had been sealed. It was one hundred and forty-four thousand; and they were from every tribe of the Israelites.
B066C007V005	66	7	5	From the tribe of Judah twelve thousand were sealed,from the tribe of Reuben twelve thousand,from the tribe of Gad twelve thousand,
B066C007V006	66	7	6	from the tribe of Asher twelve thousand,from the tribe of Napthali twelve thousand,from the tribe of Manasseh twelve thousand,
B066C007V007	66	7	7	from the tribe of Simeon twelve thousand,from the tribe of Levi twelve thousand,from the tribe of Issachar twelve thousand,
B066C007V008	66	7	8	from the tribe of Zebulon twelve thousand,from the tribe of Joseph twelve thousand,from the tribe of Benjamin twelve thousand were sealed.
B066C007V009	66	7	9	After this, in my vision, I saw a vast throng which no one could number, of people from every nation and of all tribes, and peoples, and languages. They stood in front of the throne and in front of the Lamb, robed in white, holding palm branches in their hands.
B066C007V010	66	7	10	And they are crying in a loud voice —  ‘salvation be ascribed to our God who is seated on his throne and to the Lamb.’
B066C007V011	66	7	11	And all the angels were standing round the throne and the councillors and the four Creatures, and they prostrated themselves on their faces in front of the throne and worshiped God,
B066C007V012	66	7	12	saying —  ‘Amen. Blessing and praise, and wisdom, and thanksgiving, and honour, and power, and might be ascribed to our God for ever and ever. Amen.’
B066C007V013	66	7	13	Then one of the councillors turned to me and said ‘Who are these who are robed in white? And where did they come from?’
B066C007V014	66	7	14	‘My Lord,’ I answered, ‘it is you who know.’  ‘These,’ he said, ‘are they who come through the Great Persecution; they washed their robes white in the blood of the Lamb.
B066C007V015	66	7	15	And therefore it is that they are before the throne of God, and are serving him day and night in his Temple; and he who is seated on the throne will shelter them.
B066C007V016	66	7	16	Never again will they be hungry, never again will they be thirsty, nor will the sun smite them, nor any scorching heat;
B066C007V017	66	7	17	for the Lamb that stands in the space before the throne will be their shepherd, and will lead them to life-giving springs of water; and God will wipe away all tears from their eyes.’  
B066C008V001	66	8	1	As soon as the Lamb had broken the seventh seal, there was silence in heaven for, it might be, half an hour.
B066C008V002	66	8	2	Then I saw the seven angels who stand before God, and seven trumpets were given to them.
B066C008V003	66	8	3	Next, another angel came and stood at the altar with a golden censer in his hand; and a great quantity of incense was given to him, to mingle with the prayers of all Christ’s people on the golden altar before the throne.
B066C008V004	66	8	4	The smoke of the incense ascended, with the prayers of Christ’s people, from the hand of the angel before God.
B066C008V005	66	8	5	Then the angel took the censer, and filled it with fire from the altar, and threw it down on the earth; and there followed ‘peals of thunder, cries, flashes of lightning,’ and an earthquake.
B066C008V006	66	8	6	Then the seven angels holding the seven trumpets prepared to blow their blasts.  
B066C008V007	66	8	7	The first blew; and there came hail and fire mixed with blood, and it fell on the earth. A third part of the earth was burnt up, and a third of the trees, and every blade of grass.
B066C008V008	66	8	8	Then the second angel blew; and what appeared to be a great mountain, burning, was hurled into the sea. A third of the sea became blood,
B066C008V009	66	8	9	and a third part of all created things that are in the sea — that is, of all living things — died, and a third of the ships was destroyed.  
B066C008V010	66	8	10	Then the third angel blew; and there fell from the heavens a great star, burning like a torch. It fell on a third of the rivers and on the springs.
B066C008V011	66	8	11	(The star is called ‘Wormwood.’) A third of the water became bitter as wormwood, and so bitter was the water that many died from drinking it.  
B066C008V012	66	8	12	Then the fourth angel blew; and a third of the sun and a third of the moon and a third of the stars were blasted, so that a third of them was eclipsed, and for a third part of the day there was no light, and at night it was the same.  
B066C008V013	66	8	13	And, in my vision, I heard an eagle flying in mid-heaven and crying in a loud voice — ‘Woe, woe, woe for all who live on the earth, at the other trumpet-blasts of the three angels who have yet to blow.’  
B066C009V001	66	9	1	Then the fifth angel blew; and I saw a star that had fallen on the earth from the heavens, and to him was given the key of the bottomless pit.
B066C009V002	66	9	2	He opened the bottomless pit, and from the pit rose a smoke like the smoke of a great furnace. The sun and the air grew dark because of the smoke from the pit.
B066C009V003	66	9	3	Out of the smoke locusts descended on the earth, and they received the same power as that possessed by scorpions.
B066C009V004	66	9	4	They were told not to harm the grass, or any plant, or any tree, but only those who have not ‘the seal of God on their foreheads.’
B066C009V005	66	9	5	Yet they were not allowed to kill them, but it was ordered that those men should be tortured for five months. Their torture was like the torture caused by a scorpion when it stings a person.
B066C009V006	66	9	6	In those days people ‘will seek Death and will not find it’; They will long to die, but Death flees from them.
B066C009V007	66	9	7	In appearance the locusts were like horses equipped for battle. On their heads there were what appeared to be crowns that shone like gold, their faces resembled human faces,
B066C009V008	66	9	8	and they had hair like the hair of a woman, their teeth were like lions’ teeth,
B066C009V009	66	9	9	and they had what seemed to be iron breastplates, while the noise of their wings was like the noise of chariots drawn by many horses, galloping into battle.
B066C009V010	66	9	10	They have tails like scorpions, and stings, and in their tails lies their power to harm people for five months.
B066C009V011	66	9	11	They have as their king the angel of the bottomless pit, whose name, in Hebrew, is ‘Abaddon,’ while, in Greek, his name is ‘Apollyon’ (the Destroyer).
B066C009V012	66	9	12	The first Woe has passed; and still there are two Woes to follow!  
B066C009V013	66	9	13	Then the sixth angel blew; and I heard a voice proceeding from the corners of the golden altar that stood before God.
B066C009V014	66	9	14	It spoke to the sixth angel — the angel with the trumpet — and said ‘Let loose the four angels that are in chains at the great river Euphrates.’
B066C009V015	66	9	15	Then the four angels, that were held in readiness for that hour and day and month and year, were let loose, to destroy a third of mankind.
B066C009V016	66	9	16	The number of the hosts of cavalry was ten thousand times ten thousand, twice told; I heard their number.
B066C009V017	66	9	17	And this is what the horses and their riders appeared to be like in my vision: — They had breastplates of fire, blood-red and sulphurous, and the heads of the horses were like lions’ heads, while out of their mouths issue fire, and smoke, and sulphur.
B066C009V018	66	9	18	Through these three curses a third of humanity perished — because of the fire, and the smoke, and the sulphur that issued from their mouths;
B066C009V019	66	9	19	for the power of the horses lies in their mouths and in their tails. For their tails are like snakes, with heads, and it is with them that they do harm.
B066C009V020	66	9	20	But those who were left of humanity, who had not perished through these curses, did not repent and turn away from what their own hands had made; they would not abandon the worship of ‘demons, and of idols made of gold or silver or brass or stone or wood, which can neither see, nor hear, nor walk’;
B066C009V021	66	9	21	and they did not repent of their murders, or their sorceries, or their licentiousness, or their thefts.
B066C010V001	66	10	1	Then I saw another mighty angel, descending from heaven. His robe was a cloud; over his head was the rainbow; his face was like the sun, and his feet like pillars of fire;
B066C010V002	66	10	2	in his hand he held a little book open. He set his right foot on the sea, and his left on the land;
B066C010V003	66	10	3	and he cried in a loud voice like the roaring of a lion. At his cry the seven peals of thunder spoke, each with its own voice.
B066C010V004	66	10	4	And, when they spoke, I was about to write; but I heard a voice from heaven say — ‘Keep secret what the seven peals of thunder said, and do not write it down.’
B066C010V005	66	10	5	Then the angel, whom I had seen standing on the sea and on the land, ‘raised his right hand to the heavens,
B066C010V006	66	10	6	and swore by him who lives for ever and ever, who created the heavens and all that is in them, and the earth and all that is in it, and the sea and all that is in it,’ that time should cease to be.
B066C010V007	66	10	7	Moreover at the time when the seventh angel will speak, when he is ready to blow his blast, then the hidden purposes of God, of which he told the good news to his servants, the prophets, are at once fulfilled.
B066C010V008	66	10	8	Then came the voice which I had heard from heaven. It spoke to me again, and said — ‘Go and take the book that is open in the hand of the angel who stands on the sea and on the land.’
B066C010V009	66	10	9	So I went to the angel and asked him to give me the little book. And he said ‘Take it, and eat it. It will be bitter to your stomach, but in your mouth it will be as sweet as honey.’
B066C010V010	66	10	10	I took the little book out of the angel’s hand ‘and ate it, and, while in my mouth, it was like the sweetest honey’; but, when I had eaten it, it was bitter to my stomach.
B066C010V011	66	10	11	And I was told — ‘You must prophesy again about men of many peoples, and nations, and languages, and about many kings.’
B066C011V001	66	11	1	Then I was given a measure like a rod, and a voice said to me — ‘Go and measure the Temple of God and the altar, and count the worshiper there.
B066C011V002	66	11	2	But omit the court outside the Temple, and do not measure that, for it has been given up to the nations; and the holy City will be under their heel for forty-two months.
B066C011V003	66	11	3	Then I will give permission to my Two Witnesses, and for those twelve hundred and sixty days they will continue teaching, clothed in sackcloth.’
B066C011V004	66	11	4	These men are represented by ‘the two olive trees and the two lamps that stand before the Lord of the earth.’
B066C011V005	66	11	5	When anyone wishes to harm them, ‘fire comes from their mouths and consumes their enemies’; and whoever wishes to harm them will, in this way, inevitably perish.
B066C011V006	66	11	6	These men have the power to close the heavens, so that ‘no rain may fall’ during the time that they are teaching; and they have power ‘to turn the streams into blood, and to smite the land with any curse,’ whenever they will.
B066C011V007	66	11	7	As soon as they have completed their testimony, ‘the wild Beast that ascends from the bottomless pit will make war on them and conquer’ and kill them.
B066C011V008	66	11	8	Their dead bodies will lie in the streets of the great city, which is mystically spoken of as ‘Sodom’ and ‘Egypt,’ where their Master was crucified.
B066C011V009	66	11	9	People of all nations, and tribes, and languages, and races look at their dead bodies for three days and a half, and do not allow them to be laid in a grave.
B066C011V010	66	11	10	Those who live on the earth rejoice over them and are merry, and they will send presents to one another, because these two prophets brought torments on those who live on the earth.
B066C011V011	66	11	11	After three days and a half ‘the life-giving breath of God entered these men, and they stood up on their feet,’ and a great terror took possession of those who were watching them.
B066C011V012	66	11	12	The two men heard a loud voice from heaven which said to them — ‘Come up here,’ and they went up to heaven in the cloud, while their enemies watched them.
B066C011V013	66	11	13	At that very time a great earthquake occurred. A tenth part of the city fell, and seven thousand people perished in the earthquake. Those who escaped were much terrified, and praised the God of heaven.
B066C011V014	66	11	14	The second Woe has passed; and there is a third Woe soon to follow!  
B066C011V015	66	11	15	Then the seventh angel blew; and loud voices were heard in heaven saying —  ‘The kingdom of the world has become the kingdom of our Lord and of his Christ, and he will reign for ever and ever.’
B066C011V016	66	11	16	At this the twenty-four councillors, who were seated on their thrones before God, prostrated themselves on their faces and worshiped Him,
B066C011V017	66	11	17	saying —  ‘We thank you, Lord, our God, the Almighty, who is and who was, that you have assumed your great power and reigned.
B066C011V018	66	11	18	The nations were enraged, and your wrath fell on them; the time came for the dead to be judged, and for you to give the reward to your servants the prophets, and to the people of Christ, and to those who honour your name — the high and the low alike — and to destroy those who are destroying the earth.’
B066C011V019	66	11	19	Then the Temple of God in heaven was opened, and the ark containing his covenant was seen in his Temple; and there followed ‘flashes of lightning, cries, peals of thunder,’ an earthquake, and ‘a great storm of hail.’
B066C012V001	66	12	1	Then a great portent was seen in the heavens — a woman whose robe was the sun, and who had the moon under her feet, and on her head a crown of twelve stars.
B066C012V002	66	12	2	She was pregnant; and ‘she is crying out in the pain and agony of childbirth.’
B066C012V003	66	12	3	Another portent also was seen in the heavens There was a great red Dragon, with seven heads and ten horns, and on his heads were seven diadems.
B066C012V004	66	12	4	His tail draws after it a third of the stars in the heavens, and it hurled them down on the earth. The Dragon is standing in front of the woman who is about to give birth to the child, so that he may devour it as soon as it is born.
B066C012V005	66	12	5	The woman gave birth to a son, a male child, who is destined to rule all the nations with an iron rod; and her child was at once caught up to God on his throne.
B066C012V006	66	12	6	But the woman fled into the wilderness, where there is a place prepared for her by God, to be tended there for twelve hundred and sixty days.
B066C012V007	66	12	7	Then a battle took place in the heavens. Michael and his angels fought with the Dragon. But though the Dragon, with his angels, fought,
B066C012V008	66	12	8	he did not prevail; and there was no place left for them any longer in the heavens.
B066C012V009	66	12	9	Then the great Dragon, the primeval snake, known as the ‘devil’ and ‘Satan,’ who deceives all the world, was hurled down to the earth, and his angels were hurled down with him.
B066C012V010	66	12	10	And I heard a loud voice in heaven which said —  ‘Now has begun the day of the salvation, and Power, and Dominion of our God, and the Rule of his Christ; for the Accuser of our people has been hurled down, he who has been accusing them before our God day and night.
B066C012V011	66	12	11	Their victory was due to the blood of the Lamb, and to the message to which they bore their testimony. In their love of life they shrank not from death.
B066C012V012	66	12	12	Therefore, be glad, heaven, and all who live in heaven! Alas for the earth and for the sea, for the devil has gone down to you in great fury, knowing that he has but little time.’
B066C012V013	66	12	13	when the Dragon saw that he was hurled down to the earth, he pursued the woman who had given birth to the male child.
B066C012V014	66	12	14	But to the woman were given the two wings of the great eagle, so that she might fly to her place in the wilderness, where she is being tended for ‘one year, and for two years, and for half a year’ in safety from the snake.
B066C012V015	66	12	15	Then the snake poured water from its mouth after the woman, like a river, so that it might sweep her away.
B066C012V016	66	12	16	But Earth came to her help, and opened her mouth and drank up the river which the Dragon had poured out of its mouth.
B066C012V017	66	12	17	The Dragon was enraged at the woman, and went to fight with the rest of her offspring — those who lay to heart the commands of God and bear their testimony to Jesus; and he took his stand on the sea-shore.  
B066C013V001	66	13	1	Then I saw, ‘rising out of the sea, a wild Beast with ten horns’ and seven heads. On its horns were ten diadems, and on its heads were blasphemous names.
B066C013V002	66	13	2	The Beast that I saw was like a leopard; but its feet were like a bear’s, and its mouth like the mouth of a lion. The Dragon gave it his power and his throne, and wide dominion.
B066C013V003	66	13	3	One of its heads seemed to me to have been mortally wounded, but its deadly wound had been healed. The whole earth followed the Beast, wondering;
B066C013V004	66	13	4	and men worshiped the Dragon, because he had given his dominion to the Beast; while, as they worshiped the Beast, they said — ‘Who can compare with the Beast? And who can fight with it?’
B066C013V005	66	13	5	The Beast was given ‘a mouth that spoke proudly’ and blasphemously, and it was empowered to work its will for forty-two months.
B066C013V006	66	13	6	It opened its mouth only to blaspheme God, to blaspheme his name and his tent — those who live in his tent in heaven.
B066C013V007	66	13	7	It had been permitted to fight with Christ’s people and to conquer them, and it had received power over men of every tribe, and people, and language, and nation.
B066C013V008	66	13	8	All who are living on earth will worship it — all whose names have not been written in the Lamb’s book of life, the Lamb that has been sacrificed from the foundation of the world.
B066C013V009	66	13	9	Let those who have ears hear.
B066C013V010	66	13	10	‘Whoever is destined for captivity goes into captivity.’ Whoever will kill with the sword must inevitably be killed with the sword. (Here there is need for endurance and faith on the part of Christ’s people.)
B066C013V011	66	13	11	Then I saw, rising out of the earth, another wild Beast. It had two horns like those of a lamb, and its voice was like a dragon’s.
B066C013V012	66	13	12	It exercises all the authority of the first Beast under its eyes; and it makes the earth and all who are living on it worship that first Beast, whose mortal wound was healed.
B066C013V013	66	13	13	It performs great marvels, even causing fire to fall from the heavens to the earth, before people’s eyes;
B066C013V014	66	13	14	and in consequence of the marvels which it was allowed to perform under the eyes of the Beast, it is able to deceive all who are living on the earth. It tells those who live on the earth to make a statue in honour of the Beast, who, despite the wound from the sword, yet lived.
B066C013V015	66	13	15	It was permitted to breathe life into the image of the Beast, so that the image of the Beast might speak; and it was also permitted to cause all who refused to worship the image of the Beast to be put to death.
B066C013V016	66	13	16	High and low, rich and poor, free and enslaved — it causes a brand to be put on the right hand or on the forehead of every one of them,
B066C013V017	66	13	17	so that no one is able to buy or sell, except those that bear this brand — either the name of the Beast or the number indicated by the letters of his name.
B066C013V018	66	13	18	(Here there is need for discernment.) Let him who has the ability compute the number of the Beast; for the number indicates a person’s name. Its number is six hundred and sixty-six.  
B066C014V001	66	14	1	Then, in my vision, I saw the Lamb standing on Mount Zion. With him were a hundred and forty-four thousand, with his name and the name of his Father written on their foreheads.
B066C014V002	66	14	2	And I heard a sound from heaven, ‘like the sound of many waters,’ and like the sound of a loud peal of thunder; the sound that I heard was like the music of harpers playing on their harps.
B066C014V003	66	14	3	They are singing what seems to be a new song, before the throne, and before the four Creatures and the councillors; and no one was able to learn that song except the hundred and forty-four thousand who had been redeemed from earth.
B066C014V004	66	14	4	These are the men who never defiled themselves in their intercourse with women; they are as pure as virgins. These are the men who follow the Lamb wherever he goes. They were redeemed as the first-fruits of mankind for God and for the Lamb.
B066C014V005	66	14	5	‘No lie was ever heard on their lips.’ They are beyond reach of blame.
B066C014V006	66	14	6	Then I saw another angel, flying in mid-heaven. He had the good news, decreed from eternity, to announce to those who live on the earth — to men of every nation, and tribe, and language, and people;
B066C014V007	66	14	7	and he cried in a loud voice — ‘Reverence God, and give him praise (for the hour of his judgment has come) and worship him who made the heaven and the earth and the sea and all springs of water.’
B066C014V008	66	14	8	Then a second angel followed, crying — ‘She has fallen! She has fallen — Babylon the Great, who has made all the nations drink the maddening wine of her licentiousness!’  
B066C014V009	66	14	9	Then a third angel followed them, crying in a loud voice — ‘Whoever worships the Beast and its image, and receives its brand on his forehead or on his hand,
B066C014V010	66	14	10	that person will drink the maddening wine of God that has been poured unmixed into the cup of his wrath, and they will be tortured with fire and sulphur before the eyes of the holy angels and before the eyes of the Lamb.
B066C014V011	66	14	11	The smoke from their torture rises for ever and ever, and they have no rest day nor night — those who worship the Beast and its image, and all who are branded with its name.’
B066C014V012	66	14	12	(Here there is need for endurance on the part of Christ’s people — those who lay to heart the commands of God and the faith of Jesus.)
B066C014V013	66	14	13	Then I heard a voice from heaven saying ‘Write — “Blessed are the dead who from this hour die in union with the Lord.” 
B066C014V014	66	14	14	Then, in my vision, I saw a white cloud, and on the cloud there was sitting one ‘like a man.’ On his head he had a crown of gold, and in his hand a sharp sickle.
B066C014V015	66	14	15	Then another angel came out from the Temple, crying in a loud voice to him who was sitting on the cloud — ‘Take your sickle and reap, for the time to reap has come; the Harvest of Earth is ready.’
B066C014V016	66	14	16	He who was sitting on the cloud brought his sickle down on the earth, and the Harvest of Earth was reaped.  
B066C014V017	66	14	17	Then another angel came out of the Temple in heaven; he, also, had a sharp sickle.  
B066C014V018	66	14	18	Then another angel came out of the altar; he had power over fire, and he called in a loud voice to the angel that had the sharp sickle — ‘Take your sharp sickle, and gather the bunches from the Vine of Earth, for its grapes are ripe.’
B066C014V019	66	14	19	The angel brought his sickle down on the earth and gathered the fruit of the Vine of Earth, and threw it into the great winepress of the wrath of God.
B066C014V020	66	14	20	The ‘grapes were trodden in the press’ outside the city; and blood came out of the press, rising as high as the bridles of the horses for a distance of two hundred miles.  
B066C015V001	66	15	1	Then I saw another portent in the heavens — a great and marvellous portent — seven angels with the seven last curses; because with them the wrath of God is ended.
B066C015V002	66	15	2	Then I saw what appeared to be a sea of glass mixed with fire; and, standing by this sea of glass, holding the harps of God, I saw those who had come victorious out of the conflict with the Beast and its image and the number that formed its name.
B066C015V003	66	15	3	They are singing the song of Moses, the servant of God, and the song of the Lamb —  ‘Great and marvellous are your deeds, Lord, our God, the Almighty. Righteous and true are your ways, eternal King.
B066C015V004	66	15	4	Who will not honour and praise your name, Lord? You alone are holy! All nations will come and worship before you, for your judgments have become manifest.’
B066C015V005	66	15	5	After this I saw that the inmost shrine of the tent of testimony in heaven was opened,
B066C015V006	66	15	6	and out of it came the seven angels with the seven curses. They were adorned with precious stones, pure and bright, and had golden girdles round their breasts.
B066C015V007	66	15	7	One of the four Creatures gave the seven angels seven golden bowls, filled with the wrath of God who lives for ever and ever.
B066C015V008	66	15	8	‘The Temple was filled with smoke from the glory’ and Majesty of God; and no one could enter the Temple, until the seven curses inflicted by the seven angels were at an end.  
B066C016V001	66	16	1	Then I heard a loud voice, which came from the Temple, saying to the seven angels — ‘Go and empty the seven bowls of the wrath of God on the earth.’
B066C016V002	66	16	2	The first angel went and emptied his bowl on the earth; and it turned to loathsome and painful sores on all who bore the brand of the Beast and who worshiped its image.  
B066C016V003	66	16	3	Then the second angel emptied his bowl on the sea; and it turned to blood like the blood of a corpse, and every living thing died — everything in the sea.  
B066C016V004	66	16	4	Then the third angel emptied his bowl on the rivers and springs of water; and it turned to blood.
B066C016V005	66	16	5	And I heard the angel of the Waters saying — ‘Righteous are you, you who is and who is, the Holy One, in inflicting this judgment;
B066C016V006	66	16	6	for men shed the blood of Christ’s people and of the prophets, and you have given them blood to drink. It is what they deserve.’
B066C016V007	66	16	7	And I heard the response from the altar — ‘Yes, Lord, our God, the Almighty, true and righteous are they judgments.’  
B066C016V008	66	16	8	Then the fourth angel emptied his bowl on the sun; and he was permitted to scorch men with fire;
B066C016V009	66	16	9	and men were scorched by the intense heat. They blasphemed the name of God who controlled these curses, yet they did not repent and give him praise.  
B066C016V010	66	16	10	Then the fifth angel emptied his bowl on the throne of the Beast; and darkness fell on its kingdom. Men gnawed their tongues for pain,
B066C016V011	66	16	11	and blasphemed the God of heaven, because of their pains and because of their sores; yet they did not repent of what they had done.  
B066C016V012	66	16	12	Then the sixth angel emptied his bowl on the great river Euphrates; and the water in the river was dried up, so that the road for the kings of the East might be made ready.
B066C016V013	66	16	13	And I saw three foul spirits, like frogs, come from the mouth of the Dragon and from the mouth of the Beast and from the mouth of the false prophet.
B066C016V014	66	16	14	They are the spirits of demons, and perform marvels; they go to kings all over the world, to collect them for the battle on the great day of Almighty God.
B066C016V016	66	16	16	And the spirits collected the kings at the place called in Hebrew ‘Har-Magedon.’  
B066C016V017	66	16	17	Then the seventh angel emptied his bowl on the air. (A loud voice came from the throne in the Temple; it said ‘All is over.’)
B066C016V018	66	16	18	There followed ‘flashes of lightning, cries, and peals of thunder’; and there was a great earthquake, such as had not occurred since man began to be on the earth — none so great;
B066C016V019	66	16	19	and the great city was torn in three, and the cities of the nation fell, and God remembered Babylon the Great, and gave her the maddening wine-cup of his wrath;
B066C016V020	66	16	20	and every island vanished, and the mountains disappeared.
B066C016V021	66	16	21	Great hailstones, a pound in weight, are falling on men from the heavens. And men blasphemed God because of the curse of the hail, for it was a very terrible curse.  
B066C017V001	66	17	1	Then one of the seven angels who held the seven bowls came and spoke to me. ‘Come here,’ he said, ‘and I will show you the sentence passed on that Great Harlot who is seated at the meeting of many waters,
B066C017V002	66	17	2	and with whom all the kings of the earth have had licentious intercourse; while all who live on the earth have been make drunk by the wine of her licentiousness.’
B066C017V003	66	17	3	And he bore me away in a trance to a lonely place, and I saw a woman seated on a scarlet Beast, which was covered with blasphemous names; it had seven heads and ten horns.
B066C017V004	66	17	4	The woman was clothed in purple and scarlet, and glittering with gold ornaments, precious stones, and pearls. In her hand she held a gold cup, full of idolatrous abominations, and the unclean fruits of her licentiousness;
B066C017V005	66	17	5	while on her forehead there was written this mystic name — ‘BABYLON THE GREAT, THE MOTHER OF HARLOTS AND OF ALL IDOLATROUS ABOMINATIONS on EARTH.’
B066C017V006	66	17	6	And I saw the woman drunk with the blood of Christ’s people and with the blood of the martyrs for Jesus. When I saw her, I was amazed beyond measure;
B066C017V007	66	17	7	but the angel said to me — ‘Why were you amazed? I will tell you the mystic meaning of the vision of this woman, and of the Beast, with the seven heads and ten horns, that carries her.
B066C017V008	66	17	8	The Beast that you saw was, but is not, and is about to rise out of the bottomless pit, and is on its way to destruction. Those who are living on earth will be amazed — those whose names have not been written in the book of life from the foundation of the world — when they see that the Beast was, but is not, and yet will come.’
B066C017V009	66	17	9	(Here there is need for the discerning mind.) The seven heads are seven mountains on which the woman is seated.
B066C017V010	66	17	10	They are also seven kings; of whom five have fallen and one remains, while one is not yet come. When he comes, he must stay for a little while.
B066C017V011	66	17	11	So must the Beast that was, but is not. He counts as an eighth king , although he is one of the seven, and is on his way to destruction.
B066C017V012	66	17	12	The ten horns that you saw are ten kings, who have not yet received their kingdoms, but for an hour they receive the authority of kings, together with the Beast.
B066C017V013	66	17	13	These kings are of one mind in surrendering their power and authority to the Beast.
B066C017V014	66	17	14	They will fight with the Lamb, but the Lamb will conquer them, for he is Lord of lords and King of kings; so, too, will those with him who have received the call and are chosen and faithful.
B066C017V015	66	17	15	And the angel said to me — ‘The waters that you saw, where the Harlot is seated, are throngs of people and men of all nations and languages.
B066C017V016	66	17	16	The ten horns that you saw, and the Beast — they will hate the Harlot, and cause her to become deserted and strip her bare; they will eat her flesh and utterly consume her with fire.
B066C017V017	66	17	17	For God has put it into their minds to carry out his purpose, in carrying out their common purpose and surrendering their kingdoms to the Beast, until God’s decrees will be executed.
B066C017V018	66	17	18	As for the woman whom you saw, she is the great city that holds sway over all the kings of the earth.’
B066C018V001	66	18	1	After this I saw another angel, descending from heaven, invested with great authority; and the earth was illuminated by his splendour.
B066C018V002	66	18	2	With a mighty voice he cried — ‘She has fallen! She has fallen — Babylon the Great! She has become an abode of demons, a stronghold of every wicked spirit, a stronghold of every foul and hateful bird.
B066C018V003	66	18	3	For, after drinking the maddening wine of her licentiousness, all the nations have fallen; while all the kings of the earth have had licentious intercourse with her, and the merchants of the earth have grown rich through the excess of her luxury.’
B066C018V004	66	18	4	Then I heard another voice from heaven saying — ‘Come out of her, my people, so that you may not participate in her sins, and that you may not suffer from the curses inflicted on her.
B066C018V005	66	18	5	For her sins are heaped up to the heavens, and God has not forgotten her misdeeds.
B066C018V006	66	18	6	Pay her back the treatment with which she has treated you; yes, repay twice over what her actions deserve; in the cup which she mixed for you, mix for her as much again;
B066C018V007	66	18	7	for her self-glorification and her luxury, give her now an equal measure of torture and misery. In her heart she says ‘I sit here a queen; no widow am I; I will never know misery.’
B066C018V008	66	18	8	Therefore in one day will these curses strike her — death, misery, and famine, and she will be utterly consumed by fire; for mighty is the Lord God who condemned her.
B066C018V009	66	18	9	All the kings of the earth who had licentious intercourse with her and shared her luxury will weep and lament over her, when they see the smoke from the burning city,
B066C018V010	66	18	10	while they stand at a distance, horrified at her torture, and cry — ‘Alas! Alas! Great city! Mighty city of Babylon! In a single hour your judgment fell.
B066C018V011	66	18	11	And the merchants of the earth weep and wail over her, because no longer does anyone buy their cargoes —
B066C018V012	66	18	12	their cargoes of gold, or silver, or precious stones, or pearls, or fine linen, or purple robes, or silk, or scarlet cloth; nor their many scented woods; nor their many articles of ivory; nor their many articles of choicest wood, or brass, or iron, or marble;
B066C018V013	66	18	13	nor their cinnamon, or spice, or incense, or perfumes, or frankincense, or wine, or oil, or fine flour, or wheat, or cattle, or sheep; nor their horses, or chariots, or slaves; nor the bodies and souls of people.
B066C018V014	66	18	14	The fruit that your soul craved is no longer within your reach, and all dainties and luxuries are lost to you, never to be found again.’
B066C018V015	66	18	15	The merchants who sold these things, and grew rich by her, will stand at a distance weeping and wailing, horrified at her torture, and crying —
B066C018V016	66	18	16	‘Alas! Alas! Great city! City clothed in fine linen, and purple, and scarlet cloth! City adorned with gold ornaments, and precious stones, and pearls!
B066C018V017	66	18	17	In a single hour your vast wealth vanished.’ Every ship’s captain and all who sail to any port, and sailors, and all who get their living from the sea, stood at a distance,
B066C018V018	66	18	18	and seeing the smoke from the burning city, cried — ‘What city can compare with the Great city?’
B066C018V019	66	18	19	They threw dust on their heads, and, as they wept and wailed, they cried — ‘Alas! Alas! Great city! All who have ships on the sea grew rich through her magnificence. In a single hour it has vanished.’
B066C018V020	66	18	20	Rejoice over her, heaven, and people of Christ, and apostles, and prophets, for God has avenged you on her!
B066C018V021	66	18	21	Then a mighty angel took up a stone like a great millstone, and threw it into the sea, crying — ‘So will Babylon, the great city, be violently overthrown, never more to be seen.
B066C018V022	66	18	22	No more will the music of harpers, or minstrels, or flute players, or trumpeters be heard in you, no more will any worker, skilled in any art, be found in you; no more will the sound of a mill be heard in you;
B066C018V023	66	18	23	no more will the light of a lamp shine in you; no more will the voices of groom and bride be heard in you. Your merchants were the great men of the earth, for all the nations were deceived by your magical charms.
B066C018V024	66	18	24	Yes, and in her was to be found the blood of the prophets and of Christ’s people, and of all who have been put to death on the earth.’
B066C019V001	66	19	1	After this, I heard what seemed to be a great shout from a vast throng in heaven, crying —  ‘Hallelujah! To our God belong salvation, and glory, and Power,
B066C019V002	66	19	2	for true and righteous are his judgments. For he has passed judgment on the Great Harlot who was corrupting the earth by her licentiousness, and he has taken vengeance on her for the blood of his servants.’
B066C019V003	66	19	3	Again they cried — ‘Hallelujah!’ And the smoke from her ruins rises for ever and ever.
B066C019V004	66	19	4	Then the twenty-four councillors and the Four Creatures prostrated themselves and worshiped God who was seated on the throne, crying — ‘Amen, Hallelujah!’;
B066C019V005	66	19	5	and from the throne there came a voice which said —  ‘Praise our God all you who serve him, You who worship him, both high and low.’
B066C019V006	66	19	6	Then I heard ‘what seemed to be the shout of a vast throng, like the sound of many waters,’ and like the sound of loud peals of thunder, crying —  ‘Hallelujah! For the Lord is king, our God, the Almighty.
B066C019V007	66	19	7	Let us rejoice and exalt; and we will pay him honour, for the hour for the Marriage of the Lamb has come, and his Bride has made herself ready.
B066C019V008	66	19	8	And to her it has been granted to robe herself in fine linen, white and pure, for that linen is the good deeds of the people of Christ.’
B066C019V009	66	19	9	Then a voice said to me ‘Write — “Blessed are those who have been summoned to the marriage feast of the Lamb.”’ And the voice said — ‘These words of God are true.’
B066C019V010	66	19	10	I prostrated myself at the feet of him who spoke to worship him, but he said to me — ‘Forbear; I am your fellow servant, and the fellow servant of your brothers and sisters who bear their testimony to Jesus. Worship God. For to bear testimony to Jesus needs the inspiration of the prophets.’
B066C019V011	66	19	11	Then I saw that heaven lay open. There appears a white horse; its rider is called ‘Faithful’ and ‘True’; righteously does he judge and make war.
B066C019V012	66	19	12	His eyes are flaming fires; on his head there are many diadems, and he bears a name, written, which no one knows but himself;
B066C019V013	66	19	13	he has been clothed in a garment sprinkled with blood; and the name by which he is called is ‘The Word of God.’
B066C019V014	66	19	14	The armies of heaven followed him, mounted on white horses and clothed in fine linen, white and pure.
B066C019V015	66	19	15	From his mouth comes a sharp sword, with which ‘to smite the nations; and he will rule them with an iron rod.’ He ‘treads the grapes in the press’ of the maddening wine of the wrath of Almighty God;
B066C019V016	66	19	16	and on his robe and on his thigh he has this name written — ‘KING OF KINGS AND LORD OF LORDS.’
B066C019V017	66	19	17	Then I saw an angel standing on the sun. He cried in a loud voice to all the birds that fly in mid-heaven — ‘Gather and come to the great feast of God,
B066C019V018	66	19	18	to eat the flesh of kings, and the flesh of commanders, and the flesh of mighty men, and the flesh of horses and their riders, and the flesh of all free and enslaved, and of high and low.’
B066C019V019	66	19	19	Then I saw the Beast and the kings of the earth and their armies, gathered together to fight with him who sat on the horse and with his army.
B066C019V020	66	19	20	The Beast was captured, and with him was taken the false prophet, who performed the marvels before the eyes of the Beast, with which he deceived those who had received the brand of the Beast and those who worshiped his image. Alive, they were thrown, both of them, into the lake of fire - of burning sulphur.
B066C019V021	66	19	21	The rest were killed by the sword which came out of the mouth of him who rode on the horse; and all the birds fed on their flesh.
B066C020V001	66	20	1	Then I saw an angel coming down from heaven, with the key of the bottomless pit and a great chain in his hand.
B066C020V002	66	20	2	He seized the Dragon, the primeval snake (who is the ‘devil’ or ‘Satan’), and bound him in chains for a thousand years.
B066C020V003	66	20	3	He flung him into the bottomless pit and locked it, and set his seal on it; that he should not deceive the nations any more, until the thousand years were ended. After that he must be let loose for a while.
B066C020V004	66	20	4	Then I saw thrones, and to those who took their seats on them authority was given to act as judges. And I saw the souls of those who had been beheaded because of the testimony to Jesus and because of the message of God, for they had refused to worship the Beast or its image, and had not received the brand on their foreheads and on their hands. They were restored to life, and they reigned with the Christ for a thousand years.
B066C020V005	66	20	5	(The rest of the dead were not restored to life until the thousand years were ended.) This is the first resurrection.
B066C020V006	66	20	6	Blessed and holy will he be who shares in that first resurrection. The second Death has no power over them; but they will be priests of God, and the Christ, and they will reign with him for the thousand years.  
B066C020V007	66	20	7	When the thousand years are ended, Satan will be let loose from his prison,
B066C020V008	66	20	8	and he will come out to deceive the nations that live in ‘the four corners of the earth — Gog and Magog.’ He will come to gather them together for battle; and their number will be as great as the sand on the sea-shore.
B066C020V009	66	20	9	They went up over the breadth of the whole earth, and surrounded the camp of Christ’s people and the city that he loves. Then fire fell from the heavens and consumed them;
B066C020V010	66	20	10	and the devil, their deceiver, was hurled into the lake of fire and sulphur, where the Beast and the false prophet already were, and they will be tortured day and night for ever and ever.  
B066C020V011	66	20	11	Then I saw a great white throne, and him who was seated on it. ‘The earth and the heavens fled from his presence; no place was left for them.’
B066C020V012	66	20	12	And I saw the dead, high and low, standing before the throne; and books were opened. Then another book was opened, the book of life; and the dead were judged, according to their actions, by what was written in the books.
B066C020V013	66	20	13	The sea gave up its dead, and Death and the Lord of the place of Death gave up their dead; and they were judged, one by one, each according to his actions.
B066C020V014	66	20	14	Then Death and the Lord of the place of Death were hurled into the lake of fire. This is the Second Death — the lake of fire;
B066C020V015	66	20	15	and all whose names ‘were not found written in the book of life’ were hurled into the lake of fire.
B066C021V001	66	21	1	Then I saw new heavens and a new earth. The former heavens and the former earth had passed away; and the sea has ceased to be.
B066C021V002	66	21	2	And I saw the Holy City, Jerusalem, descending new out of heaven from God, like a bride adorned in readiness for her husband.
B066C021V003	66	21	3	And I heard a loud voice from the throne, which said — ‘See! The tent of God is set up among people. God will live among them, and they will be his Peoples, and God himself will be among them,
B066C021V004	66	21	4	and he will wipe away all tears from their eyes. There will be no more death, nor will there be any more grief or crying or pain. The old order has passed away.’
B066C021V005	66	21	5	And he who was seated on the throne said — ‘See, I make all things new!’ And he said — ‘Write this, for these words may be trusted and are true.’
B066C021V006	66	21	6	And he said to me — ‘They are fulfilled. I am the Alpha and the Omega, the beginning and the End. To those who thirst I will give of the spring of the water of life, freely.
B066C021V007	66	21	7	Those who conquer will enter into possession of these things, and I will be their God, and they will be my children.
B066C021V008	66	21	8	But as for cowards, unbelievers, the degraded, murderers, the impure, sorcerers, idolaters, and all liars — their place will be in the burning lake of fire and sulphur. That is the Second Death.’
B066C021V009	66	21	9	Then one of the seven angels who had the seven bowls, and were laden with the seven last curses, came and spoke to me. ‘Come here,’ he said, ‘and I will show you the Bride, the Wife of the Lamb.’
B066C021V010	66	21	10	He carried me away in a trance to a great high mountain, and showed me Jerusalem, the Holy City, descending out of heaven from God, filled with the glory of God.
B066C021V011	66	21	11	Its brilliance was like a precious stone, like a jasper, transparent as crystal.
B066C021V012	66	21	12	It had a great high wall, in which were twelve gates; and at these gates there were twelve angels, and there were names inscribed on the gates, the names of the twelve tribes of the Israelites.
B066C021V013	66	21	13	‘There were three gates on the east, three gates on the north, three gates on the south, and three gates on the west.’
B066C021V014	66	21	14	The wall of the city had twelve foundation stones, on which were the twelve names of the twelve apostles of the Lamb.
B066C021V015	66	21	15	And the angel who was speaking to me had as a measure a gold rod, with which to measure the city and its gates and its wall.
B066C021V016	66	21	16	The city is square; the length and the breadth are the same. The angel measured with his rod; it was twelve hundred miles; its length, and breadth, and height are equal.
B066C021V017	66	21	17	Then he measured the wall; it was two hundred and eighty-eight feet, as people measure, that is as the angel measured.
B066C021V018	66	21	18	The material of the wall of the city was jasper, and the city was built of pure gold, which shone like clear glass.
B066C021V019	66	21	19	The foundations of the wall of the city were ornamented with every kind of precious stone. The first foundation stone was a jasper; the second a sapphire; the third a chalcedony; the fourth an emerald;
B066C021V020	66	21	20	the fifth a sardonyx; the sixth a carnelian; the seventh a chrysolite; the eighth a beryl; the ninth a topaz; the tenth a chrysoprase; the eleventh a hyacinth; and the twelfth an amethyst.
B066C021V021	66	21	21	The twelve gates were made of twelve pearls, each gate of one pearl. The street of the city was of pure gold, transparent as glass.
B066C021V022	66	21	22	And I saw no Temple there, for the Lord, our God, the Almighty, and the Lamb are its Temple.
B066C021V023	66	21	23	The city has no need of ‘the sun or the moon to shine on it, for the glory of God illuminated it,’ and its Lamp was the Lamb.
B066C021V024	66	21	24	‘The nations walk by the light of it; and the kings of the earth bring their glory into it.
B066C021V025	66	21	25	Its gates will never be shut by day,’ and there will be no night there.
B066C021V026	66	21	26	And people will bring the glory and honour of the nations into it.
B066C021V027	66	21	27	‘Never will any unhallowed thing enter it,’ nor they whose life is shameful and false, but only ‘those whose names have been written in the Lamb’s book of life.’
B066C022V001	66	22	1	And the angel showed me ‘a river of the water of life,’ as clear as crystal, issuing from the throne of God and of the Lamb,
B066C022V002	66	22	2	in the middle of the street of the city. On each side of the river was a Tree of life which bore twelve kinds of fruit, yielding its fruit each month; and the leaves of the tree were for the healing of the nations.
B066C022V003	66	22	3	‘Every thing that is accursed will cease to be.’ The throne of God and of the Lamb will be within it, and his servants will worship him;
B066C022V004	66	22	4	they will see his face, and his name will be on their foreheads.
B066C022V005	66	22	5	Night will cease to be. They have no need of the light of a lamp, nor have they the light of the sun; for the ‘Lord God will be their light, and they will reign for ever and ever.’
B066C022V006	66	22	6	Then the angel said to me — ‘These words may be trusted and are true. The Lord, the God that inspires the prophets, sent his angel to show his servants what must quickly take place;
B066C022V007	66	22	7	and they said Blessed will he be who lays to heart the words of the prophecy contained in this book.’
B066C022V008	66	22	8	It was I, John, who heard and saw these things; and, when I heard and saw them, I prostrated myself in worship at the feet of the angel that showed them to me.
B066C022V009	66	22	9	But he said to me — ‘Forbear; I am your fellow servant, and the fellow servant of your fellow prophets, and of all who lay to heart the words in this book. Worship God.’  
B066C022V010	66	22	10	Then the angel said to me — ‘Do not keep secret the words of the prophecy contained in this book; for the time is near.
B066C022V011	66	22	11	Let the wrong-doer continue to do wrong; the filthy-minded continue to be filthy; the righteous continue to act righteously; and the holy-minded continue to be holy.’
B066C022V014	66	22	14	Blessed will they be who wash their robes, that they may have the right to approach the Tree of life, and may enter the city by the gates.
B066C022V015	66	22	15	Outside will be the filthy, the sorcerers, the impure, the murderers, the idolaters, and all who love the false and live it.’  
B066C022V017	66	22	17	‘Come,’ say the Spirit and the Bride; and let him who hears say ‘Come.’ Let him who thirsts come; let him who will take the water of life freely.
B066C022V018	66	22	18	I declare to all who hear the words of the prophecy contained in this book — ‘If anyone adds to it, God will add to his troubles the curses described in this book;
B066C022V019	66	22	19	and if anyone takes away any of the words in the book containing this prophecy, God will take away his share in the Tree of life, and in the Holy City — as described in this book.’
B066C022V020	66	22	20	He whose testimony this is says — ‘Amen, come, Lord Jesus.’
B066C022V021	66	22	21	May the blessing of the Lord Jesus Christ, be with his people.
